<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDY-MAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX 
</HEADLINE>
 
NEW LAW INCREASES SCOPE OF HANDYMAN WORK (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _You just bought a new house and noticed that the
wrought iron gate to the spa in the back yard is busted, the wooden
fence is missing a few slats and the Santa Ana winds blew open the
gate and broke off the spigot for the garden hose.
</P>
<P>
   It's more of a nuisance than a disaster. But it's more than you
want to tackle. So who ya gonna call?
</P>
<P>
   Probably a handyman.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, thanks to a new state law that took effect Friday,
handymen can do even more work around the house.
</P>
<P>
   The new law calls for an increase in the ``monetary
jurisdiction'' of handymen. It simply ups the dollar threshold
before the job you have requires the skills of someone with a state
contractors license.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, if the cost of materials and labor exceeded $300, a
handyman needed a contractors license to do the job. Now the limit
is $500.
</P>
<P>
   Still, handymen must tell consumers that they are not licensed
even if the job is for less than $500.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good handyman is skilled in all of the trades and it is
really hard to find one that can do both electrical and carpentry.
But there are some out there,'' said Ronald F. Hammond, a Realtor
who specializes in residential property management.
</P>
<P>
   That being the case, here are some tips to follow before making
that call:
</P>
<P>
   --Use the word-of-mouth network. Ask neighbors, co-workers or
real estate agents whom they would recommend.
</P>
<P>
   --Ask the person you hire if he has workers' compensation
insurance and then ask to see a copy of the policy. You could be
protected if the handyman is hurt on your job. If he doesn't have
workers' compensation, you could be liable if he injures himself on
your property.
</P>
<P>
   --Ask to see if he has a general contractors license. Some
handymen do and this is a plus because it shows the handyman has
extra skills.
</P>
<P>
   --Find out if the license is valid. The National &AMP; California
Contractor Referral and Contractors' License Bureau will check for
a $25 fee. It could be money well spent. The Web site is
www.contractorreferral.com.
</P>
<P>
   --Make sure the handyman has a business license.
</P>
<P>
   --Get a written contract that spells out the terms and
conditions of what will be done. Costs can be negotiated.
</P>
<P>
   --If you think you'll frequently be using these kinds of
services, track down a copy of the ``Marshall &AMP; Swift Estimator.''
It is a book used by contractors and appraisers to estimate the
cost of various jobs. It includes everything from replacing a
washer on a leaky faucet to the kitchen sink.
</P>
<P>
   It costs about $40 and is updated annually.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
