<SLUG> BC-FBC-SUGAR-BOWL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE-BEATEN BUCKEYES WIN, AND NOW THEY CAN ONLY WAIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La., Ohio, Texas)  (js) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Even when his team was leading Texas A&AMP;M by 24-7
late in the third quarter, Ohio State Coach John Cooper had the
pained expression of a desperate man trying to climb out of a pit
with its sides lined with sand. Many of the Ohio State fans among
the 76,503 here at the Superdome could feel Cooper's pain.
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M has a way of doing that to opposing coaches and teams.
Entering Friday night's Sugar Bowl game, the No. 9 ranked Aggies
had five recorded victories this season after having trailed by 5
points or more. Texas A&AMP;M trailed Kansas State 27-12 with 9:20 to
play, before roaring back to tie the game 27-27 and eventually
winning it in overtime to take the Big 12 conference championship.
That game sank Kansas State's national championship hopes and sent
them spiraling from the Bowl Championship Series into the Alamo
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   With 10 minutes 22 seconds to play, Ohio State kicker Dan
Stultz's 47-yard field goal attempt clanked off the right upright,
leaving the Buckeyes with a 24-14 lead and leaving a crack for the
Aggies to squeeze through for another improbable comeback victory.
Then, the big question hung in the air: Could Ohio State beat fate?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, they could and in the process the Buckeyes (11-1) were able
to hold on and defeat Texas A&AMP;M 24-14. Now, the Buckeyes must wait
for the outcome of Monday's Fiesta Bowl game between Tennessee and
Florida State to determine whether they can finish campaigning for
a national championship.
</P>
<P>
   The Buckeyes were hoping that an impressive victory over the
Aggies, coupled with a loss by No. 1 Tennessee to Florida State in
the Fiesta Bowl on Monday night, would vault them to a national
championship. That's what Ohio State Coach John Cooper campaigned
for here this week.
</P>
<P>
   But the Buckeyes still had to do their part against the Big 12
Conference champions Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M made it look easy on its first possession, going 59
yards in six plays and taking a 7-0 lead on a 9-yard run by
tailback Dante Hall. But it was fun while it lasted: that was the
last time the Aggies scored in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State took over from there, rolling to a 21-7 first-quarter
lead. As soon as quarterback Joe Germaine figured out that he could
pick apart the Aggies' zone coverage, he exploited it. And once the
secondary was riddled, Ohio State put its rushing attack in high
gear. The combination was lethal for the Texas A&AMP;M defense. If not
for a couple of brilliant plays to break up passes in the end zone
by cornerbacks Jason Webster and Sedrick Curry, the deficit would
have been even larger.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State scored its first touchdown on an 18-yard slant pass
from Germaine to receiver Reggie Germany that capped an eight-play,
71-yard drive.
</P>
<P>
   Aggies quarterback Branndon Stewart had trouble waiting for
receivers to complete routes downfield as Ohio State's blitzes and
coverages limited Texas A&AMP;M's options. What was left was not very
appealing _ short passes and predictable runs that left receivers
and running backs wearing tattoos after hard tackles.
</P>
<P>
   The Buckeyes turned running backs Michael Wiley and Joe
Montgomery loose on their next possession. The splendid blend of
speed (Wiley) and power (Montgomery) set the Texas A&AMP;M defense on
its heels. On second-and-4 at the Aggies' 39, Montgomery burst up
the middle for a 29-yard gain. On the next play, he plowed through
the middle again for a 10-yard touchdown that helped make it 14-7
Ohio State with 4 minutes 10 seconds to play in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies were stymied again on offense, and Shane Lechler's
punt was blocked by Ohio State safety Derek Ross, who had lined up
on the left end and came free. The ball was scooped up by Kevin
Griffin, who returned it 16 yards for a touchdown and a 21-7 Ohio
State lead with 1:59 to play in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   On their second possession of the second quarter, the Buckeyes
had a touchdown opportunity wiped out when Webster deflected a
25-yard strike from Germaine to David Boston in the end zone at the
last second. The Buckeyes gambled on fourth-and-1, and the Aggies'
defense dropped Wiley for a 2-yard loss. It was a great defensive
effort, but Texas A&AMP;M's offense remained in neutral.
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies' defense saved another touchdown late in the half
when Curry tipped away a pass from Germaine to Boston, who was open
in the end zone on third-and-6 at the Aggies' 36. The Buckeyes were
forced to punt, although they initially lined up for a 54-yard
field goal before thinking better of it and calling a timeout.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State got a 31-yard field goal from Dan Stultz with 16
seconds to play in the half for a 24-7 lead. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
