<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ROSE-GAMER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA OFFENSE FALLS SHORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA _ Funny how the finger points. A month ago, UCLA's
offense blamed the defense for the devastating loss at Miami.
Friday evening, the pointing reversed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ironic how things work out,'' Bruins linebacker Brendon
Ayanbadejo said. ``Our offense couldn't get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a simplified version of what transpired in the Rose Bowl,
but true nonetheless. The defense may have played well enough to
win, but mistakes by the offense sealed the Bruins' fate in a 38-31
loss to Wisconsin before 93,872.
</P>
<P>
   Using five freshman starters, the defense overcame injuries to
safeties Jason Stephens and Larry Atkins and held the Badgers to
seven points in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   That should have been good enough to secure UCLA's first Rose
Bowl win since 1986. But two second-half turnovers _ DeShaun
Foster's fumble and Cade McNown's interception returned for a
touchdown _ created a 14-point swing, and that was enough for the
Badgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That nail got the coffin going,'' Bruins coach Bob Toledo
said.
</P>
<P>
   So UCLA's two-year charge up the rankings ended where it began,
with back-to-back losses. Last year, it was Washington State and
Tennessee at the start of the season; this year, Miami and
Wisconsin at the end.
</P>
<P>
   In between, they carved out a school-record 20-game winning
streak. That was little consolation in a dejected _ but not divided
_ locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not mad at one guy in there,'' said offensive tackle Kris
Farris, who was called for two drive-killing holding penalties.
``We were ready, and they just played better than us.''
</P>
<P>
   Of that, there was no doubt. The Badgers (11-1) are not the most
athletically gifted team that UCLA (10-2) has faced this season,
but they certainly are the smartest and most fundamentally sound.
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, they did exactly what the Bruins expected: no
tricks, no fancy passing game, just smash-mouth, Big Ten football.
Massive tailback Ron Dayne ran behind a massive offensive line for
246 yards _ one yard short of a Rose Bowl record _ averaging 9.1
yards per carry. His four rushing touchdowns also tied a Rose Bowl
mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``You watch film of him and wonder how people could miss tackles
like they do,'' UCLA nose guard Ken Kocher said. ``Then you get out
there and think, `That's how they missed tackles.' He's really
good.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA gained a Rose Bowl-record 538 yards, but it was a
deceiving. The Bruins never generated a consistent rushing game
(3.2 yards per carry) as the Badgers' line held its own against
Farris and Friends.
</P>
<P>
   In his final game, McNown threw for 340 yards and two
touchdowns, but it was far from his best performance _ in part
because starting receiver Brian Poli-Dixon missed most of the game
with a hamstring injury, allowing the Badgers to concentrate on
Danny Farmer during crucial situations.
</P>
<P>
   McNown was sacked three times, pressured throughout and had no
rhythm when the Bruins, trailing by a touchdown, took possession at
their 46-yard line with 1:42 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   First down: incomplete pass to Brad Melsby.
</P>
<P>
   Second down: incomplete pass to Melsby.
</P>
<P>
   Third down: incomplete pass to Farmer.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth down: McNown sacked.
</P>
<P>
   Really, UCLA lost the game much earlier, beginning with a wasted
possession early in the third quarter. After moving 74 yards in
seven plays, the Bruins had first down at Wisconsin's 6. But the
raucous Badgers fans crammed into the north end zone forced McNown
to call timeout.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way would you think it would have been 65 percent Wisconsin
fans,'' UCLA fullback Durell Price said. ``You'd think it would be
the other way around. It was disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   When play resumed, the noise returned. McNown audibled at the
line of scrimmage, using hand signals to change the play from a
handoff to a pitch. But Foster mistakenly thought McNown had called
a handoff. At the snap, Foster moved towards McNown and was unable
to handle the unexpected pitch. The ball squirted forward,
Wisconsin recovered at its 2, and the Bruins were denied a
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``DeShaun wasn't the only one who didn't get it,'' offensive
coordinator Al Borges said. ``That was tough.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense held, and UCLA closed to 31-28 on Jermaine Lewis'
10-yard touchdown run late in the third quarter. On the second play
of the fourth, facing third-and-9, McNown underthrew Foster on the
right sideline. Wisconsin's Jamar Fletcher intercepted and raced in
for a touchdown that gave the Badgers a 38-28 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bad decision in retrospect,'' McNown said.
</P>
<P>
   One fumble and one interception equals two turnovers, a 14-point
swing and a loss that will last a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defense played bad in the first half and good in the
second,'' guard Andy Meyers said. ``In the first half, the offense
played good. In the second, we turned it over two times. It's
unfortunate how we played.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
