<SLUG> BC-BURNED-BOY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURNED BOYS IN CRITICAL CARE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY SHERRY JOE CROSBY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Two boys who were badly burned when a suspicious
Christmas tree fire engulfed their Val Verde home remained in
critical condition Friday at the Grossman Burn Center at Sherman
Oaks Hospital, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both remain on respirators. Not much has changed, which is
what we expected _ and therefore, that's good news,'' hospital
spokesman Larry Weinberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a long time to get better from these kind of
injuries, and that's why any dramatic change is not for the good.''
</P>
<P>
   Surgeons are scheduled to operate on Shawn Williams, 17, today
to remove dead and dying tissue from the burns that cover 43
percent of his body, Weinberg said. Burn areas will be covered with
cadaver skin in an effort to fend off infection.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors also will insert a scope through his mouth and into his
airways to assess the seriousness of the burns inside his lungs.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Crawford, 7, is tentatively scheduled for similar
surgery Monday, if he has stabilized enough to cope with the
procedures. He had third-degree burns over 65 percent of his body.
</P>
<P>
   The boys, who are half-brothers, were receiving treatment to
keep their major organs functioning, Weinberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're keeping them quiet, comfortable and stable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Four people were injured in the blaze, which broke out about
8:15 a.m. Thursday at 29016 Val Verde Road in the Santa Clarita
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Also injured in the blaze were Shawn's girlfriend, Patricia Lynn
Martin, 20, and the boys' aunt, Dawn Carter, 45. Both continued to
recuperate at Los Angeles County/USC Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who suffered second- and third-degree burns over 18
percent of her body, was listed in critical condition in the burn
intensive care unit. She had burns to her arms and back and was
suffering from smoke inhalation, hospital spokeswoman Adelaide
DeLaCerda said.
</P>
<P>
   Carter was listed in fair condition with a fractured ankle,
DeLaCerda said.
</P>
<P>
   The origins of the fire remained under investigation Friday. A
dispatcher at the Los Angeles County Fire Department said arson
investigators probably will resume their investigation Monday.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
