r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-COYOTES-AZR     01-02 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-COYOTES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS WIN, BUT COYOTES SHINE, TOO  
 HULL'S GOAL EXTENDS DALLAS STREAK TO 14 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 Stars 2, Coyotes 1 (OT) 
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a game they said they wanted to use as a measuring stick.
But by once again having to play without their entire No. 1 line,
you'd think the Coyotes couldn't touch the Dallas Stars with a
10-foot pole.
</P>
<P>
   Well, get out your kiddie pocket rulers, puck heads.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes, even with the absence of superstars Keith Tkachuk
and Jeremy Roenick, can easily consider themselves in the same
company as the league-leading Stars after their gutsy effort Friday
night at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Playing before their seventh consecutive sellout crowd in a game
of inches, the Coyotes more than held their own in a 2-1 overtime
loss that was even closer than the final score indicates.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got the bounce at the end of the game, but it was
anybody's game up until that point,'' said Coyotes defenseman Deron
Quint, who couldn't have picked a better time to score his first
goal of the season. His rebound score with 33 seconds left in
regulation sent it to overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played just as well as they did. Guys played hard. Guys
competed. Shoney (Coach Jim Schoenfeld) came up with a great
system, everybody followed it, and we pretty much shut them down.
We could have scored three or four goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Brett Hull scored the biggest one, driving home Mike Modano's
sliding reach pass in front of the net just 37 seconds into the
extra five-minute period. The goal extended the Stars' club-record
unbeaten streak (11-0-3) to 14 games, matching the longest of the
season, set earlier by the Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix defenseman Keith Carney shadowed Modano into the
Coyotes' zone, knocking him off the puck. But sliding on his
stomach, Modano, who had given Dallas a 1-0 lead four minutes into
the third period, stretched out and managed to tip it over to Hull
for the one-timer that beat Nikolai Khabibulin, who had 29 saves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen a replay of it yet,'' Carney said, ``but I'll
be watching them (today) for sure. I didn't think he could get it
over there, but he's got that long reach and made a good play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes (21-8-4) pressured Dallas starting goalie Roman
Turek during the final minutes of regulation, but couldn't get
anything past him until Quint brought the crowd to its feet by
knocking in a missed shot from Shane Doan.
</P>
<P>
   Turek turned away 26 other shots, though, to remain unbeaten
(6-0-2) as Eddie Belfour's backup and to keep the Stars (24-5-6)
rolling. Coach Ken Hitchcock said the 14-game streak is just part
of the reward for hard work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just that winning feeling that you don't want to let go
of,'' he said. ``It's like a racehorse that's winning a lot of
races. You just want to keep running it week after week until it
just runs out of gas, then you kind of rest it, and then start it
again.''
</P>
<P>
   After a scoreless first period in which they skated with the
Stars stride for stride _ and may have actually outplayed them,
considering the circumstances _ the Coyotes had an excellent
opportunity to grab the lead with 13:17 left in the second. That's
when the Stars' Brian Skrudland went to the penalty box with a
double minor, putting Phoenix on the power play for four minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Skrudland took down Quint on a two-on-one rush set up by Daniel
Briere, and then he was hit with an unsportsmanlike conduct for
yapping about the call with referee Rob Shick.
</P>
<P>
   But the Coyotes, who have been struggling on the power play all
season, couldn't convert. With 12 seconds left in the four-minute
advantage, they got another chance when Modano was whistled for
hooking Jyrki Lumme. But again, nothing. The Stars killed off that
penalty, too, just as they did two others in the first period.
</P>
<P>
   It extended the Coyotes' skid to 0 for 13 to that point, dating
back four games earlier, when Phoenix broke loose with three
man-advantage goals in eight tries against Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes should have been awarded another power play in the
first, but the two-man refereeing crew of Shick and Dennis LaRue
missed it. It happened behind the Dallas net, when Modano
high-sticked Doan above the right eye, which opened up a nasty cut.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas, meanwhile, which has ranked at or near the top of the
league all season with a dominating power-play unit, probably felt
like complaining a little bit, too. The Stars, who entered the game
having scored an NHL-high 40 goals with the man advantage, went on
the power play only once during the first two periods. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
