<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-TICKETS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERE ARE TICKETS, WHERE ARE FANS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK SHAFFER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a national championship football game in town Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   But Valley ticket brokers are wondering whether anyone cares.
</P>
<P>
   They say that they already are buying tickets from bummed
speculators at their $135 face value and that the price is expected
to tumble below that by kickoff time.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were to offer below face value, I could buy a lot right
now,'' said Reed Simon, owner of Team One Tickets and Sports Tours
in Tempe. ``But I don't want to be stuck with more than 20 tickets
come game day the way things are going.''
</P>
<P>
   The best seats in Sun Devil Stadium on the 50-yard line, which
started at $950, have fallen to $375, and slightly less prime areas
are going in the $150 range, Simon said.
</P>
<P>
   Simon and other ticket brokers blame it on Florida State. They
say that losses by Kansas State, UCLA and Ohio State _ which opened
the door for the Seminoles to play in the championship game _ have
sent the market into a tailspin.
</P>
<P>
   So much so that Simon says he hasn't been able to sell an
upper-deck end zone seat for any price. It certainly hasn't helped
matters that both schools are from the other side of the country.
But it's been downright fatal that Florida State has a previous
loss and doesn't seem to generate passion on a mass scale, Simon
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that no one expected Florida State to sneak in
like this,'' said Marty Fettman, spokesman for Ticket Connection in
Phoenix. ``We were all counting on UCLA, Ohio State and Kansas
State coming here. The dreams have been ruined.''
</P>
<P>
   Fettman wouldn't say how many tickets he had sold but ``they
haven't been flying out the door, to put it mildly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This just isn't the right match-up, at least for us,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Fettman also said he expects the price of some tickets to fall
below $100 before kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   But one central Phoenix ticket broker, Bob Tuma of Ticket
Exchange, wasn't buying into all the negative thinking. He was
still trying to get $175 for goal-line seats in the upper deck and
$250 for seats in the area of the 10-yard line. Tuma had no
customers at midafternoon Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Seminole fans without tickets also haven't been opening their
pocketbooks.
</P>
<P>
   Simon says that Tennessee fans have purchased 476 of the 500
tickets he has sold thus far, Florida State backers only 18. Even
more depressing, he has sold only six tickets to people from
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been absolutely no local interest. If you asked 10
people, six of them wouldn't even know who was playing,'' Simon
said. ``You need two unbeatens and it helps if they are titans, the
last of the unbeatens. But neither of them can be from Florida
because those schools are the weakest at sending people.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon said he sold about 800 tickets for the 1996 Fiesta Bowl
national championship game between Nebraska and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those tickets bottomed out at about $225 apiece. But that had
everything to do with the fan interest from Nebraska and little to
do with Florida,'' Simon said.
</P>
<P>
   But there are no Cornhuskers this time around. Fettman, however,
is holding out hope that he can at least score one major deal. He
said he has a luxury skybox with 18 seats on the 50-yard line that
he is trying to sell for $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'll have to parcel it up to small groups and reduce the
price,'' Fettman said with a moan. ``Yeah, that's probably going to
be what happens.'' &QL; 
Mark Shaffer can be reached at mark.shaffer(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
