<HEADER>
A5109 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDINALS-PLUMMER     01-02 1274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-PLUMMER-IMAGE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAKEMANIA REACHES PEAK  
 WITH HIS PAST BEHIND HIM, QB'S STOCK SOARS WITH FANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GINTONIO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can he walk on water? Leap over buildings? Coax rain out of a
dry sky?
</P>
<P>
   In the eyes of Cardinals fans, the real question is, What
``can't'' Jake Plummer do?
</P>
<P>
   In less than two seasons as the team's quarterback, he has
established himself as the most popular athlete in the Valley. The
Snake has enchanted the populace with scrambles, dives, timely pass
completions and comebacks, beating almost impossible odds. And
don't forget that staggering contract.
</P>
<P>
   The Jake Plummer Show has been the hottest ticket in town.
Teammates and opponents sing his praises. Analysts gush; fans are
ecstatic; charitable causes are grateful for his support. The media
can't get enough of him. During the past week, he has been
virtually off-limits for daily interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer's success has been parlayed into a huge new deal: a $15
million signing bonus, the largest in NFL history, as part of a
four-year contract extension worth $29.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the contract and his penchant for last-minute heroics,
from his days as ASU's Rose Bowl quarterback to the present, he
remains refreshingly down to earth. He exudes youthful earnestness.
Plummer says that cordial relations with fans will be an easy chore
if they recognize that he can't always spend as much time with them
as they would like. He also said he ``won't be a jerk and tell
people to get out my face.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy the support around the Valley,'' said Plummer, who
also talked about the flip side, that it's nice sometimes to be
treated like the average Joe. He laughed as he recalled going this
week to see the movie ``Patch Adams,'' pulling a baseball hat over
his eyes and not being recognized.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer has done more than lead the Cardinals to the National
Football League playoffs for the first time since their arrival in
Arizona. He has virtually erased the ghosts of indiscretions past.
</P>
<P>
   It was only a couple of years ago that Plummer was embroiled in
a bitter battle over his conduct in a Tempe nightclub. The passage
of time, helped no doubt by on-field success, has all but
obliterated the public's memory of the incident.
</P>
<P>
   He was accused of groping the women _ something he said he
didn't do _ but he did admit that he ``was wrong'' to kick a woman
outside the club.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer doesn't talk about the incident, and his teammates are
more interested in the present.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leadership,'' offensive teammate Lomas Brown said. ``That's
the thing about Jake. It's his leadership qualities even more than
his athletic ability. He has a knack for leading this team in the
last few seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, one of the most respected players in the NFL, said that,
to his knowledge, no one on the team has ever brought up Club Rio.
</P>
<P>
   From all indications, the March 23, 1997, incident is ancient
history in almost every corner. Even the lawyer for three of the
four women involved is happy to see Plummer doing well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't speak for the clients, I haven't talked to them about
that, but I can say, generally, that he is a positive image for the
community,'' attorney Ed Novak said. ``He presents himself very
well both in the media spotlight and out of the media spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to hope that his actions at Club Rio were
aberrant behavior, and as time goes on my feeling about it will
probably be confirmed.''
</P>
<P>
   Plummer pleaded no contest to disorderly conduct charges,
receiving two years' probation, rather than fight the felony sex
abuse charges.
</P>
<P>
   Novak said the women involved won't talk about the case, saying
they wanted closure. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
`Rallying the city'
</P>
<P>
   The Jake frenzy is contagious, and most Cardinals fans,
including Chris Ferrara of Phoenix, are caught up in it. Plummer's
No. 16 is the most popular sports jersey in town, and it's a tossup
as to what's harder to find, the jersey on a store rack or a
Plummer detractor.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``This could be the start of a dynasty,'' Ferrara said. ``Jake
could be another (John) Elway or (Dan) Marino. His comebacks have
been awesome. His success has overshadowed anything bad that
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Another fan, Jim Greenhalgh of Paradise Valley, said Plummer's
attitude is a big thing in his favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seems nonchalant about the big contract,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pulled this team together. His past? It never comes to
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   It may be hard to find a Plummer detractor, but it's not
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (the Club Rio incident) definitely colors my perception of
him,'' said Vicky Frechette of Phoenix. ``In general, and I'm not
necessarily talking about Plummer, I'm disgusted with the behavior
of a lot of athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   Garth Jax, the Cardinals NFL program/community outreach
coordinator and a former linebacker for the team, thinks Plummer is
light-years removed from Club Rio.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has done his penance,'' Jax said. ``It's a testament to his
character, and he has been rewarded (with a new contract). He's not
a taker; he's a giver. He's the total package and a hero to a lot
of kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's rallying more than this ballclub. He's rallying this
city.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Endorsements aplenty
</P>
<P>
   During the Chargers-Cardinals game, a commercial promoting
Plummer was shown on Channel 5 (KPHO). Cutouts of the quarterback
decorate the aisles at some Bashas' stores, in place to help
promote the sale of cancer cards from Phoenix Children's Hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer's agent, Leigh Steinberg, represents many high-profile
players and also puts emphasis on developing his clients' images.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our philosophy is to take it slowly at first,'' said Jamey
Crimmins, the director of athlete services for Integrated Sports
International, the group that handles off-field activities for the
athletes it represents.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has endorsement-related deals now with Nike and Logo
Athletics, and locally with Sprint. We want to develop his
community involvement.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, continued on-field success will lead to more
opportunities down the road.
</P>
<P>
   Crimmins said big contracts don't necessarily lead to fat
endorsement deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not because of his contract; it's his play,'' Crimmins
said. ``He's one of the most exciting players in the league. We
have been getting more calls lately about him.''
</P>
<P>
   One huge plus in Plummer's favor on the endorsement trail is his
induction into the NFL Quarterbacks Club.
</P>
<P>
   The only method of gaining entrance into the elite group is a
yearly vote of peers. Crimmins said that for a player in the early
stages of his career, being a member of the club is ``quite an
honor.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
TD for charity
</P>
<P>
   Plummer has been involved in a number of charitable ventures in
the area in the past two seasons, and every appearance has served
to solidify and multiply his fan base.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer will contribute $250,000 to Cardinals owner Bill
Bidwill's favorite charity, and he plans to set up a scholarship at
his old high school in Boise, Idaho, and to begin a rebuilding of
the athletic facilities there. He also will create an endowment at
ASU that will support a student each year, and the newly created
Plummer Foundation will deal with ill and abused children and
assist in funding for research into Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt about it, he has been great for that team and great
for this community,'' attorney Novak said.
</P>
<P>
   Is he rooting for his former courtroom adversary?
</P>
<P>
   ``As for separating my representation, yes, I am a Plummer
fan,'' Novak said. ``I like the guy. I think he's a decent enough
guy.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
