<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 01:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5112 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-FIESTA-FLORIDASTA     01-02 0484
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-FLORIDA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEMINOLES LINEMEN BULK UP ON ORDERS 
</HEADLINE>
 STATE-OFFENSIVE LINE-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the end of last season, Florida State's returning offensive
linemen were given a mandate: Become bigger and stronger.
</P>
<P>
   The Seminoles had been pushed around in the final regular season
game in 1997, a 32-29 loss to Florida, and weren't able to run the
ball when they needed.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive guard Jason Whitaker did his part, gaining 36 pounds
up to 306. His colleagues did the same, gaining anywhere from 15 to
30 pounds. The line averages about 6 feet 5 { and 305 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Whitaker understands the need for the extra weight, but lugging
it around isn't so pleasant, even when you are 6-5.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a perfect world, I'd play at 225 pounds,'' Whitaker said.
``Three hundred pounds wears and tears on the body. It's just not
healthy in everyday life.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitaker was feeling the effects Monday when the offensive
linemen ran ``gassers'' at the conclusion of practice. After
completing the required 16, Whitaker collapsed face down on the
practice field at Mountain Pointe High School.
</P>
<P>
   His mom would not have been happy. When Whitaker went away to
school, she told her son not to bulk up to 300 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her, `Momma, I'm going to revolutionize the offensive
line position. I'll be an All-American at 245 pounds.' All I was
was an All-American rag doll.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitaker, a junior, is the dean of the starting offensive
linemen. Starting tackles Ross Brannon and Tarlos Thomas, guard
Jerry Carmichael and center Jarad Moon are sophomores. All of the
backups are sophomores except for center Eric Thomas, a junior.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are still feeling their way around a little bit,'' said
offensive coordinator Mark Richt.
</P>
<P>
   This line should be a dominating group for years to come, and a
few of them will be pushed next year by some impressive freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we signed the best class we've ever signed up front
last year,'' Richt said. ``I think we have five potentially great
college football players.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, however, has seen growing pains. The Seminoles have
yielded 38 sacks, twice as many as last year. Part of the reason
for the increase was quarterback Chris Weinke, an accurate passer
who is not known for his mobility.
</P>
<P>
   Weinke is injured and his replacement, Marcus Outzen, is more
mobile. Whitaker said the offensive line still has to protect
better Monday against Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had two quarterbacks (Weinke and Dan Kendra) hurt in the
same year, and we gave up a school record for sacks. We're doing
well, I guess,'' Whitaker said when asked to assess the line's
performance. The inconsistency is not unexpected, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes when you get baptized, the preacher might hold you
under the water a little more than you'd like,'' Whitaker said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-02-99 0143EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
