r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-FIESTA-BOWDENSONS     01-02 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-BOWDEN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TERRY BOWDEN LYING LOW  
 EX-AUBURN COACH REFLECTS ON JOB, FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
 SONS-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   While his former colleagues have been busy coaching in bowl
games or racking up frequent-flyer points while recruiting, Terry
Bowden has not just been sitting idly at his Auburn, Ala., home.
</P>
<P>
   He's been on a field trip with a second-grade class, attended
PTA meetings, watched youth basketball and soccer games, visited
the mall.
</P>
<P>
   And now he's in the Valley, watching his father, Bobby Bowden,
prepare his second-ranked Florida State football team to play No. 1
Tennessee in the Fiesta Bowl on Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is life after playing football, and there is life after
coaching football,'' said Terry Bowden, 42, who has six children,
including five under the age of 9.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden has had plenty of time to spend with his kids since
midseason, when he resigned as Auburn's head coach when it became
apparent to him that he would be fired at the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden is in no hurry to return to coaching and plans to take
the next year off. He probably will spend part of it working in
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still rehashing some old things and healing some old
wounds,`` Bowden said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bowden family has endured all the vagaries of the collegiate
coaching profession this season, from Terry's midseason resignation
to his older brother Tommy, 44, coaching Tulane to an undefeated
season, then leaving before its Liberty Bowl game to take the head
coaching job at Clemson.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the senior Bowden, 69, enjoyed a magical end to the
season when two teams ranked ahead of the Seminoles lost on the
last weekend, placing Florida State in the Fiesta Bowl. Another of
his sons, Jeff, coaches the receivers at Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am so proud of Tommy, and he is so deserving,'' Terry said.
``I think it gives you great perspective about this business.''
</P>
<P>
   When Terry arrived at Auburn, Tommy was under considerable heat
as Pat Dye's offensive coordinator. Now, Terry can't help but smile
at Tommy's climb to prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this business, you have to handle the adversity. I
considered this year _ when we had to go through six centers _ as
that year that every coach has to go through, when you're tested.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry Bowden watched his brother's news conference when he was
hired at Clemson and thought back to when he was hired at Auburn.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made the statement that he swaggered up to the podium
with incredible confidence,'' Terry said. ``I said, `That's Tommy
swaggering?' I see a little bit of me in him when I seem him doing
interviews.''
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, Bobby Bowden said, a school would stick with a
coach through tough times. That's how he survived at West Virginia,
despite going 4-7 in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not everybody wins all the time,'' Terry Bowden said. ``My
dad's had one national championship in his life and never been
undefeated at the end of the season in his life. But it (the
possibility of being fired) is a given going in. If you say, `Gee I
didn't expect this,' well, what are you, an idiot or something? If
you go into the business and rise to level of head coach at a major
Division I school, you have to be in a vacuum to not know there is
a lot of pressure and instability.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
