<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 01:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5115 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-FIESTA-TENNESSEE-     01-02 1209
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-TENNESSEE-FULMER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNHERALDED FULMER HAS HARD TIME BEING NOTICED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   More than two decades ago, Phillip Fulmer turned to his
roommate, John Stucky, and reflected on the greatness of
Tennessee's football program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd really like to be the head coach there some day,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer was an anonymous assistant at Wichita State at the time,
and like hundreds of anonymous assistants, he longed for a top job
at a big-time program. He got it, and today he has the Volunteers
on the verge of a national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Has anyone noticed?
</P>
<P>
   ``Which one's Fulmer?'' a Fiesta Bowl volunteer whispered
Thursday at media day festivities for Monday's national title game.
</P>
<P>
   Which one, indeed. For all the 48-year-old has accomplished at
Tennessee _ and there has been plenty _ few could pick him out of a
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   It borders on bizarre. He has coached Tennessee to four
consecutive top-10 finishes and sports the best career winning
percentage (.857) in college football, but all many seemed to care
about was his five-game losing streak to the Florida Gators, which,
mercifully, ended this year.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, even though the Volunteers won the Southeastern
Conference championship, Georgia Coach Jim Donnan beat out Fulmer
for SEC Coach of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was disappointing to me because I think Coach Fulmer
deserved it,'' linebacker Raynoch Thompson said. ``He doesn't get
the national hype from a coaching standpoint that he deserves.''
</P>
<P>
   And although Fulmer's team finished 12-0 this year, the
Volunteers are five-point underdogs to Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Athletic Director Doug) Dickey tells me all the time, `If you
can lay your head on the pillow at night and know you've done the
very best that you can do, that's all you can do,' '' Fulmer said.
``I don't worry about it. I don't read papers and don't listen to
talk shows. I surround myself with my friends who I can tell to
shut up if I need to.''
</P>
<P>
   If there were questions about his coaching ability, they were
put to rest this season. The Volunteers went undefeated, despite
having to groom a new quarterback, losing a star running back for
two-thirds of the season and needing to pull out four victories in
the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   One can't help but wonder if the previous presence of star
quarterback Peyton Manning hurt the perception of Fulmer. Sometimes
great players make things look too easy, and it didn't help matters
that the Volunteers couldn't beat Florida during Manning's tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer appears to have found peace, personally and
professionally, this season.
</P>
<P>
   He committed himself to being at home Wednesday and Thursday
evenings during the football season, something he hasn't done in
years. For the most part, he is an 18-hour, seven-day-a-week guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes we'd be lucky to get a little piece of him after a
football game,'' his wife, Vicky, said. ``He'd be up and gone
Sunday morning, and we literally wouldn't see him until Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, I think he realized his girls (Courtney, 15;
Brittany, 13; Allison, 12) aren't going to be in the house that
much longer. I think he realized he and I hadn't been touching base
that much through the last couple years and that we needed to work
on our relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Since taking over in 1992, he's made it a point of having his
three daughters involved in as much of his football life as
possible. One of his daughters can always be spotted working as a
ball girl during games.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the idea was met with resistance by Tennessee's
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was something I really pushed for because I felt like
when a coach has sons, they're at practice, they're in the locker
room, they're really a part of their dad's profession,'' Vicky
Fulmer said. ``I really saw my girls getting pushed away. College
football is a male's world. I was adamant that I wasn't going to
get left behind, and I wasn't going to let my children get pushed
away.''
</P>
<P>
   Some feared the girls could get hurt or hear offensive language.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've probably heard worse from me,'' she said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Not many pejoratives can be heard from Phillip Fulmer's mouth.
His greatest strength, those around him say, is his poise, which
has allowed him to weather the occasional storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Levelheadedness is not a hard thing for me,'' Fulmer said.
</P>
<P>
   He does have his moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day, you might catch him walking down the hallway, and he
may come up to you and joke with you and laugh with you and
stuff,'' linebacker Steve Johnson said. ``And other days he's
walking down the hallway and he has that look on his face, and you
know to watch out and not step on his toes.''
</P>
<P>
   Another trait that has served him well is his work ethic.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not going to have a `t' that's not crossed and an `i'
that's not dotted,'' defensive coordinator John Chavis said. ``It's
just not going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer came to Tennessee in 1968 as an offensive lineman out of
Franklin County High School in Winchester, Tenn. After his playing
career in Knoxville and a brief apprenticeship as a graduate
assistant, he moved on to assistant stints at Wichita State,
Vanderbilt and back at Tennessee in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   He took over the top job in 1992, replacing Johnny Majors in a
messy scene.
</P>
<P>
   After Majors underwent quintuple-bypass heart surgery, Fulmer,
then the offensive coordinator, led the team to a 4-0 start. When
Majors returned, the Volunteers lost three of their next five
games, and some critics suggested he had returned too quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Majors said Tennessee then reneged on a promise to extend his
contract, and he quit before being shown the door.
</P>
<P>
   The event put a strain on Fulmer's relationship with Majors, who
perceived his assistant as opportunistic. When asked several years
later about Fulmer, Majors said, ``I don't have anything to say
about that guy.'' He could not be reached for comment this week.
</P>
<P>
   That got Fulmer off to a rocky start in some eyes, even though
he was successful immediately _ 10-2 in his first full season. He's
managed 10 wins in five of six seasons, but some fans couldn't get
past the losses to Florida from 1993 through 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it was frustrating to me personally, but I didn't
let it play over into the football team,'' Fulmer said. ``I take
what some disgruntled fans may have to say with a grain of salt
because those are the same people who stand at the front of the
line when you're doing well.''
</P>
<P>
   He has quieted the critics this season and gained recognition,
though he's up for a tough comparison this week against Florida
State's colorful Bobby Bowden.
</P>
<P>
   His assistants insist Fulmer is funnier than most think. Vicky,
who has spent a little time with the Bowdens, ventures that
``Phillip's personality and Bobby Bowden's personality are very
much the same. He just doesn't allow (the media) to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   If the lack of recognition bothers Fulmer, he doesn't let on.
</P>
<P>
   There may be no more telling trait about Fulmer then a sign that
hangs in the locker room at the Neyland-Thompson Sports Center:
``It's amazing what you can accomplish when nobody cares who gets
the credit.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
