<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 01:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5116 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-FIESTA-FLORIDASTA     01-02 1574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-FLORIDA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT 69, COLORFUL BOWDEN WANTS TO BUILD ON LEGEND 
</HEADLINE>
 STATE-BOWDEN-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reaching the status of legend in the college coaching profession
can be tricky. You usually don't get there until retirement age,
and once you're there, everyone wants to know how long you plan on
staying.
</P>
<P>
   It's a familiar question for Florida State's Bobby Bowden, who
at 69 has accomplished nearly everything a coach can. Among active
coaches, he's second to Penn State's Joe Paterno in victories and
bowl victories. His Seminoles teams have won 10 or more games for
12 straight years and finished the season ranked no lower than
fourth for the past 11 years, not counting this one. And Bowden can
earn his second national championship if No. 2 Florida State beats
No. 1 Tennessee Monday in the Fiesta Bowl at Sun Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   So why not retire, play golf in the mornings, take naps in the
afternoon and make it home most nights in time to eat supper with
your wife, Ann?
</P>
<P>
   Why not travel to Europe and visit all those World War II
landmarks, the places that captured your imagination when you were
13, bedridden with illness and following the war through the radio
in your home in Birmingham, Ala.?
</P>
<P>
   Well, there's a bunch of dadgum reasons, as Bowden would tell
you. He already plays golf every day for three months a year, April
through June. Even during football season, he'll take a nap most
every day. He does make it home most nights in time for supper, and
football hasn't stopped him from traveling.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, he still loves the feeling of taking a bunch of
``boys,'' as he calls them, and molding them into a team that wins.
All that touchy, feely stuff wouldn't cut it if his boys lost
consistently.
</P>
<P>
   ``The losses just kill me,'' Bowden said. ``I'd rather go 11-1,
11-1, 11-1, 11-1 than be 12-0, 7-4, 12-0, 6-5. If I lose four
games, I'm leaving. Of course, if we start 0-4 next year, I'm
changing that statement.''
</P>
<P>
   What might drive Bowden more than the thrill of winning is his
hatred of losing. He was that way even when he played at Woodlawn
High in Birmingham and in college at Howard, which later became
Samford University.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing else about the profession bothers him much, not the
expectations of fans, the pressure of keeping the program at the
highest level, not even Florida Coach Steve Spurrier's occasional
snide remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think, `You must can't stand him,' '' Bowden said.
``But I kind of enjoy being around him. People don't bother me.
Losing games is something I just hate. It's a feeling that I
betrayed everybody. That nobody likes me anymore. It's an
inferiority problem, like people are ashamed of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Among his generation, Bowden is one of the sport's few remaining
icons. Paterno and BYU's LaVell Edwards are among his few remaining
contemporaries. Nebraska's Tom Osborne, Iowa's Hayden Fry and
Grambling's Eddie Robinson have all retired in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden, too, thought he would be out of the profession by now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember when I was coaching at West Virginia when (Texas
Coach) Darrell Royal and (Arkansas) Coach Frank Broyles resigned
without a month of each other,'' Bowden said. ``They were 53 and I
remember thinking, `I guess when I am that old, I'll retire, too.'
''
</P>
<P>
   But here Bowden is, at 69, about to conclude his 33rd year as a
Division I head coach, his 46th overall, and not about to retire.
``I'm like the guy who said he wanted to retire one day before he
died,'' Bowden said.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Bowden has heard that line from his father before and
doesn't believe it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you know my dad, he's not going to die the day he gets off
the football field,'' said Terry, the former Auburn coach. ``He
loves coaching, but he loves playing golf. For him, I guarantee
there is going to be enjoyment when he gets through.''
</P>
<P>
   Few coaches run a program quite the way Bowden does. He has a
loyal staff and has endured very little turnover in recent years _
only one assistant since the 1993 championship season. Three
coaches have been with him for more than 10 years, including two
who have been at Florida State for more than 20.
</P>
<P>
   The reasoning is that being an assistant at Florida State is
better than many head coaching jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main reason is Coach Bowden,'' said offensive coordinator
Mark Richt.
</P>
<P>
   The staff's experience and familiarity with Bowden's
philosophies allow him to operate more as a CEO. He gave up
play-calling in the early '90s, when the outside demands on his
time became too great, and no longer watches hours of tape on
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   He can afford to take a nap most every afternoon and make it
home at a decent time most every evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think football has changed,'' said Bowden, in his 23rd
season at Florida State. ``It's gotten more scientific. When I
began to slip away from it (play-calling) was when (quarterback)
Charlie Ward was here and we were using the no-huddle. You simply
can't call that from the sideline. It was a different game all of a
sudden.''
</P>
<P>
   The time Bowden spends in game preparation has been cut back in
the past decade. Today, Bowden will look at tape of an opponent's
kicking game, to see if he can find an advantage there. And he'll
watch one tape of the opponent's offense as a gauge of how
productive his offense will have to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we have to score 28? Do we have to score 40? Will 18 do it?
That's what I'm looking for,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He watches tape of an opponent's defense and make suggestions to
Richt and other coaches, who do the brunt of the preparation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have time,'' Bowden said. ``I used to. Now, I have to
go here, go there, do this and do that. Head coaches don't have
time for that anymore unless they are somebody who just wants to
shut everything else down.''`
</P>
<P>
   That's never been Bowden's way. He doesn't lock himself in his
office, emerging only when forced to attend weekly press
conferences. Bowden has those other interests, especially and World
War II history. He became interested in the war as a kid and can
still remember the day Germany invaded Poland.
</P>
<P>
   He and his family were taking a trip in a borrowed '37 Ford to a
river outside Birmingham when they saw someone selling ``Extra''
editions of a newspaper. The picture on the front captivated
Bowden.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was five German soldiers running across a field with hand
grenades,'' he said. ``As a 9 year old, that caught my eye.``
</P>
<P>
   Bowden turned 13 in 1943 and spent six months of that year
bedridden because of rheumatic fever. He passed the time by
listening to radio reports about the war, imagining what armies
were where, and anticipating what an general's next move might be.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Generals) have a lot of different makeups, and you can relate
it to coaching,'' he said. ``There are some generals who have the
virtue of audacity. They'd do things you wouldn't think they would
possibly do. Patton and Rommel were like that. Others were very
passive or were defensive, they would sit back and dig in.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden used to be audacious. He earned a reputation at Florida
State for being a gambler, a coach willing to try darn near
anything, anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we weren't winning in those days,'' he said. ``And I'd do
anything to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden still insists that his coaches put a few ``barnyard
plays'' in every game plan, but he doesn't use them nearly as much.
``When you're winning, you don't call them,'' he said. ``Now you
have good players and if you go out there and play the best you can
play, don't make mistakes, you're probably going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden hasn't changed much else about his style in recent years,
however. He still runs a program that's as open and accessible as
any in the country. He loves bantering with reporters, telling
stories and isn't afraid to speak his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's so brutally honest and forthright,'' said Wayne Hogan,
the former sports information director at Florida State and now the
athletic director at Montana. ``He'll take people aback.''
</P>
<P>
   One year in the late 1980s, Hogan said, Florida State was
preparing to play Miami. Several writers from across the country
were in Tallahassee, so Hogan set up an interview with Bowden. When
the writers walked into Bowden's office, the head coach had his
bare feet up on his desk and was having his hair cut and eating a
salad at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Y'all don't mind, do you?'' Bowden asked.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, the writers playfully accused Hogan of setting it all
up. ``No, that's just him,'' Hogan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He makes time for everybody, not just the media,'' Hogan said.
``I saw fans wander in his office during the busiest times, and
he'd sit down and talk to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Devoutly religious, Bowden travels throughout the South speaking
at churches. He is a captivating speaker who could make what he ate
for breakfast sound exciting. (``Y'all see this grapefruit? Why, it
started out as just a blossom.'')
</P>
<P>
   And while he enjoys all those other parts of his life, he's not
quite ready to give up the challenges of coaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't reached the point of satisfaction yet,'' Bowden
said. ``As long as I'm coaching and have another game to play, I
can't reach the point of satisfaction. When I retire, I'll either
be satisfied or not. Right now, there is another game and another
year. If I'm healthy, I want to coach that year.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-02-99 0147EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
