<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 01:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5117 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BICKLEY_COLUMN-BI     01-02 1254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BICKLEY_COLUMN-BIDWILL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE NEGATIVE IMAGE, BIDWILL ON RIGHT TRACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He is not what you expect, and very little of what you think.
</P>
<P>
   He is shy, untrusting, terrible in front of a camera.
</P>
<P>
   He tells a lot of jokes, the kind that are so unfunny they make
you laugh.
</P>
<P>
   He spends most of his time floating in the past, and if he
forgets your name, don't worry. There are probably days when he
forgets his own.
</P>
<P>
   But he is not the devil, no money-grubbing villain, nowhere near
the image that has shadowed him for the past 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   He is not a bad person. Rather, a very good person who happened
to be a very bad owner. But that is changing.
</P>
<P>
   And the more you're around Bill Bidwill, the more likable he
becomes. In the eccentric, round-the-bend uncle kind of way.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Mr. Bidwill is a little strange. But aren't we all?
</P>
<P>
   Bidwill is an owner. He inherited his team. He moved his team.
And that trifecta will get you scorned every time.
</P>
<P>
   But just as there is a shroud of privacy smothering his
personality, there is a huge gap between myth and reality.
</P>
<P>
   The image: He is a miser. Legendary for his cheapness. Moths
terrorize his wallet.
</P>
<P>
   The truth: Not since he moved to Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The image: He doesn't want to win.
</P>
<P>
   The truth: Until recently, he didn't know how.
</P>
<P>
   The image: He is cold and distant, pleasant as a snake.
</P>
<P>
   The truth: He is extremely suspicious of strangers, downright
charming among friends. But even if he knows you, he might walk
right by you without acknowledging a hello.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fans will always blame the owners for everything,'' said Larry
Wilson, former Cardinals player, current Cardinals executive.
``It's not only in Arizona. Pick up any newspaper in any city
across America and you're reading about the rottenest guy in town _
the owner. But Mr. B. has been maligned by the best of them, and I
don't think it's right.''
</P>
<P>
   It all started in St. Louis, a place where football has its
place, where there once existed, in order, the Cardinals and the
football Cardinals. A reputation was born, one that Bidwill claims
started with a couple of writers and snowballed.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happened, here's the bottom line with Bill Bidwill and
why the shadow will always exist: He simply doesn't have the
communication skills to spin opinion. Or the energy. Or the desire.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't like a lot of attention,'' said his son, Michael.
``Should he be criticized for that?''
</P>
<P>
   Bidwill is asked if he cares about his legacy. He flatly says
no.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all show business now,'' he said. ``I grew up in a
different era. When it was a sport. People want to hear from the
players, from the coaches, and around draft time, maybe from the
scouts. But they don't care what I have to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to change myself. I'm not going to self-promote
myself. I'm not going to be something I'm not.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Cardinals prepare for their first playoff game since
arriving in the Valley, Bidwill is enjoying a wave of good
publicity. But there are 11 years of history to be overcome.
</P>
<P>
   I tell the son that his father doesn't care about his legacy. I
ask if he does, and the son stares ahead, past the practice field,
into dreamland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ya' know, my father is a very good family man, and I love my
father,'' he said. ``I want people to like him. I'd like him to be
a very well-liked man, and all the thing that go along with
that.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   There are defining moments in everyone's life. Things that
happen that stay with you forever, shaping and molding the nuances
of your personality.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bidwill was 30 years old when he found out he was adopted.
Found out his given name was really Robert. Found out that his
brother, Charles a.k.a Stormy, wasn't really his brother. That both
had come from different families.
</P>
<P>
   He found this out after both his parents _ or at least who he
thought where is parents _ were dead. And he found out in a
courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   The story in brief: Two years after Charles Bidwill died in
1947, Violet Bidwill remarried a man named Walter Wolfner. When
Violet died in 1962, she bequeathed 82 percent of Cardinals stock
to her two boys, which didn't go over well with Mr. Wolfner.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfner took the matter to court on the grounds that boys had
misrepresented themselves at an heirship hearing, that neither had
told the probate judge they were adopted.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, they had no clue.
</P>
<P>
   The case crawled along for three years until they settled out of
court.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it can be sunny on the outside while a hurricane brews
within. Internal scars are always impossible to gauge. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   There is another misgiving about Bidwill, and it's all about
motive.
</P>
<P>
   He has made some bad decisions. He listened to bad advice when
he first came to the Valley, setting the highest ticket prices in
the NFL. He is resistant to change, which is bad. He's surrounded
himself with bad people. And he is loyal to a fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, but how can you call loyalty a fault?'' Wilson asked.
</P>
<P>
   When you're too tolerant of failure, that's how. But Bidwill is
changing, fast and for the better.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, the Cardinals would never have thought to stage two
fan festivals, as they did this past week. America West reportedly
floated the idea of a Cardinals plane past the old man a few years
ago, and he wouldn't budge. That plane, painted in brilliant red
and featuring the logo, flew over Sun Devil Stadium last week.
</P>
<P>
   Bidwill is a better owner because he's less of an owner, someone
who has finally surrounded himself with the right people. And he's
listening more and more to the two people with vision _ player
personnel boss Bob Ferguson and his son Michael.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have grown by releasing a lot of control, by
listening to other people,'' Bidwill said. ``I've allowed myself to
be overruled by people in the organization when they have strong
arguments for something. Sometimes I'm right, and sometimes I'm
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   It takes a big man to relinquish control, especially when this
team is his life.
</P>
<P>
   Ask him what he does for fun and he responds by telling you what
he doesn't do (golf). He likes to relax at home. He goes to bed
early. He loves the History Channel and old movies and ice cream,
except ``the three-scoop deal is a thing of the past.'' Oh, and he
did not sleep with the game ball from last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a history major, and he is a World War II naval buff,''
Michael said. ``He served in the Navy, and if you go to his house,
he has like every book written, every ``Time/Life'' series. A real
history buff.''
</P>
<P>
   Anything else?
</P>
<P>
   ``He likes to work here, run this team,'' Michael said. ``This
is his life. And he loves to tell stories about the old days. I
thought I'd heard every one of them until I started working with
him every day.''
</P>
<P>
   What you won't hear is chest-thumping over the contributions he
makes to charity. Or crying over an explicit promise for a new
stadium that crumbled along with the old guard shortly after he
arrived. Or chirping for a new dome while telling you how much
money he's spent on prototypes and planning. That is all good
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   You won't hear it because, somewhere along the way, Bill Bidwill
gave up. He quit trying to be liked, convinced himself not to care.
And he gave up the battle of perception, a battle he was never
qualified to win. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at dan.bickley(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
