</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOO LATE, UCLA DEFENSE SHOWS HEART
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA _ UCLA went into the Rose Bowl with the most ridiculed
defense since Dan White and his Twinkies. The Bruins had an image
to restore after giving up 679 yards and 49 points to Miami in the
regular-season loss that kept them out of the national-championship
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defense was !ital!maligned!off!,'' head coach Bob Toledo
said, though he didn't say he thought it was undeserved.
</P>
<P>
   Under the circumstances, the Bruins did almost everything wrong
in the first half of their 38-31 loss to Wisconsin on Friday: They
missed tackles. They let the Badgers' 1,065-pound offensive line
push them around. And they watched (exactly the right word) as
tailback Ron Dayne set out on a pace to break Charles White's Rose
Bowl rushing record.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Bruins defense did one last thing wrong: In the second
half, when its best player was injured and out of the game, when it
had undergone so many lineup changes you'd think Steve Lavin was
coaching football, when fans might finally have started to feel
sorry for the whole hapless lot, the defense came up with its best
performance literally in weeks.
</P>
<P>
   See, the Bruins had it in them all along.
</P>
<P>
   The thought of which caused any self-respecting wise guy on the
blue-and-gold side of the stadium to ask, ``Where was this
rock-solid defense when we needed it?''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA defensive coordinator Nick Aliotti is asking himself the
same thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``(I) just yelled at 'em louder, I guess,'' Aliotti said later,
sounding more bewildered than he would have been if the defense had
continued to fail. ``They really bowed their necks a little bit in
the second half. For whatever reason, the guys responded a little
better.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Bruins' first defensive series of the second half, in
which Wisconsin drove 89 yards for a 22-yard Dayne touchdown and
took a 10-point lead, they played 24{ minutes of shutout ball. Not
only that, but Dayne didn't get the record, finishing with 246, one
short of White's 1980 performance.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, it was the Bruins' offense that gave up the last,
crushing Wisconsin touchdown on a fourth-quarter interception
return.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really ironic _ everybody criticized our defense, but it
was the offense that couldn't get it done when it had to,''
linebacker Brendon Ayanbadejo said in a jibe that stirred the
embers of a locker-room civil war. ``The defense went out on a
positive note.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the theme of the evening for the defensive players,
especially the many young ones who, unlike the senior Ayanbadejo,
must work up some optimism for next season.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore cornerback Marques Anderson: ``This is something to
build on. We're a young defense that you can expect to get
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Freshman linebacker Santi Hall: ``We can take some good things
out of it and say the defense can do the job when it has to.''
</P>
<P>
   Heartwarming, huh?
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the young Bruins attributed their 24{-minute
revival less to substitutions or tactical changes than to a
collective summoning of will.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman nose guard Ken Kocher: ``To me it just seemed like we
came out and played tougher.''
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore defensive end Kenyon Coleman: ``We didn't want to
repeat the Miami game, so we went in and strapped it on. We came in
(to the locker room at halftime) and said, `Hey, fellas, we've got
to walk the walk.'''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine being Aliotti, wondering where the Bruins might have
been today, or where they might have been Monday when the Fiesta
Bowl settles the national title, if the defense had decided to walk
the walk in Miami on Dec. 5.
</P>
<P>
   That they did their best walking (since the victory over USC six
weeks ago) after star safety Larry Atkins hobbled to the sideline
with a knee sprain only magnified Aliotti's exasperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to play anybody that could give us effort,''
Aliotti said of his frequent substitutions, which often put three
true freshmen on the field.
</P>
<P>
   So this is the question: Do we permit the Bruins to feel good
about their too-little, too-late defensive show and what it
promises for 1999? Or slam them for the listless game-and-a-half
that preceded it?
</P>
<P>
   We'll side with Aliotti on this one when he says: ``Unless we
get a lot tougher, a lot more physical, and learn how to bow our
necks, it's not going to be much better than it was this year.
There is some talent there. But returning nine guys doesn't mean
you'll be good unless those nine guys are good.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
