<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 01:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5121 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-McNOWN-LBPT     01-02 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-McNOWN-LBPT </SLUG>
 
LAST DANCE FOR McNOWN 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA _ In this what-have-you-done-for-me-lately world, where
one day you're the toast of the town and the next day you're just
toast, the last impression is often the lasting impression.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Wayne Cook, the UCLA quarterback whose ended his career
in the Rose Bowl loss of 1994.
</P>
<P>
   It is ironic then that the career of Cade McNown, the most
accomplished quarterback in UCLA history, came to an end that was
most un-McNownlike. That is to say that the Bruins' money player
came up a few coins short.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers were fine for McNown --- his 390 yards passing were
the fourth most in Rose Bowl history --- but as the numbers have
rarely defined his successes, they didn't reveal his shortcomings
Friday in a 38-31 loss to Wisconsin in the 85th Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The clutch, game-turning plays that McNown has made his
signature in his four years were absent --- or worse yet, were made
in Wisconsin's favor.
</P>
<P>
   The one interception he threw was returned 46 yards for a
touchdown by Jamar Fletcher early in the fourth quarter. A mixup
with tailback DeShaun Foster resulted in the Bruins fumbling away
the ball on first-and-goal at the Wisconsin 6 midway in the third.
The Wisconsin crowd forced him to burn timeouts twice in the second
half.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with the Bruins perched at midfield and trailing by a
touchdown with nearly two minutes left, they failed to even gain a
first down. On fourth down, with the Bruins season in his hands,
McNown was sacked by Wendell Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   As the Badgers, after running out the clock, stormed the field
and celebrated at the north end of the Rose Bowl, McNown, his
helmet in his hand, walked stone-faced and purposefully toward the
Bruins' locker room at the south end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to lose,'' he said later outside the UCLA locker room.
``For it to turn out this way is frustrating. The last couple of
games have been disappointing. I wish we could have played a little
better, but sometimes things aren't going to go your way.''
</P>
<P>
   McNown threw 1,250 passes in his career and the first one he'd
like back is one he floated down the right sideline to Foster.
Fletcher trailed Foster but he had help over the top from safety
Jason Doering.
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher simply caught the underthrown ball and raced down the
sideline untouched to put Wisconsin ahead, 38-28, with 14:08 to
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bad decision in retrospect,'' said McNown. ``I
shouldn't have thrown the ball. I kind of thought (Foster) would
come back. He didn't do that, but he's not wrong for not doing
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as costly was the fumble at the goal line. The Bruins,
trailing 31-21, were planted at the Wisconsin 6 after McNown's
44-yard bomb to Danny Farmer.
</P>
<P>
   The Wisconsin crowd at the north end was so loud it forced
McNown to call timeout. The play that was called was changed twice,
but Foster and several others didn't hear the second change.
</P>
<P>
   McNown tossed the ball to Foster, but the freshman was expecting
a handoff. The ball hit him in the chest and bounced to the ground
where Chris Ghidorzi landed on it at the 3 for the Badgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a tough one,'' said offensive coordinator Al Borges.
``You'd like to say don't audible, but you don't want to run a play
that's going to run right into the defense.''
</P>
<P>
   McNown completed 19 of 34 passes for his 340 yards and also
threw two touchdown passes and scrambled for a first downs on a
pair of third downs.
</P>
<P>
   But he was hampered by the absence of receiver Brian Poli-Dixon
(hamstring) for the final three quarters and a Wisconsin pass rush
that consistently pressured him for the first time all season.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins, who had allowed 12 sacks in 10 games, allowed three
including Bryant's game-sealer and also deflected three balls at
the line of scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   ``A quarterback like that, you've got to pressure him,'' said
Wisconsin All-American defensive end Tom Burke. ``You don't try to
get sacks because he gets rid of the ball quickly, but you try to
force him into some bad decisions. We definitely did that. You
could see he was forcing some balls at the end, throwing a few in
the dirt.''
</P>
<P>
   It meant that McNown, who had helped UCLA to a school-record
20-game winning streak, back-to-back 10-win seasons and rewrote the
school's record book, wouldn't go out the way he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he deserved is to go out a winner and he didn't get the
chance,'' said Borges. ``It's disappointing because of all he's
done here. I appreciate everything he's done and the opportunity to
work with him. He deserved a better fate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
