<SLUG> BC-FBC-DAYNE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAYNE HAS MEMORABLE DAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA _ Add Ron Dayne's name to the roll call of Rose Bowl
legends.
</P>
<P>
   The Wisconsin tailback was named Player of the Game after
rushing for 246 yards and four touchdowns on 27 carries in the
Badgers' 38-31 victory over UCLA on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The four touchdowns tied the modern-day Rose Bowl record, shared
by USC's Sam Cunningham and UCLA's Eric Ball. Cunningham did it
against Ohio State in 1973; Ball scored four in 1986 against Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Dayne's yardage total fell 1 yard short of the record set by
USC's Charles White in 1980 against Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin's in-your-face running attack was a priority in the
Rose Bowl game plan, Dayne said as he was mobbed by camera crews
and reporters after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our thought process was to come in and run the ball like we
normally do,'' he said. ``When everything was going well, we
started running. It was just easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Dayne, a junior, was mentioned as a candidate for the Heisman
Trophy two seasons in a row. He now figures to be the front-runner
for the award heading into his senior season. He's already said
he's passing on the NFL this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really worried about that right now,'' he said. ``If I
win it, I'm giving it to my linemen anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Dayne's performance was all the more remarkable considering he
is not fully recovered from a shoulder injury suffered earlier in
the season.
</P>
<P>
   Dayne, known as the ``Great Dayne'' among Badger fans,
overlooked the pain and simply savored his team's win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great,'' he said. ``I probably won't appreciate it until
after.''
</P>
<P>
   Dayne's near-record day gives him 5,091 yards in three years
with the Badgers. He is already third all-time on the Big Ten
career rushing list.
</P>
<P>
   Was he thinking about the record?
</P>
<P>
   Sort of.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nah, You know I kind of said I want to get the touchdown
record,'' Dayne said. ``But when I got to about 240 (yards), then I
started thinking about the yardage.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the credit for Dayne's outstanding performance goes to
the vocal Wisconsin fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are great,'' Dayne said. ``I love the fans; they support
us everywhere we go.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA coach Bob Toledo said the Bruins recognized Dayne's
abilities going into the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's what we expected,'' Toledo said. ``He had an excellent
game, scored a lot of touchdowns. He's hard to bring down and he's
a great back.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo said he's glad Dayne is returning for his senior season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that I am happy for him that he is coming
back,'' he said. ``That makes me feel good; he's going to come back
and try to win the Heisman.''
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin coach Barry Alvarez said he wasn't surprised by the
performance of the 5-foot-10, 258-pounder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ron had a great day,'' Alvarez said. ``I thought he would have
a good day from the way he practiced this week. He played with pain
today and still had a great game.''
</P>
<P>
   Dayne's plans for today are simple. He wants to share his joy
with his 18-month-old daughter Jada, who's home in Madison.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's probably asleep now,'' Dayne said. ``So I'll call her in
the morning.'' &UR; !end! &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
