<HEADLINE>
WILDCATS TUNED UP, READY TO GO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL CORO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lute Olson finally came out from underneath the hood this week
with basketball grease smeared all over his khaki slacks and navy
blazer.
</P>
<P>
   Olson has spent the season tinkering with Arizona's engine, a
starting lineup that changed seven straight games before he found
one with the horsepower to start defending its Pac-10 crown tonight
at No. 10 UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Point guard Jason Terry and center A.J. Bramlett, arguably the
nation's top senior duo, have been the only Wildcats to start every
game as No. 6 Arizona (8-0) remains one of four undefeated Division
I teams with the assist of a fluffy schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the lineup was a tinkering job that Olson did not
tighten the bolts on until Wednesday's Bank One Fiesta Bowl Classic
championship, when he settled on a lineup with Terry, Bramlett,
freshman Richard Jefferson at off-guard and freshman Michael Wright
and sophomore Justin Wessel at forwards.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways, I think we'd have been better off with a couple
more tough ones (in non-conference play), but on the other hand,
it's been helpful to play different people,'' Olson said.
</P>
<P>
   Junior forward Eugene Edgerson and freshman guard Traves Wilson
are first off the bench, but Arizona still lacks a definitive
backup for Terry. For the first six games, Terry averaged 39
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman Ruben Douglas or sophomore John Ash will get the duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not need miracles from that position, just
consistency,'' Olson said.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona goes into its Pac-10 opener, not having been challenged
in nearly a month. Players were admittedly had their minds already
wandering Wednesday to UCLA, which it swept last season.
</P>
<P>
   It still is the second-best start in Arizona history, even if it
has come off the likes of UC-Irvine, Iowa State, Holy Cross and
Florida International of late. The Wildcats have established a
hallmark of defense this season, holding opponents to 37 percent
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had a countdown to the Pac-10 season all season, and
our goal has been to make progress every game,'' Olson said. ``Now
that we are at that point, we can't go out there and be too
uptight. There are 18 games in the Pac-10 season. The name of the
game is improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona chalks what mistakes it has made to its youthful look,
including four freshman in the eight-man mix. But at UCLA (8-2),
Coach Steve Lavin's top 10 players are freshmen and sophomores.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin felt like a baby-sitter this week when his third-leading
scorer, homesick freshman JaRon Rush, missed two practices and a
game for an extended Kansas City holiday stay. Rush was suspended
for tonight's game after returning Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   To make UCLA matters worse, guard Brandon Loyd is doubtful
(flu), forward Billy Knight is out (groin) and forward Matt Barnes
and center Dan Gadzuric are questionable (knees).
</P>
<P>
   But UCLA may be better prepared for the Pac-10 rigors than
Arizona, having played Maryland, Kentucky and Oklahoma State.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have used eight different lineups and now have Baron
Davis back from knee surgery to make for a dangerous penetrating
backcourt with sophomore classmate Earl Watson.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman center Jerome Moiso averages 13.3 points and 6.7
rebounds. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-02-99 0204EST &QL; 
