<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARIZONA-STATE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUN DEVILS RETURN TO USC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The floor of the Sports Arena has long been tidied
up and swept clean of any of the pieces that remained of Arizona
State's basketball hopes last year.
</P>
<P>
   It's a brand new Pac-10 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a whole new team,'' ASU guard Eddie House said.
</P>
<P>
   Remember? House and the other returning Sun Devils would rather
not. Needing to win its final regular-season game to stay in
contention for an NCAA Tournament berth, a sick, tired ASU team,
sapped of the energy they spent overachieving for most of the
season, lost to Southern California by 46 points.
</P>
<P>
   Hello, NIT. And goodbye season, after a first-round defeat to
Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   The loss to USC was the third-worst in the history of ASU
basketball, inflicted by a team that shocked Arizona two days
earlier but still finished 9-19.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we were an NCAA Tournament team,'' forward Mike
Batiste said. ``We knew it would be tough because they beat
Arizona, but they beat us in every phase of the game, shooting,
passing, rebounding, whatever.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played harder than us. They dove on the floor for loose
balls. They did everything to win the ballgame, and we didn't. We
got the crap beat out of us, plain and simple.''
</P>
<P>
   But Batiste, whose pride was especially wounded because he grew
up in southern California and knows some of the USC players, said
he doesn't plan to dwell on what happened. Neither does House, who
said the importance of today's game is not to get even, but to ``go
in and show the Pac-10 how we're gonna play this year.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's certainly not a factor for new ASU Coach Rob Evans,
whose knowledge of the game was a tiny line of agate type in
whatever newspaper he was reading back in Mississippi as the Ole
Miss coach.
</P>
<P>
   But even if Evans had been on the losing bench instead of former
interim coach Don Newman, it wouldn't have mattered.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have to use a ploy like that (to get a team motivated),
you don't have a sound basketball team,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With the Sun Devils sporting an 8-4 non-conference record and
winning six straight, Evans believes they are close to being a
sound basketball team heading into conference play.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can keep all the pieces healthy, I think we can be very
competitive,'' he said. ``Where that leads to, you never know
because you've got to get some breaks along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I really like this team because I think they're starting
to get some confidence. I know they like each other, and that's
huge, and they're starting to play a little bit better defense and
execute on the offensive end.''
</P>
<P>
   The primary strength of the team is the three-headed scoring
monster _ House, averaging 21.2 points a game, followed by Batiste
at 18.5 and forward Bobby Lazor at 18.1. House, a junior who
averaged 11.3 and 12.6 points a game his first two years, is
closing in on a milestone faster than expected. He needs six points
to become the 24th ASU player to score 1,000, the 16th to do it in
three years or fewer.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the offense, the Sun Devils have outrebounded their last
eight opponents and are showing a better grasp of Evans' defensive
principles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're still learning, but we're learning quick,''
Batiste said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
