<HEADLINE>
STARS HOPE TO BUILD FROM PLAYOFF LOSSES 
</HEADLINE>
 STREAK-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CRAIG MORGAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hockey cynics have long argued that there is nothing more
meaningless than an NHL regular season. For proof, they point to
the handful of sub-.500 teams that regularly qualify for the
playoffs and the top seeds that fall every year in droves.
</P>
<P>
   No team has added more support to this argument over the past
two seasons than the Dallas Stars.
</P>
<P>
   After capturing the Central Division title two years ago, Dallas
fell in the first round of the playoffs to lowly Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Stars set numerous franchise records in
capturing the President's Trophy as the league's top regular-season
club. But an injury to leading scorer Joe Nieuwendyk and a Western
Conference final loss to Detroit left another stellar season
unfulfilled.
</P>
<P>
   The recent setbacks haven't deterred the Stars, however. Through
35 games this season, Dallas is again on pace to finish with the
league's best record. Entering Friday's game at America West Arena
against the Coyotes, Dallas was six points ahead of last year's
pace with just five losses in its first 34 games. The Stars' 2-1
win Friday also extended their season high unbeaten streak to 14
games (11-0-3), tying the Coyotes for the longest mark this year in
the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   But more important for the Stars, there is a belief that this
year will be different from the past two.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know where you build from? You build from hurt,'' Stars
Coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``You can't build from success. The
losses and the adversity are where you learn about your team. We've
responded well so far this year, and we believe in ourselves.
Hopefully, that will continue on into the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Buoying Dallas' confidence is the return of Nieuwendyk, who is
fifth on the team in scoring with 23 points and has shown no ill
effects from a torn anterior cruciate ligament suffered last season
on a hit from San Jose's Bryan Marchment.
</P>
<P>
   Balanced scoring, another Dallas shortcoming, was addressed in
the off-season with the signing of sniper Brett Hull, who leads the
team in goals with 13 after scoring the game winner in overtime
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't evaluate our team on Detroit last year,'' Hitchcock
said. ``We evaluated it on the entire conference, and we felt like
we needed to sign a top-six forward just to compete.''
</P>
<P>
   Center Mike Modano, who scored the Stars' first goal Friday,
admitted that the regular-season success won't mean anything if the
Stars falter again in the playoffs. But he also likened the team to
Detroit three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had to go through some playoff failures before they
finally succeeded,'' Modano said. ``I think we might be on that
same path.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Stars think the Coyotes may be, as well. With 46 points,
Phoenix is second in the overall league standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a quality team at all positions that you can't take
lightly,'' goalie Ed Belfour said. ``They're gonna get some playoff
experience this year, and then you never know.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-02-99 0205EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
