<SLUG> BC-BKW-ARIZONA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASU STARTS WOMEN'S PAC-10 PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
  STATE-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arizona State Coach Charli Turner Thorne vowed at the Pac-10
women's basketball media day not to become the CNN ``Play of the
Day'' by giving birth to her first child on the court.
</P>
<P>
   Her former mentor and mother of two, Southern California Coach
Chris Gobrecht, kidded Turner Thorne about whether she learned
anything about timing during their two years together at
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Although he's not due until Feb. 6, Conor Thorne is beginning to
show signs of being eager to see his mother's 6-3 team, which will
begin Pac-10 play at 2 p.m. today against USC (4-5) at Wells Fargo
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   It's the first of four games in eight days for the Sun Devils,
three of them compacted into a five-day period with travel in
between because of the Tostitos Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Turner Thorne picked up a technical foul Wednesday
</P>
<P>
   against San Jose State, putting the officials on the delicate
verge of ejecting mother with child. And if a 37-point win aroused
the third-year ASU coach to a ``T'', what can be expected of a
televised Pac-10 opener that her team absolutely needs to win?
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes the focus off what I want to keep the focus on to say
we've got to win,'' Turner Thorne said. ``This team has more
expectations of its own than any I've coached at ASU. If we handle
the pressures of competition and play good basketball, I know we're
going to win our share of games.''
</P>
<P>
   But with three of the strongest Pac-10 teams, including
ninth-ranked UCLA, just ahead, the Sun Devils must break their
16-year home losing streak vs. USC to have a reasonable hope of
being 2-3 minimum after five conference games.
</P>
<P>
   The last time ASU beat the Trojans in Tempe, now New York
Liberty center Kym Hampton was a sophomore triggering a 53-51 upset
in the season before now Mercury Coach Cheryl Miller started USC on
a two-year NCAA title run. All told in the series, USC leads, 38-3.
</P>
<P>
   Making even a dent in that history, which includes a 13-point
USC win in last year's finale to decide sixth place in the Pac-10,
will be difficult without Leah Combs.
</P>
<P>
   A magnetic resonance imaging Thursday confirmed that the
6-foot-2 freshman has advanced stress fractures in both legs that
will indefinitely sideline the Pac-10's fourth leading rebounder,
who is averaging 9.5 a game.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidently, the Sun Devils will return 6-foot forward Kisha
White from academic ineligibility and NCAA suspension today and are
edging closer to the return of 6-3 freshman Theresa Jantzen from a
fractured left foot.
</P>
<P>
   Jantzen, who has not played since registering 13 points and
seven rebounds in 15 minutes of a Nov. 4 exhibition, might attempt
warm-up drills today with an eye toward returning Thursday against
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Turner Thorne said White, who averaged 8.5 points and 4.4
rebounds and started 20 games last season, ``can give us some of
the things Leah was giving us. I'm hoping for that totally hungry,
first-game-back effort.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils will need big games on the boards from not only
White, 6-3 Rachel Holt and 6-foot Kristine Sand, who will start in
place of Combs, but also from their perimeter players. Especially
5-9 small forward Leaf Newman, who blocked out enough against San
Jose State to have a team-high seven boards.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams suffered recent losses to Big West Conference power
California-Santa Barbara. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
