<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRCA-CUSTER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRO BULL RIDER REDISCOVERS SUCCESS AFTER LONG DROUGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whenever Cody Custer had about given up on himself as a bull
rider, the Wickenburg, Ariz., cowboy turned to his strength. His
spiritual faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt God wanted me back riding bulls to do some Biblical
studies at the bull ridings,'' said Custer, who was so busted up
from 1993-97 that his '92 Professional Rodeo Cowboys Association
world championship was merely a fading belt buckle. ``Then lo and
behold, I have the best year I've ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   Between the PRCA, in which he placed fourth on the money list,
and the Professional Bull Riders (ninth), Custer won $222,602 in
1998, almost 50 percent more than his '92 PRCA-only earnings.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder the best bull riders are gravitating almost
exclusively to the PBR, which makes its Phoenix debut tonight at
America West Arena. Even without riding in enough PRCA events to
qualify, there is plenty of money to be had.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-one PBR riders won between $50,000 and Chris Shivers'
tour-leading $300,213 this year. The PRCA's top 17 money-winners
ranged from $55,000 to Ty Murray's $167,154.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel so bad that the saddle-bronc and bareback riders don't
have the PBR and I do,'' Custer said. ``I know where I'm going a
year in advance, I can buy my (plane) tickets and get rates on
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning, we were hated by some of the (PRCA)
higher-ups, I'm sure of it. It was one of them deals where we saw
we had something that would stand on its own outside of rodeo and
was the only event that could really do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vision we had in '92 was to see some kids then in diapers
be able to make a million dollars a year. What we foresaw, we're
reaping some of it now. If I'd won $300,000 like Chris Shivers at
age 19, I'd probably be dead now.''
</P>
<P>
   Shivers, who turned 20 Wednesday, was second in Bud Light Cup
points behind Troy Dunn and third at the Bud Light Cup World
Championships, which preceded the NFR in Las Vegas by a month.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn dislocated his hip in the first round of the PBR Finals,
putting him out until late March or April, and is home in Australia
celebrating the recent birth of his daughter, Tyrah.
</P>
<P>
   But the Eight Second Thunder field here will include not only
Shivers and Custer but also Phoenix native Murray, who clinched a
PRCA-record seventh world all-around title at the NFR as well as
winning his second bull-riding crown.
</P>
<P>
   And fresh from Thursday night's opener of the 29-city PBR tour
in Salt Lake City are top-three finishers Cody Hart, Leslie Doyle
and Tater Porter.
</P>
<P>
   All were absent from October's Coors Rodeo Showdown in Phoenix
because of a scheduling conflict. So that title went to
little-known Vince Stanton, who was the only one of four finalists
to complete a ride, scoring 83.
</P>
<P>
   Custer, by contrast, produced a PBR Finals-record 95.5 ride on
the still feared Red Wolf, 1996 PRCA and NFR Bucking Bull of the
Year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had that bull at a rodeo in California in '96, and he
stuffed me on my head right quick,'' Custer said. ``He bucked me
off so fast, I never got to see how he was going to feel. He feels
real good. He has a lot of power and speed. Most bulls his size
(2,000 pounds) are not as fast as he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Custer had five Bud Light Cup top-10 finishes before the Finals,
where he was fifth and won $65,450. He also won the Laughlin
Shoot-Out in mid-September to spark a glorious fall.
</P>
<P>
   Coming into Laughlin with PBR earnings of $30,000, Custer said
he rode the first round ``like a Girl Scout instead of a man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, I went behind the chutes and had a fit back
there,'' Custer said. ``I kicked and screamed. I told my wife I was
leaving if I didn't ride better on my second one.'' She reminded
him that his last such outburst led to a victory, which, sure
enough, happened again.
</P>
<P>
   Custer scored 87.5 and 86.5 on his next two bulls and 88 in the
finals. That resulted in an $18,465 windfall and buried for good
the ``operation years'': 1993 (left biceps/elbow), '94 (right
shoulder), '95 (right shoulder), '96 (broken hand), '97 (right
shoulder).
</P>
<P>
   The injuries sent him home to what he jokingly calls his
half-acre in-town ranch that he soon hopes to trade in for a
10-acre spread where his three children (Aaron, 5; Lacey, 4; Brett,
11 months) can grow up with horses and he can retire to raise
bucking bulls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm closer to the end than the beginning,'' Custer said. ``I'm
going to try to enjoy the ones I've got left.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
