<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CASSTEVENS-CARDINALS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GREAT DAY TO DEFEAT COWBOYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Arizona Cardinals aren't playing the most
valuable sports franchise in North America, worth $413 million,
according to ``Forbes'' magazine.
</P>
<P>
   They aren't playing Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Or its 381 luxury suites.
</P>
<P>
   Or its fancy Stadium Club.
</P>
<P>
   Or a 146th consecutive sellout crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals aren't playing the Cowboys Ring of Honor.
</P>
<P>
   They aren't playing NFL Hall of Famers Bob Lilly and Roger
Staubach and Tony Dorsett and Randy White and Mel Renfro.
</P>
<P>
   They aren't playing five Super Bowl rings.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals aren't playing the ``Dallas Cowboys Official
Weekly,'' the largest team publication in sports with a circulation
of almost 70,000.
</P>
<P>
   They aren't playing the Dallas Cowboys' vast radio network.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals aren't playing ``The Chan Gailey Show''.``''
</P>
<P>
   Or ``Cowboys Special Edition'' with team owner Jerry Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, ``one of the NFL's most influential and active owners,''
according to his bio. Jones, a ``man of varied interests.'' Jones,
who engineered ``what may have been the most dramatic and visible
turnaround in the history of professional sports.'' Jones, who
``will not rest on yesterday's achievements.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals (unfortunately) aren't playing Ronda and Pamela
and Shaina and Johnene. The Dallas Cowboys Cheerleaders recently
reached a major milestone by making more international
entertainment trips to U.S. military bases than any other
professional performer or group over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals are not playing Cowboys Parkway.
</P>
<P>
   They're not playing the team's sprawling's stone-and-glass
headquarters known as Valley Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals aren't playing the plush executive offices or the
acres of soft blue carpeting trimmed in silver-gray.
</P>
<P>
   They aren't playing a fan base that _ this from Jones' bio again
_ ``spans the nation and reaches all corners of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans like Bill ``Cowboy'' Lamza, president of a Houston-based
fan club and editor of a Cowboys newsletter he distributes
worldwide. Cowboy has his own trading card. He is pictured sitting
atop a horse, reins in hand. The back of the card reads, ``Better
to die as a young child than to grow up disliking the Dallas
Cowboys.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals aren't playing Dallas Cowboys Travel
(1-800-6-COWBOY).
</P>
<P>
   They aren't playing Pepsi.
</P>
<P>
   Or Nike.
</P>
<P>
   They aren't playing the Lombardi Trophy.
</P>
<P>
   They aren't playing Cowboys mystique.
</P>
<P>
   They aren't playing Don Meredith's 95-yard pass to Bob Hayes or
Staubach's ``Hail Mary'' to Drew Pearson or Danny White's
club-record 155 touchdowns or the team's 20 consecutive (1966-85)
winning seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a surprise, the Cardinals aren't playing Deion Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals are playing a solid, well-coached team they
respect but believe they can beat.
</P>
<P>
   They're playing a team Jake Plummer took apart by throwing for
more than 400 yards six weeks ago. A team that watched its 28-0
lead melt like a sugar cube in hot water.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals didn't beat a team with a winning record this
season. The Cowboys beat one. The Cards.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals are playing a team with playoff experience. But
how important is experience?
</P>
<P>
   ``If experience is so important,'' said Doug Rader, the former
big-league manager, ``we'd never have had anyone walk on the
moon.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals are playing a team that lost to the Bears and the
Saints.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals are playing a team that most everyone believes
will win.
</P>
<P>
   But can the underdogs surprise? Sure. The Cardinals are going to
beat the Cowboys someday. Today seems as good a day as any. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached atdavid.casstevens(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
