<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-COHN-PAC-10 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAC-10 COACHES RATE THEIR CONFERENCE HIGH 
</HEADLINE>
  NOTES-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After four teams made the NCAA Sweet 16 last season and the
predictors loaded up the front ends of their preseason polls with
the likes of Stanford and Washington, are we ready to officially
declare the Pac-10 a basketball conference?
</P>
<P>
   Like any other subject of vast importance and cosmic meaning, it
depends on how you look at it.
</P>
<P>
   Or, to put it another way, how should I know?
</P>
<P>
   This week's Associated Press rankings show three teams _
Stanford, Arizona and UCLA _ in the Top 10. That's the same number
as the Atlantic Coast Conference, where college basketball was
presumably invented. A fourth team, California, is likely to crack
the Top 25.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the RPI (power ratings to you), which indicates
that the Pac-10 is the third-strongest conference in the nation,
behind the Big Ten and ACC.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, other than Cal beating North Carolina on its
home court in Oakland, and maybe Washington's win in Seattle over
overrated New Mexico, the Pac-10 hasn't generated many
attention-getting victories.
</P>
<P>
   But you don't have to convince the coaches. To a man, they are
sure their conference is the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been an absolutely incredible season for the
conference,'' Stanford Coach Mike Montgomery said.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the analysis of first-year Arizona State Coach Rob
Evans probably is the most sensible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it would be tough,'' he said. ``But what's happened now
is, some of the teams that haven't been as tough have really turned
up the heat. Oregon. Southern Cal. Cal. They've done a great job
recruiting, and the coaches have really done a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans didn't mention himself and the Sun Devils, but we will.
</P>
<P>
   There.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the bottom part of the league starts meeting up with the
top, your league is very, very difficult,'' Evans said.
</P>
<P>
   With conference play starting today, a look at who's where: &QL;  &QL; 
Stanford (10-2) &QL;  &QL; 
Montgomery said ``there's a lot of stuff we can do better'' after
the Cardinal's victory over Temple Tuesday, but despite injuries
that have weakened the bench, this remains the team to beat.
</P>
<P>
   As advertised, the Cardinal frontcourt is rough and tough, but a
little finesse around the basket wouldn't hurt, either.
</P>
<P>
   Point guard Arthur Lee, is having a strong all-around season and
backcourt partner Kris Weems can shoot. &QL;  &QL; 
California (9-1) &QL;  &QL; 
For those who overlooked the Golden Bears at the start of the
season, the secret's out. Tuesday's victory over North Carolina was
no fluke.
</P>
<P>
   With the Bears off to their best start since 1980-81, brainy Ben
Braun is the early leader for Pac-10 Coach of the Year, and guard
Geno Carlisle is a candidate for Player of the Year. The heretofore
obscure (outside the league) Sean Lampley, a 6-foot-7 forward,
sometimes plays 7-foot-6. &QL;  &QL; 
Arizona (8-0) &QL;  &QL; 
The Wildcats are the only unbeaten team in the Pac-10 and just one
of four nationally, although their biggest test of the season comes
today against UCLA at Pauley Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   Senior point guard Jason Terry is the best player in the
conference, scoring, passing, defending and exerting leadership on
a team that needs it. Center A.J. Bramlett has become a genuine
presence inside.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman forward Richard Jefferson (Moon Valley High School) is
starting to live up to the hype as Coach Lute Olson finally has
settled on a lineup after using seven different combinations. &QL;  &QL; 
UCLA (8-2) &QL;  &QL; 
With a very talented, very young team, no one said it wouldn't be
interesting. Freshman forward JaRon Rush, the club's third-leading
scorer, went back to Kansas City, Mo., for Christmas and stayed
there because he was homesick. Problem was, the Bruins had a game
against Loyola Marymount. Rush later returned but was suspended for
today's Arizona game.
</P>
<P>
   Two more members of the highly touted freshmen class, center Dan
Gadzuric and forward Matt Barnes, have battled injuries, and
sophomore guard Billy Knight is out for the season. On the other
hand, sophomore point guard Baron Davis is regaining his form after
reconstructive knee surgery. &QL;  &QL; 
Washington (7-3) &QL;  &QL; 
The Huskies were oversold by many at the start, and injuries, plus
Coach Bob Bender's decision to send his team on a six-game death
march away from home, fueled the notion until last week's win over
New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's hard to get excited over this bunch, which struggled
to beat Portland at home after the New Mexico win. Center Todd
MacCulloch is a first-rate college center, and guards Donald Watts
(who is still out) and Deon Luton can score. But the Huskies don't
get the type of play from the point guard position necessary to
compete for a championship. &QL;  &QL; 
Arizona State (8-4) &QL;  &QL; 
The improvement is noticeable, and not just because senior forward
Mike Batiste has regained his academic eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils are finally grasping first-year Coach Rob Evans'
system, which harps on defense, rebounding and total effort. It
also helps that ASU has perhaps the best scoring threesome in the
conference _ Batiste, senior forward Bobby Lazor and junior guard
Eddie House, whose transformation this season has been nothing
short of amazing. &QL;  &QL; 
Oregon (8-1) &QL;  &QL; 
Like ASU, the Ducks had to get used to a new coach. Except that
they did it last season, when Ernie Kent replaced Jerry Green, and
the year of getting acclimated is paying off.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks still haven't beaten anyone of note, but the talent is
there, and they hustle. The backcourt is strong, with Alex Scales,
a junior college transfer, and freshman Frederick Jones joining
veteran Terik Brown. &QL;  &QL; 
Southern California (8-1) &QL;  &QL; 
The Trojans lost big to Kansas on the road in their only test of
legitimacy, but this looks like a team with lots of athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Juco transfer Brain Scalabrine, a 6-9 forward/center, is
probably making the biggest impact of any newcomer in the
conference. &QL;  &QL; 
Oregon State (6-3) &QL;  &QL; 
The Beavers have defeated Brigham Young and Notre Dame. Whoops,
make that BYU-``Hawaii'' and ``College of'' Notre Dame. After
beating the latter by 32 points this week, forward Jason Heide
said, ``Offensively, we still stink.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Coach Eddie Payne, the Beavers have won two, three and two
Pac-10 games during the past three seasons. Don't expect much
better this time around. &QL;  &QL; 
Washington State (6-5) &QL;  &QL; 
The injury-marred Cougars have done better since an 0-4 start that
included a loss to Division II Alaska-Fairbanks, and guard
Jan-Michael Thomas is another impressive juco transfer in the
conference. &QL;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
