<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOLUNTEERS' DEFENDERS HOLD THEIR OWN DURING PRACTICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Volunteers' scout team is probably having the most fun it's
had at practice. The defensive backs have been instructed by their
coaches to hold Tennessee's star receivers at every possible
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are just holding us to death,'' sophomore wide receiver
Cedrick Wilson said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The reason? It's the best way to prepare for Florida State,
Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their defensive backs are really good, but they hold all the
time, and the referees don't call it,'' he said. ``So that's how we
decided to work on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson has been lost in the hype surrounding the Fiesta Bowl's
big-time receivers, primarily the Seminoles' Peter Warrick and the
Volunteers' Peerless Price.
</P>
<P>
   But he was the player who caught the game-clinching touchdown
pass in the Southeastern Conference championship game against
Mississippi State. He is Tennessee's No. 2 receiver with 33 catches
for 558 yards and six touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's OK,'' he said. ``I like it hush-hush.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Rope trick
</P>
<P>
   After Florida State lost to North Carolina State in the second
game of the season, Seminoles defensive coordinator Mickey Andrews
went to a hardware store to buy some rope.
</P>
<P>
   No, the longtime assistant wasn't going to hang himself. The
rope was used as a motivational tool, which obviously worked. The
Seminoles have won 10 straight and are playing Tennessee for the
national championship Monday in the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the story of a guy in the mountains,'' Andrews said
Friday. ``He falls and he's holding onto a limb. He knows he's
going to face his death with a 10,000-foot drop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `If you're in that situation, look around the room.
Who do you want to have at the end of the rope.' I said, `How many
of you are willing to hang on to the rope and be accountable?' ''
</P>
<P>
   After finishing the story, Andrews told reporters who had asked
about the rope, ``I don't think that has a lot to do with the
football game, but I appreciate your question anyway.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Million-dollar man &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although Phillip Fulmer's new contract may sound like a lot,
Tennessee Athletic Director Doug Dickey said it's just a sign of
the times.
</P>
<P>
   ``The contract is in keeping with the economic standards of
college coaching and is deserved,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, Fulmer signed a six-year contract worth $1 million
a year on Thursday. It will raise Fulmer's total pay by about
$200,000 and makes him the second-highest paid coach in the SEC
behind Florida's Steve Spurrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look forward to many more years coaching this team,'' Fulmer
said.
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer's new base salary will be $175,000. The largest chunk
comes from radio and television commitments, which pay $400,000;
apparel and shoe contracts pay $250,000; and he gets a $250,000
annual retention bonus that began after the 1997 season. Other
benefits bring the total to $1 million. &QL; 
 &QL; 
No midnight madness &QL; 
 &QL; 
Florida State players opted to stay at their hotel Thursday night
instead of ringing in the New Year at the Block Party in Tempe as
planned. The team captains made the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wanted to take a chance of some Tennessee fan taking a
shot at us there,'' linebacker Lamont Green said. ``That would have
gotten us in trouble with the coaches, especially if it meant not
being able to play in the game. I want to be able to celebrate
being national champions on the Fiesta Bowl logo at the 50-yard
line Monday night.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Going long
</P>
<P>
   The Volunteers watched Mississippi's 35-18 victory over Texas
Tech in the Independence Bowl Thursday with considerable interest.
</P>
<P>
   They were rooting for David Cutcliffe, Tennessee's offensive
coordinator since 1992, who left after the SEC title game to become
Mississippi's coach.
</P>
<P>
   The Rebels were impressive, and quarterback Romaro Miller threw
for three touchdowns, a bowl record.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were throwing the ball deep, and I was jealous,''
Tennessee quarterback Tee Martin said. ``He (Cutcliffe) used to
tell me we were going to throw deep eight times in a game, and then
we'd throw it two times.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
