<HEADER>
A5132 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-FIESTA-FLAST-OUTZ     01-02 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-FLA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEASON TO CROW ABOUT  
 `ROOSTER' OUTZEN RESCUES SEMINOLES 
</HEADLINE>
 ST-OUTZEN-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   His teammates call him Rooster, one of the few things Marcus
Outzen could do without at Florida State. He hates the nickname,
given to him last year by then-quarterback Thad Busby.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bobby Bowden says he used to sing ``The Rooster'' song in
college. Nobody on the team knows the words to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a good thing,'' Outzen said.
</P>
<P>
   Outzen responds to Rooster only to his teammates and coaches,
and, lately, the red-haired quarterback with the buzz cut has been
hearing it a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, and unexpectedly, Outzen finds himself in the middle
of one of the biggest games in Florida State history. The
20-year-old sophomore, a year removed from questioning his future
as a Seminole, has spent the week coolly handling questions from
national media on everything from the pressures of leading the
Seminoles in the national championship game to his nickname.
</P>
<P>
   With only two games as a starting college quarterback on his
resume, Outzen can't wait to run into Sun Devil Stadium on Monday
in the Tostitos Fiesta Bowl against top-ranked Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love this situation,'' he said. ``I don't look at this as a
tough situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Outzen's good fortune came with Chris Weinke's misfortune on
Nov. 7. Weinke, a 26-year-old sophomore who spent six years playing
minor league baseball in the Toronto Blue Jays' organization,
suffered a season-ending neck injury in the last 30 seconds of the
first half of the Virginia game. Outzen led the Seminoles to 24
second-half points, completing 5 of 6 passes.
</P>
<P>
   The following week, Outzen led Florida State past Wake Forest,
connecting on 11 of 19 passes for 164 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The big question, however, was how would Outzen hold up against
Florida. There is no bigger game each year for the Seminoles.
</P>
<P>
   He twice fumbled, once resulting in a safety, and Bowden had
doubts in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's going through my mind is, `Gee, I'm not sure he's going
to be good enough to win this game,' '' Bowden said. ``He came out
and just did an excellent job in the second half, which should help
his confidence. It sure helped ours about him.''
</P>
<P>
   His teammates never got down on him. After Outzen fumbled,
cornerback Mario Edwards came up to Outzen on the sideline and
said, ``Rooster, keep doing what you're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of series later, he threw a touchdown pass,'' Edwards
said. ``I'm talking to (another player) and I just happen to look
around, and Rooster is this close to me. He was fired up and just
waiting for me to congratulate him.''
</P>
<P>
   Outzen ended up passing for 167 yards in a 23-12 victory that
put the Seminoles in a wait-and-see mode. What they saw was UCLA
and Kansas State fall on the same day, sending them to Tempe for
the national championship game.
</P>
<P>
   He dismisses any nerves leading up to this showdown, as he did
in the Florida game. Eric Outzen, Marcus' father, confidant,
adviser and No. 1 fan, made up for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He couldn't sleep all week and lost weight,'' Outzen said of
his dad. ``I probably gained two pounds during the Florida game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big game, but I took it with a grain of salt. I
ignored the pressures that were put upon me. I knew what I had to
do to lead the team. Focusing on the pressures won't help you do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinke, who threw for more than 200 yards in nine of the 10
games he played and didn't throw an interception in his last 218
attempts, still is hurting from not being able to finish what he
started. But he said he is here to support Outzen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He says he's not nervous, but he will be as it gets closer to
the game,'' Weinke said. ``I'll be there to encourage him. This is
a huge game. He knows it. But he's been through it.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a long way from Fort Walton Beach, Fla., where Outzen
was raised with a pitcher's mound on one end of his back yard and
an old tire to throw at on the other.
</P>
<P>
   He followed former Florida quarterback and Heisman Trophy winner
Danny Wuerffel at Fort Walton Beach High and led the school to the
Class 5A championship his senior year. But Outzen grew up
worshiping Florida State football.
</P>
<P>
   His father took him to the 1990 Fiesta Bowl. The Seminoles beat
Nebraska, and the young Outzen got Bowden's autograph.
</P>
<P>
   He was in awe of Bowden then. A year ago, however, Outzen
wondered if he had a future in Tallahassee. He played in all 12
games as a freshman, but as a holder on extra points and field
goals. He was the fourth-team quarterback, behind Busby, Dan Kendra
and Weinke.
</P>
<P>
   After the season, Outzen was in Bowden's office, asking if it
might be in his best interest to transfer. Bowden told him to stick
it out through spring football.
</P>
<P>
   Outzen was running third string in the spring, until Kendra, a
junior, blew out his knee in a scrimmage that wiped out his 1998
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a sophomore, I knew that I'd be a backup and the most I
could ask for was some mop-up duties in games,'' Outzen said.
``Going into the season, I prepared myself for that role.''
</P>
<P>
   It was difficult to sit. But as impatient as he was, his heart
was with the Seminoles. He leaned on his father, who told him not
to worry, things would work out, he'd get his chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't deny myself the privilege of being a Seminole,''
Outzen said. ``I couldn't get away from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Flanker Peter Warrick said Outzen possesses the same take-charge
attitude in the huddle that Weinke had.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to rally around a guy like that,'' Warrick said.
``We know he's going to get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Outzen's mobility gives the Seminoles another dimension, the
ability to take off with the ball. The quarterback draw, rarely
used since Charlie Ward led Florida State to its only national
championship in 1993, is back in the playbook.
</P>
<P>
   The Rooster is amazed and exhilarated at where he is now. But
how long will he be in FSU's plans? Weinke and Kendra both should
be back in the fall, completely healed. He'll also have to contend
with Jared Jones, a hotshot freshman from Walla Walla, Wash. The
Seminoles don't go as far as Walla Walla, Wash., for someone whom
they think is going to sit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, at Florida State, we don't lose jobs to injuries,''
Outzen said. ``But I'd have to say, if we win the national
championship, that it will be an open battle again.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
