r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-FIESTA-T-ENN-MART     01-02 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-T-ENN-MARTIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLITZ EASY AFTER GUNFIRE  
 FAMILY HELPED VOLS QB ESCAPE VIO LENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He is 12-0 as a starting quarterback, 0-12 as a friend to those
who died young.
</P>
<P>
   Think about it. National championships and 6-foot-5 defensive
linemen don't seem nearly as intimidating when you've lived by the
beat of a metronome of gunfire. When you've lost enough friends,
12, to field an offense and then some.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's why Tennessee quarterback Tee Martin keeps
stiff-arming adversity, and why he once said oncoming blitzes make
him, well, giggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can put everything in perspective now,'' the junior said.
``I see football as a game. Being in the situations I was in
growing up really taught me to be calm under tough situations. You
just can't panic if things are going bad.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a good lesson to take into Monday's Fiesta Bowl game
against Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that the Volunteers weren't supposed to be here,
and a big reason was Martin. How could Tennessee get to a title
game with a quarterback with zero starts, when one of the best in
the country, Peyton Manning, couldn't do it?
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't scary, because I didn't prepare like I was filling
the shoes of Peyton Manning,'' he said. ``Coming in and saying I
was going to do something he didn't do and this, that and the other
thing, it never came into my thinking. I was just going to be me.''
</P>
<P>
   He did, and by the fifth game of the season, when Tennessee's
coaches finally opened up the offense for the maturing quarterback,
he flourished. During the final seven games, he threw 10 touchdown
passes and two interceptions, and he completed 63 percent of his
passes.
</P>
<P>
   He also set three NCAA records with a 23-of-24 effort against
South Carolina. By Nov. 8, the Volunteers had moved into the No. 1
spot of the Associated Press poll for good.
</P>
<P>
   Martin was a big reason. A peek into his past may explain why
the quarterback remained so poised, even during a season that
included four fourth-quarter victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always felt God was watching over Tee,'' his mother, Marie,
said. ``He had to be, considering what he's been through.''
</P>
<P>
   Marie was 16 when Martin was born in Mobile, Ala. His father,
Maurice Marshall, was a freshman football player at Mississippi
Valley State. After several years, Marie and Maurice married, and
after several more, they divorced. Marshall drifted in and out of
Tee's life.
</P>
<P>
   Tee got his name, Taumaurice, after Marie handed the newborn to
Marshall and said, ``To Maurice.''
</P>
<P>
   As he grew up, he lived at different times with his mother,
grandmother and great-grandmother. Marie said she has lived in more
than 20 places since Tee was born and that most moves were prompted
by a search for safer neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Drugs and violence surrounded Martin's youth. As a senior in
high school, he left a friend, Gary Simmons, outside his house for
a minute. He heard gunshots. When he ran outside, Simmons, who had
been holding his baby boy, had suffered two gunshots to the head.
The baby had been shot in the foot. The baby survived. The father
didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Martin would lose at least 11 more friends to violence,
accidents or illness.
</P>
<P>
   Although he saw it, Martin said violence never directly touched
him because the women and the uncle who raised him instilled proper
values from a young age. He had to be home by dark. He cooked and
cleaned.
</P>
<P>
   ``They weren't strict, but they were strong,'' Martin said. ``I
knew what to do by the time I was 2 or 3. They did a good job of
molding my mind and trying to put me on the right path when I was
young. When I got older, they didn't have to worry about what I
would do because they raised me the right way.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin said he still has a good relationship with his father and
that they write to one another.
</P>
<P>
   He received plenty of letters from colleges as a standout
quarterback at Mobile's Williamson High School. He chose Tennessee,
even though he felt Tim Couch was its No. 1 choice. Couch ended up
at Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   After backing up Manning as a sophomore, he was handed the reins
for the 1998 season. While the coaching staff respected his
abilities, they simplified the offense and limited what he was
allowed to do in the early part of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Volunteers started out 4-0, including recording
their first victory over Florida since 1992, it wasn't easy for the
parties involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was very frustrating for our senior receivers,
Peerless (Price) and Jeremaine (Copeland),'' sophomore wide
receiver Cedrick Wilson said. ``They were used to Peyton throwing
the ball 75 percent of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Out of necessity, and because they grew more confident with
Martin, the coaches opened up the offense in the fifth game of the
season, against Georgia. One week earlier, standout running back
Jamal Lewis went down with a season-ending knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   Martin went 16 of 26 for 156 yards, two touchdowns and two
interceptions in a 22-3 victory over the Bulldogs. Two weeks later,
he had the record-setting effort against South Carolina. That's
when Tennessee faithful, among others, realized the Volunteers had
something special.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early on, I understood, and it was only right for the coaches
to do what they did,'' Martin said. ``They had to depend on the
players that had already proven themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of like I was being contained by my own coaches,
living in my own jail. When they finally let me out, I was like a
little kid in a candy store.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin flourished and led Tennessee to a 12-0 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's out there controlling the offense and calling the huddles
with a lot more firmness than he did early on,'' cornerback Steve
Johnson said. ``He's a real field general now.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Martin's contributions on the field, Coach
Phillip Fulmer said he likes what the player contributes off of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's as fine a person as you'd ever want to meet,'' he said.
``He's a guy you'd say, `Tee, I'm going to be gone for a month,
watch my house and take care of my kids.' He's that kind of a guy.
He's got as good a heart as any person I've been around.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-02-99 0216EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
