<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 02:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5134 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-FIESTA-FLAST-SIMO     01-02 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-FLA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INJURIES TO AC COLADES: SEMINOLES' SIMON WORKS THROUGH PAIN 
</HEADLINE>
 ST-SIMON-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just how good is Florida State's No. 1-ranked defense?
</P>
<P>
   This good:
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Seminoles' starting nose guard Larry Smith
suffered a sprained knee that will keep him from playing in
Monday's Tostitos Fiesta Bowl national championship game against
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   The guy who will step into the starting lineup in Smith's place
is an Associated Press first-team All-America selection.
</P>
<P>
   That's really good.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Corey Simon, the 6-foot-4, 275-pound junior who will
move into Smith's spot, is not a typical backup.
</P>
<P>
   But Florida State's interior defense isn't typical, either.
Three players, Smith, Simon and Jerry Johnson, rotate at nose guard
and tackle, keeping fresh and talented bodies coming at the
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is the team's best run-stopping tackle and brings
boundless energy to the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's our intensity guy, the most aggressive defensive
lineman we have,'' linebacker Lamont Green said.
</P>
<P>
   But Simon led the group with 65 total tackles, 16 tackles for
losses, five sacks and five pass deflections.
</P>
<P>
   Simon, who was shocked to be named to the All-America team after
having his first two seasons shortened by injuries, was the
recipient of the Atlantic Coast Conference's Brian Piccolo Award,
given to the player who makes the most courageous comeback from an
injury.
</P>
<P>
   Question is, which injury?
</P>
<P>
   Simon has had six major injuries, including a rotator cuff
injury in his shoulder, a dislocated shoulder, a neck injury and
knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very concerned that he could stay healthy,'' said
Mickey Andrews, Florida State's defensive coordinator. ``He hadn't
been able to the entire time he had been at Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came in with a hurt shoulder that had surgery. He got out
to practice for a few days in spring, and he's hurt again. We come
into fall, and he hurts a knee. He seemed like he had a blue jersey
on (for the injured) more than garnet.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon has had some minor injuries this season, but nothing to
keep him from playing and producing big plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been great to receive the accolades,'' he said. ``It's
always nice to be recognized as an All-American or all-conference.
But the focus of my season wasn't what I can accomplish as far as
accolades. It was to go in and help this team win a national
championship, and we have that opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``This season is so much sweeter than last season or the season
before that when I really didn't have much say so in what we did.
That's what makes everything sweeter, to be recognized as an
All-American and still be playing for a national championship and
helping the team be the No. 1 defense in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``That makes it extra special.''
</P>
<P>
   But Smith's loss was a blow to the Seminoles, emotionally as
well as strategically against a Tennessee offensive line that is
the heart and soul of the Volunteers' attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went down (for two games) early in the season, but this is
something different,'' Simon said. ``It's not like we're playing
Duke. This is for the national championship. He's a great player,
and it's motivation for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Normally, the threesome of Smith, Simon and Johnson make their
own adjustments during games and will take themselves in and out of
the lineup to stay fresh. Simon says he's got enough ``in my tank
to go all the way,'' but he won't hesitate to call on sophomore
Bryne Malone, who is preparing to back up the interior starters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bryne has really stepped up to the challenge since we lost
Larry,'' Simon said. ``He's a great player when he decides to step
it up, and we're confident he can do the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's a safe bet that Simon is going to be less willing
than usual to share time with a national title on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't say enough about him,'' Andrews said. ``He never
lost the faith. He never gave up, and the rehab he had to go
through was just unbelievable because it has happened so many times
to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corey Simon is a very talented football player, and when he's
healthy, he's got the ability to go make plays.''
</P>
<P>
   It's what All-America backups do. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
