<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPERFAN_COLUMN-CARDS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDS NOT SO BAD AFTER ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   So I was laying in supplies for today's Cardinals playoff game
when . . .
</P>
<P>
   Wait a second. I can't believe I just typed those words
_ &UR; Cardinals
 &UR; playoff game. Still sounds weird, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   I feel like one of those guys from the 1800s who wondered if he
would live to see the country linked by rail. You occasionally
allowed yourself to dream about it, but when it finally happens,
you almost can't believe it.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the hype, fair amounts of people are jumping on the
Big Red bandwagon. No surprise there. It's hard not to. The last
time the Cardinals were in the playoffs, people were reading
``Sports Illustrated'' by gas lamps and listening to radio call-in
shows with ear horns. The novelty is exciting. And when you're
playing a love-to-hate-'em team like Dallas, it only gets sweeter.
</P>
<P>
   And I have to admit, I'm excited, too. True, with all its
injuries, the Arizona defense couldn't stop a dung beetle with a
sledgehammer. But if Jake Plummer gets hot, who knows? Maybe it'll
come down to an end- zone call again this time _ and maybe this
time the officials will remember to pack their backbones.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, I cannot claim to have always been so excited about
Cardinals football. I looked back at some of the things I've
written about the team over the years, and I have to admit, on
first blush, not everything was so positive. But in this age of
spin doctoring, I think I can explain away almost all of it. A few
examples:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Comment: Sure, nearly everyone on whom the Cards spent more
than $1 million to acquire during the off-season played as if they
were worth something approaching minimum wage . . . but there's
still hope. For instance, Joe Bugel hopes he won't have a new
address next year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Explanation: Is anything more optimistic than hope?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Comment: The good news is that police found 11 missing Boy
Scouts at Sun Devil Stadium. The bad news is that they're beating
the Cardinals by 14 points.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Explanation: Actually, humor is more optimistic than hope.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Comment: Things are supposed to be different this season. Last
season's defense was great . . . but the offense couldn't score
with Heidi Fleiss' help. This season, Dave Krieg is in charge, at
least until he starts drawing Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Explanation: A clear nod to Krieg's leadership ability, nothing
more.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Comment: You have to start wondering, is Dave Krieg the answer?
Only if the question is, ``Who's better than Tom Tupa?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Explanation: Oops. Well, I did say he was better than Tupa,
didn't I?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Comment: I guarantee you that the Cardinals will not lose
today. Of course, they don't even play today, but you take the
little victories where you can find them. Or the little non-losses,
at least.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Explanation: Sometimes we hurt because we love.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Comment: Here's a familiar phrase: The Cardinals' game today
will be blacked out in the Phoenix area, because they failed to
sell out Sun Devil Stadium. It's like typing ``embattled
President'' before ``Bill Clinton'' _ your fingers seemingly move
by themselves, because it's something you type so often. I think
it's called muscle memory.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Explanation: I certainly nailed the Clinton thing cold.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Comment: You would think that in a state so stubbornly
right-wing that car-pooling and seat belt laws are considered merry
skips down the roads to socialism and fascism, football fans would
enjoy a good old-fashioned conservative offense. Apparently not.
Cardinals fans have spoken and have said they like the occasional
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Explanation: Still true today.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, I'm hoping for several Cardinals' scores. You never can
tell in the playoffs. A win today and then an upset next week and .
. .
</P>
<P>
   Whoa, pardner. I'm dreaming again. &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-02-99 0220EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
