A5137 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDINALS-WADSWOR     01-02 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-WADSWORTH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL FOR THE BEST  
 IN THE END, CARDS GET THEIR WADSWORTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Only Andre Wadsworth could sign a $42 million
contract and then apologize.
</P>
<P>
   Wadsworth, the Cardinals' rookie defensive end, apologized for
being a distraction before the season-opening loss to Dallas at
Texas Stadium. Then, he apologized again for costing rookie
free-agent defensive lineman Mike Moten of Florida a job.
</P>
<P>
   Moten was led off the team plane on the tarmac at Sky Harbor
Airport, minutes after Wadsworth ended his 44-day holdout on Sept.
5. The Cardinals needed to cut a player to leave a spot for
Wadsworth on the roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really did feel bad because I know him personally,''
Wadsworth said. ``He worked hard in two-a-days. He came from
nowhere. I'm just glad it all worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals re-signed Moten to the practice squad on Oct. 27,
and he was promoted to the active roster Dec. 10.
</P>
<P>
   Both Wadsworth and Moten are expected to play against the
Cowboys today at Texas Stadium in an NFC wild-card playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was happy Andre got his contract, and I knew I would get
another chance,'' Moten said. ``I just didn't know when. But, even
now, when I tell people what happened on the plane, they don't
believe me. I wasn't mad. I'm just glad the way everything went
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly four months later, Wadsworth acknowledges that playing
against the Cowboys one day after he signed was bizarre. He hadn't
even practiced with the team, except for a three-day minicamp last
May.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't put on full pads since the (bowl) game,'' said
Wadsworth, the third pick overall in the 1998 draft out of Florida
State. ``I don't think I'd ever been that unprepared.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the health risks, Bob Ferguson, Cardinals vice
president-player personnel, agreed with the coaches' decision to
play Wadsworth immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was excited to get on the field,'' Ferguson said of
Wadsworth. ``Like Vince (Cardinals Coach Vince Tobin), I say, `Put
him out there and let him play.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Wadsworth assisted on one tackle in the game. He also put heat
on Cowboys quarterback Troy Aikman on one play and drew a holding
penalty on offensive tackle Erik Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I did all right for a pop quiz,'' Wadsworth said.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals defensive coordinator Dave McGinnis thinks Wadsworth,
who finished the regular-season with 5{ sacks, will become a
dominant player next year after going through a training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, the two reminisced about their last trip to
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Andre, we're going back to where it all started,' ''
McGinnis said. ``I told him it seems like it was 100 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been through a lot in this league. I've been through two
strike teams _ the ``Spare'' Bears and the real Bears, but I never
had been through anything like that, one guy signing and playing
the next day and another guy having to be taken off the plane. That
was hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't know what Andre could do that day. We didn't know
what Andre could do in the NFL. We knew what he could do at Florida
State.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we found out what kind of person Andre was. He felt awful
about what happened to Mike. Then, when we brought Mike back, Andre
was the guy who went to get him.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
