<HEADLINE>
GRAHAM CAN'T MEET TICKET DEMAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cardinals center Aaron Graham grew up in Denton, Texas, and said
playing in the NFL playoffs in Texas Stadium was his boyhood dream.
He also said he could use ``probably 500 tickets'' for family and
friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a rookie, I bought 50 tickets when we played
there,'' Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys made only 500 tickets available to the Cardinals. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Loaner ball?
</P>
<P>
   After Cowboys running back Emmitt Smith broke the NFL record for
rushing touchdowns with two against the Redskins in the
regular-season finale, giving him 125, the Pro Football Hall of
Fame came calling _ and Smith put them on hold. His father advised
him to keep all the balls he scored touchdowns with, and he has 121
of them in his possession. He has given four of them away, three to
teammates and one to a Vietnam veteran he met in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave me a Congressional Medal of Honor,'' Smith said. ``He
had one simple request _ the first touchdown I scored that year
(1995), he wanted me to dedicate to him. I told him I'd do better
than that. The first one I scored, I'd send him the football.''
</P>
<P>
   On the request from Canton, Smith said: ``I might loan it to
them, as long as I get it back.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
After-Christmas sale &QL; 
 &QL; 
Phoenix artist Bill Tomsa has been sitting across from the
Cardinals practice facility this week, trying to sell two acrylic
paintings. One, titled ``Center of Attention,'' depicts Larry
Centers walking past fans. The other, called ``Birds of a
Feather,'' shows Cardinals paraphernalia. Asking price: $1,750
each.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an excellent time to be out here,'' said Tomsa, who
did the paintings for a show during Super Bowl XXX. He said he has
one potential buyer for the Centers picture.
</P>
<P>
   He also has a third Cardinals-related painting that's not for
sale, but it may turn out to be a prediction. In the rendition, a
newspaper gives a final score: Cardinals 35, Cowboys 0. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Extra points
</P>
<P>
   Keith Brown, who has been the team chaplain for the Cardinals
and Suns for 11 years, will be in Dallas to hold a prayer service _
and he's paying his own way.
</P>
<P>
   It will be the first road trip this season for Brown, who is
also the football coach at Phoenix Christian High School, will
conduct the service at the team hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Metcalf is third all-time in the playoffs with 22 kick
returns for 499 yards. The leader in number of returns is former
Cardinal Kevin Williams, now a member of the Bills. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
