<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 02:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5139 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  PM-BUDGET-NYT     01-02 1631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
 (js) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For SATURDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Saturday, Jan. 2.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA-DEFECTORS (Phnom Penh) _ Hun Sen, the Cambodian leader,
responding to criticism for his statement that defecting Khmer
Rouge leaders should be met with bouquets rather than handcuffs,
said he favors punishing them, but that it is the province of the
courts to decide. Earlier, a Khmer Rouge spokesman suggested
putting the U.S. on trial for its bombing of Cambodia. By Seth
Mydans. (With map)
</P>
<P>
   EURO (Frankfurt, Germany) _ Thursday was a day for champagne and
confetti. Friday began the long weekend of strong coffee and
takeout food as financial institutions in Europe began the daunting
job of re-programming their electronic networks for the euro era
before the markets open for business on Monday. By Edmund L.
Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   EURO-INVEST (Undated) _ Many investment managers believe that
the planned changes from adopting a single monetary policy for much
of Europe will offer opportunities to profit for years to come.
They believe Europe could see a period of prosperity not dissimilar
to what occurred in the United States in the 1980s and 1990s from
U.S. corporations' efforts to downsize and restructure themselves.
By Reed Abelson.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-ANNIVERSARY (Santiago de Cuba, Cuba) _ It has been 40 years
since Fidel Castro declared the end of the Batista dictatorship.
For residents here, it has been 40 years of socialism, economic
sacrifice and endless maneuvering in a cold war with the United
States. But on Friday it was hard to find anyone on the streets who
would openly criticize the 72-year-old Cuban leader or his
policies. By James C. McKinley Jr. (With photo)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   METHADONE-POLICY (New York) _ Methadone frees, but it also
imprisons. It is a wizard at blocking the yearning for heroin, but
much less so the simple craving to get high. It is highly addictive
in its own right, with fiendish withdrawal symptoms. At more than
moderate doses, it can leave some patients in a barely functional
daze. All of which goes a long way toward explaining why methadone
has long been caught in the cross-currents of social policy, though
never more so than right now in New York. By N.R. Kleinfield. (With
photo)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-RENAISSANCE (Hilton Head, S.C.) _ President Clinton rang
out his most unusual of years in his usual, if peculiar, way: in
very earnest policy discussion with more than a thousand
acquaintances and fans _ and a few old friends and unimpressed
strangers _ assembled at the annual Renaissance Weekend here. By
James Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   CONSERVATIVE-RETREAT (Phoenix) _ A journal: Conservatives rang
out their year at the Weekender retreat, formerly known as the Dark
Ages Weekend where disgust with the president is so pervasive that
he seems to have replaced the Soviet Union as the organizing
principle around which conservatives can rally. By Katharine Q.
Seelye. (With photos)
</P>
<P>
   MISSOURI-RIVER (Nebraska City, Neb.) _ Big changes are coming to
the Missouri River, America's longest, stretching from Three Forks,
Mont., to St. Louis. The fracas over the river's future is fierce
as environmentalists, farmers, barge operators, recreation
boosters, hydroelectric utilities, Indian tribes and municipal
leaders all try to make sure the river stays _ or becomes _ what
they want it to be. By Pam Belluck. (With photo and map)
</P>
<P>
   SANFRAN-CITY-HALL (San Francisco) _ Not since the 1920s has the
sunlight glinted so brightly from San Francisco's City Hall dome, a
shapely structure taller than the 90-foot dome of the capitol in
Washington. The landmark building and its dome were closed for more
than three years of renovation, but beginning Tuesday, San
Franciscans will once again be able to step inside their Beaux-Arts
seat of government. By Bill Staggs. (With photo)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-BUDGET (Washington) _ Heeding warnings from the
nation's military chiefs, President Clinton has decided to propose
the first real increase in the Pentagon's budget in nearly a decade
and the largest since the Cold War buildup of the mid-1980s,
administration and defense officials said. By Steven Lee Myers.
(With photo)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MARKETS-FOREIGN (Undated) _ Overseas stocks rebounded sharply in
the fourth quarter, both in developed and emerging markets. But in
some emerging markets even 100 percent rallies were not enough to
make up for the sell-offs that pushed stocks to their lows just as
the quarter began. Many of these markets still ended the year with
declines. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   CASPIAN-OIL (Balakhani, Azerbaijan) _ Even after taking into
account the drop in oil prices, the rush of energy development in
the Caspian region is expected to cause cash to pour into the
treasuries of Azerbaijan, Kazakhstan and Turkmenistan. All three
nations will probably have more than enough money to guarantee
every citizen a comfortable life. But while oil money has made some
countries prosperous, it has helped destroy others. By Stephen
Kinzer. (With photo and graphic)
</P>
<P>
   CADBURY-STRATEGY (Undated) _ By agreeing to sell nearly all its
international beverage business to the Coca-Cola Co., Cadbury
Schweppes PLC made it clear last month that it was leaving the
global soft-drink field to Coca-Cola and Pepsico Inc. What is less
clear is Cadbury's strategy for its remaining soft-drink business,
which will now be concentrated in its most profitable market, the
United States. By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   CURRENCY-STABILITY (Undated) _ Last year's dominant economic
story might be summed up this way: When currencies float, economies
sink. From Thailand to Russia, many nations' currencies floated
when their exchange rates against the U.S. dollar collapsed, often
under pressure from speculators. Now, that currency-induced turmoil
has shaken some core assumptions of modern economics. By Joseph
Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   OIL-U.S. (Gillette, Wyo.) _ The lowest oil prices in two decades
are shutting down of vast swaths of the nation's oil industry. Low
prices and foreign competition, which favor the Exxons and Mobils
over the wildcatter mean that the oilman in jeans and boots,
legendary for his enterprise and daring, is giving way to the
oilman in a suit. By Allen R. Myerson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RICH-COLUMN (New York) _ Perpetual New Year's Eve anxiety is
officially here. The annual societal pressure that New Year's Eve
be the bubbliest, happiest, most spiritual and yet entertaining
night of the whole year is already rising to a previously
unimaginable pitch for Dec. 31, 1999. By Frank Rich.
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (Moved in ``e'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LIBRARIES (Undated) _ It was the year of the library. Last
summer, London inaugurated the new British Library; in October,
Paris witnessed the grand opening of the new National Library of
France; the next month the New York Public Library unveiled its
renovation of the Main Reading Room at its flagship 42nd Street
branch. The great library race: New York vs. London vs. Paris.
(With graphic)
</P>
<P>
   GRAPHIC-NOVELS (Undated) _ Graphic novels, like those done by
Will Eisner and Art Spiegelman get serious attention. By Sarah
Boxer.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE-AGES-RETURN (Undated) _ Is it possible that cyberspace
and economic globalization are pushing the modern world back into
the Middle Ages? The idea is that the existing system of nation
states might be replaced, in the words of Oxford's Hedley Bull, by
``a modern and secular equivalent of the kind of universal
political organization that existed in Western Christendom in the
Middle Ages.'' By Paul Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   NEWYEAR-RESOLVE (Undated) _ How do your New Year's resolutions
stack up against Epictetus's?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FBC-RHODEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports of The Times column on the
glut of bowl games on Jan. 1, even though they have been
essentially rendered meaningless. By William C. Rhoden.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-ROSE-BOWL (Pasadena, Calif.) _ Now UCLA will not have to
wonder about the national championship that could have been. Not
after Friday, when Wisconsin beat the Bruins, 38-31, in the 85th
Rose Bowl. By Ken Gurnick.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-SUGAR-BOWL (New Orleans) _ The Buckeyes (11-1) were able to
hold on and defeat Texas A&AMP;M 24-14. Now, the Buckeyes must wait for
the outcome of Monday's Fiesta Bowl game between Tennessee and
Florida State to determine whether they can finish campaigning for
a national championship. By Timothy Smith.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-FIESTA-SEMINOLES (Tempe, Ariz.) _ Florida State sneaked into
the national championship game in typical college football fashion:
they lost early, surged late and then watched the other contending
teams lose on the last major weekend. A feature about the team as
it prepares for the Fiesta Bowl on Monday. By Joe Drape.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-PLAYOFFS (Miami) _ The NFL playoffs begin Saturday with two
wild-card games: Arizona at Dallas, and Buffalo at Miami. An
advance on all four wild-card games over the weekend. By Mike
Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-NBA-LABOR (Undated) _ The National Basketball Association
owners finally got a glimpse of the union's latest proposal Friday.
The only problem was that they found out about the players'
compromises through the news media.
</P>
<P>
   By Mike Wise.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NYT News Service &LR;  &QL;
</P>
