<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-SERIES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORDON, `LITTLE E' DOMI NANT PERFORMERS 
</HEADLINE>
 LOOKBACK-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A look back at the major developments on the major racing
circuits during the 1998 season: &QL; 
 &QL; 
NASCAR Winston Cup
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998 champion: Jeff Gordon, No. 24 DuPont Automotive Finishes
Chevrolet Monte Carlo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reviewing 1998: Gordon, 27, nearly was invincible. Boy Wonder
won 13 of 33 races, tying Richard Petty's modern-era record, and
recorded a remarkable 26 top-five finishes. If not for Gordon,
runner-up Mark Martin might have been the unstoppable driver.
Martin won a career-high seven races, had 22 top-five and 26 top-10
finishes, yet still finished a distant second by 364 points.
Chevrolet won the manufacturer's title, but the Ford Taurus,
NASCAR's first four-door stock car, wasn't the lemon so many Ford
teams cried it was before the season's first race. Chevy drivers
won 16 races, followed by Ford (15) and Pontiac (two).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Previewing 1999: Records are made to be broken, and rules are
made to be changed. A new test session procedure will go into
effect, possibly reducing a major multicar team advantage. Although
teams still receive seven tests throughout the season, four must
take place at Daytona (Fla.) International Speedway, Talladega
(Ala.) Superspeedway, Charlotte (N.C.) Motor Speedway and
Indianapolis Motor Speedway, and all will be run by the Ford and
General Motors manufacturers and monitored by NASCAR officials.
Chevy will debut a new Monte Carlo in May at Charlotte. Team Gordon
is developing the super speedway version of the new hardware. &QL; 
NASCAR Busch Series
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998 champion: Dale Earnhardt Jr., No. 3 ACDelco Chevrolet
Monte Carlo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reviewing 1998: The younger Earnhardt, now known as ``Little
E,'' made a dramatic entrance into big time stock-car racing.
Despite a rocky start, it wasn't long before he began to audition
for a future position as Winston Cup king. Earnhardt Jr., won seven
races and edged Matt Kenseth, another emerging star, for the
driving title.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Previewing 1999: Earnhardt Jr. will spend another season in the
Busch Series but also will make five Winston Cup starts. And guess
who is scheduled to make five Busch starts? You guessed it, Jeff
Gordon. Unfortunately for Valley race fans, Gordon has said he
won't make one of those Busch starts at Phoenix International
Raceway, which was added to next season's schedule. No word yet on
whether Earnhardt will make PIR's Winston Cup race one of his
starts. But keep your fingers crossed. &QL; 
NASCAR Craftsman Trucks
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998 champion: Ron Hornaday, NAPA Brakes Chevrolet.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reviewing 1998: What a season and what a fierce battle between
Hornaday and defending series champion Jack Sprague. The two
drivers not only delivered some memorable on-track skirmishes, but
also a war of words off the racetrack. In the end, Hornaday (six
wins) won a second championship in four years, edging Sprague (five
wins) by a scant three points.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Previewing 1999: Both Hornaday and Sprague are returning, but
at the moment, third-place finisher Joe Ruttman is not. Ruttman was
told to take a walk by his car owner and is being replaced by Mike
Bliss. Tony Raines (three wins), Stacy Compton (two) and Bliss were
the only other drivers to bag more than one trip into victory lane
last year. &QL; 
CART
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998 champion: Alex Zanardi, No. 1 Target/Chip Ganassi Racing
Reynard-Honda.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reviewing 1998: For the second successive season, Zanardi led
all drivers in wins (seven) and points. Jimmy Vasser, Zanardi's
teammate, won three races and finished runner-up in the series.
Up-and-coming Dario Franchitti also won three times and led all
drivers with five pole positions, one more than Greg Moore.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Previewing 1999: In an effort to reduce downforce and contain
escalating speeds on short ovals, the aerodynamic packages used
this season on intermediate ovals at Homestead-Miami Speedway, Twin
Ring Motegi in Japan and Gateway International (Ill.) Raceway also
will be in effect at Nazareth (Pa.) Speedway, The Milwaukee Mile
and the new Chicago Motor Speedway. Because of on-track incidents
this past season, Paul Tracy is suspended for the March 21 season
opener at Miami. Keep an eye on Franchitti. He may be your next
CART champion. &QL; 
Indy Racing League
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998 champion: Kenny Brack, No. 14 A.J. Foyt Enterprises/Power
Team Racing Dallara-Aurora.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reviewing 1998: Five drivers led more laps, but Brack still won
a series-high three races. Eddie Cheever, a native Phoenician, won
the Indianapolis 500, and Billy Boat of Glendale was a qualifying
blur. Boat captured six pole positions, and Tony Stewart had four.
Despite what many fans think of the IRL, it has a loyal following.
And no one can criticize what happened on the racetrack, which
produced several exciting races.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Previewing 1999: Tony Stewart, once tabbed as the IRL poster
boy, has departed for the NASCAR Winston Cup circuit. Several IRL
racetracks still are struggling at the box office, and one of them
_ New Hampshire International Speedway _ has decided to throw in
the towel and won't return. Texas Motor Speedway, however, draws
well, and will host the season finale instead of Las Vegas. Several
night races have boosted attendance, and Pikes Peak International
Raceway now has two races. Of course, the Indy 500 continues to be
a sellout, with an estimated crowd in excess of 300,000. FOX Sports
and FOX Sports Net have joined the world of motorsports and will
televise 9 of 11 races. ABC will televise the remaining two,
including the Indy 500. &QL; 
Formula One
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998 champion: Mika Hakkinen, No. 8 McLaren-Mercedes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reviewing 1998: Michael Schumacher may be not only the world's
greatest driver but its richest one after signing a three-year
contract extension worth an estimated $42 million a year. Maybe the
money will allow Schumacher to rest easier after finishing as
series runner-up for the second straight year. Still, Schumacher
won six races when early on it appeared Hakkinen and teammate David
Coulthard might run the table.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Previewing 1999: Can Alex Zanardi do what CART champion Jacques
Villeneuve did two years ago, which is follow up the CART title
with the F-1 crown the next year? Villeneuve has left Williams and
signed with the new British American Racing team, and Zanardi has
replaced Villeneuve at Williams. McLaren and Ferrari still are the
teams to beat. &QL; 
National Hot Road Association
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998 champions: Gary Scelzi, Team Winston Top Fuel Dragster;
John Force, Castrol GTX Ford Mustang Funny Car; Warren Johnson, GM
Goodwrench Service Plus Pontiac Firebird Pro Stock; Matt Hines,
Vance &AMP; Hines Racing Suzuki Pro Stock Motorcycle.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reviewing 1998: Scelzi made it two straight, and Force now has
won six in a row and eight of the past nine. Johnson (nine wins)
had a monster season after two straight championship runs by Jim
Yates. And Hines has won two successive titles, this time beating
runner-up Angelle Seeling.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Previewing 1999: NHRA officials apparently have decided not to
implement rules to curb escalating speeds, much to the happiness of
Top Fuel and Funny Car drivers, who maintain the 325 mph speeds are
safe. Teams are confident Goodyear Tire &AMP; Rubber Co. has remained
ahead of the speed game, supplying them with rubber that not only
meets safety requirements, but also tremendous adhesion. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
