<SLUG> BC-CAR-1998YEAR-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1998 A SEASON FOR THE BOOKS  
 YEAR SAW BOTH TRAGEDY, TRIUMPH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Clearly, it was a season filled with good tidings as well as
dark moments.
</P>
<P>
   For Jeff Gordon, it was a season for the ages.
</P>
<P>
   For Al Unser Jr., it was a third consecutive season in which he
failed to crack victory lane.
</P>
<P>
   Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there was the horrible tragedy in late July at Michigan
Speedway. After a single-car accident, an errant wheel flew into a
section of the Turn 4 grandstands, resulting in three spectator
deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Controversy also reared its head during the NASCAR Winston Cup
season, which is nothing new. But this time it involved alleged
cheating by Team Gordon, which was accused by car owner Jack Roush
of doctoring its Goodyear Eagle radial tires with an illegal
softening compound.
</P>
<P>
   Please.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, Dale Earnhardt finally won the Daytona 500, and John
Force won a sixth-successive National Hot Rod Association Funny Car
championship, yet didn't need to win 9,000 races to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most significant story of the year, however, had
nothing to do with an on-track event.
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis Motor Speedway President Tony George announced the
famed Brickyard would be the site of a Formula One race beginning
in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   That's the good news.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is the ongoing rift that separates Championship
Auto Racing Teams and George's Indy Racing League continued to
cause open-wheel headaches.
</P>
<P>
   Although there were terrific races in both circuits, how many
were watching? Television ratings are poor as fans are left to pick
and choose between the two series. At some IRL venues, attendance
was abysmal; so abysmal that New Hampshire International Speedway
discontinued scheduling IRL races.
</P>
<P>
   The recently concluded season also meant retirement for Bobby
Rahal, who despite going winless over the past six seasons remains
one of the sport's all-time greats.
</P>
<P>
   Arie Luyendyk, who moved to Scottsdale eight years ago, also
decided to call it quits. Luyendyk recently announced he will make
next May's Indianapolis 500 the final act of his career, although
he hasn't ruled out future sports-car endeavors at Le Mans and
Daytona International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   That's it. Turn out the lights, the 1998 racing party finally is
over. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-02-99 0230EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
