r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-1998-BESTANDWORST     01-02 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-1998-BEST </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1998 RACING SEASON'S BESTS AND WORSTS 
</HEADLINE>
 AND WORST-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Season's best &QL; 
 &UR; Best race: If not for the tragic accident that resulted in three
spectator fatalities, Championship Auto Racing Teams' U.S. 500
easily would be the top pick. Some consider the race the best in
history. Non-stop action. Three-hour, seat-of-the-pants racing.
Yet, three fans died. So the choice goes to the Indy Racing
League's True Value 500K at Texas Motor Speedway.
 &UR; Greg Ray put both left-side wheels in the grass attempting to pass
 &UR; Billy
 &UR; Boat in the final few laps. Boat survived and won by .928 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Best moment:  &UR; Dale Earnhardt winning the Daytona 500. If you
believe in the conspiracy theory, then you probably believe NASCAR
officials helped make Earnhardt's win possible. Doesn't matter. He
won. And what a grand moment it was.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Best ad-lib:  &UR; A.J. Foyt smashing a laptop computer in the pits
at the Indy 500 after his team miscalculated fuel mileage for
 &UR; Kenny Brack.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Best rags-to-riches story: Dale Earnhardt Jr. Nice guy doesn't
finish last. He finishes first, capturing the NASCAR Busch Series
championship.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Best performance by a runner-up:  &UR; Mark Martin. Do you get the
feeling that whenever Martin talks, you always get the honest
truth? Martin had a career season, yet never sulked.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Best set of lungs: John Force. Don't ever try to interview this
guy without a tape recorder. He can talk 10 minutes straight
without stopping to take a breath.  &UR; Michael Jordan goes through
several pairs of sneakers a season. Force goes through a year's
supply of Sucrets in seven days.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Best quote: ``No Chevy is going to win the championship this
year.'' Who said that? Crew chief  &UR; Ray Evernham following the Las
Vegas 400, a race dominated by Ford Taurus drivers. Oh, by the way.
Evernham is  &UR; Jeff Gordon's chief mechanic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Best driver you might never have heard of: Indiana teenager
 &UR; Boston Reid. Watch out for this sprint-car driver. He may be the
next Gordon. That's Jeff, not Robby. Runner-up?  &UR; Juan Pablo
Montoya.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Best driver never to win a major championship: Where do we
start?  &UR; Paul
 &UR; Tracy?  &UR; Mark Martin?  &UR; Cory McClenathan? Why not  &UR; Robby Gordon?
Gordon soon will announce 1999 CART plans, and let's hope it's with
a contending team so he can display those immeasurable talents.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Best drive: Ageless  &UR; Ivan Stewart winning another Baja 1000
championship. Stewart should move to New York and start a taxi cab
company. No one can negotiate more potential potholes and
roadblocks than Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Best television analyst without a job: Derek Daly. Some people
don't like his style. Not me. He should be working somewhere. &QL; 
 &UR; Season's worst &QL; 
 &UR; Worst race: Pontiac ``U''n-Excitement 400. Yawn. Don't forget to
turn out the lights. Come to think about it, the Las Vegas 400
wasn't all that exciting, either.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Worst crash: A tie between  &UR; Michael Andretti's amazing
non-injury accident at Mid-Ohio and the Formula One race in Belgium
that twice had to be restarted because of opening lap demolition
derbies. How did Andretti escape injury? Although he wound up in
the sand and looked like Pig Pen from the ``Peanuts'' cartoon when
he climbed from the car, Andretti was in one piece. Whew!
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Worst controversy: Car owner  &UR; Jack Roush accusing &UR; Jeff Gordon's
team of illegally tampering with his team's tires.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Worst cloak and dagger scene: Foyt accusing someone of
illegally entering team's garage in Gasoline Alley. Where's Lt.
Columbo when you need him?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Worst performance by a former champion: Car owner  &UR; Roger
Penske. What's happened to this once-dominant team?  &UR; Al Unser Jr.
and  &UR; Andre Ribeiro were mostly non-threats. No way that should
happen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Worst traffic jam: Dura-Lube/Kmart 500 at Phoenix International
Raceway. Except for the race washing away the final 52 laps or so,
there were no problems on the racetrack. But a crowd in excess of
100,000 had to battle aggravating traffic congestion before and
after the race.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Worst decision: Adding a second IRL race at Pikes Peak
International Raceway. Why?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Worst decision II: Pairing television analysts  &UR; Buddy Baker
with Dr.  &UR; Dick
 &UR; Berggren. Baker is as good as there is, and Berggren is
terrifically knowledgeable, but when they're together, they just
don't seem to mesh.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Worst rumor: Gossip that  &UR; Mike Skinner would not return to
Richard Childress Racing in 1999. Guess what? He's back.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Worst memory: The empty section of the Turn 4 grandstands at
Michigan Speedway, which was cleared of spectators after a wheel
flew into the crowd. Shouldn't the race have been stopped?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Worst financial investment: Come on, now. I don't care
if &UR; Michael
 &UR; Schumacher could put a horse and buggy on the pole at Monaco, no
driver is worth $42 million a season or whatever the ridiculous
amount he is being paid. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
