<HEADLINE>
ALL-1998 RACING TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
 TEAM-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Arizona Republic's All-1998 Racing Team. The envelope,
please . . . &QL; 
 &UR; DRIVER OF THE YEAR &QL; 
 &UR; Jeff Gordon
</P>
<P>
   Can you spell d-o-m-i-n-a-n-t? Gordon won 13 NASCAR Winston Cup
races and finished outside the top five about as often as A.J. Foyt
wears a tie. Critics maintain any driver could have climbed behind
Gordon's steering wheel and delivered the same performance. Bull. &QL; 
 &UR; 2. Alex Zanardi
</P>
<P>
   There were many secrets falling into the worst kept category
throughout the year, but few could match the rumor of Zanardi's
impending departure to Formula One. Although Zanardi is pulling a
Jacques Villeneuve and leaving the Championship Auto Racing Teams
circuit after seven wins and a second straight championship, at
least he is leaving in style. Zanardi clinched the title in race
No. 15 of a 19-race season. Now that's getting the job done. &QL;  &UR; 3.
Mika Hakkinen
</P>
<P>
   Ferrari's Michael Schumacher easily could be in this position.
In a Formula One season in which McLaren-Mercedes (Hakkinen and
teammate David Coulthard) was a heavy preseason favorite,
Schumacher still won six races and took Hakkinen down to the wire.
But Hakkinen was brilliant. He could have wilted under Schumacher's
constant pressure, but he won eight races, including the season
finale to capture the crown. That's a record worth rewarding. &QL;   &UR; 4.
 &UR; Michael Schumacher
</P>
<P>
   See above. &QL;   &UR; 5. Mark Martin
</P>
<P>
   If not for Gordon, the gritty Martin would have sat at
Waldorf-Astoria's head table during the NASCAR awards banquet.
Martin had a career year by winning seven races and finishing in
the top five almost as often as Gordon. But as Gordon is proving,
banner seasons aren't nearly enough. &QL;   &UR; 6. Dale
 &UR; Earnhardt Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Where in the name of Valvoline did this good-natured kid come
from? Sure, we knew there was an Earnhardt Jr. out there trying to
scratch out a short-track living. But who could have guessed he'd
jump into the NASCAR Busch Series and treat it as if he'd been
around for a dozen years? ``Little E'' won seven races, four more
than anyone else, and also captured the title. Yes, he jumped into
a good seat, replacing Steve Parks on a team owned by his parents.
But the younger Earnhardt still had to produce. He did. &QL;   &UR; 7. Kenny
Brack
</P>
<P>
   Swedish driver won the Indy Racing League title, putting a smile
on car owner A.J. Foyt's face that will last until spring. Although
some might question the overall talent in the IRL, any gearhead
worth his or her salt knows Brack knows how to turn left. En route
to the championship, he won three races. In the end, he won more
than that. He won over Foyt. &QL;   &UR; 8. Warren
 &UR; Johnson
</P>
<P>
   Don't look now, Bob Glidden, but someone is nearing your
National Hot Rod Association winning record. Glidden, now retired,
has 85 career Pro Stock wins. Johnson, who drove into nine victory
lanes this season, now has 73. But the feisty Johnson also is 55
years old. Time will tell whether ``WJ'' still has enough giddy-up
left in his tank to overtake Glidden. &QL;   &UR; 9. Gary
 &UR; Scelzi
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of giddy-up, how about that Scelzi guy? A newcomer in
1997, Scelzi was hand-picked to replace the late Blaine Johnson,
and he responded with the NHRA Top Fuel championship in his rookie
season. He won another title in '98, which included six wins and
the fastest quarter-mile blip in NHRA history with an astonishing
326.44 mph blast at the Texas Motorplex. Scelzi also delivered the
second quickest pass in history with a 4.525-second run. &QL;   &UR; 10.
Dario Franchitti
</P>
<P>
   Franchitti didn't finish first or second in CART's final
standings _ he was No. 3 _ but he won three races, second only to
Zanardi. Compare those statistics to 1997, his rookie year, when
his best finish was ninth. Franchitti outdrove teammate Paul Tracy.
Give the Scotsman a cigar, but make him smoke it outside. &QL; 
 &QL;  &UR; Honorable mention
</P>
<P>
   Steve Kinser (World of Outlaws champion), Jason Leffler (U.S.
Auto Club Silver Crown and Midget champion), John Force (NHRA Funny
Car titlist), Dale Jarrett (NASCAR Winston Cup third-place
finisher), Ron Hornaday (NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series champion),
Jimmy Vasser (CART runner-up), Paul Gentilozzi (Sports Car Club of
America Trans-Am champion), Matt Kenseth (Busch runner-up) and Tony
Stewart (IRL third-place finisher). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
