<HEADLINE>
ASU COMBINES SWIM PROGRAMS  
 WOMEN'S COACH FIRED 
</HEADLINE>
 SWIMMING-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a move most surprising because of the in-season timing,
Arizona State is combining its swim programs under first-year men's
Coach Mike Chasson and firing 14th-year women's Coach Tim Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Hill was placed on administrative &QL; 
leave this week, and his contract will not be renewed.
</P>
<P>
   The decision came after a formal monthlong committee study of
problems with attrition in the women's program that affect
competitive results and graduation rates.
</P>
<P>
   When seniors Carrie Anderson and Kelly Wilson quit early this
season, which began in October and continues through March, ASU was
left with one senior, Tiffany Houser, from a class that began with
eight. The junior class that once was 15 now is seven. Staff
turnover also has been high.
</P>
<P>
   Hill's teams had slipped from five top-10 NCAA finishes in the
late 1980s and early '90s to 23rd, 28th and 29th in the past three
seasons. The Sun Devils are ranked 21st in the most recent Speedo
America College Swimming Coaches Association top 25.
</P>
<P>
   ASU athletic department officials are restricted in their
comments about Hill's release because of university policy, but
associate athletic director Sandy Hatfield Clubb said her committee
did extensive research into the issue of combined vs. separate
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our initial thought was to find another Mike Chasson on the
women's side,'' Hatfield Clubb said. ``We're committed to hiring
women coaches for women's teams when we can do that. But the
(female coaching) pool is very small in swimming, very much like in
track.''
</P>
<P>
   So after studying successful combined programs, including the
University of Arizona under Frank Busch, the 1998 USA Swimming
Coach of the Year, and Southern California, with U.S. 2000 Olympic
men's Coach Mark Schubert, as well as the standout separate
programs at Stanford and Texas, a decision was made to combine.
</P>
<P>
   ASU officially combined its men's and women's track teams under
a single head coach, now Greg Kraft, in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Hatfield Clubb said positives of a combined program include a
higher-quality training environment, particularly for the women,
and better morale and respect between the men's and women's
swimmers. The biggest negatives for a relatively small staff are
recruiting demands and getting over the top to a national title.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our swimming image is one that needs some rebuilding on both
the men's and women's side to attract that national U.S. kid,'' she
said. ``We believe combining the program will help facilitate that
more quickly since the top prospects all come from combined (club)
programs.''
</P>
<P>
   The recruiting issue has become especially sensitive in recent
years because local elite high schoolers such as Misty Hyman
(Stanford), Sarah Tolar and Emily Mastin (both UA) are excelling
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Wales, who was working with the men, and Heather
Johnston, Hill's first-year assistant, will serve on Chasson's
staff, along with Derigan Silver, promoted from graduate assistant.
Mark Bradshaw is in his second season as diving coach.
</P>
<P>
   Hatfield Clubb said a national search for two assistants will be
held after the season, with Johnston and Silver able to reapply.
</P>
<P>
   Chasson, 46, came to ASU from Harvard after the retirement of
men's Coach Ernie Maglischo. He has coached a combined team (Los
Altos and Santa Barbara swim clubs) and was assistant women's coach
at Stanford before taking the Harvard men's head coaching job in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike has a terrific plan moving into this new combined
program,'' Hatfield Clubb said. ``He's already got the guys
swimming faster than ever.''
</P>
<P>
   The ASU men are ranked 11th nationally, one spot below their
1998 NCAA finish. At the Texas Invitational in early December,
senior All-America Francisco Sanchez broke meet records in the 50-
and 100-yard freestyles and was part of two record-setting free
relays.
</P>
<P>
   The ASU men (1-2) will return to dual-meet competition Friday
against Brigham Young. The men and women (2-2-1) then will host
Utah on Jan. 9. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
