<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-STARS-COYOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HULL, STARS SINK COYOTES IN BATTLE OF WEST'S BEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ It has to be destiny.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars simply can't be stopped right now. Heck, they can't
even be slowed down.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with the possibility of swallowing a disappointing tie
with the Phoenix Coyotes, the Stars came up with their first
overtime victory of the season and extended their franchise record
unbeaten streak to 14 games (11-0-3) with a 2-1 victory last night.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get on a roll, those things tend to go right for
you,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``And right now, things are
going right.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Coyotes tied the game with 32.6 seconds remaining in
regulation on a Deron Quint goal with the extra skater on the ice,
the Stars appeared to have finally had too much hockey in too short
a time. Playing on back-to-back nights against a hungry pack of
Coyotes, a tie seemed a noble defeat.
</P>
<P>
   But Mike Modano wouldn't hear of it. The Stars center finished
off a heroic night with a heroic play as he set up Brett Hull for
the game-winner 37 seconds into the extra period.
</P>
<P>
   Modano took a pass from linemate Jere Lehtinen and fought
through the check of Coyotes defenseman Keith Carney, falling to
the ice while diving over Carney's stick. But keeping his head
about him, Modano was able to sweep a pass to Hull, who was
trailing down the right wing, and the sniper popped in his
team-leading 13th goal.
</P>
<P>
   The play sucked the juice right out of an arena bent on making a
point against the league-leading Stars. With the Coyotes playing
without their first line of Keith Tkachuk (broken rib), Jeremy
Roenick (concussion) and Dallas Drake (suspension) _ a trio that
has combined for 37 goals _ the Coyotes wanted to prove something
in a Pacific Division battle matching the teams with the two best
winning percentages in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to make a statement, and I think they did to some
extent,'' Stars defenseman Craig Ludwig said. ``They wanted this
game.''
</P>
<P>
   As did the Stars. Despite missing defenseman Richard Matvichuk
with a charley horse and missing New Year's Eve festivities after
having flown after a game in Dallas the night before, the Stars
were in no mood to be charitable.
</P>
<P>
   So, they ran their league-best record to 24-5-6, moved eight
points ahead of the Coyotes (21-8-4) in the standings, and matched
this season's NHL-best 14-game unbeaten streak, ironically enough,
set by the Coyotes earlier in the season.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Stars goalie Roman Turek stayed undefeated at
6-0-2, the Stars set a franchise record for longest road unbeaten
streak (nine games) and the Stars' power play proved itself by
scoring against the best penalty killers in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   That power-play goal appeared to be the turning point in the
game as Modano scored off a smooth pass from Lehtinen at the 4:24
mark of the third period. The game had been dominated by Turek and
Coyotes' goalie Nikolai Khabibulin until that time, but the Stars
scored their league-best 41st power-play goal against a Coyotes
penalty kill that was yielding its 16th.
</P>
<P>
   That goal looked to be the game-winner as both teams played
physical defense for the remainder of the period. But Quint was
able to stuff in the rebound of a Shane Doan shot with 32.6 seconds
remaining, and the Coyotes appeared to have made their point.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing. You're going against the best team in the
league while you're missing your three big guns, and you have a
chance to win the game,'' Quint said. ``There's no question we were
in there, and we gave them a little scare, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   Ludwig agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a playoff game,'' he said. ``It's the kind of game we
might have to play against that team in the playoffs, if it comes
to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the records say it could.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
