<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 10:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5171 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABR-RUSSIA-BITTER-CAP     01-02 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABR-RUSSIA-BITTER-CAPITALISM-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLOOM DESCENDS ON RUSSIANS AS HOPES OF QUICK CAPITALISM FADE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: A full-length version of this story,
RUSSIA-BITTER-CAPITALISM, has also be transmitted.) 
(js) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON and CELESTINE BOHLEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ It was near midnight seven years ago when a vast crowd
gathered outside KGB headquarters here as four cranes hoisted from
its pedestal a statue of a hated man: Felix Dzerzhinsky, founder of
the secret police that helped keep the Soviet Union in fear for 74
years.
</P>
<P>
   This month, Russia's Parliament voted to put the statue back.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the two events bookmarks in Russia's story.
</P>
<P>
   One opened an era of almost dizzy optimism about the nation's
prospects for the freedom and economic prosperity that have eluded
it for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   The other closed it. The extravagant hopes that a Western-style
capitalism would emerge straight away out of the ruins of the
Soviet empire are gone, buried in the financial collapse and mood
of bitter disappointment that have swept Russia this fall.
</P>
<P>
   After seven years of democracy, and economic disarray that has
passed for capitalism, Russians are more divided than ever about
which direction their country should go: whether to embrace the
West and its models, or to remain apart, wrapped in the solace of
Russia's historical peculiarities.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to reassure the nation, President Boris Yeltsin insisted
in a year-end message that free-market reforms would continue. Yet
many ordinary Russians think of reforms as a sidewalk game of
three-card monte: However often the cards are played, there is no
way they can win.
</P>
<P>
   On one thing, most of them concur: Yeltsin, who promised to lead
them safely out of Communism, has betrayed their trust. Polls show
him with the support of 1 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
   Even more telling of the widespread disillusionment, the most
popular politician in public opinion surveys is usually ``none of
the above.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I became disenchanted with the reformers three years ago, when
it became clear that reform is a battle for power, for the division
of property, and that there is no clear economic program,'' said
Nikita Makulov, 69, a retired system programmer whose monthly
pension today is worth all of $20.
</P>
<P>
   While the Yeltsin era may be drawing to a close, it is too soon
to write the epitaph for Russian reform. The re-establishment of
the Soviet Union's brutal totalitarian controls and the widespread
renationalization of factories and refineries seem the remotest of
possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   But Oleg N. Sysuyev, Yeltsin's deputy chief of staff, says it
could be several years before any further attempt to liberalize the
economy is possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're facing very difficult years; stagnation is possible,''
Sysuyev said in an interview. ``But a U-turn is not possible.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A quick snapshot of Russia today suggests something far beyond
stagnation. The nation's gross domestic product fell 5 percent in
1998 and experts predict a similar drop in 1999. Roughly half the
nation's business is conducted in barter.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the nation has made important _ even fundamental _ progress.
For all of its troubles, the country is in many ways unrecognizable
compared with the hulk of a nation Yeltsin inherited in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has become a noisy, even raucous democracy. Though often
subservient to economic interests, Russian media is uncensored. The
phenomenal rise of the Internet _ even the Communist Party has a
web site _ seems to insure there can be no retreat to the days when
the state defined reality.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is the economic news all bad. Moscow's streets, barren 15
years ago, now are jammed 18 hours a day; the number of autos has
tripled in seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Store shelves are no longer bare, although the foreign consumer
goods are often beyond the means of many Russians. Russians own
more home appliances than they could have dreamed of in Soviet
times.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the current period such a singularly bitter one is
the deep disillusionment over Russia's ability to pull itself out
of its quagmire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We underestimated the time it would take to prepare people for
reforms,'' Sergei V. Kiriyenko, the prime minister who was ousted
after the August crash, said in an interview. ``People did not
understand how much needed to be done to carry out the reforms or
the price they would have to pay to achieve them. And the
government maintained the illusion that it would be easy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Communists also threw a monkey wrench into the gears. They
used their control over the Parliament to block legislation that
would have provided the legal underpinnings for a new capitalist
order: the right to buy and sell land, protection for foreign
investors and the overhaul of an anachronistic tax system.
</P>
<P>
   And then the Aug. 17 financial crisis robbed the government of
its two greatest economic achievements: a stable currency and, by
Russian standards, relatively low inflation.
</P>
<P>
   It also robbed many Russians of their hope.
</P>
<P>
   The harshest realization for many Russians is the discovery that
one of the biggest obstacles to change lies within themselves. Even
reformers admit that they are still burdened by a mentality
bequeathed to them by a Soviet regime that squashed initiative,
fostered hypocrisy and taught its citizens to abdicate
responsibility for a government they never thought of as theirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia is the only one to blame for our situation, not the IMF
or the G-7,'' Sysuyev said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all their short-term pessimism, many Russians _ known
for their patience _ take a long view. Makulov looks to his son,
Alyosha, a mathematician who develops data bases for a private
company and whose salary supports his parents (even after it was
halved by the summer's financial crisis).
</P>
<P>
   ``He is different from me, of course,'' said the father. ``I
think that the next generation _ or maybe the next after that _
will find a way to make this potentially rich country rich. My
sense is that everything that is happening is movement in the right
direction, albeit by the most mistaken and painful of means. It
just wasn't thought through.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-02-99 1048EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990102.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 10:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5174 &Cx1f; tib-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      01-02 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: NO MORE WAGGING  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MAUREEN DOWD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As John McCain gets ready to be sworn in as a juror
in the Senate trial judging the president's sins, he must also
ponder how he will answer questions about his own sins, with all of
America sitting as the jury.
</P>
<P>
   After the Clinton trauma, will voters want to know more or less
about candidates' peccadilloes? Will they care more or less about
virtue in a president? Will they recoil from Republicans for
perceived hypocrisies?
</P>
<P>
   The 62-year-old senator from Arizona knows he is dropping his
handkerchief into the presidential ring in a weird and virulent
time.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to computer big shots recently, McCain drew an angry
reaction when he said he had a problem with the president's lying
under oath. ``One guy yelled that he'd rather have his daughter
raised by Larry Flynt than Bill Bennett,'' he recalls. ``I almost
fainted.''
</P>
<P>
   Back home in Phoenix after a Fiji vacation, the usually
unequivocal Republican equivocated about what should happen to
Clinton. ``One thing I don't believe in is a fine,'' he hedges.
``It would just mean an added tax on Barbra Streisand, Tom Hanks
and Steven Spielberg.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans are embarrassed by all this,'' he continues. ``They
want to have somebody straightforward we can rely on not to ever
wag his finger at us on any issue and say something that's not
true. At the same time, they want people's private lives not to be
in the public domain.'' (It's a campaign slogan: I won't wag the
dog or the finger.)
</P>
<P>
   He has admitted that his carousing, after his return from five
and a half years of torture and solitary confinement in a Hanoi
prison, broke up his first marriage. ``I think it depends how you
present yourself,'' he says. ``Are you the missionary from Somerset
Maugham's play `Rain'? Or are you the person who says, `Look, life
is full of mistakes and I've made mine and I acknowledge them'?''
</P>
<P>
   How did he persuade his reluctant wife to agree to a run? ``It
was like pulling teeth,'' he concedes. ``I promised her she does
not have to come to Iowa and New Hampshire. She's nothing along the
lines of the present first lady, whom I respect and admire, but
Cindy's not a lawyer or a political person. She just wants to raise
her family.''
</P>
<P>
   He says she will address her sins. In 1989, after back surgery
and during the Keating Five scandal, she became addicted to
painkillers and purloined some from a medical charity she ran. ``I
think people will understand Cindy's situation,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The senator is cherished by journalists for his quixotic fights
on campaign finance reform and tobacco, his scorn for pols driven
by polls or pork, and his loose tongue. He denounced Leonardo
DiCaprio as ``an androgynous wimp,'' and, speaking to
conservatives, trashed Al Gore for his Buddhist fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   But many Republicans resent him because he promotes virtue
without being a member of the Virtue Gang.
</P>
<P>
   How will he raise the millions he needs after preaching so
vociferously on the evils of big money? ``I'll just have to get
14,000 or 15,000 of my closest friends to give in thousand-dollar
chunks,'' he says, adding that he would not _ like Dan Quayle, Gary
Bauer, Lamar Alexander, Jack Kemp and John Ashcroft _ form a PAC in
Virginia where the laws permit unlimited contributions.
</P>
<P>
   How about that famed temper? ``Every time I've lost my temper
I've regretted it,'' he says. ``Those times have reduced in
frequency.''
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning for Phil Gramm in '96, McCain learned, ``Don't spend
all your money early.'' Then, campaigning for Bob Dole, he learned
that being a hero is not enough. ``You've got to be able to
transmit a message you truly believe in.'' From George Bush's '92
run, he learned it was folly to underestimate your opponent.
</P>
<P>
   The current boomer infatuation with war heroes and sports heroes
might give him a boost _ even though he modestly refuses to
acknowledge the honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, God, no,'' he says. ``It doesn't take any talent to get
shot down.''
</P>
<P>
   What did he take away from those long years in that dank cell in
Hanoi that would help him as president?
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to try to do the things you know you should do,'' he
says. ``Personally and politically, I have not always done the
right thing. But I have tried to do the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, senator, I ask, one final question: Boxers or briefs?
</P>
<P>
   ``None of your business,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   None of your business. It was music to my ears.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
