<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990102.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 11:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5182 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-BITTER-CAPITAL     01-02 1304
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BITTER-CAPITALISM-1STLD-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLOOM DESCENDS ON RUSSIANS AS HOPES OF QUICK CAPITALISM FADE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS 2nd graf to correct Parliament vote to last month. No other
changes.)  (js) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON and CELESTINE BOHLEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ It was near midnight seven years ago when a vast crowd
gathered outside KGB headquarters here as four cranes hoisted from
its pedestal a statue of a hated man: Felix Dzerzhinsky, founder of
the secret police that helped keep the Soviet Union in fear for 74
years.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Russia's Parliament voted to put the statue back.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the two events bookmarks in Russia's story.
</P>
<P>
   One opened an era of almost dizzy optimism about the nation's
prospects for the freedom and economic prosperity that have eluded
it for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   The other closed it. The extravagant hopes that a Western-style
capitalism would emerge straight away out of the ruins of the
Soviet empire are gone, buried in the financial collapse and mood
of bitter disappointment that have swept Russia this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over a Dzerzhinsky resurrection pinpoints a
disturbing split in Russian society, which is not only about ways
of looking back on history. After seven years of democracy, and
economic disarray that has passed for capitalism, Russians are more
divided than ever about which direction their country should go:
whether to embrace the West and its models, or to remain apart,
wrapped in the solace of Russia's historical peculiarities.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to reassure the nation, President Boris Yeltsin insisted
in a year-end message that crisis or not, free-market reforms would
continue. Yet many ordinary Russians have to think of reforms as a
sidewalk game of three-card monte. However often the cards are
played, Russians feel there is no way they can win.
</P>
<P>
   On one thing, most of them concur: Yeltsin, who promised to lead
them safely out of Communism, has betrayed their trust. Polls show
him with the support of 1 percent of the population _ roughly the
same level as that of his predecessor and nemesis, the former
Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
</P>
<P>
   Even more telling of the widespread disillusionment, the most
popular politician in public opinion surveys is usually ``none of
the above.''
</P>
<P>
   As Russians celebrated the coming of a new year, the jokes and
toasts all hinted at more gloom to come. There was a similar sense
of uncertainty back in January 1992 when Russia made its first leap
into a market economy. But then, at least, there was a hope that
change, however painful, was all for the good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pessimism has descended on us,'' said Vasily Rybin, who used
to work in an iron casting factory but now sells stuffed animals
outside McDonald's restaurant at Pushkin Square. ``I am afraid it
will stay for the year. I would like to hope for the best, but I
think things will get worse.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Yeltsin era may be drawing to a close, it is too soon
to write the epitaph for Russian reform. For all of the nostalgia
about the secure days of Soviet rule, when paychecks and pensions
were guaranteed, if meager, few want to re-create the past. The
re-establishment of the Soviet Union's brutal totalitarian controls
and the widespread renationalization of factories and refineries
seem the remotest of possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Even senior Kremlin aides agree that Russia is exhausted by its
political war with itself. Oleg N. Sysuyev, Yeltsin's deputy chief
of staff, says it could be several years before any further attempt
to liberalize the economy is possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're facing very difficult years; stagnation is possible,''
Sysuyev said in an interview. ``But a U-turn is not possible.''
</P>
<P>
   A quick snapshot of Russia today suggests something far beyond
stagnation. The nation's gross domestic product fell 5 percent in
1998 and experts predict a similar drop in 1999. Roughly half the
nation's business is conducted in barter.
</P>
<P>
   Even demography appears to be delivering its harsh verdict on
the new Russia. With the toll of early mortality outpacing births,
Russia's population in 1998 fell to 146.4 million, a drop of more
than 600,000.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's distress was summed up when a schoolteacher in
Ulyanovsk, Lenin's birthplace, died after a prolonged hunger
strike, started because of months of unpaid wages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had some bad times, but I have never seen people as
panicky as today,'' said Dmitri Maratovich, the editor of labor
newspapers in the Kemerovo coal mining basin in southern Siberia.
</P>
<P>
   Such misfortune, however, does not provide a full measure of
where Russia has come from. And by that standard, the nation has
made important _ even fundamental _ progress. For all of its
troubles, the country is in many ways unrecognizable compared with
the hulk of a nation Yeltsin inherited in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has become a noisy, even raucous democracy. Its citizens
can now travel abroad, and millions of them do.
</P>
<P>
   Though often subservient to economic interests, Russian
newspapers, radio and television are uncensored. Virtually any
political opinion can be found at the thousands of newsstands in
Moscow alone.
</P>
<P>
   The phenomenal rise of the Internet _ even the Communist Party
has a web site _ seems to insure there can be no retreat to the
days when the state defined reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected more from the democrats, but nevertheless they have
not given up on freedom of speech and freedom of conscience,'' said
Dmitri S. Likhachev, one of the nation's most venerated scholars.
``It is essential not to lose those freedoms, especially now when
they are under attack.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor is the economic news all bad. Moscow's streets, barren 15
years ago, now are jammed 18 hours a day; the number of autos has
tripled in seven years, and the pollution is horrific.
</P>
<P>
   Store shelves are no longer bare, but stocked with foreign
consumer goods, although they are often beyond the means of many
Russians. Russians own more home appliances than they could have
dreamed of in Soviet times.
</P>
<P>
   Nadezhda Inshev, her husband, Leonid, and their two children,
are crammed into two rooms of a communal apartment near the Moscow
River. They live off her husband's wages as a truck driver and
whatever she can earn from her knitting.
</P>
<P>
   Times were tough, even before the financial crisis. But the
Inshevs own a Sony color television, bought the other year when her
husband's employer finally paid six months in back wages.
</P>
<P>
   It is the deep disillusionment over Russia's ability to pull
itself out of its quagmire, however, that makes the current period
such a singularly bitter one.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Russia's pro-capitalist reformers were never widely
popular. They inherited a nightmarish burden: labor-intensive
factories that were unable to compete in the world marketplace,
chronically inefficient collective farms and a gargantuan,
money-draining military establishment.
</P>
<P>
   But they proved to be poor politicians. Their guiding assumption
was a kind of economic determinism that held that the public would
be brought along if only the economic software was changed.
</P>
<P>
   And in a calculated exercise in realpolitik, the reformers
forged an alliance with the bankers and other buccaneers of
Russia's wild new capitalism, who acquired billions of dollars
worth of government oil and metal companies at rock-bottom prices.
</P>
<P>
   At first, this worked. But, over time, the insider privatization
gave capitalism a bad odor and the public's patience wore out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I became disenchanted with the reformers three years ago, when
it became clear that reform is a battle for power, for the division
of property, and that there is no clear economic program,'' said
Nikita Makulov, 69, a retired system programmer whose monthly
pension today is worth all of $20.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The reformers insist they were on the right track but
acknowledge that they never got their message across.
</P>
<P>
   ``We underestimated the time it would take to prepare people for
reforms,'' Sergei V. Kiriyenko, the prime minister who was ousted
after the August crash, said in an interview. ``People did not
understand how much needed to be done to carry out the reforms or
the price they would have to pay to achieve them. And the
government maintained the illusion that it would be easy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Communists also threw a monkey wrench into the gears. They
used their control over the Parliament to block legislation that
would have provided the legal underpinnings for a new capitalist
order: the right to buy and sell land, protection for foreign
investors and the overhaul of an anachronistic tax system.
</P>
<P>
   The underdeveloped legal system is summed up by a nondescript
stucco building that fronts a narrow street east of the vast,
magnificent Kremlin. Only a tarnished plaque by the door makes
clear that it is the office of the Russian Constitutional Court.
</P>
<P>
   Every week, it seemed, Russia's ruling classes mocked the laws
and rules they promised to uphold. The head of the State Tax
Service took lavish Pacific cruises on his modest government
salary, even as tax collection was plummeting.
</P>
<P>
   The coup de grace for the Russian public, however, was the Aug.
17 financial crisis, which robbed the government of its two
greatest economic achievements: a stable currency and, by Russian
standards, relatively low inflation.
</P>
<P>
   It also robbed many Russians of their hope. Festooned now around
their gritty capital are a series of patriotic summons: ``Nobody
will help Russia, except ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The placards have been installed by the State Tax Service to
prod tax delinquents to pay up. While there is no indication that
they have accomplished that purpose, the posters have almost
unconsciously tapped the public mood.
</P>
<P>
   Russians no longer believe the West will come to their rescue.
They do not even count on their own government to pay overdue
pensions and back wages or to protect the billions of rubles in
savings that Russians had deposited in banks that collapsed with
the rest of the economy after the August devaluation of the ruble.
</P>
<P>
   A new nationwide survey of 4,800 Russians by the Center for
International Sociological Research captures the sour mood. An
overwhelming majority _ 79 percent _ said the country was stymied
by political paralysis. Asked to name the political figure they
trusted the most, ``Nobody'' won with 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But then, the survey notes, this is a nation in which virtually
everyone _ 97 percent _ agrees that their standard of living took a
turn for the worse in 1998, potatoes are the most common food _ 58
percent _ and slightly more than half _ 51 percent _ think the
coming year will be ``ominous.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia's inability to rally around a common standard is
symbolized by the continuing debate over the Dzerzhinsky statue.
Those in the countryside, workers and Communists strongly support
the vote to restore the monument. Most Muscovites remain opposed,
leaving the fate of Parliament's decision in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   For all the fiery emotion, the real issue is not the statue but
the political gridlock that makes Russia almost impossible to
govern.
</P>
<P>
   The harshest realization for many Russians is the discovery that
one of the biggest obstacles to change lies within themselves. Even
reformers admit that they are still burdened by a mentality
bequeathed to them by a Soviet regime that squashed initiative,
fostered hypocrisy and taught its citizens to abdicate
responsibility for a government they never thought of as theirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia is the only one to blame for our situation, not the IMF
or the G-7,'' Sysuyev said. ``All of us suffer from a Soviet
mentality because we lived almost our whole lives under an
absolutely inhuman system. The first real free person in Russia
today was born in some maternity ward just in the last few years.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Russians look deeper into their history, past the 70 years
of Communism, into a society and a culture that has long been riven
by debates over whether Russia does or does not belong in the West.
Echoes of those old debates can be heard again now, as ugly
anti-Semitism and bitter anti-Americanism creep into the political
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   But while Russia sometimes seems to revert to its old peculiar
ways, there is also evidence that even if it wants to, it can no
longer afford to shun the club of civilized nations, hemmed in as
it is by MTV on one side and the International Monetary Fund on the
other.
</P>
<P>
   And for all their short-term pessimism, many Russians _ known
for their patience _ take a long view. Makulov looks to his son,
Alyosha, a mathematician who develops data bases for a private
company and whose salary supports his parents (even after it was
halved by the summer's financial crisis).
</P>
<P>
   ``He is different from me, of course,'' said the father. ``I
think that the next generation _ or maybe the next after that _
will find a way to make this potentially rich country rich. My
sense is that everything that is happening is movement in the right
direction, albeit by the most mistaken and painful of means. It
just wasn't thought through.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
