<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 11:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5192 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-JETS-NYT &LR;      01-02 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAMELESS IN A KMART LINE, SIGNIFICANT ON JETS' DEFENSIVE LINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wherever they are shopping Sunday, enjoying their week off
before joining the playoff battle, the four players on the Jets'
defensive line will hardly be bothered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice when you go to the malls,'' said Rick Lyle, who is
among those who toil on one of the National Football League's most
successful yet least-noted units. ``You can walk around with your
family and nobody comes up to you.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sport that has produced defensive lines with such menacing
nicknames as the Purple People Eaters, the Steel Curtain, the
Fearsome Foursome and the Sack Exchange, the most imposing member
of the Jets' line is named Pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the only one in the history of the N.F.L. to be named
Pleasant,'' right end Anthony Pleasant claimed. And he is almost
correct. He is the only Pleasant who has ever played a full season.
The boast is a rare show of ego for a religious man who wants to be
identified not for whom he throws around on the field, but for whom
he can save off it.
</P>
<P>
   The line's work has been instrumental in the Jets' run to a 12-4
record and the East Division title, achievements that gave them
this weekend off. All they have to do Sunday is wait to see who
they will play next Sunday at Giants Stadium. It will be
Jacksonville if the Jaguars can beat New England Sunday afternoon.
Otherwise, they will play the winner of Saturday's Miami-Buffalo
game.
</P>
<P>
   The linemen are not well known in part because they are not
noted for their attention-getting sacks. Pleasant led the line with
six while the others combined for seven. Still, they were
instrumental in holding together a defense that allowed the
second-fewest points in the league, trailing Miami by only 1 point.
</P>
<P>
   The line was the most unsettled element of the defense in
training camp, when Pleasant, who plays right end, joined forces
with the well-traveled Ernie Logan at right tackle, Lyle at left
end and the second-year left tackle Jason Ferguson.
</P>
<P>
   Logan and Lyle had arrived a year earlier at bargain-basement
prices, free agents cut by their teams, while Ferguson, from
Georgia, was the Jets' final draft choice in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   When Pleasant joined the Jets he at least had the advantage of
familiarity, having been a teammate of Logan's and Lyle's in
Cleveland. But he was 30, had suffered an ankle injury in Baltimore
in 1996, and was a part-time player in Atlanta last season after
hurting a knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``One common thing about them is that they're all clean-living
kids,'' coach Bill Parcells said.
</P>
<P>
   Another was that each of the three was essentially in a
last-chance situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ernie knew this was his last shot,'' Parcells said. ``Rick
would have been out of football. Anthony had to stay healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was because of that united sense of desperation, but
it became apparent after practices in camp that there was something
different about this group.
</P>
<P>
   Pleasant would remain in the summer heat, and he and Logan would
discuss techniques and how to use their hands. ``Some of the other
guys would see us working,'' Pleasant said, ``and they'd just
gravitate to it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us was a real high draft pick,'' Lyle said. ``It was a
lot like being a walk-on in college. You have to work that much
harder because you kind of had two strikes against you.''
</P>
<P>
   Pleasant, who went to Tennessee State and spent six seasons with
the Browns before going to Baltimore and Atlanta, said he did not
mind staying after practice to help out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been that way,'' he said. ``My father died when I
was 2 and my mother raised me. I grew up in a small town _ Century,
Florida _ no bigger than a matchbox. But I had good role models _
my uncle, teachers, a professor at college.''
</P>
<P>
   His mother cleaned houses until she got a job working in a
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize I was poor,'' he said. ``I thought I was
middle class until I got to college and saw what other people
had.''
</P>
<P>
   Pleasant's no-nonsense approach to the game makes perfect sense
considering his philosophy: ``I do not want to be defined by the
sport I play.''
</P>
<P>
   Pleasant, who rarely inhabits the locker room during the 45
minutes Parcells allows for interviews, lives in Point Lookout, a
Long Island summer resort all but deserted by tourists in the
winter. There, his wife, Renita, and 2-year-old daughter, Hannah
Denette, rarely go out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not known as a core Jet,'' he said. ``I'm not recognized.
But I do a lot of things people don't know anything about.'' He
works with various programs to help children, and talks of becoming
a minister when he stops playing.
</P>
<P>
   While he and Lyle talk about their Christian faith, Logan is a
Muslim who wears a watch with a compass to help him locate the
northeast on road trips, so he can pray every evening.
</P>
<P>
   Logan and Ferguson have enjoyed the group identity the players
have forged.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the year progressed, we started to feel more comfortable in
each other,'' Logan said. ``We had faith that the other guy would
get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson said: ``I'd describe this like a brother relationship.
Once we got a feel for each other, once we got a `W,' we got going.
They teach me a lot of things. They're all very spiritual, and I've
learned what road to take and what road not to take.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, in a quiet way, you understand, the line glories in its
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just can't come in here and push us around,'' Ferguson
said. ``We thrive on not being known.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
