</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-BUSTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWSER-BUSTING PROGRAM COULD BOOST US IN MICROSOFT CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Microsoft Corp. says it's impossible to remove Internet browsing
software from the company's Windows 98 operating system without
crashing the computer. But an Australian biologist, Shane Brooks,
says he's not only written a program to remove the browser, but
that his technique will actually make many Windows machines work
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was simply looking for a way to speed up Win 98 on my slow
computer and remove all the redundant files that I don't use,''
says Brooks, a post-doctoral researcher at the University of
Maryland. Brooks says he's a fan of Microsoft products and wishes
the company well. But his browser-buster, called 98lite, could
provide the US Justice Department with fresh ammunition in its
ongoing antitrust suit against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   The suit accuses Microsoft of using its near-monopoly in
operating system software to muscle its way into dominance in many
other software markets, including Internet browsers. The government
argues that Microsoft started adding browsing software to its
Windows 95 and 98 operating systems in an effort to crush rival
browser maker Netscape Communications Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has responded that browsing software is a logical
addition to the operating system. The company also argued it had
integrated the browser into Windows 95 and 98 in such a way that it
would be impossible to offer a fully-functional version of these
products with the browser removed.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, a federal appeals court rejected the government's
arguments, saying Microsoft has a right to add browsing software to
its products if doing so provides a benefit to consumers. But the
Justice Department still hopes to convince Judge Thomas Penfield
Jackson that Microsoft can separate the browser from the operating
system and should be forced to do so. The trial resumes Monday
after a holiday recess.
</P>
<P>
   Several weeks ago, Princeton University computer science
professor Edward Felton testified in the Microsoft case, saying
he'd written a program that would remove nearly all browser
components from Windows 98 without harming the operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Now Brooks has weighed in with his own program created for the
same purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Necessity was the mother of his invention. Brooks doesn't have a
computer of his own and uses one borrowed from the university _ an
old Pentium-133 laptop that's slow by today's standards. Brooks
tried Windows 98 and found it was less prone to unexpected crashes
than Windows 95.
</P>
<P>
   But Windows 98 uses the built-in browser to display information
on the monitor. Brooks found that this made his computer run much
slower. In addition, the browser components took up precious space
on his computer's hard drive. So he decided to figure out which
files were related to the browser, and then delete them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did the job manually at first,'' Brooks said. ``I then
decided to refine the procedure and package it in a program just
for the hell of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is 98lite, a program that is run by the user during
the installation of Windows 98. It simply prevents certain parts of
the software from being installed. Brooks says the final result
gives him all the usual functions of Windows 98, only without the
browser.
</P>
<P>
   ``The core of the OS (operating system) remains untouched,''
said Brooks. ``It is pure Win 98 and very stable.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft officials aren't so sure. Microsoft program manager
Shawn Sanford admitted that owners of Windows 98 can modify it as
they see fit, but warned that Microsoft cannot guarantee the
reliability of a computer modified with 98lite.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Sanford noted that 98lite deliberately leaves
behind a few portions of the browser, such as a piece of code that
allows Windows 98 to display files written in HTML, the coding
language of the World Wide Web. Some firms that write software for
Windows 98 use this feature to display information, and these
programs would not work properly if this code were removed.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Brooks says that for all practical purposes, 98lite blots
out the Microsoft browser _ and saves about 40 megabytes of hard
drive space in the process. He's now at work on a program to remove
the browser from computers that already have Windows 98 installed.
This version will also allow users to remove a host of Windows 98
features they may not want, such as a movie player, graphics files,
and diagnostic software.
</P>
<P>
   To download a copy of 98lite, go to
http://www.wam.umd.edu/ssbrooks/98lite/. The download is free, but
Brooks requests a donation to cover his expenses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
