</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WEEK IN REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chinese Got Arms Secrets, House Panel Says
</P>
<P>
   A special House committee concluded that over the past two
decades China obtained, sometimes through theft, some of the United
States' most sensitive military secrets, including designs for
nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's findings confirmed recent Clinton administration
assessments that information given to Chinese scientists by two
U.S. satellite companies helped Beijing improve its ability to
launch satellites and long-range missiles.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's 700-page report is secret because of the
classified material it covers, but Congress plans to make a
declassified version public in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ERIC SCHMITT
</P>
<P>
   Mixing Work and Welfare
</P>
<P>
   Most states are meeting the work requirements of the 1996
welfare law, and 28 percent of adults on the rolls are
participating in some type of work activity, the Clinton
administration reported.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs are plentiful in a booming economy. But Rep. Sander Levin,
D-Mich., said people combining work and welfare were typically paid
less than $8 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ROBERT PEAR
</P>
<P>
   Europe Greets the Euro
</P>
<P>
   The euro, the currency common to 11 European countries, arrived
on Jan. 1. So must francs and marks be traded in now? Far from it.
There won't even be euro coins and bills until 2002, and local
currency will be good for six months after that.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, euros will exist mainly in the dark recesses of
computers at banks and stock exchanges, though they will show up in
credit-card bills and traveler's checks. But for travelers to
Europe, price comparisons should become easier.
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   Online Shopping Takes Off
</P>
<P>
   Early holiday sales figures for Internet retailers were stronger
than even the most bullish predictions of a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   One consumer survey suggested that online sales would reach $5
billion. That would be four times the total sales last year between
Thanksgiving and Christmas and twice expectations for this year of
$2.3 billion in sales. While the data were preliminary, they sent
many electronic-commerce stocks soaring.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LESLIE KAUFMAN &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Fallout From Bus Crashes
</P>
<P>
   The cruel fact is that if people climb into vehicles and hit the
road, some will die. So the question is: What's the safest way to
travel?
</P>
<P>
   A spate of bus crashes in New Jersey on the busy routes to
Atlantic City has politicians calling for new safety measures. But
the statistics show that this is an extremely safe means of travel.
</P>
<P>
   Of 41,967 highway deaths in 1997, large trucks accounted for
5,355; just 41 involved tour buses. ``What,'' asked a bus industry
official, ``is the problem that you're trying to solve?''
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   McCain Tests the Water
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., took a big step toward a presidential
candidacy in 2000 by announcing the formation of an exploratory
committee to begin raising money for a campaign.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, the first Republican to signal his plans, is a war hero
who took on his party's leadership in pressing, unsuccessfully, for
campaign finance reform and anti-tobacco legislation.
</P>
<P>
   His aides said one reason for the timing of McCain's
announcement was to upstage his many rivals and draw press coverage
before the White House scandal again dominates the news.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICHARD L. BERKE
</P>
<P>
   Woman in Top Swiss Post
</P>
<P>
   Switzerland's first woman president _ and the first Jew in the
largely ceremonial top post _ took office Friday. Ruth Dreifuss,
58, was elected in December in one of the narrowest Parliamentary
votes in recent years. Her presidency comes amid recent revelations
questioning Switzerland's cherished myths about its neutrality
during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dreifuss said she viewed her election as an opportunity for
the nation to come to terms with its ``complex and
conflict-loaded'' wartime history.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ELIZABETH OLSON
</P>
<P>
   Octuplet Mother Goes Home
</P>
<P>
   The Houston woman who gave birth to octuplets last month left
the hospital three days after the death of one of the infants Dec.
27. Nkem Chukwu and her husband, Iyke Louis Udobi, said they were
too busy caring for their seven surviving babies to get involved in
ethical debates over the births.
</P>
<P>
   Some doctors are suggesting guidelines to help regulate the use
of the advanced fertility drugs that Ms. Chukwu and others have
taken, because too many resulting babies die or suffer lifelong
medical problems. Louis said the family didn't want to rehash its
history of fertility treatments: ``That is in the past. Now all of
our concerns must be for caring for the babies.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICK LYMAN
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
