<HEADER>
A5220 &Cx1f; var-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-FINAL-N     01-02 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-FINAL-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, Jan. 3, moved Saturday:
</P>
<P>
   _ In the `a' category.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-ECON-REVIEW (Washington) _ Impeachment vs. the economy.
Somewhere between Washington's certainty that the impeachment
controversy matters to the the nation and its economy, and the
markets' view that the such political wars and moral arguments are
irrelevant, lies a dynamic that seems bound to define 1999. By
David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   CRIME-REVIEW (Undated) _ Earlier this decade, some
criminologists and politicians predicted that a crime wave teeming
with a new breed of adolescent superpredators would emerge in the
late '90s. But it isn't happening. A look at possible reasons why
the predictions are wrong. By Jacques Steinberg. WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTHCARE-REVIEW (Undated) _ A real debate is emerging over
whether HMOs and other managed-care businesses can wring more
efficiencies out of the health-care system and therefore make money
over the long haul. While they prospered by taking advantage of
easy one-time savings, like the use of their clout to get doctors
and hospitals to accept less to provide care, their fat profits
could prove ephemeral in the face of medical costs that they, too,
cannot control. By Reed Abelson.
</P>
<P>
   NOSE-JOBS-REVIEW (New York) _ Amid an explosion in cosmetic
surgery, the number of nose jobs has dropped significantly. The
reasons are partly cultural and partly economic, according to
plastic surgeons who have watched the evolution of a procedure that
was once a benchmark in a young girl's life, especially among
Jewish teen-agers. By Jane Gross.
</P>
<P>
   CHARTER-SCHOOLS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Test-tube babies: private
public schools. A look at the growing focus on proposals for
charter schools. By Anemone Hartcullis.
</P>
<P>
   JOB-OPENINGS-REVIEW (Undated) _ A look at some interesting and
unusual employment want-ads.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the `i' catgeory:
</P>
<P>
   HITECH-WAR-REVIEW (Undated) _ Putting a high a premium on
bloodless combat and faith in high technology raises some troubling
questions. One is whether the electronic razzle-dazzle creates the
expectation, some would say illusion, in the American public that
the new weapons can accomplish every military mission, and
therefore that the loss of any GIs in a future operation is
tantamount to failure. By Serge Schmemann.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-HOMELANDS-REVIEW (Johannesburg) _ Old scars on the new
South Africa: the homelands, which were designed in the apartheid
era to segregate blacks, were legally abolished in 1994, but many
blacks remain in these economically-depressed areas because of
family ties. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA-REVIEW (Sihanoukville) _ Cambodia's choice: neither
truth nor reconciliation. In freeing Khmer Rouge leaders, Cambodia
is bucking a worldwide trend toward accountability. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   CASPIAN-U.S.-REVIEW (Almaty, Kazakhstan) _ As it helps funnel in
billions of dollars for oil development, the U.S. has wanted to
transform the Capsian nations into democratic and economically
transparent meritocracies. But as the Caspian leaders see it, they
have been willing to sign almost any agreement and have handed over
their oil fields, so why does Washington makes a fuss about their
corrupt and repressive politics? By Steve LeVine.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-SANCTIONS-REVIEW (Baghdad) _ The sanctions on Iraq do not
appear to be having the desired effect. What they are doing,
though, is fueling anti-Western sentiment among Iraq's people,
possibly helping keep Saddam in power. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-DISSIDENTS-REVIEW (Beijing) _ Dissonance in China: so many
liberties, so little freedom. While the majority of Chinese are
enjoying unprecedented material and economic freedom, repression of
political freedom continues. BY Erik Eckholm.
</P>
