<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-OHIOSTATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OHIO STATE STANDS READY IF NO. 1 SLOT IS AVAILABLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ The legendary Louisiana politician Huey Long could
have picked up a few pointers on politicking from Ohio State coach
John Cooper. Shortly after his team had beaten Texas A&AMP;M, 24-14, in
the Sugar Bowl at the Superdome on Jan. 1, Cooper was pushing his
team for the national championship in the event that Tennessee
falters against Florida State in the Fiesta Bowl on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any argument if Tennessee wins and runs the
table,'' Cooper said. ``But if Tennessee plays sloppy and Florida
State wins, I think Ohio State can lay claim to being the best team
in the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, part of Cooper's argument had been that Ohio State
(10-1) needed to dominate Texas A&AMP;M (11-3). Like a good politician,
he backed away from that part of his argument after the victory.
However, Cooper's position is strong. The Buckeyes will have
finished the season as strong as any other team if Tennessee loses.
</P>
<P>
   They were dominant against the Aggies for the first half Friday
night, scoring 21 points in six and a half minutes (one touchdown
was scored on a blocked punt that was returned 16 yards), before
lapsing into a stupor in the second half (1 for 3 on field-goal
attempts).
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a lot of mental mistakes,'' said Ohio State's Joe
Montgomery, who had nine carries for 96 yards and a touchdown.
``You look at the number of times that we could have scored and
it's very frustrating. But we still got the win.''
</P>
<P>
   Those close scoring opportunities came in the first half on
passes that quarterback Joe Germaine threw in the end zone to David
Boston _ the game's most valuable player with 11 catches for 105
yards. One of 25 yards was tipped away at the last second by the
Texas A&AMP;M cornerback Jason Webster; another of 36 yards was batted
down by cornerback Sedrick Curry. If those plays had gone for
scores, Ohio State would not have been worried about the Aggies
coming back in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   At the half, the Buckeyes were thinking about how they had led
Michigan State and appeared to have that game in hand, only to have
the Spartans come back and win, thereby ruining a perfect season
and derailing a clear path to the national championship. Cooper
reminded them that Texas A&AMP;M had stormed back against Kansas State
in the Big 12 Conference championship game, erasing a 27-12 deficit
in the last 9:20 to tie the score, 27-27, and win it, 36-33, in the
second overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper left his team with these words: ``Play as well as you're
capable of playing and if you're the better team then you'll win
the game. If they're the better team, they'll win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Buckeyes went out and soon began the first stage of their
second-half folding act, missing field goals of 49 and 47 yards
and, committing 3 penalties worth 40 yards on an 11-play, 68-yard
scoring drive that pulled A&AMP;M to within 24-14 with 5:24 to play in
the third quarter. The Aggies' defense clamped down on the Buckeyes
in the second half, thanks in large part to linebacker Dat Nguyen,
the Lombardi Award winner who had 14 tackles (13 solo).
</P>
<P>
   It was a good thing for the Buckeyes that Texas A&AMP;M's offense
was just as error-prone as they were. Most costly was a lateral by
quarterback Branndon Stewart to fullback Ja'Mar Toombs, which was
recovered by Ohio State linebacker Jerry Rudzinski at the Aggies'
48 with 9:15 to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're far too talented a team to try and play catchup
football against, and it just took us too long to get going,'' said
Texas A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum. ``It's disappointing to end the season
with a loss, but I can't say enough about my team. We were Big 12
champions, we won 11 games this season and played eight Bowl teams
and a loss tonight doesn't take away from a tremendous season.''
</P>
<P>
   The Buckeyes left here thinking there was still some life left
in their season, even though they had played their final game. ``I
don't think we'll be any worse than No. 2 in the country,'' Cooper
said. ``Depending upon what happens Monday night, we can make the
claim that we're as good as anybody in the country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
