<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5260 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-LOTT-ART-2TAK     01-02 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-LOTT-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOTT, ON IMPEACHMENT'S CENTER STAGE, FOCUSES ON CONSENSUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After the Republican losses in November's
elections, a disheartened Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott quickly
got the hint: Voters wanted a mended Social Security system, an
orderly budget, good schools. They wanted action, not self-serving
brawling about legislation and impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in his leather armchair speaking to reporters, Lott, of
Mississippi, promised the ``American people'' results, plumping up
his wish list for the new year, being careful to stay away from the
scandal enveloping President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   He had been watching from afar, with a bit of trepidation, as
House Speaker Newt Gingrich's political career disintegrated over
his choice of strategies for capitalizing on Clinton's problems.
And then Lott saw how Rep. Bob Livingston, Gingrich's designated
successor, got ensnared in the impeachment web.
</P>
<P>
   But Lott, a strait-laced, starched-shirt Southern conservative,
can no longer keep a safe distance from impeachment, even holed up
in Mississippi, where he has spent the holidays. Instead, he will
play a pivotal role in shaping the way the Senate will handle two
articles of impeachment sent over by the House, one charging
perjury by Clinton, the other, obstruction of justice in the
investigation of the Monica Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   And already Lott, who colleagues say is keenly aware of the
historical import of his actions, is being jostled by traditional
political crosswinds from the right and left.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows he has an awesome responsibility,'' said Sen. Susan
Collins, R-Maine, a moderate who spoke to Lott on the telephone
last week. ``It's difficult because I know he wants to be fair to
the president and he has a caucus of 55 Republicans, all of whom
have very different views on how this should unfold, and all of
whom are convinced they are right.''
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Republicans, of which he is one, are pushing Lott
to hold a full trial, with testimony from witnesses, followed by a
vote on the articles of impeachment. Many of them disapprove of
censuring Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Most Democrats, led by Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, the
second most important figure in an impeachment trial, are lobbying
for a swift proceeding and a vote on censure. Lott is said to be
considering a proposal that would serve as a compromise between the
Democratic position and that of Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of that tug-of-war is the fact that convicting and
removing Clinton from office requires a two-thirds majority, or 67
senators. Even if all 55 Republicans stuck together and voted to
convict, 12 Democrats would have to break with their party to do
the same, something that most senators concede is next to
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is constrained by the fact that he has to get `X' number of
votes to do anything,'' said Sen. Rick Santorum, R-Pa., a
conservative. ``He may not have the support within his own caucus
and with Democrats to proceed the way he wants. He's the leader,
not the dictator.''
</P>
<P>
   It is this mathematical calculation, and Lott's desire to avoid
a drawn-out trial in the face of public opposition to Clinton's
impeachment and removal, that is governing the majority leader's
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Senator Lott is doing is acting as majority leader of the
entire Senate,'' said Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., an influential
senator who has been in close touch with Lott as he formulates his
plan. ``He views this not as a partisan exercise and not as a fight
between Democrats and Republicans, but a carrying out of the
Senate's constitutional responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been involved in widespread consultations with members
on both sides of the aisles,'' McConnell added.
</P>
<P>
   Even Democrats say Lott appears to be resisting the squeeze from
his conservative backers, the people who helped elect him to the
Senate and who have at times signaled their discontent with him,
most recently after the elections.
</P>
<P>
   Lott is classically conservative on many levels, and his more
extreme views have sometimes alienated the more moderate members of
his own party. Last year, he triggered a firestorm of protest when
he likened homosexuality to a disease, like alcoholism, and called
it a sin.
</P>
<P>
   His past has also been intertwined with pro-Confederacy groups
and an organization whose leaders have espoused white supremacist
views. Lott addressed the Sons of Confederate Veterans and spoke to
a magazine that extols the virtues of the Confederacy, Southern
Partisan. And he spoke in 1992 to members of the Council of
Conservative Citizens, although he later renounced the organization
and the racial views of some of its leaders.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Lott drew the ire of many senators when he sharply
criticized Clinton's decision to bomb Iraq, calling it an
orchestrated maneuver to stall the House's scheduled vote on
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   But for now at least, Lott appears to be clutching the center
and the Constitution, focusing more on consensus than on anything
else.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The latest proposal Lott is considering will attest to his
desire for compromise, and seems to contradict the harder line he
appeared to be taking early on that called for a swift but complete
trial, and a vote on the articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal would provide for a test vote of sorts in the
Senate, requiring a two-thirds majority, on the two articles of
impeachment. If 67 senators vote to approve the test resolution,
after hearing a summation of the evidence by the House and the
White House, the Senate will go forward with a full trial. If the
resolution fails, the Senate will turn to a censure proposal.
</P>
<P>
   In telephone interviews, several of Lott's Republican colleagues
responded to the compromise proposal with displeasure, saying they
would like witnesses to testify and believe that 67 votes to move
forward with a trial is too steep a cut-off. Democrats approved of
the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Lott has not commented on the proposal and declined to be
interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Lott has proceeded professional and in the best
traditions of the Senate,'' said Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., a
liberal who leads the Senate Democratic campaign committee. ``I
don't think he will succumb to pressure because there is a common
interest. We want to deal with issue and don't want the president
to be crippled, and Republicans realize they are acting against
public desires and at great political risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Lott's philosophical differences with Daschle, and their
past skirmishes over issues like managed care and education, the
majority leader has kept in close touch with his Democratic
counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   The two leaders speak daily, trading ideas about how to manage
the trial and sharing concerns about the obstacles that the Senate
needs to overcome to see impeachment though will little turbulence.
The Senate's complicated rules, and its deference to individual
members, make it easy for one dissenter, either Democrat or
Republican, to tangle up the process.
</P>
<P>
   Lott has also reached out to moderate Republicans and Democrats
in his party in the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that he is reaching out and talking to all of us is a
good sign,'' Senator Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   One Democrat who is close to the negotiations between Lott and
Daschle called them as ``productive and cooperative as one could
expect given the circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He is determined to do the right thing here,'' said the
Democrat, who spoke on the condition of anonymity. ``And he
realizes that he will be judged more by history than by his
peers.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott's colleagues also say he has paid close attention to the
partisan quagmire that nearly subsumed the House impeachment
proceedings. Much of that partisanship can be avoided in the
Senate, where the process is not governed by a single committee
rife with rock-hard conservatives and unflinching liberals, as it
was in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't work as well as anyone would have liked it to work
in the House,'' said Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., who has also been
in close consultation with Lott. ``One hopes that Lott and the
minority have learned from that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
