</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COLUMN-HOLMGREN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: HOLMGREN COMES HOME TO SAN FRANCISCO, POSSIBLY FOR
GOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Is this where Mike Holmgren's heart really
resides? Is his dream job to coach the San Francisco 49ers, where
he coached under Bill Walsh and helped win championships before
traveling to Green Bay seven seasons ago?
</P>
<P>
   Well, Holmgren comes home Sunday afternoon, back to his
hometown, back to where he left his heart long ago. Holmgren brings
his Green Bay Packers here one more time, in the National Football
Conference wild-card playoff clash against the 49ers at 3Com Park.
</P>
<P>
   If Holmgren wants to come home and stay, he is setting the
proper foundation. He has used a sly formula: if you can't join
'em, beat 'em. Holmgren has won five consecutive games over the
49ers and has kicked them out of the playoffs in each of the past
three seasons. He left for Green Bay in 1992, missed the playoffs
that first season and has since gained a franchise record string of
six post-season berths. He has the best record among active coaches
who have coached at least 100 games _ a 75-37 regular-season
record, a .670 percentage. He won Super Bowl XXXI over the New
England Patriots. He reached Super Bowl XXXII last year but lost to
the Denver Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren, 50, has one year left on his current contract. The
49ers already have a head coach in Steve Mariucci. But so what, on
both counts. Holmgren has a clause in his contract that says he can
leave to accept a general managing/head coaching job with another
team. Mariucci? Nice job in two seasons. But if the 49ers want to
make the move, they will make the move. Easily. Ask guys like Tom
Landry and Jimmy Johnson and Don Shula. Or even George Seifert,
whom Mariucci replaced. Super Bowl winners all, and all
unceremoniously booted for a new twinkle in the eye.
</P>
<P>
   Ask the five head coaches all dumped in one day last week.
</P>
<P>
   And that is another indication that even if Holmgren does not
wind up here, he is still all but gone from Green Bay. There are
seven head coaching vacancies in the National Football League. The
Carolina Panthers like Holmgren. Seattle has long flirted with him.
Holmgren has said he will wait, that he will see. But it appears
that the door is shut, that the book is closed, that this man is
gone.
</P>
<P>
   Could be a seven-year itch.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren came to Green Bay because Ron Wolf, the Packers'
general manager, liked his manners and fondness for football and
quick offensive mind. They formed a partnership: Holmgren coached
the players, Wolf picked them. Through the past seven years this
tandem has worked as well as any duo in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, both say their relationship remains strong. But
this could also be a case of familiarity breeding boredom and more.
Holmgren has looked around and seen Bill Parcells picking and
coaching his own players with the Jets. Mike Shanahan picks 'em and
coaches 'em with Denver. Dan Reeves picks 'em and coaches 'em with
Atlanta. Holmgren would like to try that. Be your own boss. Build
your own thing. Is it ego? Sure it is. Is it the new challenge, the
new drive? No doubt. Could be that Holmgren also thinks the best of
this current group of Packer players is behind them.
</P>
<P>
   We can look back to the Nov. 29 Philadelphia-at-Green Bay game
to see how the current situation in Green Bay may be wearing on
Holmgren. Ahead by 10-6 as he and his team walked off at halftime,
Holmgren became embroiled in a shouting match with a fan.
Frustration, no doubt, over the way the Packers had played in the
first half. Frustration with injuries and a taxing season in which
the Minnesota Vikings were supplanting Green Bay as the dominant
team in the NFC Central Division. All season, Holmgren has heard
critics say that he is simply playing out the string. That he is
jockeying for position to move and that his coaching has suffered.
That he wanted to leave last year and could not. For Holmgren, that
hurts.
</P>
<P>
   He has always loved the Green Bay franchise and its fans, but
familiarity, again. What is it breeding?
</P>
<P>
   He could not have been happy over the shots he took after last
year's Super Bowl loss for forgetting the count on downs in
Denver's late drive, when Holmgren decided to let Terrell Davis
walk into the end zone from the 1-yard-line with under two minutes
left. Holmgren conceded the touchdown because he wanted the ball
back for a final drive with as much time as possible for Brett
Favre. The strategy did not work. And the fact that Holmgren took
so much abuse for it at home in particular has not warmed his heart
toward staying in Green Bay. Especially after all he has
accomplished there.
</P>
<P>
   And here is another thing: Holmgren's leaving the Bay Area for
the head coaching job in Green Bay was a wonderful career move
seven years ago, but to do it, he drastically changed environments,
his roots, for himself and his family. Might be time to get back to
those roots for the same reasons, for himself and his family.
</P>
<P>
   On the table from Wolf is a contract extension for Holmgren. He
has not signed it. He will wait until after the season, he said, to
make that decision.
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it. This is Holmgren's last hurrah, his final playoff
tour with Green Bay. This goose looks cooked. Mike Holmgren is
ready to fly the coop.
</P>
<P>
   The question is where he will land. So many options. But there
is no place like home. Home is where the heart is for most,
including Holmgren. And that gives this playoff tangle here Sunday
a pinch more spice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-02-99 1326EST &QL; 
