<DOCNO> NYT19990102.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5269 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-ANDRSON-COLUMN-NY     01-02 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ANDRSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: GREEN'S SUCCESS LIFTS BLACK COACHES' STATURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dennis Green doesn't deserve the burden of being a beacon. He
has been too successful for too long. But the more games that Green
and his Minnesota Vikings win in the Super Bowl XXXIII playoffs,
the more visible other black candidates should be in the fog that
seems to surround most National Football League club owners when
searching for a new head coach.
</P>
<P>
   The shame of pro football is that black players represent
roughly two-thirds of the NFL's 30 rosters, but Green and Tampa
Bay's Tony Dungy represent the league's only two black head
coaches.
</P>
<P>
   From around the time that the Buccaneers hired Dungy three years
ago, other club owners have hired 18 head coaches, all of them
white. And with at least seven new vacancies, including five from
last Monday's massacre in Philadelphia, Chicago, Baltimore, Seattle
and Carolina, that embarrassing streak could hit 25.
</P>
<P>
   If it does, it will prove that some pro football club owners
have not checked this season's final standing or glanced to see
who's in charge on the Vikings' sideline.
</P>
<P>
   Only three NFL teams have had a 15-1 record _ the 1984 49ers
(under Bill Walsh), the 1985 Bears (under Mike Ditka) and now the
1998 Vikings. And if the Vikings win the Super Bowl, Dennis Green
will be the first black head coach to caress the Vince Lombardi
Trophy.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe then some pro football club owners will realize that more
black head-coaching candidates should be considered and hired.
</P>
<P>
   Green suddenly has an opportunity to do for other black coaches
what Doug Williams did for other black quarterbacks. Until Williams
threw four touchdown passes in the Redskins' 42-10 rout of the
Denver Broncos in Super Bowl XXII, a black quarterback was
considered a novelty, a curiosity. Witness one question during the
Super Bowl inquisitions in San Diego that week.
</P>
<P>
   ``How long,'' one interrogator asked Williams, ``have you been a
black quarterback?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody laughed,'' Williams has said, ``but I knew what the
guy meant. I answered, `Since I've been in the NFL.' At Grambling,
I'd just been a quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   As soon as Williams earned the Pete Rozelle Trophy as that Super
Bowl's most valuable player, he was just a quarterback again. And
ever since, an African-American football player who happens to play
quarterback is considered just a quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   The same situation could occur for black coaches if Dennis Green
and the Vikings win Super Bowl XXXIII in Miami on Jan. 31. Maybe
then all those black head-coaching candidates will be considered
just head-coaching candidates.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the Vikings get knocked off, Green's success in
Minnesota has established his stature as a coach.
</P>
<P>
   Over his seven seasons there, Green has a 71-41 record with
three National Conference Central titles and three wild-card berths
despite constant changes at quarterback: Sean Salisbury, Jim
McMahon, Warren Moon, Brad Johnson and now Randall Cunningham. Most
of those quarterback changes resulted from Green's 1-5 playoff
record, which this explosive Viking team should rectify.
</P>
<P>
   Green agreed that a Vikings victory in the Super Bowl would
create more visibility for black coaching candidates, but he
preferred to discuss why the Bucs hired Dungy off his Viking staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bucs knew exactly what they were looking for in Tony, and
they got it,'' Green said. ``He took them from last place to the
playoffs a year ago and almost to the playoffs this year. He
represented a coach who knew the Central Division and had the
ability to coach against it. Tony's 3-3 against us in his three
seasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Dungy, who had been the Vikings' defensive coordinator,
choreographed the Buccaneers' 27-24 victory at Tampa Bay on Nov. 1,
Minnesota's only loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look around for the best guy for that job; that's what teams
should do when they need a new head coach,'' Green said. ``That's
what the Bucs did.''
</P>
<P>
   Green endorsed two black assistant coaches in particular:
Sherman Lewis, the Packers' offensive coordinator, and Willie Shaw,
the Raiders' defensive coordinator. Green and Lewis were together
on the 49ers' staff; Shaw was the defensive coordinator at Stanford
when Green was the head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people think Sherman is too old at 56, but he acts like
he's 40,'' Green said. ``If Sherman was in my job the last seven
years, he'd have done as good. Willie took that Oakland defense,
which ranked next-to-last in the league a year ago, and moved it up
to third in the AFC this season.''
</P>
<P>
   But the more playoff games the Vikings win, the more Dennis
Green will lift the club owners' fog for all those black coaching
candidates who just want to be considered coaching candidates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
