<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-MEX-BASS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD-CLASS BASS TREASURE IN THE SIERRA MADRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KEN SCHULTZ    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TECHOBAMPO, Mexico _ There are as many people in this remote
village in the Sierra Madre _ about 240 _ as live in some apartment
buildings in many cities in the United States. Most are Indian
descendants whose previous houses are now under water. All of
Techobampo was relocated in 1994 when a dam on the Rio Fuerte was
completed and a new impoundment, called Huites and built for
irrigation and hydroelectric purposes, started to fill.
</P>
<P>
   That dam backs up the Chinipas River, a serpentine watercourse
that flows into Huites from rugged peaks near Copper Canyon, or
Barranca del Cobre, Mexico's larger and deeper version of the Grand
Canyon, with a maximum depth of more than 6,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest of canyon country on the outskirts of the Sierra Madre
Occidentals, Lake Huites is 22 miles long and covers 30,000 acres
when full. It is so remote that most of the guides employed at Ron
Speed's fishing camp there had never seen a boat or outboard motor
before 1994, and the nearby villages got electricity only four
years ago. The nearest telephone is an hour away in the city of
Choix.
</P>
<P>
   The drive from Los Mochis takes more than three hours, 18 miles
of which are on a winding, rutted, neck-wrenching burro trail. It
took 22 days to bring in the two mobile trailers that serve as
sleeping quarters for anglers, and each had to be cut in half
lengthwise.
</P>
<P>
   But adventurous North American anglers, showing the tenacity of
burros themselves, are flocking here for unparalleled
largemouth-bass fishing action. Florida-strain largemouth bass _
which grow quickly and have been exported by fisheries managers to
many states in the southern United States _ were brought here in
1994, and already specimens 11 pounds and up have been recorded.
</P>
<P>
   This exceptional growth rate produces football-shaped bass that
have small heads and a large girth, plus a hot chili pepper
disposition. Landing these dynamos is a 50-50 proposition, and
always a challenge. Huites is completely loaded with trees and
brush, and the bass are amidst this protective cover. When the fish
strike a lure, they dive for the nearest wood, often a multi-limbed
cactus, and either break the line or achieve freedom when an angler
is unable to extract them.
</P>
<P>
   But there are so many bass, and so much opportunity, that losing
half the fish that strike is no problem. In fact, the bass often
congregate in spots, usually off points near deep water, that
produce so much action that anglers do not have to search all over
this expansive water, a rarity in most U.S. bass fishing lakes.
</P>
<P>
   One morning I was paired with Kris Leistritz of Woodland, Wash.,
whose employer, the fishing rod manufacturer G. Loomis, sent her
and two colleagues to Huites to test new equipment. Our guide,
Racindo Rodriguez, took us up the Chinipas River, past steep
canyons, red rock cliffs and narrow passageways, stopping at a
rocky section that was loaded with bass. Once, having just cast a
plastic worm to the sharply sloped rock, I watched Leistritz hook a
large bass and laid down my rod momentarily to take a photograph.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez deftly netted the fish, posed, then yelled and pointed
behind me. My rod was out of the boat and heading toward the lake
bottom. I fell on the rear deck, reached into the water, and barely
snatched the end of the handle. A bass had taken my motionless lure
and pulled the $300 rod, plus reel, out of the boat. Still hooked,
it jumped out of the water while I scrambled to my feet, and a few
moments later a potbellied fish was in Rodriguez's hand.
</P>
<P>
   The fishing was seldom that easy during a three-day visit, as an
unusually extreme cold front had made the bass less active and sent
them deep. The norm here is shallow-water angling, with so much
activity that even a poor caster or first-time bass angler can have
success.
</P>
<P>
   That action has been drawing people to Huites since fishing
first began in October, when Speed, of Malakoff, Texas, got the
trailers in place and the boats, equipment and services
established.
</P>
<P>
   This is never an easy job in Mexico, and even more difficult in
such a remote location. It is also risky in the long term, because
virtually all other new bass fishing lakes in Mexico have been
damaged within five years of opening by legal and illegal
commercial fishing. The illegal fishing has already begun on
Huites, Speed said, but the Sinaloan state government has been
patrolling the lake and confiscating illegal nets, shooting holes
through the bottom of more than a dozen boats.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, there's a conflict between the state government
and local communities, which want to promote tourism and maintain
the quality of this resource, and the Mexican government, which
issues permits to commercial fishermen and does little to curb
illegalities. Commercial interests have won out at other lakes.
</P>
<P>
   In Techobampo and throughout this rugged region, the people earn
very little from modest farming efforts; a laborer makes about $4 a
day. Fishing guides earn a daily salary of $12, plus an average tip
of $20. They are eager to assist, and many serenade their clients
while guiding.
</P>
<P>
   But it is important to be extremely still in the narrow sections
of the lake, especially on the Chinipas. Boats travel through
chasms so steep that the sun doesn't penetrate until midmorning.
Overhead, huge boulders hang on precipices hundreds of feet up, and
every osprey that flies by has a fish in its talons.
</P>
<P>
   Below, the tips of 40-foot-tall trees barely make it to the
water's surface, and the bass might pull your fishing rod into the
water if you don't hold on to it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-02-99 1335EST &QL; 
