<SLUG> BC-WINTER-STORM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORM PUMMELS MIDWEST AND GULF COAST STATES 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Ark., Ill., Ind., Iowa, Mo., Neb., Texas)   By JO THOMAS  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   URBANA, Ill. _ A giant storm howled across the Midwest Saturday
, from the Canadian border to the Gulf of Mexico, grounding most
flights in Chicago and St. Louis, knocking out power, and
threatening a foot of snow or more in northern states.
</P>
<P>
   Winds of 25 miles an hour or more have created near-blizzard
conditions in Chicago, making it difficult even to cross the
street. Motorists seemed to heed the advice of highway officials to
stay off the roads.
</P>
<P>
   ``The secondary roads are shut down, but the Interstates are
still open,'' said Sgt. Kenneth Dicken of the Illinois State
Police. ``We've had very few accidents.''
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters said parts of Illinois, Indiana, Iowa and Missouri
could get 15 to 20 inches of snow by Saturday night, with high
winds bringing the wind chill well below zero. On Saturday, the
snow covered parts of Iowa and the Dakotas and was moving into Ohio
and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   At Chicago's O'Hare Airport, most of Saturday morning's flights
were canceled, and airport personnel provided hundreds of cots for
travelers who may be stranded by the storm. All 140 Trans World
Airline flights into and out of Lambert Airport were canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Deputies in Texas said tornadoes injured at least seven people
and destroyed three mobile homes east of Huntsville. None of the
injuries were life-threatening.
</P>
<P>
   In Arkansas, freezing rain toppled power lines and cut service
to more than 100,000 utility customers.
</P>
<P>
   The storm has been blamed for at least seven deaths. Six of
these, including two in Arkansas, two in Nebraska and two in
Missouri, occurred in traffic accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Word that the snowstorm was on the way swept the Midwest before
New Year's Eve, and shoppers jammed stores to buy food, shovels,
and firewood _ and party supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Mittman, office manager at the County Market grocery store
in Urbana, Ill., said: ``Yesterday I had one customer buy 18 loaves
of bread, 20 pounds of hamburger, 6 bags of sugar, a whole case of
macaroni and cheese, 6 boxes of cereal, 4 gallons of milk. He said
he didn't plan on coming back in a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Marla Henson, a dispatcher at Tatman's Towing in Urbana, said:
``We started getting calls yesterday afternoon. It was `Pull me out
of here,' `Pull me out of here.' As the night went on, the snow got
deeper, and people stopped calling,'' she said. ``Some of the
businesses are now coming in to plow. If they can't get through, we
can't get through.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-02-99 1339EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990102.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5272 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TENN-NYT     01-02 1409
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TENN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CLOSE BUNCH OF CHARACTERS HAS GIVEN TENNESSEE ITS CHARACTER
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOE DRAPE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ Their quarterback says with soulful eyes that
football is just a sport to him and has nothing to do with what he
is about. Their captain, once a boxer, now a linebacker, calls the
game war and plays through injuries that would sideline others.
</P>
<P>
   Their place-kicker is president of the Tennessee chapter of the
Fellowship of Christian Athletes, but also gets evangelical about
calling converts to the altar of Southern football. Their center
has a long, jagged scar on each arm, an unruly mountain-man beard
and, once you get past his salty language, old-fashioned opinions
about respect.
</P>
<P>
   Overseeing them and the other Tennessee Volunteers is a coach
who makes sure he is home for family time on Wednesday and Thursday
evenings and who fought the school's administration until his
daughters were allowed on the sideline during games as ball girls.
</P>
<P>
   All are characters who together have developed enough character
to win all 12 of their games, capture the No. 1 ranking in both
national polls and play Florida State (11-1) for the national
championship here Monday night. Still, they are relative no-names,
suspect because four of their victories were pulled out in the
fourth quarter, and significant underdogs to a team with an
inferior record.
</P>
<P>
   And they don't care about any of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd rather earn respect than have anyone give it to us,''
said the center, Spencer Riley, his voice booming through his beard
and seeming to jiggle his 295 pounds. ``That's fine with us. It's
been like that all year. We will earn your respect.''
</P>
<P>
   How this bunch became a team has everything and nothing to do
with the departed Peyton Manning. Now the Indianapolis Colts'
starting quarterback, Manning became the most beloved Vol of all
during a four-year career in which he set nearly every Tennessee
passing record.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond the state, a certain skepticism developed when his
won-loss record never seemed to catch up to his lineage (son of
Archie from Ole Miss) and all-American billing. He did indeed put
up a one-loss season and a couple of two-loss seasons, but never
got the Volunteers where they were picked to be in three of his
four seasons: the national title game.
</P>
<P>
   And everyone except this season's freshmen suffered for it _
especially the head coach, Phillip Fulmer. That he and Manning
failed to beat Florida in their four years together obscured the
fact that Fulmer's 66-11 career record, an .857 winning percentage,
is best among active college coaches with five or more seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got the reputation of underachievers and he got the rap of
not being able to coach,'' the senior linebacker Al Wilson said of
Fulmer. ``We had Peyton and Leonard Little and all these big-name
stars, and people didn't understand why we didn't put it all
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson is the Volunteers' captain _ the ``heart and soul'' of
the team, according to Fulmer. He was named first-team all-American
despite playing through excruciating shoulder and groin injuries
that forced him out of two games near the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson learned as a teen-ager in the boxing gym to identify
weaknesses and then attack them. Last August, he called the
Volunteers together and told them what he felt was their weakness:
the lack of big names. They didn't have any stars, he said. Manning
was gone and the defense had lost seven starters. Then Wilson told
them how the team was going to attack it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody expects anything from us,'' he said he told them. ``The
only way we would prove anyone wrong was to be a team, for
everybody to contribute. I loved Peyton, and he was a team guy. We
played hard for him, but sometimes we relied on him to make a big
play to bail us. When he couldn't, no one else was prepared to step
up. Now everyone is ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Manning is gone, he is hardly forgotten. In a corner of
the Tennessee Football Hall of Fame exhibit on campus in Knoxville,
next to the original manuscript of the school's anthem, ``Rocky
Top,'' is a life-sized, lifelike mannequin of Manning in his letter
jacket. Outside Neyland Stadium, a 105,000-seat monument to college
football, is a street named Peyton Manning Pass. Who could possibly
step out of that shadow?
</P>
<P>
   His name is Tee Martin. He is a soft-spoken, 6-foot-3-inch
junior from Mobile, Ala., from the dark heart of its toughest
neighborhood, Birdsville. When 12 friends and family members have
died in the past three years by murder, accident, or illness,
football truly becomes just a game.
</P>
<P>
   When you have escaped death in a drive-by shooting because you
happened to go inside a building to fill up some water balloons,
only to find your playmate dead on the street because he didn't, it
is not that big a deal to succeed a football folk hero. ``I'm not
Peyton, but I can do some good things,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   One of them is to give the Vols what Manning could not: a shot
at the national title.
</P>
<P>
   Only the fifth-ranked passer in the Southeastern Conference? And
only seventh in total offense? His favorite target, Peerless Price,
said those facts do not measure an undefeated quarterback. These
do: fourth-quarter game-winning drives against Syracuse, Florida,
Arkansas and Mississippi State. ``There's a calm about him that
lets us know we're going to do it,'' Price said.
</P>
<P>
   Twice this season, Martin has driven the Vols into scoring range
only to cede the spotlight to a 182-pounder place-kicker who is as
manic and talkative as the quarterback is serene and stoic. Jeff
Hall beat Syracuse with a 27-yard field goal to open the season on
the road, then booted a 41-yarder in overtime the following week to
beat Florida and end the Gators' five-year domination. He doesn't
drink, doesn't smoke, and takes his faith seriously _ as he does
the tradition of Southern football.
</P>
<P>
   Hall grew up in Winchester, Tenn., a town of 6,700 where Fulmer
also was raised. He signed with Tennessee in September of his
junior year in high school, a 16-year-old who had never even been
on an official recruiting trip to Knoxville. He said he knows that
Florida State has won 12 of its last 13 bowl games, captured the
national title in 1993 and is among the most dominant football
programs of the 90's.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we got something going, too,'' he said. ``We play in big
stadiums across the South where the great multitudes gather on
Saturday afternoons to celebrate loyalty and passion.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall stopped to catch his breath. ``I mean, really,'' he said,
``don't you think we have some destiny on our side?''
</P>
<P>
   The Volunteer faithful thought so on Nov. 14, when Arkansas
quarterback Clint Stoerner fell down and fumbled while the
Razorbacks were trying to run out the clock on a 24-21 victory. In
less than a minute and a half, Martin drove his team for the
game-winning touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   But Riley, the rugged center, has no use for magic. He rubs the
scar on his right arm, where he tore his triceps last year against
Nebraska on the second series of the Orange Bowl. It was the most
pain he ever felt, he said, worse than when he broke his other arm
as a kid, and worse than his back surgery. The pain was n0t helped
by the 42-17 beating the Cornhuskers gave the Vols on the way to
their co-national championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is what's going to help us,'' Riley said. ``We got beat
bad. We know now what a big game is.''
</P>
<P>
   Holding all these emotions together now is Fulmer. The coach who
couldn't coach was recently voted coach of the year by his SEC
colleagues. Last week, he signed a six-year contract worth $1
million a year. His wife, Vicky, and daughters Courtney, 15,
Brittany, 13, and Allison, 12, have joined him here. He said
Monday's game was rivaling what until now has been the highlight of
his football life: being voted captain of the Vols as a senior
offensive lineman in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer prides himself on his consistency, his levelheadedness.
He said this group embodies those characteristics, though he has
had far more talented teams. There's something else, too. ``At
practice all year, you would hear this chatter on the field, '' he
said. ``You'd look around and see the older players with their arms
around the younger guys, trying to explain things to them. You try
to attain that every year, but sometimes you can't.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a close bunch. They're a team.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
