<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5273 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MASS-RURAL-INTERNET-A     01-02 1250
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASS-RURAL-INTERNET-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RURAL TOWN TAKES ON OBSTACLES TO AN INTERNET CONNECTION
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. A map is being
sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH ADAMS, Mass. _ Even unimaginative futurists predict that
some not-so-distant day, geography will barely matter. Humanity's
web of electronic connections will trump it utterly. That will be
particularly nice for isolated spots like this long-depressed
former mill and factory town, cupped in the Berkshire Mountains in
the remotest corner of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   But here is the transitional rub: Sometimes the places that most
need to overcome geography have the hardest time doing it, because
they are handicapped by their distance from the nearest trunk lines
of the long-distance carriers that offer Internet connections.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, words used by members of Berkshire Connect, an
unusual task force formed by local civic and business leaders with
state help to address the problem, high-speed Internet connections
like T-1 lines are too expensive here. Connections often cost
double, triple or more what a user would pay in Boston or even
Springfield, Mass., because of the high local telephone charges to
reach the big carrier.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone companies say that with the region's sparse
population, local demand is not sufficient to justify laying new
lines that would cut the cost. So the electronic road to the rest
of the world can sometimes seem as annoyingly narrow as the winding
local Mohawk Trail.
</P>
<P>
   That gets in the way of the region's hopes, just beginning to be
realized, to replace its dead mills with engines of the new
information economy: high-tech start-ups, new media businesses and
other companies that project their presence using the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Berkshire County is not alone in its connection problem, said
Donald Dubendorf, a Williamstown lawyer and head of Berkshire
Connect's action committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of rural counties find themselves disconnected and
presenting too small a demand profile'' to prompt telephone
companies to improve and therefore cheapen Internet connections,
Dubendorf said. ``There are parallels in history _ rural
electrification in the 30's, 40's and 50's.''
</P>
<P>
   Dubendorf also found a parallel in history for what local
politicians and business leaders are trying to do with Berkshire
Connect: It is something like the cooperatives that Western farmers
formed when the new intercontinental railroads asked too much to
bring their goods to market, he said. They pooled their produce and
sought ways to buy or build railroad spurs. About a century later,
Berkshire Connect appears about to settle on information-age
equivalents to the farmers' tactics. The group is about to issue
business and technological plans, and though details have not been
released, members say they are expected to involve some laying of
fiber optic cable. In a 90's version of economic development
tactics _ what some are already calling tele-development _ the
group is expected to call for drawing the millions needed from
public and private money.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, Berkshire County residents have been at odds over
how and where to make the road improvements they need to connect
them better to the Massachusetts Turnpike and the rest of the
world. With no consensus over routes, nothing has been done. But,
task force members say, there is no not-in-my-back-yard attitude
about better telephone lines. Everyone seems to want them.
</P>
<P>
   Especially two forces: a handful of tech upstarts, most of whom
have come from Williams College and into Williamstown, down the
road from here, in the last five years; and the high-tech
Massachusetts Museum of Contemporary Art, a mammoth museum
scheduled to open its first phase in May in North Adams.
</P>
<P>
   The young founders of Tripod, one of the most visited sites on
the Web, do not complain about the high telephone rates. The
machines that handle their Internet traffic are based in New Jersey
anyway, at a company that specializes in baby-sitting for such
servers. And the higher connection cost for their Williamstown
office is offset by their rent on a sprawling former factory floor:
$2.50 a square foot. Per year.
</P>
<P>
   Bought by Lycos last year for $58 million, Tripod is not
hampered by connection costs and has been increasing its staff from
40 last year to 80 now, to perhaps 150 by the end of the fiscal
year, said Bo Peabody, 27, Tripod's president.
</P>
<P>
   Still, said Kara Berklich, 26, Tripod's director for
communications, it is cheering on the push for better connections
because one of its goals is to help bring jobs and development to
the region where stagnation so struck its founders when they were
Williams students in the early 90's.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew C. Harris, a classmate of Peabody and Ms. Berklich at
Williams and a venture capitalist who seeks to lure more
information-age companies to the region, said the price of Internet
connection was not a deal breaker when he tried to bring companies
here, but it was a liability.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is for marketing, that it labels us a backwater,''
said Harris, managing director of The Berkshires Capital Investors
in Williamstown.
</P>
<P>
   It is a disadvantage, Harris said, of about the same magnitude
as high property or electricity costs. He said he tried to counter
it by saying, ``You're going to pay more than in Boston, but your
rent will be 10 percent what it would be there, and your salaries
20 percent lower because cost of living is lower.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem looks more serious, and the hunger for better
connections seems sharper, in neighboring North Adams at the
Massachusetts Museum of Contemporary Art, the long-awaited
institution called MASS MoCA that will offer performing arts as
well as exhibitions, and aims to be a ``creative campus'' with an
emphasis on the intersection of art and technology.
</P>
<P>
   The museum already offers a technology center that allows people
to use computers and take courses on them free; it also plans to
devote some of its space in a 700,000-square-foot abandoned mill
complex to rent offices to technology-related companies.
</P>
<P>
   It plans to offer prospective tenants as ``smart'' a building as
possible, with video teleconferencing and more. But to put in a
big-bore T-3 connection, said Brett McDowell, the museum's
information and media technology director, would cost perhaps
$35,000 a month, compared with less than half that in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   When a company reaches the point that it needs a T-1 line here,
McDowell said, its manager often ends up protesting: ``You're
telling me that just to access the Internet at the rates I need is
five times more expensive than my rent?'' That, McDowell said, ``is
when the six-man new media company moves to Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   One MASS MoCA tenant, Kleiser-Walczak Construction, a film
special-effects and animation company, knows the connection problem
firsthand. Keeping in T-1 touch with the company's other offices in
New York and Hollywood costs about $7,000 a month, said its
president, Jeff Kleiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be here, we have to pay the price,'' Kleiser said. Still,
he added, the price brings admission to a ``once-in-a-lifetime
experience:'' watching the museum and economic changes help North
Adams metamorphose ``from a post-industrial wasteland to a new
high-tech-connected art community.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
