<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5275 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     01-02 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: AT LAST, VOLS AND SEMINOLES IN A BOWL GAME THAT MEANS
SOMETHING 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ Anyone lethargic enough to spend time in front of
the tube this past week is no closer to enlightenment than when
this long and trivial clutter of bowl games began.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, they finally play a meaningful game, when
undefeated Tennessee takes on Florida State in the Fiesta Bowl. The
ticket scalpers are getting killed out here because of the lack of
enthusiasm, but that's the way it goes in the old capitalism game.
</P>
<P>
   This Fiesta Bowl is for the national championship, and not a
moment too soon. There has not been a significant act in college
football in a month, since the lords of the bowls buried a very
large pickax in the back of Kansas State.
</P>
<P>
   Poor arriviste Kansas State was foolish enough to lose a double
overtime game to Texas A&AMP;M on Dec. 5 for its first loss of the
season, thereby becoming terminally disqualified from the
new-fangled Bowl Championship Series game, No. 1 vs. No. 2, here.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State understood that part well enough, but the school
had not understood just how out of the mainstream it was until the
four major bowl games finished gobbling up their eight favored
teams _ based on potential ticket sales, advertising glamour,
glorious histories and general pizazz.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of playing for around $12-million in a major bowl _
which would have enabled it to buy even better student-athletes for
its ``program'' _ Kansas State was relegated to something like a
$1-million payoff in a bowl game whose name I cannot remember.
</P>
<P>
   Looking (in vain, as usual) for a good movie on the tube one
night in late December, I happened upon Purdue overcoming benumbed
Kansas State just before the final whistle of the Alamo Bowl, a
self-fulfilling prophecy if ever there was one.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, Kansas State truly did not belong in anybody's top
eight, but every bowl season needs one team barking annoyingly on
the doorstep, against all hope of getting inside.
</P>
<P>
   According to bowl officials who raised ticket prices and
speculators who invested in them like Internet stocks, UCLA was
supposed to be Tennessee's opponent here, but UCLA was stunned by
Miami on the same strange day that Kansas State fell to earth,
while Bobby Bowden of Florida State sat in front of the television
in stunned gratitude.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA promptly died in the irrelevant Rose Bowl on Friday,
leaving Ohio State to play the role of the pretender, albeit mostly
for comic relief. Ohio State went into Friday night's Sugar Bowl
wanting to prove something by thumping Texas A&AMP;M, and thereby
setting up some scenario by which it could slip into the top
position while Florida State was staggering past Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   It was a very wobbly theory, but it was the best thing we had
going during the interminable wait. (How much alcohol or school
loyalty does it take to trek to a bowl game that means absolutely
nothing?)
</P>
<P>
   After all, the coaches who vote in the ESPN poll are already on
record that they will vote for the team that wins the Fiesta Bowl.
Otherwise, what is the whole silly business about, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   After a decent 24-14 victory over the Aggies Friday night, John
Cooper, the Ohio State coach, said, ``This was not a perfect
season, but there's no question it's a good, solid season. I don't
think we're going to be any worse than No. 2 in the country. And
depending on what happens Monday night, we might make a strong
argument that we're as good as anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper was trying to influence the writers who vote in the
Associated Press poll to somehow have a change of heart late Sunday
night.
</P>
<P>
   In this bizarre vision, the writers would say to themselves,
``Oh, man, this was one dog of a game. I have wasted my valuable
time for the better part of a week, and therefore I am voting for
Ohio State.'' That doesn't sound like human nature to me, or even
sportswriter nature, and it is not going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of hapless Kansas State, drummed out of the enriched
eight, and the pipe dreams of Ohio State are going to be used as a
rationalization for a three-week system of playoffs _
quarterfinals, semifinals and finals _ producing a real
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Don't buy into it. The traditional bowl system, tying certain
powerhouse conferences to major bowls, was a delightful Marx
Brothers conclusion for a generally ludicrous sport that invokes
the aura of higher education.
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, you had significant bowl games on New Year's
Day, the coaches voted, the writers voted, even President Nixon
chimed in with his opinion one year, and everybody argued for years
to come. Schools carried grudges, boosters provided voluminous
foolscap with comparative scores to prove that Slippery Rock could
still beat Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Michigan and Nebraska split the honors, and that was
fine, too. America was built on the democratic principle, and what
is more American than football, right?
</P>
<P>
   Even this new Bowl Championship Series does not work too badly.
Tennessee is the only top-level team in the country to go
undefeated, unless you count Tulane, which beat Brigham Young in
some bowl game a few days ago.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, nobody counts Tulane. Take a hike, Tulane. Come on,
get out of here. Time for the big boys to play. Everything else on
television last week was just a communist plot to rot your mind.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
