<HEADER>
A5276 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COSBY-MURDER-APPEAL     01-02 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSBY-MURDER-APPEAL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN SEEKS TO HAVE CONVICTION IN COSBY SLAYING SET ASIDE
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Lawyers for the man convicted of killing Bill
Cosby's son have filed a petition to set aside his conviction,
citing testimony in another trial that their client did not write
letters admitting to the murder.
</P>
<P>
   The client, Mikail Markhasev, was found guilty of first-degree
murder and attempted robbery in the death of Ennis W. Cosby, 27,
who was fatally shot while changing a flat tire here on Jan. 16,
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, David Gomez, a witness in an unrelated murder
case, testified that he had forged confession letters attributed to
Markhasev, and acknowledged having a forgery conviction on his
record.
</P>
<P>
   The letters, which prosecutors said Markhasev wrote to Gomez
while they were inmates in the Los Angeles County jail, were the
only direct evidence linking Markhasev to the crime.
</P>
<P>
   In a petition filed on Dec. 23 with the California Court of
Appeals for the Second District, lawyers for Markhasev said he
should be granted a new trial.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Ingalls, the Deputy District Attorney who prosecuted
Markhasev, said through a spokeswoman that her office stood by
Markhasev's conviction.
</P>
<P>
   In response to a prosecutor's question in the unrelated trial,
Gomez testified: ``At the time, I was in the process of forging a
case against Markhasev, the Cosby case. I had three or four guys I
was forging cases on at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the same examination, Gomez said, in response to a
question about fooling handwriting experts: ``There ain't too much
you can't give me that I can't forge. When you read my rap sheet,
you forgot the felony conviction, forgery. I was just involved in
the Markhasev case.''
</P>
<P>
   A prosecutor in that case said that the statement by Gomez was
undermined in court by other witnesses and that he might have made
it to protect himself from developing a reputation as an informer.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez was testifying in a murder case against Billy Joe Cornejo,
who was accused of fatally shooting a rival gang member. Deputy
District Attorney Michael Camacho, who prosecuted the Cornejo case,
said in an interview that Gomez had turned over jail letters in
which Cornejo implicated himself. But Gomez said he would refuse to
testify at the trial, Camacho said, possibly to protect his safety
among other inmates who would target him if he was known to
cooperate with authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Markhasev was sentenced to life in prison without parole last
August for the killing of Ennis Cosby, who was on vacation from his
studies at Columbia Teacher's College in New York when he was shot.
</P>
<P>
   The case was not straightforward. Nearly two months after the
shooting, a witness with Cosby at the time of his death failed to
identify Markhasev in a police lineup. Prosecutors used the letters
to buttress circumstantial evidence tying Markhasev to the murder
weapon and witness testimony about his statements and demeanor
after the killing was reported.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Gomez and another witness, Chris So, separately approached
The National Enquirer with offers of evidence before they went to
the police in the hopes of reaping financial rewards from the
tabloid.
</P>
<P>
   The letters are full of vague statements in a mixture of English
and Spanish. Markhasev emigrated from Ukraine but associated with
Hispanic gangs as a teen-ager. Apparently the letters carried some
weight with jurors; during about six hours of deliberations, the
only question they asked was how prosecutors obtained the writing
sample from Markhasev that was used for comparison. In them, the
writer called the Cosby killing a robbery gone bad, and wrote, ``I
went to rob a connection but obviously found something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Markhasev's lawyer, Henry Hall, sought to undermine the letter
evidence at the trial by saying that the handwriting varied within
each letter and that the letters contained inaccuracies. He said
Cosby was killed by a friend of Markhasev's who was with him that
night.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on Thursday, Hall said the judged barred
evidence he tried to introduce of Gomez's purported forgery. In the
petition, Hall said that Gomez made up the letters to get a $10,000
reward from The National Enquirer.
</P>
<P>
   Copies of the letters were originally provided to the tabloid,
which then notified the authorities of their existence. The letters
themselves were seized from several places, including the backyard
and the trash at the home of Gomez's wife, Dawn. Handwriting
experts testified to their authenticity at the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez was convicted in March of several felonies, including
robbery, forgery and rape, and sentenced to 91 years in state
prison; at the time of the trial in the Cosby murder he was serving
time in a Texas Federal prison for bank robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Camacho, the prosecutor in the Cornejo case, said Gomez
testified that he had forged the letters in that case and the
Markhasev case, and that he had a conviction for forgery. That
testimony was later challenged by a bailiff, who testified that he
had overheard Gomez and Cornejo colluding to undermine the case
while they were in a courthouse holding cell, Camacho said. Cornejo
was convicted of second-degree murder last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was trying to throw in something else to bolster
his credibility that he was a forger,'' Camacho said.
</P>
<P>
   A judge must determine whether to hold a hearing on Markhasev's
petition or rule on it without argument.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-02-99 1349EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
