<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5277 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT     01-02 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIKINGS REFLECT GREEN'S BOLDNESS AND SAVVY ;  OTHER MVPS;   THE JOB
FAIR 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Several days before last April's draft, Minnesota Vikings Coach
Dennis Green was on the telephone, predicting that if the Vikings
were able to draft wide receiver Randy Moss, their offense would be
practically unstoppable and the Vikings and Denver Broncos would be
the two best teams in football.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watch out for the Vikings,'' Green said then. ``We could be
very scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Green is doing better than those psychics on late-night
television.
</P>
<P>
   There are a lot of solid candidates for coach of the year in the
National Football League this season, but because of Green's
boldness in taking Moss, his motivational skills and his smart
free-agent pickups, the Vikings were able to cruise to the best
record in the NFL at 15-1. Minnesota also set a single-season
scoring record with 556 points.
</P>
<P>
   That is why Green leads our second annual awards _ trumpets,
please _ for excellence in the regular season. No one did a better
coaching job than Green.
</P>
<P>
   He orchestrated a number of moves that were scoffed at by other
teams when they were made but proved to be brilliant. First he
lured quarterback Randall Cunningham out of retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Then he stuck to his guns on picking Moss. Green also kept the
Pro Bowl defensive end John Randle, who had 10{ sacks this year,
the most by any interior lineman this season, from leaving by
matching a huge offer made by the Miami Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   But Green's best move may have been the one people know the
least about. After picking Moss, Green traded a third-round pick to
New England for cornerback Jimmy Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots Coach Pete Carroll did not think Hitchcock could play.
But with the Vikings, Hitchcock returned seven interceptions for a
team-record 242 yards, breaking Charlie West's mark of 236 set in
1971. Hitchcock scored three touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've built something special here,'' Green said.
``But no one will be satisfied until we win a Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   With regards to: Dan Reeves, Atlanta. The Falcons won their
first division title since 1980. Bill Parcells, Jets. New York won
the American Football Conference East for the first time since the
merger.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EXECUTIVE OF THE YEAR
</P>
<P>
   Bill Parcells, Jets. He made one mistake, sending linebacker
Hugh Douglas to Philadelphia, where Douglas had 12{ sacks. But look
at Parcells' acquisitions: linebacker Bryan Cox, right tackle Jason
Fabini, center Kevin Mawae, running back Curtis Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget what he did with quarterback Vinny Testaverde.
</P>
<P>
   With regards to: A.J. Smith, Buffalo's director of pro
personnel. He pushed to sign Doug Flutie.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MOST VALUABLE PLAYER
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Randall Cunningham, Minnesota. He and Moss actually practice
those bombs Cunningham throws Moss' way. Cunningham finished the
regular season with 34 touchdown passes and just 10 interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I feel like I'm the mvp?'' Cunningham said recently. ``I'm
just a humble guy, man. Hopefully, things will work out that way.
But a Super Bowl would be even more awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   With regards to: Doug Flutie, Buffalo. He saved the Bills'
season. Terrell Davis, Denver. He rushed for 2,000 yards.
</P>
<P>
   OFFENSIVE PLAYER OF THE YEAR
</P>
<P>
   Terrell Davis, Denver. He joins Eric Dickerson, Barry Sanders
and O.J. Simpson as the only players to rush for more than 2,000
yards in a season. Because of Davis, the Broncos are the favorites
to reach the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   With regards to: Vinny Testaverde, Jets.
</P>
<P>
   DEFENSIVE PLAYER OF THE YEAR
</P>
<P>
   Michael Strahan, Giants. It is not an overstatement to say that
Strahan has a chance to become one of the best defensive linemen of
the decade. This season, if he had not been playing, the Giants
might have won only four games. He had 15 sacks.
</P>
<P>
   With regards to: Reggie White, Green Bay. He had 16 sacks. Ty
Law, New England. He had nine interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ROOKIE OF THE YEAR
</P>
<P>
   Randy Moss, Minnesota. He finished with 17 touchdowns, a
startling number, displaying the kind of explosiveness the NFL has
rarely seen from a rookie.
</P>
<P>
   With regards to: Charles Woodson, Oakland. He had five
interceptions. Jacksonville running back Fred Taylor and New
England running back Robert Edwards each had more than 1,000
rushing yards. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BROWNS' MERCHANDISE MART
</P>
<P>
   The expansion draft of veterans, coming next month, is as
important to the Cleveland Browns as the rookie draft in April. The
Browns could pick up some good players who are either too expensive
for their original teams to keep, or are backups and deserve a
chance to start.
</P>
<P>
   Each team must expose five players, and the league is
strengthening several rules to keep teams from cheating. The main
one has to do with exposing injured players. Only one player of the
five can have been on injured reserve this past season or have had
a post-season operation. Either way, doctors must certify that the
player will be able to play in 1999.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A VOTE FOR THE BRONCOS
</P>
<P>
   The Jacksonville Jaguars played both the Broncos and Vikings
this season. They lost at Denver, 37-24, on Oct. 25 and lost at
Minnesota, 50-10, on Dec. 20. So which team is better in
Jacksonville's opinion, the Broncos or the Vikings?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Denver is a stronger team,'' Jaguars linebacker Kevin
Hardy said. ``The Vikings have a lot of weapons, but I think Denver
is stronger because they can really pound the ball with Terrell
Davis. The Vikings rely more on the big play.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville's Pro Bowl offensive tackle, Tony Boselli, wouldn't
voice an opinion, but he said he would rather play at Denver than
at the noisy Metrodome, which is one of the loudest stadiums in the
league.
</P>
<P>
   When Jacksonville played Minnesota, the Jaguars' linemen could
not hear the calls of quarterback Jonathan Quinn several times.
Boselli and other linemen had to turn around to hear the cadence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept telling him to yell louder,'' Boselli said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE JOB FAIR
</P>
<P>
   If Green Bay Packers Coach Mike Holmgren leaves Green Bay to
become general manager and coach of another team, the team he joins
must give the Packers a second-round pick. Holmgren could end up in
San Francisco or Seattle. . . . Stanford Coach Tyrone Willingham
continues to be discussed as a potential head coaching candidate in
the NFL, but friends say Willingham has no intention of leaving
Stanford this year unless something extremely attractive comes
along to change his mind. . . . The Pittsburgh Steelers' defensive
coordinator, Jim Haslett, interviewed last week for the
Philadelphia Eagles' head coaching job and remains the
front-runner. If Haslett does get it, look for him to secure Norv
Turner as his offensive coordinator _ if Turner is fired as
Washington's head coach. Haslett is also interested in the Giants'
defensive backs coach, Johnnie Lynn, as a defensive coordinator.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
