</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-RUTGERS-WOMEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUTGERS RELISHES CHALLENGING TENNESSEE IN THE GARDEN
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the last two years, the Rutgers women's basketball program
has been rising steadily, like a mountain climber striving to reach
new heights. Last season, the Scarlet Knights reached the Round of
16 in the NCAA tournament. This season Rutgers is 10-2 and ranked
No. 15 in the Associated Press poll, and the Scarlet Knights are
expected to challenge Connecticut and Notre Dame for the Big East
championship.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday afternoon, Rutgers will take another significant
step. In the first women's college basketball game at Madison
Square Garden since 1981, Rutgers will face Tennessee, the
defending national champion and the most dominant women's team this
decade.
</P>
<P>
   It will be a showcase for both teams, the type of event that can
help a program's reputation and recruiting. For the players, it
will be a memorable experience. And for Rutgers, it will be another
chance to show how far the program has come, and how far it has the
potential to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great game not just for us, but for women's college
basketball,'' said C. Vivian Stringer, now in her fourth season as
the Rutgers coach. ``I understand the historical significance.''
</P>
<P>
   Stringer was also part of the last women's game at the Garden,
as the coach of Cheyney State in 1981, when her team played Rutgers
as part of a doubleheader. Louisiana State played Old Dominion in
the other game. More than 17 years later, Stringer is ready to do
Manhattan again, and according to Garden officials, about 11,000
tickets have already been sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been so many years since there has been a women's game
at the Garden, and it could open the door for other games to
follow,'' Stringer said. ``I want us to look good. If we can play
the way we need to, we can come out of there with a win. But we'll
have to play better.''
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers was eagerly looking ahead to Sunday following
Wednesday's 79-67 victory over Georgetown, which extended the
Rutgers winning streak to four games. It was a typically balanced
offensive performance by the Scarlet Knights, who have five players
averaging at least 9 points a game. The 5-foot-10-inch junior
forward Shawnetta Stewart is a versatile scorer and solid defender,
the senior guard Tomora Young is the team's main 3-point shooter
and forward Linda Miles is coming off a splendid 19-point
performance against Georgetown.
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers is talented and deep, dominated by sophomores and
juniors who keep improving. Key players like Stewart, Miles, Tasha
Pointer, Davalyn Cunningham, Usha Gilmore, Tammy Sutton-Brown and
Coko Eggleston will all return next season, and the foundation for
a consistent top 20 team has been set.
</P>
<P>
   ``By all measurements, our program is probably ahead of
schedule,'' said Stringer, the only women's coach to take two
different schools (Cheyney State and Iowa) to the Final Four. ``But
I don't tell our kids we're ahead of schedule. I'm not satisfied,
and I fully expect us to reach another level.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing Tennessee, which has won three consecutive NCAA
championships, will show Stringer exactly where Rutgers stands. The
No. 2-ranked Lady Vols (10-1) will enter the Garden riding a
nine-game winning streak, and the dynasty built by coach Pat
Summitt looks as strong as ever. Sunday's game will be a homecoming
for Chamique Holdsclaw, the 6-2 senior forward from Queens who is
the nation's best player, averaging 21.6 points and 8.5 rebounds.
Holdsclaw, the sophomore forward Tamika Catchings and the sophomore
guard Semeka Randall give Tennessee three all-Americans from last
year in the starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   A 78-68 loss to Purdue is the only blemish on the Lady Vols'
record, and they have looked extremely impressive since then. In
their last game, they dominated Mississippi, 92-51.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people would not play Tennessee at this time of year,
but I'm happy,'' Stringer said. ``They're a great team with a great
coach. Just to have the opportunity to play in that great arena is
a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity. These young women may not
appreciate it now, but when they walk in that great arena, they'll
know. I think they'll step up and rise to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the challenge of facing Tennessee was too much for
Rutgers. It was the Lady Vols who ended the Scarlet Knights' season
by whipping them, 92-60, in the NCAA tournament. The Rutgers
players have not forgotten, and they insist Sunday will be
different.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no intimidation,'' Gilmore said. ``We learned a
lot last year, but it's also just a game, a regular-season game.
This is not the Sweet 16 or the Final Four. We're going to try and
take care of business, and if we win, thank you, Lord. But if
something else happens, we're not going to drop our heads. The
season is still going to go on.''
</P>
<P>
   But as regular-season games go, they do not get much bigger.
Stringer said that for weeks, part of her practices have focused on
Tennessee. It is an opportunity that Stringer and her players
relish, a chance to shine on center stage. And no matter what
happens, Stringer knows the game itself is another milestone for
the Rutgers program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not too many players can walk around saying they had a chance
to play at the Garden,'' Stringer said. ``Thirty years from now,
it'll be something they still remember.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
