A5303 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-NBA-LOCKOUT-NYT     01-02 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NBA-LOCKOUT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMEMBERING '94, SOME ARE TAKING PLEASURE IN NBA'S PAIN
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MURRAY CHASS     
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   People in baseball wouldn't wish their 1994 experience on their
worst enemy, but David Stern isn't their worst enemy.
</P>
<P>
   As the National Basketball Association enters its do-or-die
week, baseball officials know the feeling. But all they did was
kill the World Series for the first time in 90 years. Stern, the
NBA commissioner, is on the brink of wiping out an entire season.
If he and the team owners take that fatal step, they will go from
history of one sort to history of another, from having been the
only league never to have lost a game to a work stoppage to being
the only league ever to lose a whole season.
</P>
<P>
   No one in baseball will say it publicly, but some officials have
acknowledged privately that they have enjoyed watching Stern
plummet from one stage toward the other. The perfect commissioner
of the perfect league could use some soiling, they have long felt,
and now, even if a jury-rigged season is salvaged, the stains will
be indelible.
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball has an economic stake in the NBA's
problems as well. The NBA has been perceived in recent years as the
sport of the moment. Sports fans do not have unlimited money to
spend, so if more becomes available to spend on tickets to baseball
games or on baseball merchandise, so much the better for major
league teams, which desperately seek increased revenue.
</P>
<P>
   As a labor dispute, the NBA's problem is no different from the
one baseball endured in 1994. It's all about the division of
revenue between owners and players. The only difference is that the
baseball dispute prompted the players to strike, while the
basketball fight resulted in an owners' lockout.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the players walked out Aug. 12, and after a few more
futile bargaining sessions, Bud Selig, then the acting baseball
commissioner, set Sept. 9 as the day on which the rest of the
season and the World Series would be canceled if no agreement was
reached.
</P>
<P>
   The day before the deadline, the union presented a new proposal
to the owners centered on a tax that would be levied on the
revenues and the payrolls of the 16 higher-revenue clubs. More than
a year later, it was a luxury tax on the five highest payrolls that
brought an end to the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   On the day before the deadline, however, the owners' negotiators
rejected the tax plan, sticking instead to their quest for a salary
cap. As a footnote to baseball labor history, one member of the
seven-person contingent that presented the new proposal to
management was Kevin Brown, who recently became the sport's
highest-paid player and whose $105 million contract should put the
Los Angeles Dodgers firmly in the tax-paying group.
</P>
<P>
   Selig let the Sept. 9 deadline pass. Five more days went by
before the owners voted by 26-2 to cancel the rest of the season
and the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Stern has set Thursday as the NBA deadline. If the two sides
have no agreement, he has said, he will recommend to the owners
that they call off the season. Taking an even harder position,
going into the weekend the commissioner had refused to meet with
union officials to receive their latest proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The union responded by saying no meeting, no proposal. But
details were leaked to the news media, so the league knew the union
was willing to place a cap of $15 million on individual player
salaries. No such limit exists in any major sports league.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Stern has lobbied heavily with the players,
twice mailing them details of league proposals and urging the union
to allow the players to vote on the league's latest proposal. Even
more aggressively, he has called the union's 19-player negotiating
committee a runaway group that is holding the rest of the players
hostage, has accused some agents of destructively influencing
negotiations and has suggested that players who express opposing
views are disciplined by the union.
</P>
<P>
   David Falk, Stern's No. 1 target among the agents, has said
Stern's words and actions are those of a desperate man. Indeed, an
outsider watching and listening to the commissioner could
reasonably conclude that he is desperate to save the season his
lockout has jeopardized and wants the players to rescue him.
</P>
<P>
   Although there has been more noise than substance to the
complaints about agents' influence on the talks, in the baseball
strike, three agents were instrumental in helping lay the
groundwork for an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The basketball union's use of a negotiating committee, for which
it has been criticized, is routine. In each baseball labor
negotiation, the union's executive board has appointed a
negotiating committee that has had the authority to make a deal.
The dissenting comments of a handful of rank-and-file players do
not demand a major change in the committee's position.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is there any reason for a union to listen to a commissioner
when he calls for a vote of the membership. These negotiations have
been far different from those of 1995, when Stern had a friendlier
union head, Simon Gourdine, to bargain with.
</P>
<P>
   If the season is canceled, the NBA and the players face a risk
of unknown proportions. Once the season is lost, the incentive for
an agreement lessens greatly and positions harden. After the World
Series went down in 1994, negotiators did not meet for two months,
and it took a judge's ruling, not collective bargaining, to enable
the 1995 season to begin.
</P>
<P>
   If the NBA does not have a 1998-99 season, no one can guarantee
1999-2000.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
