<HEADER>
A5305 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;      01-02 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL NOTEBOOK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   YOU'VE BEEN TRADED, SON
</P>
<P>
   Bob Boone remembers the time Al Campanis, then the Los Angeles
Dodgers' general manager, traded his own son, Jimmy, to the Kansas
City Royals. Boone never thought he would have a similar
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a strange emotional feeling,'' Boone said. ``I've had the
opportunity in the course of my career to do some pretty unusual
things and be around some special things. I never had the
opportunity to trade your kid. It's pretty unique.''
</P>
<P>
   As a member of the Cincinnati Reds' front office, Boone
participated in the November trade that sent his son Bret Boone to
the Atlanta Braves for Denny Neagle. Did Bob, a former major league
catcher, feel any guilt?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I'm pretty analytical,'' he said. ``My wife is a little
upset at me. I tend to look at things and say what's the best for
all parties here. This is a good deal for him. He lives right by
the complex in spring training. He doesn't have to move. He and his
wife are building a home in Orlando. When he goes on the road, if
she wants to go home, it's an easy plane flight.''
</P>
<P>
   Bret Boone was the Reds' second baseman. His younger brother,
Aaron, could be the Reds' third baseman next season. ``Aaron's his
own man,'' their father said. ``He and his brother are very good
friends. You don't like to see your friend leave, but it'll have no
effect on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Boone the elder is not completely void of feelings when he
watches his sons play. Explaining that he looks at them from two
perspectives, father and baseball appraiser, Boone said: ``I
probably get a little more nervous for them when they're in
situations. `Come on, you gotta get a hit here, show off a little.'
I managed against Bret a couple years in the coast league and I
coached him when I was a bench coach in '94.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been around it more than most. I don't know if it's
easier, but you get used to it. You get used to watching them with
a daddy's eye and a professional eye. My job is to evaluate, so you
have to be analytical.''
</P>
<P>
   WHEN $15 MILLION ISN'T ENOUGH
</P>
<P>
   If a pitcher is paid $15 million a year, he should reasonably be
expected to be one of the best pitchers in the league, certainly
among the top five. But the Dodgers apparently don't think $15
million is enough for Kevin Brown. His contract calls for award
bonuses, including for his placement in the Cy Young award voting.
If he finishes as low as fifth, he receives $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   That $15 million a year isn't enough for other expenditures,
either. Much has been made of the 12 round-trip flights in a
private jet for his family to selected games _ he will make enough
to buy his own plane _ but the Dodgers will also pay for ground
transportation and eight premium season tickets.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are not alone in their eagerness to force
unnecessary bonuses and payments on players. Along with $13 million
a year, the Mets will give Mike Piazza bonuses for certain awards
and the use of a luxury box at Shea Stadium for regular-season and
post-season games.
</P>
<P>
   On top of his $13.1 million a year and award bonuses, Randy
Johnson has the use of a luxury box at the Arizona Diamondbacks'
park and also gets two season tickets for the Phoenix Suns.
</P>
<P>
   The Baltimore Orioles aren't giving Albert Belle tickets for
basketball games, their games or plane flights, but they will give
him $1 million on top of his $13 million salary if he wins the most
valuable player award. If he finishes 10th in the voting, he gets
$125,000.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, Bernie Williams missed out in his $12.5 million-a-year
contract with the Yankees. No plane flights, no luxury box, no
bonuses for being 12th in the MVP voting. Just his salary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
