<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BAADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERIC CRULL BAADE, 70, CLASSICIST AND TEACHER
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eric Crull Baade, a scholar of the classics, a teacher and a
co-author of a widely used Latin textbook series, died on Dec. 15
at his home in Rockport, Mass. He was 70.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was pancreatic cancer, said a spokeswoman for the
Brooks School in North Andover, Mass. Baade taught and headed the
classics and theater departments at the college preparatory school
until his retirement eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Fort Wayne, Ind., he graduated in 1949 from Yale
University, where he also earned his doctorate degree in 1956. In
the intervening years he served as an Army Intelligence analyst and
operations chief in the Korean War from 1951 to 1953.
</P>
<P>
   He first taught at the Brooks School from 1949 to 1951, and he
returned in 1964. Over the years he also taught the classics at
Yale, Phillips Academy in Andover, Mass., Columbia University and
St. Stephen's School in Rome.
</P>
<P>
   He was the author or co-author of six books on Greek and Latin
writers. His scholarship was recognized early in his career when he
was awarded the Prix de Rome for 1956-57 by the American Academy in
Rome.
</P>
<P>
   He also was a co-author with Charles Jenney and Rogers Scudder
of ``Jenney's First Year Latin'' and ``Jenney's Second Year
Latin.'' First published in 1968, both texts went to seven
editions.
</P>
<P>
   Baade is survived by his wife, Isobel Milne Baade; a daughter,
Anne C. Baade of Larchmont, N.Y.; and two grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
