<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MANNERS-ACTOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVID MANNERS, 98, FILM ACTOR MENACED ON SCREEN BY LUGOSI 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Canada, Calif., Ill.)   By ERIC PACE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Manners, who starred in Hollywood films in the 1930's and
played the hero in Tod Browning's 1931 ``Dracula'' and other
classic horror movies of that day, died on Dec. 23 in the health
center of a retirement community in Santa Barbara, Calif. He was
98.
</P>
<P>
   Almost a decade ago, Manners modestly told a film historian that
horror films were his ``only claim to movie fame.'' But horror
films were only a fraction of the more than three dozen movies in
which he appeared during that era, often in romantic leads.
</P>
<P>
   In Browning's ``Dracula,'' which starred Bela Lugosi in the
title role, Manners played the role of John Harker, the sturdy
fiance of the heroine, Mina, played by Helen Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1932 film ``The Mummy,'' which starred Boris Karloff in
the title role, Manners and Zita Johann portrayed a terrified pair
of lovers. In Edgar G. Ullmer's ``Black Cat'' (1934), Manners,
playing a young American novelist, got third billing after Karloff,
as the leader of a cult of devil worshipers, and Lugosi, as the
husband of one of Karloff's victims.
</P>
<P>
   In one of his romantic roles, Manners played the fiance of
Katharine Hepburn in her film debut in ``A Bill of Divorcement''
(1932). His other partners in on-screen romances included Barbara
Stanwyck in ``The Miracle Woman'' (1931) and Loretta Young in
``Kismet'' (1930), in which he played the caliph.
</P>
<P>
   Manners was born far from Arabia or filmland, in Halifax, Nova
Scotia, the son of George M. Acklom and the former Lillian Manners.
His original name was Rauff de Ryther Duan Acklom, but he evidently
felt that plain David Manners would look better in lights.
</P>
<P>
   He attended the University of Toronto. After training in acting
at the Hart House Theater in Toronto, he made his stage debut there
in 1924 in the title role of Euripides' ``Hippolytus.'' He also
performed in plays in New York and Chicago before moving on to
Hollywood and in the 1940's made further appearances on the New
York stage.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his Hollywood successes, a friend recalled, Manners came
to dislike the pressures and pretensions of the film world and left
Hollywood for a ranch in the Mojave Desert of Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   A book of excerpts from the journals he kept during those years
was published with the title ``Awakening From the Dream of Me.''
His writings in his later years also included the novels
``Convenient Season'' and ``Under Running Laughter'' and a
nonfiction work, ``The Soundless Voice.''
</P>
<P>
   An early marriage ended in divorce. He leaves no immediate
survivors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
