<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   Austin American-Statesman Y2K package
</P>
<P>
   AUS-Y2K-DOOM _ From their extravagantly untidy goat farm hidden
in the Texas cedars, Kerry and Prisca Wooster are trying to jump
start America's survival instincts. The Woosters are self-anointed
messengers of the millennium. From this remote and unlikely nerve
center, where rusted ghosts of cars and scrap metal outnumber the
15 goats, they send high-tech warning sirens to the Internet. The
message: The Year 2000 computer bug will push life so far off-line
that only the well-prepared will survive. (Gamino, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   w/AUS-Y2K-ELPASO _ The gravity of the year 2000 glitch became
clear the day the lights went out in El Paso. At 4:30 p.m. on
August 21, the Texas Department of Mental Health and Mental
Retardation lost power at a facility where 123 people with mental
disabilities live. No contingency plan was in place for a major
electric failure. The year 2000 computer problem had nothing to do
with the crisis in El Paso. But state officials say incidents just
like it _ or worse _ could occur in Texas if state agencies do not
conquer the Y2K bug. (Gamino, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   AUS-Y2KARE _ Depending on which expert you listen to, the Y2K
problem could be as unnoticeable as a minute tick on a seismic
flatline or a cacophonous pre-Apocalyptic roar shattering our
otherwise Zen-like calm. Where the differing opinions on the
computer bug from Hell meet is that we should all, to some degree,
be prepared. While most caution going overboard on the food
hoarding and money withdrawal, others say you can never do too
much. (Kallenberg, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   RIVER-RESTORE _ HABERSHAM COUNTY, Ga. _ Severe erosion along the
Soque River was causing the loss of100 tons of soil a year on
Justin Savage's farm in Habersham County in North Georgia. The soil
was washing into the Soque, a tributary of the Chattahoochee River,
making the stream unfit for fish and destroying its natural beauty.
Now, an intensive project by EPA and environmental groups is
restoring the natural flow of the river and the native vegetation
to bring the stream back to life. Already, native brown trout have
returned to the stream. Seabrook. The project is being watched
closely by water experts around the Southeast as an example how a
degraded river can be restored. (Seabrook, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   AUS-ELECTRONIC-TONGUE _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Big companies want it to
test new food and drink products. The American military has
something more distasteful in mind: monitoring the disposal of
chemical and biological weapons. Competing with them to pick the
first practical and profitable use of an electronic tongue invented
at the University of Texas are four UT graduate business students
who won't get their degrees until May. (Stanley, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
