<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-STADIUM-SEATING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATCHING ON AT THE MOVIES: A CLEAR VIEW FOR ALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By IVER PETERSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST WINDSOR, N.J. _ It is the week after Christmas, schools are
out and in towns everywhere grandparents and grandchildren, cousins
and uncles, sleepover friends and just moms and dads are flocking
to the local movie house. Then, the minute they sit down, a giant
with hair up to here sits down in front of them and blocks the
screen.
</P>
<P>
   To hear moviegoers tell it, that universal gripe is becoming
less common thanks to the latest in theater design: stadium-style
seating that puts patrons head and shoulders above the row in
front.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a theater closer to us, but it seems that every time
Kerianne sits down there someone blocks the view, and that just
ruins the experience for her,'' said Nancy Watlington, who with her
husband, Don, was just then sitting down in the Regal Town Center
Cinema here to see ``The Rugrats Movie'' with their 3{-year-old
granddaughter, Kerianne.
</P>
<P>
   Even with a grown-up seated in front of her, the little girl's
view of the screen was clear.
</P>
<P>
   In an age when entertainment technologies are converging _ car
stereos sound like home systems, televisions act as computer
screens and a combination of multichannel home sound and high
definition television promises to mimic the real movies _ theater
owners are striving to offer more of the comforts of home,
including an unobstructed view of the screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been going to the movies on the old slab floors for
nearly 100 years, and in a way it's amazing that it hadn't changed
earlier,'' said Phil Zacheretti, Regal's senior vice president of
marketing and advertising. But since the movies' modern competition
includes not just broadcast television but also videotape, digital
video discs and cable, ``our thought is that you have to give
customers extra value to bring them out,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Stadium seating started in Dallas in 1994, and it still tends to
be found mainly in new suburban multiplexes. But Regal Cinemas,
United Artists, Loews Cineplex and other theater chains have plans
to bring the design to more city movie houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every theater we build now is stadium, and I think you'd be
hard-pressed to find any theater company that isn't doing it,''
said Marc J. Pascucci, senior vice president of Loews Cineplex,
which has 2,800 screens at 450 locations worldwide. ``Not only is
the sight line better but you also get increased legroom.''
</P>
<P>
   And because stadium seating theaters have to have higher roofs
to accommodate the 8- to 14-inch rise between each row, the new
theaters can have bigger screens in relation to their seating
capacity. ``You get a bigger wall for your screen because you're
building a higher box,'' Pascucci said.
</P>
<P>
   Loews plans to open two new stadium seating multiplexes in
Manhattan in the spring and summer, including a 13-screen building
in Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   The big movie chains are also busy converting some of their
conventional theaters to stadium seating, although Pascucci of
Loews said such retrofitting was difficult to do in any but the
most recently built spaces.
</P>
<P>
   Stadium seating costs about half again as much to build as
conventional seating with a sloping floor, theater officials said,
and the design reduces the number of seats in a given space by 10
to 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Yet since conventional theaters are still far more numerous,
theater owners dare not charge much more for the new seating,
Zacheretti said. Regal's $4.75 matinee admission is the same as
what conventional theaters charge in central New Jersey, and its
evening rate of $7.75 is only 25 to 50 cents higher than most of
its competition.
</P>
<P>
   So with school out and the afternoon free, Bonnie Gagnon of
Allentown, N.J., took two children to a matinee at the Regal
specifically to take advantage of stadium seating.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be so hard to go to the movies with little kids because
a lot of times they just can't see, unless you sit way down in
front,'' Ms. Gagnon said.
</P>
<P>
   As it happened, they sat only a few rows back _ and up _ because
the children wanted to sit in one of the double-wide love seats,
another feature adapted from home television-viewing by many
theaters.
</P>
<P>
   The love seats are actually designed for parents with small
children, Zacheretti said, but love finds a way to use them, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sit in them with my husband,'' said Ann-Marie Adamko, of
East Windsor, ``because you can, you know ...'' She made a cradling
motion with one arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sat in one once, with a girl,'' said Kevin Perdoni, a
freshman at Rowan College. ``It was her idea.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
