<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOTEL-LAWSUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALE OF A LAVISH HOTEL IS MIRED IN LEGAL FIGHT
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Four Seasons, whose lavish rooms and panoramic
views of the New York skyline make it one of the world's most
expensive hotels, is not an easy sell.
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say the sleek 52-story hotel, on 57th Street east
of Madison Avenue, has trouble filling its 370 rooms, where the
limestone, onyx and beechwood interiors feature bedside switches
that operate the window blinds and bathrooms with color televisions
and tubs that fill in 60 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   But only two years after buying the Four Seasons _ where the
3,000-square-foot presidential suite goes for $10,000 a night _ a
Hong Kong company that needs to sell the prized hotel to pay
mounting debts finds itself unable to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The company, Lai Sun Hotels, recently became ensnared in a legal
battle with Gene E. Phillips, a Dallas real estate operator, and a
company he controls, American Realty Trust.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips, who said in court that he signed a purchase deal with
Lai Sun, has brought the sales effort to a virtual halt, even as
three other wealthy buyers are clamoring to snap up the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   It is only the latest evidence that New York real estate is not
for the fainthearted.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York is perceived as the capital of the world and the Four
Seasons is one of the top hotels in the city,'' said Daniel Lesser,
senior director of the hotel group at Cushman &AMP; Wakefield, a real
estate broker. ``But in New York, real estate deals can be a
full-contact sport.''
</P>
<P>
   With a financial crisis sweeping Hong Kong and much of Asia, Lai
Sun has been forced to raise cash by selling the Four Seasons, as
well as the Beverly Wilshire Hotel in Los Angeles. The Four
Seasons, which has no connection to the Four Seasons restaurant in
New York, is considered a world-class trophy by hoteliers. It has
the highest average room rates in the country, at more than $600 a
night.
</P>
<P>
   Lai Sun owns a 50 percent stake in the hotel through a complex
web of foreign companies that, according to the lawsuit, were set
up to avoid income taxes, a not uncommon real estate practice. The
other owners are also based in Hong Kong, and real estate
executives say that each one has tried to tinker with the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not able to speak as a unified group,'' said one real
estate banker who negotiated unsuccessfully with Lai Sun in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   American Realty Trust contends in a lawsuit filed earlier this
month in New York State Supreme Court that it made a $2 million
down payment and signed a letter of intent in October to buy the
Four Seasons for $270 million, $80 million more than Lai Sun paid
for it in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of closing on the deal in November, the lawsuit
says, Lai Sun fraudulently used the offer ``as a stalking horse to
generate other offers for the hotel.'' American Realty is seeking
$80 million in damages and an injunction barring Lai Sun from
selling the hotel to anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   In response to American Realty's complaints, the lawsuit says,
Lai Sun promised to abide by the preliminary deal but then demanded
an additional $15 million down payment, which the Dallas company
rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Real estate executives and rival bidders said that in November
and December at least three other investment groups, including
Apollo Real Estate Advisers, reviewed financial documents in what
is referred to as the war room at the Four Seasons and were
interested in buying the hotel. Several real estate bankers
complained that American Realty tied up the hotel and then tried,
unsuccessfully, to secure financing for the acquisition. Lawyers
for both American Realty and Lai Sun in New York declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips, whose family trust is the largest single shareholder
of American Realty, once headed the Southmark Corp., a large real
estate company that fell into bankruptcy court in 1989 after losing
$1 billion in nine months. Angry investors waged a legal war
against him that continues to this day. Still, companies controlled
by Phillips bought many of Southmark's assets at bargain prices.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel analysts contend that the longer it takes to sell the Four
Seasons in New York, the less money Lai Sun will make on the deal.
They said that the market in New York had peaked, with sale prices
having retreated since the spring.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Strategic Hotel Properties of Chicago walked away from
a deal to buy the Four Seasons for $370 million, or about $1
million a room. Five months later, American Realty signed a letter
of intent to buy the hotel for $730,000 a room.
</P>
<P>
   ``This hotel should have been sold a year ago,'' said Arthur
Adler, a partner at the Sonnenblick-Goldman Corp., a real estate
investment bank. ``It's a little bit tougher now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
