<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 15:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5337 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPRINKLER-NYFIRE-NYT &LR;      01-02 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINKLER-NYFIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTIGATION CENTERS ON USELESS SPRINKLERS IN FATAL FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn., Ky.)  (dw) 
 By KEVIN FLYNN     
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Investigators may never find out who turned off the
sprinkler system in a Brooklyn high-rise building where three
firefighters died in a fire last month. But an equally troubling
mystery is how the system's uselessness could have gone
undiscovered _ probably for years.
</P>
<P>
   Maintenance workers at the 10-story residence for the elderly,
which is run by the New York City Housing Authority, have told
investigators that they never knew the sprinkler system had been
turned off, because they did not know about several closed valves
hidden in a drop ceiling on the first floor. These valves were
critical because they controlled the flow of water to the
sprinklers on the upper floors.
</P>
<P>
   But according to Fire Department records and interviews with
city officials, several of the workers responsible for the system
were required as part of their city training to review schematic
plans of the sprinklers that should have disclosed the location of
those valves.
</P>
<P>
   Hilly Gross, a spokesman for the Housing Authority, said three
employees at the building had been tested on the intricacies of
sprinkler networks before being certified by the Fire Department to
inspect the system. Given that training, Gross said, he could not
explain why these employees later could not pinpoint the sprinkler
system's basic components.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are valid questions, and they are the same questions
that the inspector general is asking,'' said Gross. ``But we just
have to wait until the inspector general completes his report.''
</P>
<P>
   The Housing Authority's inspector general is conducting the
investigation with other officials at the New York City Department
of Investigation, the Fire Department and the Brooklyn District
Attorney's Office.
</P>
<P>
   Fire officials have said that working sprinklers might have
saved the firefighters, who were engulfed by flames as they
struggled to save a tenant on the top floor. Their deaths on Dec.
18, and a second fatal high-rise fire in Manhattan five days later,
have pushed city officials toward considering requiring sprinklers
in new apartment towers.
</P>
<P>
   Maintenance workers at the Brooklyn building have told
investigators that they had thought the only control valve to worry
about was a main valve in the basement, which was open during the
fire. But the system failed because five other valves, behind
separate panels in the first-floor ceilings, were closed.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators say they believe those valves had been closed for
years, because the panels do not appear to have been opened since
the hallway was painted in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Since sprinkler systems come in many different configurations,
the city fire code requires that the person responsible for
maintaining a system knows how it works. That person must pass an
exam on that particular type of system before the Fire Department
will give him a certificate of fitness to maintain the system.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, applicants must bring to the test a blueprint or
drawing of the sprinkler system that is detailed enough to show the
location of critical components like control valves, fire officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gross said three Housing Authority workers assigned to the
building at 17 Vandalia Ave. had received the proper certificate of
fitness to inspect its sprinkler system.
</P>
<P>
   But Gross said it was possible that the plans they reviewed as
part of the test did not show the critical valves. ``Maybe they
didn't appear on the drawings,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to reach the three workers were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Fire officials said they could not clarify the issue because all
drawings and plans are returned to the applicant. The Housing
Authority already has acknowledged that it cannot find a second set
of records, the required inspection reports for the sprinkler
system that its certificate holders should have been filing each
month.
</P>
<P>
   The building's superintendent and manager were transferred after
the fire because of the lapses.
</P>
<P>
   Given the absence of inspection records, investigators are now
going through 12 years' worth of maintenance records that catalog
repairs to the building.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Regan, a Fire Department spokesman, declined to comment
on the sprinkler issue, citing the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   New York City is ahead of many other places, sprinkler
contractors said, in that it requires some training and a
certificate of fitness for people who maintain and inspect
sprinkler systems.
</P>
<P>
   The fire codes in many other places require only that the
responsible person be someone considered ``qualified,'' they said.
</P>
<P>
   But several states, including Tennessee and Kentucky, require
that annual inspections be performed only by licensed sprinkler
contractors, according to Claude Chafin, the president of Security
Fire, a sprinkler contractor in Tennessee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
