</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYC-CROWDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS VISITORS SWARM INTO NEW YORK, RESIDENTS FEEL CROWDED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By BARBARA STEWART    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Waiting in line at the 47th Street Starbucks last
Thursday afternoon, Denise Vasquez and Georgia Locko took a break
from sightseeing to assess their first 12 hours in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Up early, they had found their way to the No. 1 line and pushed
into a train at rush hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Packed,'' Ms. Locko said. ``Jam-packed, like sardines _
people's shoulders were in my face.''
</P>
<P>
   At Times Square, they made their way to TKTS, where discounted
theater tickets are sold, dodging pedestrian traffic on the
sidewalks of Broadway. At the TKTS booth, a few thousand people,
covering Duffy Square and spilling onto the street, were standing
in line. Ms. Vasquez and Ms. Locko took places at the far end. It
took them an hour to move up close enough to discover that all the
shows were sold out.
</P>
<P>
   So, how did they like New York City so far?
</P>
<P>
   ``Really exciting,'' said Ms. Locko, 20, from Nacogdoches,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely fun,'' said Ms. Vasquez, 36, from Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of city residents, though, would consider a
day of pushing through crowds and waiting in line to be hellish.
They may appreciate the boost that outsiders bring to shops,
restaurants and other businesses, but as private citizens, their
feelings tend to range from irritation to sheer hatred.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, many visitors are straying from the tourist sights
and venturing into territory that residents more or less consider
their own: the sidewalks of Greenwich Village; the lesser-known
museums, like the Frick and the Asia Society, and the quiet
neighborhood restaurants. They are crowding the already crowded
subways and flagging the empty taxis.
</P>
<P>
   All this is making some of the city's already grumpy residents
even grumpier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate these crowds,'' said Sid Schneider, a research
psychologist in line at the TKTS booth. ``Where do they come from?
There must be nobody at home in places like Kansas City. They're
all here. I've never seen anything like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, New York probably hasn't, either. There is no official
count of visitors in the city this holiday season, which stretches
from late November to the first Monday of the new year. But several
markers indicate that more visitors are in New York than ever
before.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the number of passengers arriving at La Guardia
and Newark Airports this season has risen by almost 5 percent over
a year ago, according to estimates by airport officials.
</P>
<P>
   Radio City Music Hall expects to sell 30,000 more tickets than a
year ago to the 206 performances of its Christmas Spectacular.
There has been a 10 percent increase in the number of people
touring the Empire State Building. Big Apple Greeters, a nonprofit
organization in which resident volunteers guide visitors around
various neighborhoods, has given twice as many tours as a year ago.
This season, 100 guides have given tours of Brooklyn Heights,
Harlem, Arthur Avenue in the Bronx, and other areas.
</P>
<P>
   And of course, there were the New Year's Eve crowds at Times
Square. With a half-million people covering 40 square blocks, it
was the biggest New Year's Eve gathering ever, according to police.
</P>
<P>
   The event is one of the times that residents willingly join the
enormous crowds, enjoying the energy that tens of thousands of
people can generate together _ the way they do at the Macy's
Thanksgiving Day parade and at a baseball game at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Tourists _ some of them, anyway _ think crowds are fun,
especially multicultural ones. ``A menagerie of people,'' as one
Wyoming college student put it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what New York is,'' said Todd Gitlin, a professor of
media studies at New York University. ``That's how they know
they're not in Texas. The tall buildings in lots of places, the
press of human flesh _ they feel they're getting the New York
essence, which is congregation.''
</P>
<P>
   While city residents generally do not feel that joy in the
everyday crowds, academics say there are benefits that suburbanites
are missing out on.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've discovered that all the suburbanization and shopping
malls are boring, boring, boring,'' said Marshall Bermen, a
professor of political studies at the City College of New York.
``Crowds are good. Crowds make the city safer. People come here to
be part of New York's conviviality.''
</P>
<P>
   And in this freeze, crowds are warmer, said Ann Douglas, author
of ``Terrible Honesty: Mongrel Manhattan in the 20's.'' Shopping at
Macy's, she found herself in ``an ocean of bodies, moving in two
directions. There were so many people on the streets, it was like
an outdoor heater. Everyone was a little furnace. It felt festive _
New York as a mecca.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
