<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUT WEST, RANGERS SHARE THE ART OF STAGED FISTCUFFS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Defenders of hockey's fistfighting subculture often
say that punching outbursts are spontaneous reactions during the
frantic action of a fast-paced, collision-based sport.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes this is true, but most fights are calculated affairs
between cool-headed specialists. Such was the case in the Rangers'
game at Colorado last Thursday, a 6-3 victory for the New Yorkers,
who Saturday night were to play the Blues here on the last stop of
a four-game trip.
</P>
<P>
   The fight between Darren Langdon of the Rangers and Scott Parker
of the Avalanche was scripted before the opening face-off when
Ranger Coach John Muckler put Langdon in his starting lineup and
Avalanche Coach Bob Hartley countered with Parker. Both are
part-time players known primarily for fisticuffs. Anyone familiar
with the National Hockey League knew what would quickly occur.
Twelve seconds after the puck dropped, without any contact between
the two, Langdon and Parker exchanged words, dropped their sticks
and gloves and raised their clenched fists to begin a lengthy
battle.
</P>
<P>
   Both gave as much as they received and Langdon sat down in the
penalty box with a deep, red gash on the small finger of his right
hand and ice bags over both sets of knuckles. He has appeared in
only 18 of the Rangers' 34 games but has accumulated 41 penalty
minutes. Parker has 43 minutes in 16 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``With fighting, you've always got confidence until you get
knocked out or something like that,'' Langdon said. ``Then you lose
a bit and you want to get back at it. That didn't happen yet, knock
on wood.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Canadian author Roy MacGregor once noted, hockey fights
are ritualistic, with a series of moves as precise as those of a
minuet. When Langdon and Parker squared off, the linesmen did not
try to break them up. Instead, they moved the sticks away so no one
would be injured.
</P>
<P>
   Apologists and advocates for hockey fights, including the
Canadian commentator Don Cherry, often say that baseball has more
bench-clearing brawls than hockey. While this is true, it is also
true that baseball teams, unlike hockey teams, do not decorate
their rosters with one or two players whose best skill is punching.
The consensus around the league is that Tony Twist of the Blues is
the best in the business. Langdon is in the top echelon, with a
workmanlike style that is effective but not especially
entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   As a group, these warriors are like gunslingers from movies
about the old West, with their own code of the hills. Elite
fighters rarely battle outside their class; it would be bad form to
pick on someone who does not aspire to their level. Parker is a
rookie with a reputation from his days as a junior with Kelowna of
Canada's Western League. Last season, Parker had 243 penalty
minutes in 71 games. Like many fighting specialists, he studies
videotape of future foes. This helped him in a recent tiff with
Vancouver's Donald Brashear. ``I've watched a lot of his fights,''
Parker told The Rocky Mountain News. ``I knew what I had to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in this decade, there was serious momentum to ban
fighting in the NHL by ejecting those who fought. Critics said
fighting gave hockey a bad image in the United States and would
make it hard to expand in cities of the Sun Belt. Wayne Gretzky,
now a Ranger, was among the anti-fighting advocates, as was Mario
Lemieux, the retired Pittsburgh Penguin.
</P>
<P>
   Gil Stein, the league's acting president in 1992-93, used an
anti-fighting plank in his platform during his unsuccessful
campaign for the newly created title of commissioner. But the
anti-fighting movement was defeated when Glen Sather, the Edmonton
Oilers' general manager, persuaded his fellow team officials to
instead support a watered-down rule that called only for the
ejection of instigators. Even that penalty, called only
occasionally, has been diluted from a game misconduct to a
10-minute misconduct. In a standard fight, each man gets only a
five-minute major penalty and their teams continue to play with the
full complement of five skaters each.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is often said that players are rarely injured in
fights, there are now more injuries than ever, partly because the
specialists have become such experts. Last season, the career of
Toronto's Nick Kypreos ended because of a concussion from a fight
in an exhibition game.
</P>
<P>
   Colin Campbell, the former coach of the Rangers who is the
league's senior vice president and chief disciplinarian, often
praised certain fighters as ``honorable tough guys.'' Among them,
in Campbell's estimation, was Stu Grimson, now with Anaheim.
Grimson, a born-again Christian known as the Grim Reaper, is the
type of fighter who will tell linesmen to break up a battle if he
feels he has hurt his opponent so badly that the foe can no longer
defend himself.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell has also harshly criticized fighters like Buffalo's Rob
Ray, who used to take advantage of foes by shedding his jersey and
fighting bare-chested. This gave Ray an extra edge because
opponents could not clutch his jersey for balance while swinging
with the clenched fist of the other hand _ the standard style.
Because of Ray's innovation, the league passed a rule calling for
the ejection of players who shed their jerseys in fights. The
Devils' Lyle Odelein was recently ejected for this.
</P>
<P>
   It is acceptable for a fighter to rip the helmet from a foe's
head, as Parker did to Langdon. This exposes his skull while saving
wear and tear on the knuckles of the puncher. However, it is taboo
to sucker-punch a foe from the blindside during the flow of play.
Matt Johnson, the Los Angeles Kings tough guy, was suspended for 12
games by Campbell after Johnson knocked out Jeff Beukeboom of the
Rangers with a thundering blow to the back of the head. To live
outside the law, as someone once sang, you must be honest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-02-99 1536EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
