<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5355 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOHNSON-DESCENDANT-AR     01-02 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-DESCENDANT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARRYING A FAMILY HISTORY OF IMPEACHMENT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Va, Wash.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JOSEPH BERGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTVALE, N.J. _ Thomas C. Colt III is not what you might expect
in the great-great-great grandson of a president, even an impeached
one like Andrew Johnson. At 63 years old, he lives on Bergen
County's northern rim with a cat named Sheena in what he blithely
describes as a hovel, orderly and booklined as his weather-beaten
bungalow is. He makes his living delivering pizza for $5.25 an hour
and selling hardware at Sears. His rusting 1970 Opel has notched
500,000 miles, he says, and he spends hours fixing it.
</P>
<P>
   He is something of a Herzog, compulsively writing letters of
complaint to presidents and editors. On a snowy day, he likes to
grab a cup of coffee and settle himself near the wood-burning
furnace that sits idiosyncratically on an outdoor porch, instead of
indoors where most of the human race would expect to find it. He
enjoys watching the snow swirl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 63 going on 15,'' he likes to say.
</P>
<P>
   But pixilated as he seems, he is also a cultivated man and has
made a thorough study of his ancestor's impeachment. He has
concluded that Andrew Johnson was railroaded by zealous Republicans
who despised his opposition to their Reconstruction policy toward
the South, a policy Johnson inherited from Lincoln. Colt is sure
the nine other living Johnson descendants feel pretty much the same
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``There hasn't been a legacy of shame,'' he said ``We knew him
and he was very true to his standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Colt, who has the rough white beard and stout build of a Burl
Ives, does not blame his ancestor's history for his own modest
station. He met descendants of other presidents on ``The Joan
Rivers Show'' years back and found them an assorted lot, ranging
from distinguished Roosevelts to a humble heir of Calvin Coolidge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a matter of their own accomplishment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In his case, his father was a Virginia museum director, but the
family broke up and his mother _ the Johnson descendant _ moved the
children to New Hampshire. In college, he majored in broadcasting
but grew disillusioned after deciding that television had become a
wasteland.
</P>
<P>
   ``The business did not satisfy my standards,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, he lived like a beatnik in San Francisco, enjoying
good times ``in a rooming house filled with fellow travelers'' and
adopting Kerouacian philosophies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't do anything unless it's worth doing, and by `worth' I
don't mean money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So it is no surprise that his resume proceeds in fits and
starts, like his Opel on a bad day: reporting for the Bergen
Record, editing a trade newspaper, public relations at Bergen
Community College, driving a taxi, delivering pizza.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a little bit slower than the rest of my crew, who are
mostly college and high school kids,'' said his boss, Gary Sernak
at Natale's Pizza. ``But he is willing to do anything. He has no
qualms doing dishes or sweeping up.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever one thinks about the arc of his life, Colt sees
everything he does with a tenderfoot's wide-eyed cheerfulness.
Selling hardware? ``You potentially have the opportunity to make a
new friend every day,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He never married, never had children. He is a realist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had any prospects sufficient for supporting a family,
so I just didn't,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   While others dismiss Johnson as incompetent, Colt sees him as
principled, a president who stuck to his guns in the face of a
mutinous Congress. Still, he suggests that a legacy of such
resolution has been a handicap in a world that requires a certain
amount of calculation and accommodation for success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mostly, it's been a limiting factor in my life,'' he said.
``Johnson set the standard for our conduct, and all of us pretty
much adhered to it. There're just certain things I don't feel I can
do.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
