<HEADER>
A5360 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-REGION-COLD-NYT &LR;      01-02 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-REGION-COLD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGION BUNDLES UP AS IT BRACES FOR SNOW, SLEET AND RAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN     
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With the bone-piercing cold that ushered in the new
year set to give way to snow, sleet and ultimately freezing rain,
emergency crews across the New York metropolitan region were on
alert Saturday, watching the forecasts as they prepared to salt
hundreds of miles of roadways and respond to downed power lines and
other weather-related problems.
</P>
<P>
   At 6 a.m. in Central Park, the thermometer measured a trifling 9
degrees _ above the record of 2 degrees set in 1918 but cold enough
to keep many people in bed on a Saturday morning and to remind
those who dared to venture out that, after two years of atypical
warmth, there still is a season called winter in New York.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a colossal storm rampaging across the Midwest, not
the cold, that sounded the warning siren for this region's
sanitation departments, utility companies, transportation officials
and other emergency workers. The forecasts predicted an inch or
more of snow, followed by sleet and rain.
</P>
<P>
   Officials predicted widespread delays at the airports for today
and Monday, with hundreds of flights canceled and thousands of
travelers stranded at the end of the holiday weekend as the storm
paralyzed airline hubs throughout the Midwest. In New York, the icy
rain predicted to last through Sunday morning was expected to slow
traffic on the runways.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the city's Sanitation Department loaded its 353
huge salt-spreading trucks and readied more than 1,000 snowplows,
said Paula Young, a department spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ready,'' proclaimed Nick Calabrese, a superintendent at
a garage on the West Side Highway in Manhattan, where there were
trails of sand-colored rock salt on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have our spreaders loaded and plows on our trucks, just in
case,'' Calabrese said, adding that extra personnel had been called
to work in anticipation of the storm. ``We have got it down to a
science, when to start preparing and when to send the trucks out.
They train for this all year round.''
</P>
<P>
   The heaviest precipitation was expected to hit late Saturday
night. Fred Gadomski, a meteorologist at Pennsylvania State
University, said that New York City would probably see a steady
transition from snow to sleet to rain, possibly leaving a fine
glaze of ice on power lines and roads by this morning. After that,
temperatures were expected to climb into the 40s.
</P>
<P>
   The interior regions north and west of the city were expected to
be hit hardest by snow and ice, Gadomski said, with temperatures
not expected to rise much above freezing.
</P>
<P>
   Consolidated Edison said it expected to receive the greatest
number of emergency calls in Westchester County, where the company
maintains its largest number of overhead power lines. The ice and
heavy precipitation were expected to down numerous lines, said Jim
Larkin, a spokesman. Larkin said the company spent two days
preparing its trucks and that 32 additional crews were called to
work Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, Public Service Electric &AMP; Gas doubled and, in
some areas, tripled the number of people on duty Saturday night,
with extra attention paid to the southern and western portions of
the state, said Mark Capalbo, a company spokesman. ``With the storm
coming, we put everybody on call,'' he said, adding that a major
problem would be tree branches knocking down power lines.
</P>
<P>
   Michael R. Fleischer, a spokesman for the New York State
Department of Transportation, said officials would make use of
high-technology sensors built into the pavement of major roadways
as well as weather satellite systems to monitor conditions and
coordinate anti-icing efforts. ``It's a pretty sophisticated
system,'' he said. ``We gear up for these type of events. We are
prepared for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The state had readied an arsenal of antisnow equipment,
including 1,300 plows that weigh 25 tons each, and about 500 pieces
of other equipment, including bucket loaders, graders and large
snow blowers. An army of 3,400 equipment operators and another 600
support staffers would come in to put it all to work, Fleischer
said.
</P>
<P>
   But even as the emergency crews prepared for the worst, many
people throughout the region said they were glad to experience
winter again. ``It's never too cold,'' Bill Arsell and Fred Pudash
exclaimed in unison as they hunted for ducks Saturday on Long
Island. Wearing long johns and a camouflage coat and hat, Pudash
set off on an aluminum skiff into Oyster Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want the cold weather because it pushes some of the birds
from their nests,'' Pudash said.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, many people said they were unfazed by the
weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not cold, it's winter,'' said Bruce Temkin, 35, as he
went to buy groceries at a supermarket in Greenwich Village
Saturday morning. ``I am praying for snow,'' Temkin added. ``It's
beautiful, it blankets the city, and it's peaceful and it doesn't
ruin your day like rain.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-02-99 1545EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
