<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5362 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-PATAKI-GIULIANI-NY     01-02 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PATAKI-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: THE UNEASY RELATIONSHIP BETWEEN PATAKI AND GIULIANI  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAN BARRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In struggling to describe the curious relationship between Gov.
George E. Pataki and Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani, people who are
close to the two men sum it up this way: It's nothing personal.
</P>
<P>
   That seems to ring true. No matter how often the state's top two
Republicans smile and praise each other before the cameras, the
governor is not likely to invite the mayor for a heart-to-heart
chat during one of his periodic strolls through the leafy woods
near his home in Garrison. Politics and politics alone defines
their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   So then what is one to make of the broadsides that Pataki has
aimed at the city since his re-election in November?
</P>
<P>
   The most damaging volley came when the governor ignored the
mayor's protests and signed a bill that could lead to much higher
pay raises for the city's police officers and firefighters. Given
that Pataki vetoed a similar bill in 1996 _ earning Giuliani's
gushing gratitude at the time _ his action smacked of aggression.
</P>
<P>
   The governor also has blocked the city's efforts to collect more
money from a settlement with tobacco companies, vetoed a bill to
give nearly $100 million to the city's Health and Hospitals Corp.,
and gave a costly pension-related concession to the United
Federation of Teachers. The mayor and the governor also have been
at odds over how much money the state will provide for housing the
homeless mentally ill.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Giuliani has continued to sing Pataki's praises, but
through gritted teeth. Although he usually does not hesitate to
criticize and even ridicule those who cross him, the mayor has good
reason to hold his tongue. First, he knows that the city will need
the Pataki administration's assistance with scores of other
matters; second, the governor controls the state Republican Party,
whose endorsement Giuliani may someday seek in a possible campaign
for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The Giuliani-Pataki relationship has a troubled past and a
competitive future. Giuliani famously cast his lot with the
Democratic incumbent, Mario M. Cuomo, rather than with Pataki in
the 1994 election, and has been self-flagellating ever since to
mollify those Republicans who see him as a traitor. Now, both men
are rising stars in a national Republican Party thought to have the
intestinal fortitude for only one New York hotshot at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no wellspring of affection, no predisposition to be
pleasant,'' said Gerald Benjamin, dean of the College of Liberal
Arts and Sciences at the State University of New York at New Paltz
and a close observer of state government. ``And as they pursue
their ambitions, the less positive elements of their relationship
come forward. You tend to remember the last fight, even though in
between you had some good times together.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Pataki and Giuliani say they get along better than most of
their predecessors, which is saying something. Because of their
competing interests, mayors and governors often quarrel, even when,
or especially if, they belong to the same party (see
Lindsay-Rockefeller and Koch-Cuomo). Still, the subtle distrust
between the two men has risen close to the surface since the
beginning of last year's campaign season.
</P>
<P>
   When Giuliani volunteered to campaign for Pataki in the city and
in the suburbs, the offer was politely declined. When the governor
fared poorly among city voters in his decisive re-election, some in
the mayor's camp complained that Pataki's anemic showing had
contributed to the defeat of Sen. Alfonse M. D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   When a Giuliani adviser said publicly that the mayor might
someday challenge the governor in a primary, some in Albany took
quiet note, despite Giuliani's convincing pledge that the adviser's
musings were flat-out wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some state Republican leaders wondered whether the
mayor could have done more to help Dennis C. Vacco, the attorney
general, in his failed quest to challenge voter registrations in
New York City. Vacco, who was ousted in a close election, wanted
the mayor to dispatch police officers to knock on doors to check
registrations. The mayor said he would do so, but only if a judge
ordered such action. Vacco failed to obtain such an order, and the
whole drama left some Republicans with the sense that Guiliani did
not do enough for a mortally wounded Republican colleague.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not surprised by our glorious Republican mayor,'' said a
senior Republican official who spoke on the condition of anonymity,
referring sarcastically to the Vacco case.
</P>
<P>
   Since his re-election, Pataki has made several decisions that
have benefited the city. But from the city's perspective, the bad
has far outweighed the good.
</P>
<P>
   The most serious blow was the governor's decision to sign a bill
that gives the Patrolmen's Benevolent Association and other police
and firefighter unions the right to ask that a state panel _ rather
than a city one _ arbitrate wage impasses. The union believes that
the bill will create higher salaries for city officers who make
less than their suburban counterparts; the city believes that it
will create budget problems.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki vetoed the earlier version of the legislation in 1996,
but the state Legislature embarrassed him by overriding the veto.
The Giuliani administration succeeded in having the law overturned
in court, but the episode left Pataki smarting, according to a
person close to the Pataki administration who spoke on the
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   That person said that Pataki had hoped Giuliani would resolve
his differences with the police union and instead has aggravated an
already strained relationship. The governor, who received the
endorsement of the Patrolmen's Benevolent Association last year,
saw the matter in a different light this time.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani would say only that the governor's decision was a big
mistake and vowed to challenge it again in court. His aides point
out that it affects the city more than it does the Giuliani
administration, whose term, limited by law, will be close to an end
when the next police contract is scheduled for negotiation.
</P>
<P>
   One Giuliani aide attributed Pataki's recent decisions on police
arbitration and other city matters to the governor's poor showing
among city voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a few weeks before the election, they were talking about
winning New York City with a certain amount of bravado,'' said the
aide, who insisted on anonymity. ``I think they realized that they
lost in New York City worse than two-to-one, and this is what
happens. Politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin, however, said that he was not convinced that Pataki's
decisions reflected any pattern of anti-city, anti-Giuliani
sentiment. Rather, he said, Pataki's behavior has to be seen in
terms of Pataki's goals.
</P>
<P>
   It's not personal; it's politics. As Benjamin said, ``It's
nuanced.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
