<HEADLINE>
DISTRIBUTOR OF ARAB PAPER GOT THREAT BEFORE FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By SUSAN SACHS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two days before an attack on the Queens company that
distributes the influential international newspaper Al Hayat and a
number of other Arabic-language newspapers, an unidentified caller
left a vague but threatening message in Arabic on the company's
answering machine, Yazid A. Mourani, its president, said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the holidays, the company, Media Marketing Research
Inc., discovered the message only after an attack on its
distribution center in Queens in which a car was driven through a
steel gate in front of the building and set on fire on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was someone cursing, but there were no specifics, no
nothing,'' Mourani said.
</P>
<P>
   The caller did not mention any of the newspapers handled by the
company, he added, and the poor quality of the tape makes it
difficult to make out either the Arab dialect or the nationality of
the caller.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the car, a stolen 1992 Mitsubishi, did not contain
explosives, but was gutted in the fire. No one was injured at the
warehouse building, at 25-25 51st Ave., and the burning car caused
only minor damage to the gate.
</P>
<P>
   A Police Department spokesman said Saturday that the
investigators had not determined a motive for the attack or its
specific target.
</P>
<P>
   The Joint Terrorist Task Force, which includes local law
enforcement agencies and the Federal Bureau of Investigation,
responded to the 4:30 p.m. fire. A spokesman for the New York City
office of the FBI said the agency had not decided whether it would
stay involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, the sorting-out process is still continuing
here, as to what happened and who is responsible,'' said the
spokesman, Joseph Valiquette. ``Our interest is, obviously, to see
if those events would warrant a federal investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Hayat, which is printed and distributed in the New York City
area by Media Marketing Research, was the target of a letter bomb
campaign at several of its overseas offices and its London
headquarters two years ago. One of the bombs exploded in the mail
room at the London office, injuring two workers. The other bombs,
including those sent to the Washington and New York bureaus of the
paper, were discovered before they blew up.
</P>
<P>
   Mourani said his company has been threatened before because of
its association with Al Hayat. In May, he said, a caller threatened
to blow up the distribution company's building but nothing came of
the threat.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper has not received any threats recently, a
spokeswoman for Al Hayat in London said Saturday. Reporters in the
paper's bureaus in Washington and New York also said they had
received no threats.
</P>
<P>
   Al Hayat, owned by a relative of the Saudi royal family, is
widely considered the world's most prestigious Arabic-language
newspaper. It prints a broad spectrum of political opinion and
recently covered the activities of Islamic fundamentalist groups in
Egypt and the dispute between leaders of Iraq and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Al Hayat, the Queens company distributes another
Saudi-owned international daily newspaper, Asharq Al Awsat, the
semiofficial Egyptian daily Al Ahram, the independent Palestinian
daily Al Quds, and a variety of New York City publications in
Arabic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
