<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYC-SECURITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL SAFETY OFFICERS BRIDLE AT TRANSFER TO POLICE CONTROL
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By LYNETTE HOLLOWAY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Police Department took control of
security in the city's schools on schedule on Dec. 20, police
officials said last week.
</P>
<P>
   But many of the 3,200 school safety officers who used to report
to the board of education said they were unhappy with the change in
their supervision, complaining that as their responsibilities were
changing significantly, their status and pay were not. They will be
called safety agents, not officers, to avoid confusion with police
officers, and will not have guns or badges.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the guards learned for the first time last week that
they would be subject to some of the rules that affect police
officers, including the one that prohibits officers from
moonlighting for other city agencies. Many of the security agents
frequently rely on such second jobs to supplement their salaries.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials informed the agents of the new regulations last
week at two two-day orientation sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're changing everything but the color of our skin and our
salary,'' Marva Grant, a school safety officer said Thursday. ``We
need second jobs to feed our families. Were we considered in any of
these decisions? Show us what we get for this.''
</P>
<P>
   The police official making the presentation was silenced by the
outburst.
</P>
<P>
   Other guards also expressed disatisfaction, although others
still were sanguine.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis Samuels, 32, who has worked as a school safety guard for
nine years and has a second job as a school custodian for a private
company that works for the board of education, said he was unsure
whether he would be able to keep his custodial job.
</P>
<P>
   Another guard, who refused to give her name, saying she feared
reprisal, complained after attending an orientation meeting that
``they beat around the bush about everything. They are not telling
us anything.''
</P>
<P>
   But Constance Middleton, a school safety officer for 20 years,
did not oppose the change. ``I'm all right with it,'' she said. ``I
don't think we're being asked to do more. We're not police officers
so we're not going to get everything they get.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Mancuso, secretary-treasurer of Local 237 of the
International Brotherhood of Teamsters, which represents the
agents, said that in March the workers would receive a minor
increase in retirement benefits and a raise of 4.75 percent,
bringing their salaries to about $24,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Mancuso said that some of the workers' concerns related to
holidays, which are still under negotiation. The police department
has refused to recognize days such as Christmas Eve and the day
after Thanksgiving, as holidays, he said. Another unresolved issue
is whether agents will be given bullet-proof vests, a move that
Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew has resisted, Mancuso said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're seeking is no diminishment in benefits and we're
seeking equality with all school-safety officers,'' Mancuso said.
</P>
<P>
   In September, the board of education voted unanimously to
transfer control of security in the city's public schools to the
police department. The vote came despite pleas from parents and
civil libertarians that the presence of quasi-police officers would
interfere with the learning atmosphere in the schools.
</P>
<P>
   Many objections to the plan came from black leaders, who argued
that many black children have strained relations with the police.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 safety officers will remain at the board of education,
19 of them in a new Division of Student Safety and Prevention
Services, which will track student absenteeism and tardiness. The
others who remain at the board of education will continue to
provide security at the board's headquarters on Livingston St.
Police officers will continue to patrol 128 of the city's schools
to which they have previously been assigned.
</P>
<P>
   A police official who spoke at the orientation meetings warned
all the officers to document everything they do in case
revenge-seeking students file false complaints against them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-02-99 1557EST &QL; 
