<DOCNO> NYT19990102.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5372 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUS-Y2K-DOOM-COX     01-02 1539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUS-Y2K-DOOM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Survivalists preparing for collapse of electronic society
 &HT;    (WITH PHOTOS.)
 &HT;    Survivalists getting ready for collapse of computers
 &HT;    By Denise Gamino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEXAS HILL COUNTRY _ From their extravagantly untidy goat farm
hidden in the Texas cedars, Kerry and Prisca Wooster are trying to
jumpstart America's survival instincts.
</P>
<P>
   The Woosters are self-anointed messengers of the millennium.
From this remote and unlikely nerve center, where rusted ghosts of
cars and scrap metal outnumber the 15 goats, they send high-tech
warning sirens to the Internet. The message: The Year 2000 computer
bug will push life so far off-line that only the well-prepared will
survive.
</P>
<P>
   They fully intend to be on the safe side of the silicon brink _
far from what Kerry Wooster calls ``the advancing Twinkie-starved
hordes'' who will be scavenging for food next year. They are ready.
</P>
<P>
   Medicinal herbs? Check. Whole grain in storage? Check. Windmill?
Check. Kerosene lanterns? Check. Wood stove? Check. Nonhybrid
garden seeds? Check.
</P>
<P>
   Gun? Slingshot? Check, check.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are just the common people of America, desperately
scrabbling for what we perceive to be a chance of survival,'' said
Wooster, 53, who cleans houses with his wife for poverty-level
wages. ``What is wrong with preparation?''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's virtually no doubt we're going to be dropping back to
pre-1800s lifestyle,'' he said as he sat in the cluttered cottage
he built years ago as an add-on to the beached 40-foot refrigerator
trailer he used to haul as a trucker.
</P>
<P>
   As the Woosters prepare for the worst, they're not alone. A
small but growing number of people are becoming consumed by the
doom of a possible disaster on Jan. 1, 2000. They are stockpiling
food, water, toilet paper and even generators. Some suppliers of
freeze-dried food already report being sold out.
</P>
<P>
   And while government officials believe the Woosters'
all-or-nothing attitude is excessive, they are beginning to warn
the public that making some emergency preparation would be wise. In
Austin, some mainstream families are converting garages into Y2K
caches.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials expect the Y2K bug to cause something
abnormal, but they predict it will remain in the inconvenience
category. They acknowledge that not everything that runs on a
computer chip will be fixed by Jan. 1, 2000, and say there is a
potential for disruptions in electricity, telephones and public
transportation. Contingency plans are in place, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prudent precautions are really all that's necessary,'' said
Gary Chapman, director of the 21st Century Project at the LBJ
School of Public Affairs at the University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   He recommends storing supplies for a week, including food,
water, cash and flashlights or candles.
</P>
<P>
   As the millennium approaches, surveys show Americans are divided
on the Y2K issue, Chapman said. The Woosters in the Hill Country
are millennial pessimists, fiercely lined up on the extreme edge of
the one-third of Americans worried about computers going haywire on
Jan. 1, 2000. Another third know nothing about a potential Y2K
problem, and another third are sure things will be corrected in
time.
</P>
<P>
   The Woosters are trying to alert people by running the Texas
Hill Country Christian Survival List on the Internet. The messages
range from what type of garden seeds to buy (open-pollinated; they
reproduce) to fears about airplanes falling from the sky if
computers seize up.
</P>
<P>
   Although their Internet messages connect them with scores of
people, their face-to-face dealings with people have suffered
because of their absorption with the Y2K issue. They have lost
friendships and even a job because people tire of their gloomy talk
and ask them not to return. Church doesn't offer a regular link to
society because they don't belong to one. ``We home-church,''
Prisca Wooster said.
</P>
<P>
   Their shrinking world saddens them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot even get our friends and families to listen to us
and begin to prepare for the disaster that we fear is about to
happen,'' Kerry Wooster said. ``It is heartbreaking that we are
having to leave them behind, when it could all be so easy if they
would just help.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more we try, the more we find we are really completely
alone.''
</P>
<P>
   The Woosters do not want the exact location of their 27 acres
revealed, because they fear desperate looters will arrive to look
for water and food after Jan. 1, 2000. Their farm is west of
Kerrville.
</P>
<P>
   The clutter inside their stone-floor cabin is nearly as thick as
the rubbish that dots their farm. Outside are tin cans, used tires
and odd piles of scrap metal. Inside the house are magazines, jars,
two computers and even an old Navy siren that doesn't work.
</P>
<P>
   The wall calendar says March 1972, but they are too busy with
their day jobs and the added burden of preparing for Y2K to even
notice. The only date they care about is Jan. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   They gladly offer a tour of their gardens, where they grow
herbs, peaches, sweet potatoes, pumpkins, strawberries, squash and
assorted other organic food. Prisca makes yogurt from the goat milk
and also makes soap. They have stored several hundred pounds of
whole grains but do not plan to save more than is necessary for
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not purchasing all of the Twinkies that we can get our
hands on,'' Kerry Wooster said.
</P>
<P>
   The Woosters haven't kept track of how much they have spent to
prepare for the Y2K bug. She says $15,000, but he says far less.
</P>
<P>
   Adequate preparing for the Y2K bug shouldn't cost that much,
said Chapman, the UT lecturer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything that is available to people like (the Woosters) is
certainly an advantage, but it's not worth spending a tremendous
amount of money to provide or to take it up as an entire
lifestyle,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm telling people to have enough cash and emergency supplies
for a week,'' said Chapman, who is organizing a town hall meeting
on Y2K with local and state officials who want to raise public
awareness of potential problems.
</P>
<P>
   People also should obtain paper copies of important financial
and legal documents such as savings account balances and birth
certificates in the event of computer shutdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm telling people to be somewhere safe on Jan. 1, 2000,''
Chapman said. ``I personally wouldn't want to be in a airplane, an
elevator or a subway.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither does Sam Loy or Kevin McConnell. They are computer
professionals in Austin who are worried enough about the potential
for Y2K problems to store food, water and other supplies for their
families. They both were inspired by Y2K warnings published by Ed
Yourdon, a national computer expert who wrote ``Time Bomb 2000,'' a
book about possible calamities.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're basicaly preparing as reasonably as we can for a
worst-case scenario,'' Loy said. ``We're not counting on a worst
case-scenario and don't go around trying to scare people. At the
same time, we're not hiding'' their preparations.
</P>
<P>
   Loy, a software engineer at Interphase, plans to spend about
$1,500 laying in a year's worth of emergency supplies for himself,
his wife and their two teenage daughters: 400 pounds of whole grain
that can be milled by hand. 3,000 gallons of water. Canned food.
Candles. Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Loy has been trying to get the Shady Hollow neighborhood
interested in the Y2K problem and formed the Shady Hollow Community
Coalition for Preparedness. But he was met with overwhelming
indifference from his neighbors and has scaled down his direct
alert campaign to the people on his block. Loy isn't sure what will
happen on Jan. 1, 2000, but he wants to be ready.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not going to be somewhere in the middle,'' he said.
``It's going to be one extreme or another. It's probably going to
be either very easy or very difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   ''If one bad thing does happen, I think it will be a ripple
effect,'' he said. ``My gut feeling is it's going to be pretty
bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin McConnell, who designs and coordinates computer network
systems for IBM, also foresees trouble. His family of four is going
to stockpile a month's worth of food, water and supplies, he said,
just as if they were preparing for a blizzard or mammoth ice storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got our Y2K storage cabinet we're stashing stuff in,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other employees at IBM are making similar preparations, he said.
But he finds most people still have a complacent attitude toward
the Year 2000 glitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us are, `Well, someone else will take care of it,' but
when you start understanding all the implications of what happens
if we lose power for so long or if small businesses have issues
getting supplies from a supplier because they have a Y2K problem
...
</P>
<P>
   ``The snowball will get created. It's just a matter of how
big.''
</P>
<P>
   Snowball, ripple effect, dominoes _ whatever you call it, those
who are preparing say taking precautions doesn't erase the worry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that we are scared to death,'' Kerry Wooster said.
``We are damned if we do and damned if we don't. The truth is, we
have the guts and the vision and the faith to go for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We intend to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
