<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5373 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUS-Y2K-ELPASO-COX     01-02 0439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUS-Y2K-ELPASO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Power outage in El Paso a hint of what could be
 &HT;    By Denise Gamino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The gravity of the year 2000 glitch became clear
the day the lights went out in El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   At 4:30 p.m. Aug. 21, the Texas Department of Mental Health and
Mental Retardation lost power at a facility where 123 people with
mental disabilities live. The staff had no contingency plan for a
major electric failure.
</P>
<P>
   The year 2000 computer problem had nothing to do with the
problem in El Paso. But state officials say incidents just like it
_ or worse _ could occur if state agencies do not conquer the Y2K
bug.
</P>
<P>
   The staff wrote purchase orders by the light of flashlights to
get oxygen tanks for residents who could not breathe on their own.
Food was taken to nearby homes so it could be put in a blender for
residents who could not eat solids. Residents were taken to
air-conditioned shopping malls to protect them from the summer
heat. Coin laundries kept linens fresh. Ice chests stored
medications.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, a kind of bucket brigade was formed to fuel an
emergency generator with gasoline from local service stations.
</P>
<P>
   The power outage lasted more than three days, and it took
another three days to get the computers working. The electric
problems were traced to a faulty cable.
</P>
<P>
   The El Paso outage is ``similar to what might be expected from
Year 2000 failures,'' says a recent report by the Texas Department
of Information Resources, which is overseeing the Y2K corrections.
</P>
<P>
   The El Paso emergency would have been worse if it had been
caused by Y2K, say mental health officials. ``In the event of
power-related problems due to failures brought on by the year 2000
event, the outages will be regional in nature and not isolated to
one facility,'' said an agency report on the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``In addition, the power grid in this area extends into and
connects with power suppliers in Mexico,'' the report said of
concerns that any Mexican failure could quickly affect Texas power
grids.
</P>
<P>
   In a regional power failure, malls would have been without
power, emergency generators would have been grabbed by others, and
local frozen-food storage facilities could not have saved the food
supply.
</P>
<P>
   The emergency in El Paso prompted the Texas mental health agency
to start drawing up contingency plans for each medically fragile
resident in its two dozen institutions, and to plan other backup
measures. The agency also plans to ask for emergency money for each
institution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
