<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990102.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 16:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5374 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUS-Y2K-PLANS-COX     01-02 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUS-Y2K-PLANS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Generators, seeds on shopping list
 &HT;    By Gregory Kallenberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Depending on which expert you listen to, the Y2K
problem could be a minute tick on a seismic flatline or a
cacophonous, pre-Apocalyptic roar.
</P>
<P>
   Where the differing opinions on the computer bug from Hell meet
is that we should all, to some degree, be prepared. While most
caution against going overboard on the food hoarding and money
withdrawal, others say you can never do too much.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first things alarmists say will go, as the computer
clocks change from 1999 to 2000, is the power. Therefore, a
generator is at the top of most hyper-Y2Kers' lists. Home Depot is
selling 5,000-watt generators for $499. Salesman Bob Kotell said
they're far from flying off the shelves. He has only sold a few
generators all year, and never has Y2K been mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of doubt this whole thing,'' Kotell said. ``I think
everything will be OK. I know I'm personally not doing anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The Y2Kaphobes are also calling on the masses to withdraw all of
their money. Computer glitches, they warn, will erase bank records
and leave people penniless.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's sort of ridiculous,'' said Bill Stewart, a customer
service representative at a local bank. ``As far as I know, we
totally have it under control.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart said he knew of no one who had taken money out of an
account to prepare for Y2K. He did say a man entered the bank and
asked how to withdraw all of his money. But the man _ who Stewart
said ``looked the part of a guy that's not all there'' _ didn't
want to make a scene and left without making a withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, the Y2K isn't that scary to me,'' Stewart said.
``To prepare, I'll probably take some cash out on December 30 and
order a couple of pizzas.''
</P>
<P>
   The Austin-area Gardenville is seeing some of the Y2K fervor.
The nursery promotes organic, self-sustaining gardening. This sort
of gardening is the type the Y2Kers are preaching to the masses.
The idea is to set up a constant source of food. As a result, there
has been a small run on open-pollinated fruit, grain and vegetable
seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Beal is a nursery manager at Gardenville. She said the
open-pollinated seeds enable fruits and vegetables to reproduce.
Most seeds on the market are sterile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every three or four weeks I'll get a customer that's talking
about Y2K,'' Beal said. ``Usually that person will buy about $200
worth of seed, which is a tremendous amount. ... Because they are
so specific on what breeds they want, I assume they know what
they're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Gardenville has also sold an unusually high number of fruit and
nut trees. Beal said she has run into people who have wanted to
plant entire orchards of peaches, apples, pears, plums and pecans.
</P>
<P>
   But after seeing all of this buying for the Y2K Apocalypse, does
she believe in the impending horror?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, not really,'' Beal said. ``I just know I don't want to
be in a plane or anywhere like that. When the year 2000 comes
around, me and my husband will be on a mountain or in a park.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-02-99 1606EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990102.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 16:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5375 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUS-Y2K-SUITS-COX     01-02 1338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUS-Y2K-SUITS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Litigation could also be a Y2K problem
 &HT;    By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Don Summers, whose small company repairs
emergency generators in more than 200 Austin-area buildings, could
be a popular guy on New Year's Eve 1999: If electric utilities are
affected by the Y2K computer bug and power goes out, all those
generators will kick in, and some may need quick repairs.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past six months, dozens of Summers' customers have
asked him to guarantee that Y2K, or year 2000, problems won't delay
service. But while Summers has upgraded his own computers, he
worries about his suppliers. A lawyer has advised him not to make
any promises: Many of the customers are afraid they'll be sued as a
result of Y2K mishaps _ when computers may erroneously interpret
the two-digit date ``00'' as 1900, not 2000 _ and they want to
include Summers in their ``line of liability.''
</P>
<P>
   Because computers play a part in the delivery of nearly every
product and service, the potential for Y2K lawsuits stretches the
imagination. Some say litigation costs could approach $1 trillion,
and the U.S. Chamber of Commerce has asked Congress to set up an ad
hoc Y2K court to handle all of the cases.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing a deluge of lawsuits that could paralyze the state's
economy, Texas lawmakers have proposed limits to Y2K liability.
Summers, who says he and most other small-business men wouldn't be
able to hire high-priced lawyers to defend themselves, heartily
endorses the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like ripples on a pond _ a gigantic pond with no limit to
the expansion of those ripples,'' Summers said. ``We could be
destroyed, and I don't think that's proper.''
</P>
<P>
   But others warn that far-reaching immunity from Y2K lawsuits
will leave consumers _ and small-business men such as Summers _
unprotected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're certainly concerned about granting the computer and
software industry complete immunity or cutting off the legal right
of small-business owners when we don't know the extent of the
problem,'' said Richard Hile of the Texas Trial Lawyers
Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``These industries have known for years about the Y2K problem,
but have continued to sell computer products with embedded chips as
recently as the last couple of years,'' Hile said. ``Now they're
seeking to shift the burden of any financial losses to the consumer
and take it off the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Y2K legislation
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim Pitts, R-Waxahachie, has filed a bill that would allow
plaintiffs in Y2K lawsuits to recover damages ``resulting from
personal injury or wrongful death, excluding mental anguish.'' The
bill also would enable plaintiffs to recover the cost of
reprogramming or replacing computer systems, but not financial
losses related to computer breakdowns or work stoppages.
</P>
<P>
   State agencies and local governments, which already enjoy
``sovereign immunity'' from most lawsuits, would get more extensive
protection from Y2K lawsuits. Shannon Porterfield of the Department
of Information Resources, which is monitoring the Y2K preparations
of 200 state agencies and universities, said the state has
completed more than half of its Y2K remediation plans.
</P>
<P>
   Pitts aide Reggie McElhannon said the ``spirit'' of the
legislation is to protect people or entities that have made a
``good faith'' effort to correct their Y2K problems. But the
language is imprecise, and McElhannon said the bill is likely to be
altered and folded into more comprehensive Y2K legislation being
drafted by Rep. Brian McCall, R-Plano, and Sens. Robert Duncan,
R-Lubbock, and Troy Fraser, R-Horseshoe Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The broader bill includes incentives for people to fix their Y2K
problems ahead of time and is designed as a ``blueprint'' for
solving Y2K disputes, Duncan said. For example, if a defendant can
prove that pre-2000 testing of a computer system suggested that it
would pass Y2K muster, but then it fails anyway, the defendant
would not be liable.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also would bar lawsuits involving equipment or software
older than 10 years, and would require that claimants give
defendants 90 days to correct a Y2K problem before filing a
lawsuit. The seller of faulty equipment or software would have to
fix it for the cost of delivery and installation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all responsible for Y2K problems,'' Duncan said.
``You've got to take steps no matter where you are in the stream of
commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   The comprehensive bill also would protect governments' sovereign
immunity. Four other states _ Florida, Georgia, Hawaii and Virginia
_ have passed laws limiting government Y2K liability, according to
the National Conference of State Legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be like El Nino _ everything that goes wrong will be
blamed on computer date failure,'' Duncan said. ``The taxpayers of
this state will be much better off if we continue government
immunity, or sovereign immunity, for the state and political
subdivisions.''
</P>
<P>
   At the federal level, a new law seeks to encourage companies to
disclose their potential for Y2K problems by ensuring that such
information won't be used in a lawsuit against them.
</P>
<P>
   Limiting liability
</P>
<P>
   For the past year, Austin attorney Bill Hulsey has been helping
local high-tech companies draft contracts and agreements that won't
expose them to Y2K lawsuits. Hulsey argues that even computer
manufacturers, programmers and software companies _ those who would
appear to be most at fault for Y2K problems _ deserve some
protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those people who knew (about the Y2K problem) probably thought
the software would be replaced before it became an issue,'' said
Hulsey, who works in the Austin office of Gray, Cary, Ware and
Freidenrich, a California-based firm with mostly high-tech clients.
</P>
<P>
   Hulsey also pointed out that many software programs designed for
one purpose have been dropped into other applications, making it
difficult to trace blame.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Texas insurers, who would end up footing the
bill for many Y2K damages, also support some liability limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's got to be some way that we can keep this national
problem from becoming a lawsuit bonanza. These type of things can
get out of hand in a hurry,'' said Rick Gentry of the Texas
Insurance Organization, which represents small to medium-sized
insurers.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers stand to gain the most from Y2K litigation, and their
opposition to liability limits comes as little surprise. At one of
several Y2K panels at the American Bar Association's annual
convention in Toronto this past summer, Atlanta lawyer Evelyn
Ashley proclaimed that ``the bug finally provides lawyers the
opportunity to rule the world.''
</P>
<P>
   But trial lawyers aren't the only ones who are concerned about
granting immunity from Y2K liability. If the Y2K bug erases health
records or causes medical equipment to fail, patients may sue
doctors or hospitals. But the Texas Medical Association, realizing
that doctors are likely to be on both ends of Y2K lawsuits, hasn't
yet taken a position on liability limits. Last month, an Illinois
gynecologist filed a lawsuit seeking class-action status on behalf
of health-care providers who bought Y2K-infected software and
hardware from IBM.
</P>
<P>
   Summers says he has no intention of suing anybody, even if Y2K
problems that are no fault of his own prevent him from doing his
job on New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who would I sue? Would I sue the telephone company for not
having the lines up? Would I sue suppliers for not having enough
stock nearby?'' Summers said. ``I'm not experienced with
litigation. We've never been sued. We've never sued anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Howden of the Texas branch of the National Federation of
Independent Business says his group is still polling its members on
their views on liability limits. Howden said small-business men
generally favor less litigation but ``still need to have an option
to go the courthouse if they absolutely think it's necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-02-99 1606EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990102.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 16:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5376 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUS-Y2K-SUITS-COX     01-02 1338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUS-Y2K-SUITS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Litigation could also be a Y2K problem
 &HT;    By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
