<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5392 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHICAGO-LOOP-REAL-2TA     01-02 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICAGO-LOOP-REAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHICAGO BETS ON THEATER TO REVIVE THE LOOP 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By ROBERT SHAROFF    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ In an effort to revive the downtown Loop commercial
district as an entertainment area and add a substantial new tourist
attraction, Chicago is betting heavily on live theater.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the plan is a theater district along Randolph
Street that includes the newly renovated Oriental Theater as well
as two projects that are currently under way _ restoring the
historic Palace Theater and building a two-theater complex for the
Goodman Theater, the city's oldest and largest nonprofit ensemble.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the city recently finished an elaborate streetscape
improvement project along eight blocks of Randolph Street. It
includes new sidewalks and streetlights &UR;  &LR;  as well as colorful
banners and signs ballyhooing the district.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, the city has put about $60 million into the project,
much in the form of tax-increment financing. ``The idea is to make
the Loop a 24-hour neighborhood, and we think theaters will do
that,'' said Christopher Hill, the city's planning commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   ``When everything is in place, people will be buying upwards of
15,000 tickets a day on Randolph Street,'' said Daniel P. Coffey,
president of Daniel P. Coffey &AMP; Associates, the architecture firm
renovating the Palace Theater. Coffey's firm also did the Oriental
Theater, which reopened this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The theater district is the crest of a sudden wave of new
live-theater development downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Two other theaters  &UR; _ &LR;  the Chicago Theater on State Street and
the Arie Crown Theater at the McCormick Place convention center  &UR; _ &LR; 
were recently renovated. A third project, construction of a home
for the nonprofit Shakespeare Repertory Theater, is under way at
the nearby Navy Pier.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the downtown projects are partnerships that involve both
private developers and the theater companies or managers and
producers that will eventually be the tenants. An example is the
renovation of the Palace, which is part of a hotel and office
building that dates from 1926.
</P>
<P>
   The entire complex was acquired early last year by Pal/Met
Venture, a real estate partnership of the developer Michael Moyer
and the VanKampen family. The hotel _ formerly the Bismarck and now
called the Allegro _ reopened earlier this year. The Palace, a
2,350-seat former vaudeville house that has been closed many years,
will follow this summer, and the office building sometime in 2000.
The total cost of the project is $75 million, including $21.5
million for the theater. Fox Theatricals, the Palace's tenant, is
putting up $4 million, and the whole project received $17.6 million
in tax increment financing from the city.
</P>
<P>
   Fox is a locally based production firm that began in the early
1980s and has been a major player in the Off-Loop theater scene,
the Chicago parallel to Off Broadway. The company has also done
several productions on Broadway, including the current musical
``Jekyll &AMP; Hyde.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox has the theater for 98 years. ``We structured it as two
49-year leases,'' said Michael Leavitt, executive producer of Fox.
``Effectively, it's like owning the building.''
</P>
<P>
   Leavitt said the Palace would be used for Fox productions as
well as for touring Broadway shows. ``We've designed the house so
that it can hold just about any production,'' he said. ``We've
expanded the stage depth to 45 feet and added three &UR;  &LR; loading docks.
It's very presenter friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   The other two projects under way are the Goodman and the
Shakespeare Repertory.
</P>
<P>
   The Goodman, which occupies a half block at Randolph and
Dearborn streets, has been in the works many years. Its cost is $44
million, of which $18.8 million is coming from the city. The rest
is being raised in a fund-raising campaign. Half the site is
vacant; the other half is occupied by two small historic theaters,
the Harris and the Selwyn.
</P>
<P>
   The Selwyn is being renovated into a 400-seat studio theater,
while all but the Beaux-Arts facade of the Harris has been torn
down. The rest of the project consists of a new 800-seat main
auditorium as well as a lobby and administrative space. The complex
will also include about 50,000 square feet of rentable retail space
on three levels.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the site was once occupied by the Garrick Theater, which
was designed by Louis Sullivan in 1892. The theater was razed in
the 1960s over the protests of preservationists and eventually
replaced with a parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   According to Roche Schulfer, managing director of the Goodman,
the theater will own the building and have a 99-year lease on the
land. The architects for the project, which is expected to be
finished in the fall of 2000, are Kuwabara Payne McKenna Blumberg
Architects of Toronto and Decker Legge Kemp Architecture of
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The Shakespeare Repertory project is the final piece of the
redevelopment of Navy Pier, which began several years ago. The
pier, which extends into Lake Michigan, is just northeast of the
Loop and has been turned into an urban amusement park with numerous
shops and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   The pier is controlled by the Metropolitan Pier and Exposition
Authority, which has proposed several plans over the years to bring
live theater to the Pier before signing a deal with the Shakespeare
company in 1997. Shakespeare Repertory, which was founded 12 years
ago but has never had a permanent home, is Chicago's third-largest
nonprofit theater.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The new complex, which will open next fall, will have a 550-seat
main auditorium and a 350-seat studio theater. The cost is $26
million. In exchange for a 90-year lease, Shakespeare Repertory is
putting up $12 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a perfect model of the public and private sectors working
together,'' said Criss Henderson, executive director of Shakespeare
Repertory. ``Metropolitan Pier is building the shell, and we're
doing the interior.''
</P>
<P>
   When the dust finally settles at the turn of the century,
Chicago will have added 10,000 live theater seats downtown to an
existing base of about 15,000 seats.
</P>
<P>
   According to the League of Chicago Theaters, a trade group that
runs several half-price ticket booths downtown, the Chicago area
currently has about 54,000 live theater seats.
</P>
<P>
   Can the city support the new activity? It depends on whom you
talk to. There is little consensus, even among theater
professionals. ``New theaters coming on line do not scare me,''
said Dulcie Gilmore, general manager of the Oriental Theater, which
is also known as the Ford Center for the Performing Arts and is
owned and managed by Livent. ``What scares me is the availability
of product. It's almost totally tied to what gets produced in New
York. If New York dries up, it's a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you talk to performing-arts centers anywhere in the country
that rely on blockbuster Broadway shows, you can hear the panic in
their voices,'' said Douglas Kridler, president of the Columbus
Association of Performing Arts, based in Columbus, Ohio, which
recently took over the Chicago Theater.  &UR; ` &LR; `I don't think &UR;  &LR; Broadway
is going to go into free &UR;  &LR; fall, but there is a drought in
mega &UR; - &LR; musicals. &UR; '' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Kridler added that the Chicago plans to sidestep this problem
with a booking philosophy that stresses  &UR; `` &LR; a wide variety &UR;  &LR; of arts
and entertainment events, &UR; '' &LR;  including theater, dance, music
and &UR; , &LR;  possibly &UR; ,  &LR;  film.
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, see it differently.  &UR; ` &LR; `If you pick up the
weekend entertainment section in New York, how many good or great
plays are being presented at any one time? It's a lot more than
three or four, &UR; '' &LR;  said Robert Wislow, chairman of U.S. Equities
Realty, a real estate firm that worked with the city to devise &UR;  &LR; the
plan for the theater district.  &UR; ` &LR; `Up until now, Chicago has never
had the houses to support this level of activity. Now we do. I
don't really understand what we're worried about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
