<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS, VISITING OTTAWA, TRY TO FORGET THE PAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OTTAWA _ The last time the Devils saw the inside of the Corel
Center, they were trudging off the ice, cloaked in disbelief and
disappointment, seeing the seconds tick down on their season and a
celebration they were not a part of beginning in the stands.
</P>
<P>
   The Ottawa Senators ended the Devils' season last year in the
opening round of the playoffs with a surprising 4 games to 2 upset.
As they returned for Saturday night's game, they tried to remember
that it was a new season, a new year, and to focus on the present
rather than past. With the Senators lingering just above the .500
mark and the Devils occupying the top spot in the Eastern
Conference, they hope to avoid an upset again.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to go in with the attitude that you're going to
win, just like you're walking into Washington, Toronto, or any
building,'' said Devils Coach Robbie Ftorek. ``You're New Jersey
and you're going in there with that attitude. You can't think about
anything else.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing you can do about the past, just learn and go
ahead. If you're thinking about the past, you're already behind the
eight ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss to Ottawa actually helped bring Ftorek to his current
position with the Devils, with Jacques Lemaire's five-year tenure
ending after the disappointing finish to the season. Ftorek was an
assistant to Lemaire, but chooses not to linger on the problems
that the Devils ran into, instead concentrating on the team's
current success. They won the first two games on the three-game
road trip that ended here Saturday night, and entered the game
unbeaten in their last eight road games.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened was that we didn't play well enough to win and
they played better than we did,'' Ftorek said of last season's
playoff series. ``So we've just got to play better. It's not a
question of whether you lose a series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever you play against a team, you've got to be 100 percent
focused on what you have to do. If an individual gets motivated by
reliving a past occurrence, so be it. That's everybody's individual
prerogative. You can't dwell on things like that. If you have
emotion, it's got to be a controlled anger or emotion. You've got
to go out and play and focus.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devils have done that of late, still playing the solid,
defensive style that is their trademark. But they have also been
far more successful on the offensive end of the ice than the team
was under Lemaire.
</P>
<P>
   A big part of that has been the play of Bobby Holik, who had 12
goals and 18 points in December, both figures leading the National
Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ftorek stressed that it is not the Devils' new-found
flash that will change the result of last year's series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jacques Martin always plays a disciplined, position-oriented
counterattack,'' Ftorek said. ``His teams play a solid,
hard-working game. That's Jacques' style. He's always played that
way, although he's modified it and enhanced it. To play Ottawa, you
have to be on your game. Seldom do they give you anything and they
take all that you give them.''
</P>
<P>
   SLAP SHOTS
</P>
<P>
   Randy McKay, still feeling the effects of the flu that sidelined
him for the last three games, did not make the trip. McKay
practiced with the team the last two days, but showed fatigue as a
result of having lost about 10 pounds due to the illness, and
having missed 10 days of skating because of a cut to his elbow and
an infection that preceded the flu. Bob Carpenter, nursing a
bruised toe, also remained in New Jersey, and missed his seventh
consecutive game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
