u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILDHOOD-CANCER-1STL     01-02 1249
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDHOOD-CANCER-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVIVORS OF CHILDHOOD CANCER LEARN THE PRICE OF A MIRACLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
(SUBS to delete clauses in last sentence of 5th graf and first
sentence of 6th graf. No other changes.)  (mk) 
 By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAYTOWN, Texas _ The scrapbook that documents Camelia Cruz's
days as a teen-age cancer patient is yellowing now, its photographs
and newspaper clippings fading with the passage of time. On this
sunny Monday morning, Mrs. Cruz cracked it open, as she does every
now and then, unleashing a flood of memories from what seems like a
former life.
</P>
<P>
   There she is in a wheelchair, bald and frail, her face shielded
by a surgical mask, a white hospital blanket draped over her knees.
There she is, smiling, her head swathed in a blue scarf beneath a
sparkling tiara, on the day she was crowned Miss Periwinkle at a
camp for children with cancer. There's Sandy Cuellar, her best
friend from the hospital; Camelia clutched her hand as she died, at
16. Her newspaper obituary is tucked inside Mrs. Cruz's album,
along with a dried rose petal from the funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Cruz, now 22, is a survivor of osteosarcoma, a highly
malignant bone tumor. The cancer was diagnosed when she was 13. At
an age when most girls are worried about pimples and boyfriends,
Mrs. Cruz, the former Camelia Trevino, lost her left leg; doctors
had no choice but to amputate above the knee. Then she endured a
year of sickening chemotherapy that has left her with damaged
kidneys, and received blood transfusions that are probably
responsible for infecting her with hepatitis C, a potentially
lethal virus.
</P>
<P>
   In the annals of cancer treatment, Mrs. Cruz's story is hardly
extraordinary. Yet that is precisely what makes it worth noting.
She is part of a trend that experts describe as a miracle of modern
medicine: the transformation of childhood cancer from killer to
curable disease. But thankful though they and their families are
that they are alive, the growing legion of survivors are
discovering that the miracle has not been without a price.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1960s, fewer than one-third of cancer patients under
age 15 lived for five years past their date of diagnosis, the point
at which experts consider them cured. Today, survival is not the
exception but the rule. Roughly three-quarters of all children
currently being treated for cancer are expected to reach the
five-year mark. And as oncologists continue to refine their
methods, the population of childhood cancer survivors, which stands
at an estimated 250,000, is rapidly growing.
</P>
<P>
   This turnabout is often cited as evidence that a cure is within
reach. But as the first large wave of childhood cancer survivors
reaches its 20s and 30s, the word ``cured'' is a misnomer for many.
Though some, particularly those treated more recently, glide
through life virtually unscathed, others are finding that the two
staples of cancer treatment, chemotherapy and radiation, can bring
with them health problems: heart, lung and kidney dysfunction,
memory loss, infertility and even second cancers.
</P>
<P>
   And as they leave their parents' homes to grapple with college,
careers and relationships, they face an array of social
difficulties, as well, from awkwardness in dating to difficulty
finding jobs to an obstacle that can seem as insurmountable as
cancer itself: finding health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Fiduccia, a disability rights consultant in California
who works with survivors of childhood cancer, said, ``The single
biggest part of my job is explaining to people why they are not
going to get health insurance or what will happen when they lose
it.'' When it comes to insurance, he said, former cancer patients
``have a lot of very poor choices.'' If they work for a large
employer, they will usually have health coverage. If not, they may
seek coverage from state high-risk insurance pools or Medicaid, the
federal insurance for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Though it is illegal to discriminate on the basis of a person's
health history, companies worried about the cost of insuring their
workers may be wary about hiring someone they know is a survivor of
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kids are able to walk and talk and look like the average
American,'' Fiduccia said, ``but I'm getting more and more calls
about kids who were treated more than 10 years ago for cancer who
are now living at home with their parents and are unemployed. This
is not like falling off your bike and breaking your arm and once
the cast is off, that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last two years, Mrs. Cruz, who wears a prosthesis and
walks with a pronounced limp, has discovered that her kidneys do
not retain enough magnesium, a disorder she corrects by taking
supplements and medication. More worrisome is the hepatitis C. Her
doctors suspect she contracted it during a blood transfusion;
experts say as many as 10 percent of childhood cancer patients who
received transfusions before 1992, when blood banks began screening
for the virus, may be similarly infected.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1997, she married Pablo Cruz, a pipefitter. The wedding
took place in a gazebo at the ``Cancer Survivors Plaza,'' a grassy
park not far from Texas Children's Hospital in Houston, where
Camelia was treated. ``It never bothered me,'' Pablo Cruz said of
his wife's cancer. ``I know what she's been through and I respect
her for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple make their home in a modest frame house, flanked on
one side by railroad tracks and on the other by an oil refinery, in
this working-class industrial city about an hour east of Houston.
Health insurance is a big issue; now that Mrs. Cruz is married, she
no longer qualifies for Medicaid, and at times she has skipped
doctors' appointments because she could not afford them. Her
husband has a policy through his new employer, but the couple are
not sure yet whether Camelia is covered. They have been paying $100
out-of-pocket for her medication each month.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Mrs. Cruz thought she would never conceive a child,
an impression her doctors say was erroneous. Fourteen months ago,
she and her husband had a baby, a girl. The pregnancy was
difficult; Mrs. Cruz was exhausted all the time from the loss of
the magnesium, and her hepatitis C, at the time still undiagnosed,
fouled the results of a blood test that screens for birth defects.
``They told me, `Either you have an abortion, or the baby is going
to be dead when it is born,''' she said. ``I was a wreck.'' The
baby was born healthy, at 6 pounds 2 ounces. They named her
Milagro, the Spanish word for ``miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the chances of a recurrence of her cancer are slim,
Mrs. Cruz still worries. A bigger threat is the hepatitis, which
could eventually destroy her liver. She is now contemplating an
experimental treatment for the disease; so far, both her husband
and her baby have tested negative. There is no cure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody can be sure about what can happen in their future,''
Mrs. Cruz said, casting a glance at her daughter. Over the strains
of ``If You're Happy and You Know It,'' the mother continued:
``What would happen to the baby? How would she grow up?''
</P>
<P>
   It is estimated that about half of all children cured of cancer
experience moderate to severe medical problems years after their
treatment. In the lexicon of cancer survival, these are known as
``late effects.'' Dr. Philip Steuber, the pediatric oncologist who
treated Camelia Cruz, uses another name: ``the cost of cure.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Because so few children survived cancer decades ago, doctors are
only just beginning to comprehend how high those costs can be.
Experts know quite a bit about late effects in the first decade
after treatment, but less about the second decade and very little
after that. The issues are complicated; childhood cancer is really
an array of more than a dozen different diseases, each with its
course of treatment and side effects.
</P>
<P>
   Patients with Hodgkin's disease, for example, sometimes require
radiation to the chest; girls who receive this therapy are at high
risk for breast cancer later in life. Patients with brain tumors
almost invariably need radiation to the head; often, their
intellect is impaired, causing problems at school and at work.
Doxorubicin, a mainstay drug of chemotherapy, can cause heart
damage, while another anti-cancer agent, cis-platinum, can harm the
kidneys.
</P>
<P>
   Much of today's research revolves around devising new treatments
to minimize late effects, so that the children treated today may
have fewer problems than their predecessors. To that end, Dr.
Leslie Robison, a pediatric cancer expert at the University of
Minnesota, is supervising a study of 15,000 childhood cancer
survivors.
</P>
<P>
   The nationwide study, paid for by the National Cancer Institute,
involves 26 institutions and more than 100 researchers who are
tracking patients treated between 1970 and 1986. The participants,
whose median age is 26, have answered questionnaires about a range
of issues, from their physical and psychological health to whether
they engage in risk-taking behaviors, such as smoking cigarettes.
The research is important for all cancer survivors, but especially
for children, who could be expected to live an average of 60 years
after they are cured.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the late 1960s, 1970s and 1980s there was very
aggressive attention and remarkable success in treating childhood
cancer,'' Robison said. ``Now we are putting the focus on looking
at the survivors. We need to know what are the long-term adverse
effects of having had cancer as a child, not just what happens in
the first 10 years after they are treated, but what potentially
could happen 30, 40 and 50 years down the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Cruz is ineligible for Robison's study; she received her
diagnosis three years after the cutoff date. But her battle with
osteosarcoma, a relatively rare form of childhood cancer that
afflicts about three out of every million children ages 14 and
under, provides a window into the world of cancer treatment and
survivorship.
</P>
<P>
   Her first sign of sickness was a pain in her left leg; her
family doctor, she said, dismissed it as ``growing pains,'' until
he took an X-ray. The film showed a tumor the size of a misshapen
orange, a lesion so destructive it was clear the limb could not be
saved. In August 1989, one month after her 13th birthday, Camelia
sat in Steuber's office at Texas Children's Hospital. He had the
delicate task of telling her that, the following week, she was
going to lose her leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing I remember about her to this day is her
courage,'' Steuber said. ``She was upbeat then, even under the
hardest of circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Cruz, for her part, remembers feeling more scared than
courageous. On the morning of the operation, she didn't want to get
out of bed. ``I remember that I wanted to take small steps
everywhere, because these were my last steps that I was going to
take with both my legs.''
</P>
<P>
   Her surgery, and the 13 months of chemotherapy that followed,
were part of a controlled experiment. This is routine for children
with cancer. Because there are so few of them, it has been standard
practice at oncology centers to enroll all youngsters they treat in
clinical trials. Hundreds of such experiments, conducted at
academic institutions under the auspices of two large pediatric
cancer research networks, have taken place since the 1970s, and
their results, rather than the development of any new miracle
drugs, are largely responsible for the improved survival
statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been a few new drugs, but that is a minor thing,''
said Anna Meadows, a leading expert in pediatric oncology who
directs the Office of Cancer Survivorship at the National Cancer
Institute. ``We have learned how to use the drugs in a better
way.''
</P>
<P>
   The osteosarcoma study in which Mrs. Cruz participated, Study
8651 of the Pediatric Oncology Group, was typical. One hundred
children were enrolled; half received chemotherapy before surgery;
half, including Mrs. Cruz, did not. The study found that children
do equally well with either course of treatment; as a result,
Steuber said, oncologists today have greater flexibility in
treating osteosarcoma.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest danger with osteosarcoma is that it will spread to
the lungs. The disease is aggressive, Steuber said, and if it is
going to recur it will usually do so within a year. That Mrs. Cruz
has lived for more than eight years since finishing chemotherapy,
he said, bodes well for her.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Mrs. Cruz is followed closely by a kidney specialist and
a specialist in infectious diseases, who keeps tabs on her
hepatitis. She visits the oncologists at Texas Children's Hospital
only once a year, where her progress is monitored along with that
of other long-term survivors. The visits are largely social.
``We've been through hard times together,'' Steuber said. ``It's
nice to have good times together.''
</P>
<P>
   Were she able to rewrite her personal history, Mrs. Cruz would
not leave out her cancer. ``Until you come close to death like I
did,'' she said, ``you don't realize what it is to take another
breath.'' She is grateful for that, yet her days are tempered by
uncertainty, and by the reality of life with one leg. She cannot
hop in the shower and dash out the door. She cannot play volleyball
or ride a bike. She is too modest to wear a dress, and with her
prosthesis, high heels are out. ``I would like,'' she said, ``to
wear high heels.''
</P>
<P>
   At night, however, her body is made whole. ``In my dreams,'' she
said, ``I still dream that I have both my legs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
