<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5430 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDLIFE-COLLEGE-PREP-A     01-02 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDLIFE-COLLEGE-PREP-ART-2TAKES(930)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING THE GRAND TOUR OF COLLEGE CAMPUSES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Maine, Mass., N.Y., Vt.)  (ART ADV: Photo of Allen Cowett, a senior at Middlebury College,
who spends most of his time on tours walking backward. The photo is
being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036. 
(Charles Strum edits the Public Lives page of The New York Times) 
(rl) 
 By CHARLES STRUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The car is littered with empty plastic bottles of spring water,
granola bar wrappers and CDs by the Dave Matthews Band, Live and
the Grateful Dead. That last band name takes on fresh resonance as
we drive west on Interstate 90 toward Utica, N.Y. It is the fourth
day of a five-day, 1,383-mile car journey, which pushes the
odometer past 100,000 miles.
</P>
<P>
   My companion is a buff young woman, a month shy of 17, who is
sleeping curled up in the shotgun seat, direct from rebuilding
trails in the Idaho wilderness. She is the firstborn, Kate, in
T-shirt and cutoffs. The dashboard is scored with the dusty tread
marks of her running shoes.
</P>
<P>
   We are visiting colleges. Five days, five campuses _ a
mini-marathon beyond brochures, a road trip to the future. We need
a guide. Five of them, in fact. They turn out to be Dave, Kurt,
Kirsten, Anna and Sarah. They are campus tour guides, the first
tenuous link between campus and prospective undergraduate.
</P>
<P>
   We're on a tight schedule but hardly a record setter. Along the
way _ was it Colby? Bowdoin? _ we have encountered Amanda from
Chappaqua, N.Y., who is doing 10 schools. On our last day, a
Thursday, we meet up with her again at Hamilton College, in
Clinton, N.Y., about 12 miles south of Utica. She and Kate, both
lacrosse players, confer.
</P>
<P>
   Each has seen Colby, Bates, Bowdoin and Middlebury on this trip.
Amanda has also stopped at the University of Vermont, Cornell,
Colgate, Skidmore and Union. The girls look bright and stylish, but
their glazed eyes betray them. Too much college _ their normally
acute teen-age sensors are nearing overloaded.
</P>
<P>
   ``She doesn't know where she wants to go, either,'' Kate says
sullenly, standing in the entry hall of Hamilton's admissions
office, which, by the way, is a house that was once occupied by
Elihu Root, Theodore Roosevelt's secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   We are stuffed with facts, exotic and otherwise. But they
quickly lose their distinctive flavor as one verdant college
quadrangle morphs into the next. Rewinding our brain tapes, we
realize we know everything and nothing. For example: Each school
has dormitories and classrooms, swimming pools, hockey rinks and
professors. The dining halls are open from 6 a.m. to 9 p.m., or 7
a.m. to 8 p.m., or 6 a.m. to midnight, or all night. The snack bar
delivers pizza until 2 a.m. Or not. Freshmen live separately from
upperclassmen. Or not. Substance-free dorms are available for those
who don't smoke and don't want to be around those who do.
</P>
<P>
   The big mudholes we walk past are being dug for a new
multimillion-dollar science hall or a field house or a library. The
president is friendly. And each year, the entire junior class
leaves campus for someplace like Europe.
</P>
<P>
   You could get all this from the official video, catalog or view
book. But you can't really get it unless you take the tour.
</P>
<P>
   So we do, walking and shuffling across acres of private,
nonprofit country club. We stroll among vast exhibitions of
architecture and ideas, and we get museum feet _ that mildly achy
feeling in soles and calves that comes from wandering without
knowing where you're headed, or why.
</P>
<P>
   But there is help from our guides. All are well versed in campus
lore, with a knack for sounding both genuine and honest.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday: A travel day, to Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Monday: We meet our first guide of the week at Colby, in
Waterville. He is Dave Famiglietti of Windsor Locks, Conn., a
German major entering his junior year. He has a girlfriend in
Toronto and a sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   Like his counterparts at other schools, Dave is casually
dressed, wears sandals and walks backward for an hour, talking
almost nonstop, breaking for questions, greeting friends with a
wave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I volunteered to give tours because I wanted to make Colby
stand out in people's minds,'' he says. ``I went on so many tours
during my search, and so many were dry, boring.''
</P>
<P>
   He recalls one: ``She kept telling us little dumb facts about
the school: `This building was built in 1874 by three green men
from Mars, who at first didn't like their life here on Earth, but
then grew to like it, so they moved to Minnesota.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Dave, who chooses what to say and the route to take, says he
always tries to be honest about the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Families only remember about 10 percent of what I talk
about,'' he says. ``Of that 10 percent or so, I would guess that 7
percent is something they asked the tour guide about. So I am
always careful to pause for questions, and sometimes really try and
drag questions out of the group.''
</P>
<P>
   The questions tend to be routine, including those about drug and
alcohol use, which Dave fields confidently. Students in the wilds
of small-town Maine can still have fun, he says, but they don't
want to get thrown out of school. So they make their own fun. He
cites the Mr. Colby contest last winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``My favorite part,'' Dave says, ``was the swimwear and
evening-wear competition.''
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoon, we're at Bates College, in Lewiston. Our
guide, Kurt Eilhard, has just finished his freshman year. It
drizzles, but he pushes on valiantly, explaining the electronic
dorm cards, praising the debating team and noting that construction
of the new social-sciences building is ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Kate likes the tour, but my thoughts drift. Waiting for her to
emerge from an hourlong interview in the admissions office, I gaze
across the waiting room. There are people with gray hair and liver
spots, women with flabby arms, men who should be barred from
wearing form-fitting knit polo shirts. And it hits me: I am one of
these people.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday: Bowdoin. Kirsten Partenheimer, another German major,
from Haddonfield, N.J. Long skirt, sandals. We watch her walk
backward, into Druckenmiller Science Hall. Its lobby is open all
night for study, she says, and it's especially good if you're not a
science major: there's nobody to talk to, so your time isn't
wasted.
</P>
<P>
   Kirsten calculates she did more than 125 tours last summer.
(Most guides are paid between $5 and $6 an hour, with tours given
year-round.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone always comments on how well we walk backward,''
Kirsten says. ``And we usually hear the same old jokes, but one of
the guides thought it was cute when a father offered to have
everyone on the tour walk backward so the guide could walk forward.
Actually, the only time I fell on the tour was when I was walking
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday: Middlebury, Vt. Anna Tiven, from Williamstown, Mass.,
a Latin American studies major entering her junior year. Another
big, beautiful campus; the Adirondacks on one side, the White
Mountains on the other.
</P>
<P>
   Backward she walks, into a seminar classroom, past small dorms
that look like ski chalets, into a larger dorm.
</P>
<P>
   By this time, buildings are beginning to resemble tombstones in
a cemetery. We walk among them, looking at the dates on
cornerstones and hearing about who came before us.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday: Final day. Hamilton. Sarah Lamont, political science,
Cobleskill, N.Y. Many in her family attended Hamilton before her.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody knows everybody else, she says. Professors are your
friends. Fraternities no longer have hegemony over the social
whirl.
</P>
<P>
   Recent visitors: Colin Powell, F.W. de Klerk, B.B. King.
</P>
<P>
   We do the library, we pass the theater, we enter a chapel.
</P>
<P>
   And toward the end of the tour, Sarah recalls the day she
watched a visiting performer in the Beinecke student center. He was
billed as a regurgitationist. Apparently, he was able to swallow
bits of this and that and then regurgitate them. Sarah asks for our
help.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ever see him, would you ask him two questions for me?''
she says. ``One, `How did you discover you had this talent?' And
two, `How did you find a market for it?' ''
</P>
<P>
   I am thinking about Sarah's questions on the drive back to New
Jersey later that afternoon, preparing to point out to Kate that a
good liberal arts education, besides still sounding like a lot of
fun, sometimes means deconstructing the meaning of an apparently
meaningless vaudeville act. But Kate, her sneakers off for the
first time in days, is fast asleep.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
