<SLUG> BC-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 
Postcards from the ledge ... 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dennis Franchione stood there on the Sun Bowl turf in El Paso
Thursday afternoon, shivering after the traditional icy Gatorade
shower, his silver hair still somehow neatly combed, his smile
broad, his voice resonant and firm, articulately telling the TV
cameras how proud he was of his Frogs' 28-19 victory over Southern
Cal, and who couldn't help but think:
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere, somebody in a bigtime athletic program _ no
disrespect to TCU intended, but you know the kind I'm talking about
_ is sitting there, watching this, and saying to himself, ``Why
isn't this guy coaching for us?''
</P>
<P>
   I predict one more year, and then some school's Tom Hicks is
going to swoop in with an offer Coach Fran can't refuse and TCU
can't match and he'll be gone.
</P>
<P>
   It's frustrating, it's sad, but it should be expected.
</P>
<P>
   But does it have to be that way?
</P>
<P>
   Obviously Franchione has a great thing going at TCU. Any chance
he'll like it in Fort Worth so much, enjoy the challenge of turning
a small, private university with a pretty neat history into a
perennial power in the Southwest, that he might just decide he's
making enough money to be comfortable and stay?
</P>
<P>
   And then there was the one that begins, ``Once upon a time....''
</P>
<P>
   Which reminds me, the next time you hear some professional
athlete or coach say he ``reluctantly'' has to opt for the big
bucks ``because I have to think about my family,'' wouldn't it be
nice if his family spoke up and said, ``Hey, we've got enough,
we're happy here.''...
</P>
<P>
   Pat Sullivan kept telling us all last season that the Frogs
should have been better than 1-10, that the talent was better than
that. Turns out he was absolutely right. They just needed someone
who could show them how to win. Exit Sullivan, enter Franchione....
</P>
<P>
   For those who complain that Cowboys quarterback Troy Aikman is
too conservative, isn't creative enough and doesn't scramble,
please note the flipside of the coin: The Cowboys led the NFL with
only 15 turnovers and had the fewest sacks, numbers directly
related to Aikman's unwillingness to gamble and risk huge losses or
interceptions....
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Wiley Curtis, president of the Frogs' basketball booster
club, was playing golf this summer with Billy Tubbs, head coach of
the men's team, and Mike Petersen, who coaches the TCU Lady Frogs.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, there were a few side bets riding on the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``These matches always start out for fun but those two guys
being extremely competitive start to really battle it out,'' Curtis
says.
</P>
<P>
   On the back nine the threesome comes up to Billy's ball laying
directly on the cart path. Tubbs asks for a drop but as Coach Pete
starts to his drive in the center of the fairway he reiterates that
the rules for the day were to play everything as its lies, no
relief.
</P>
<P>
   Let Dr. Curtis pick up the story:
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Pete chuckles from the middle of the fairway as Coach
Tubbs takes a practice swing and sparks fly as the clubhead goes
across the pavement. Tubbs then takes a vicious swing (sparks fly
again) and knocks his shot four feet from the hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``Petersen, in amazement, shouts, `Great Shot! What did you
hit?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Tubbs looks up and snaps, `Your 5-iron.'''...
</P>
<P>
   The winter's free agency lunacy has Rangers' president Tom
Schieffer shaking his head, even as his team jumps in with both
feet. He sees the rich continuing to get richer and the poor
looking for bankruptcy lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really the Big 10 and the Little 20, and that's not good
for baseball,'' Schieffer says. ``Fortunately for our fans locally,
we're one of the big 10, so I think we'll be able to continue to
have a competitive team, but it's better if every city can have at
least the hope of winning. That's the essence of baseball, the
anticipation of spring and a new beginning, but for the majority of
teams, that's becoming increasingly difficult to do.''...
</P>
<P>
   Why, you ask, isn't revenue sharing working in baseball? Because
owners of the teams on the south side of the tracks are cutting
their payrolls, giving them no chance to win, then pocketing the
revenue sharing checks from the richer teams in order to break even
or even make a little money. It's the teams with the $30-$40
million payrolls that are getting clobbered....
</P>
<P>
   Toronto Star columnist Richard Griffin went on record last week
urging that Blue Jays' general manager Gord Ash pull the trigger on
a deal that would send Roger Clemens to the Rangers for pitcher
Rick Helling, centerfielder Tom Goodwin and a prospect. It could
happen....
</P>
<P>
   There were a lot of reasons why Dave Wannstedt was fired as head
coach of the Chicago Bears, but the fact that he'd lost 10 straight
to the Packers hurt as much as anything....
</P>
<P>
   You think there were some big New Year's Eve parties Thursday
night? Wait'll you see the celebration in Alvin on Tuesday after
it's announced that favorite son Nolan Ryan has been elected to the
Baseball Hall of Fame in his first year on the ballot. We should be
able to hear the hootin' and hollerin' from here....
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Ryan is a foregone conclusion. So, I figure, are George
Brett and Robin Yount. Carlton Fisk will eventually get there, but
maybe not this year. Others who got my vote: Gary Carter, Tony
Perez....
</P>
<P>
   Ryan can't help but look at the contracts Randy Johnson and
Kevin Brown have just been awarded and wonder what ``The Express''
at 30 would be worth on today's free agent market. ``It would be
pretty nice,'' he says, ``to be in your prime right now.'' Nice and
very, very lucrative....
</P>
<P>
   Best holiday party of the year? Probably the very small
gathering in Darrell Royal's hotel suite Wednesday night, when
Larry Gatlin put on a mini-jam session in Royal's honor....Next to
the Longhorns' season, Royal may be most proud of the golf round
this past year when he shot his age 41-33-74, despite being plagued
by arthritis in one hand.
</P>
<P>
   RIMSHOTS
</P>
<P>
   That ``Here Leezard, Leezard,'' headline in the LA papers back
when it was announced that USC would play _ yawn _ ``lowly'' TCU in
the Sun Bowl was kind of cute at the time, but overlooked the moral
to the story. The chihuahua in the taco commercial didn't realize
he was setting a trap for Godzilla. It goes back to being careful
what you ask for _ you might just get it. Think maybe the Trojans
get the real punchline now?...
</P>
<P>
   A New York newspaper reported that the George Foreman-Larry
Holmes' battle for Senior Citizen supremacy has been called off.
Holmes' managers say it's still on, which prompts the question: Has
anybody checked these guys for Alzheimer's? You think I'm kidding?
</P>
<P>
   Most ambiguous sign of the year was on the Cotton Bowl
scoreboard before Friday morning's game: ``The Cotton Bowl strongly
discourages smoking.'' So what, if someone lights up, ushers will
respond with a barrage of harsh language?
</P>
<P>
   Texas players entering the stadium through a thick haze produced
by a smoke machine run amok didn't look particularly mysterious or
intimidating, more like a group of school kids being subjected to a
mass de-licing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
