<HEADER>
A5435 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDLIFE-TESTS-NYT     01-02 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDLIFE-TESTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COPING WITH RENEWED EMPHASIS ON TESTING: EXPERTS' ADVICE
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
By JACQUES STEINBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Among the epidemics spreading from one school district to the
next in recent years has been the compulsion to test.
</P>
<P>
   By the time they were ready to graduate to sixth grade last
June, New York City fifth graders had taken eight standardized
tests over the previous 14 months; this year's fourth-grade reading
test, to be given statewide next week, will take three days to
administer. In Chicago, pupils took 12 standardized tests from the
winter of third grade through the spring of fourth grade.
</P>
<P>
   And President Clinton's proposed national tests in fourth-grade
reading and eighth-grade math, while tabled by Congress for further
study, still loom.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to pick apart this trend for anxious parents and
children, two professors at Teachers College at Columbia University
_ Dr. Peter W. Cookson Jr. and Dr. Joshua Halberstam _ have written
``A Parent's Guide to Standardized Tests in School: How to Improve
Your Child's Chances for Success'' (Learning Express).
</P>
<P>
   The new book presents test-taking strategies and sample
questions for widely used tests like the Iowa Test of Basic Skills,
the Stanford Achievement Test and the Terra Nova (though not the
SAT).
</P>
<P>
   After school one recent afternoon, the authors spoke of the
testing craze and its impact.
</P>
<P>
   _ Why are students being subjected to so much testing?
</P>
<P>
   Cookson: It has a lot to do with the accountability movement.
The idea of holding schools accountable for kids' achievement has
almost become accepted wisdom in American education. There is a
sense that if we can measure kids' achievement we can have a pretty
good idea of whether they are learning or not. That's an open
question.
</P>
<P>
   I think the testing industry can be lucrative for some people,
so they push a lot of these tests. And, lastly, I would say it's
grown because it gives the public some measure _ rightly or
wrongly, and that's a good question _ of how to think about
schools.
</P>
<P>
   _ Was there not this demand for accountability several decades
ago?
</P>
<P>
   Cookson: No, I don't think the schools were held accountable in
the same way. I am not sure schools were worse, either. We didn't
think about education that way. But with the changes in the economy
_ the idea that we're a knowledge economy _ the pressure to measure
this knowledge has increased.
</P>
<P>
   Halberstam: Parents may have had a better sense a generation ago
of how their kids were doing. They were home more. You had at least
one parent in the house. There is a general sense out there that
parents don't have much control over their kids' lives. It's really
important to them to know that the education of their kids is up to
par.
</P>
<P>
   _ How important are these tests in terms of shaping children's
futures and academic careers?
</P>
<P>
   Cookson: If schools use these tests basically for diagnostic
purposes, they might actually be able to identify learning problems
that individual kids have, and that would be good, especially over
a period of time.
</P>
<P>
   The other positive side would be that it does give a school a
sense of where they are at, with grade inflation and all the
subjective factors going into education. Testing does tell you
something about the nature of the academic climate at a particular
school.
</P>
<P>
   What may not be great about this is that you cannot funnel an
education through a number. We need to become much more
sophisticated about these results so they don't become sports
scores. Also, it's a pretty battering experience for a kid who
might be having difficulty with a subject _ or who might be
creative, or who might think differently _ to constantly get back
the message that you are not good enough. Most of these tests are
not going to make you think in ways that, as adults, you might
think of as important.
</P>
<P>
   _ Since these tests are not optional for most students, what can
parents do, what can kids do, to reduce the stress?
</P>
<P>
   Halberstam: You don't want the kid, and you don't want the
parent, to think this is trivial. It's not. On the other hand, it's
just a test. You don't want this child's whole self-image to be
pinned on it. More important, parents look at these scores and
decide whether their kids are smart or not. Some kids are not good
test-takers. But some just don't know the techniques. That can be
learned.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, figure out your child's learning style. This will
be different for different ages. Some kids are better learners by
listening, some kids are better by reading. Sometimes, they can
mouth the words if they are listeners.
</P>
<P>
   For kids who have never taken these tests, for young kids, they
have to learn that this test will be like nothing they have ever
taken before.
</P>
<P>
   Their teacher, who they love and is so kind and sweet, is going
to say, Pencils down! and mean it. They are not going to be able to
raise their hands and say, Just another minute, I need time to
finish. You have to explain to them what a standardized test is.
One of the things that's very important is to do some sample tests
with them in testing conditions.
</P>
<P>
   What's most critical, though, is that you can't prepare for one
single test. The real story is to get parents to learn how to make
education part of their lives. It is clear that parental
involvement in a child's education makes a significant difference.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if you are cooking with your child, do the math: we
have three more guests, we have to triple the amount of salt. Your
kid's driving with you, well, why don't you let him be the
navigator, draw a map of where you are going.
</P>
<P>
   One other thing we suggest here is to pull the plug on the TV.
The one piece of data that is clear is that watching too much
television is a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   _ What steps should parents of disabled children take in
advance?
</P>
<P>
   Cookson: The parents of kids who are handicapped have a lot of
rights here, and they ought to learn those rights. These kids have
rights to take these tests timed, untimed, and under special
circumstances. Secondly, the school and the parent probably have to
make a special effort, assuming it's not just physical, but that
there are emotional and mental issues as well, to create test
conditions that the kids can succeed in. Interpretations of these
tests have to be very sensitively and delicately handled.
</P>
<P>
   _ When you look at the layering of tests on top of one another _
particularly for third, fourth and fifth graders _ should we be
wary? Do we need to test so much?
</P>
<P>
   Halberstam: Psychologically, people like to be tested. Look at
magazines. Every women's magazine has, Here's a test to find out if
you are a good lover. We're a whole culture based on these quick
answers. And so we think this is right for kids. We don't see the
damage. We're probably hurting a lot of kids along the way.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, we do need some accountability, so we are in
this mess.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-02-99 1813EST &QL; 
