u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDLIFE-MOM-ART-3TAKES     01-02 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDLIFE-MOM-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BABY SITTER WHO LEFT HER MARK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(Patricia James Jordan, Ph.D., was New York State Teacher of the
Year in 1993 and received the Disney American Teacher Award for
mathematics that year. She teaches at Roslyn High School on Long
Island, N.Y.) 
(lb) 
 By PATRICIA JAMES JORDAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For almost all her adult life, my mother, Juanita
James, was the neighborhood baby sitter. Every morning, working
women brought their infants to our apartment in the Melrose Housing
Projects in the South Bronx; children from outside the neighborhood
stayed overnight. On any given day, there might have been four
youngsters playing in the apartment.
</P>
<P>
   My mother charged far less than the minimum wage, and she spent
a large part of her meager salary buying educational toys and
materials, doing laundry and sewing outfits for the children.
</P>
<P>
   On the morning of June 13, 1985, at the age of 57, Juanita James
died of complications of diabetes. I had found her, seemingly
asleep, lying in bed. It was a sudden loss that remains painful to
me even now, and it touched the old neighborhood as well.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the young men and women who tearfully walked past my
Miss Nita's coffin had been toilet-trained by her. Some recalled
sitting at her kitchen table doing their homework, jumping
double-dutch with her or playing on the white sheet she transformed
into a hopscotch pattern.
</P>
<P>
   And though she died more than 13 years ago, she is still having
an influence on the youth of the South Bronx through the college
scholarship I established in her honor, which since 1989 has
awarded a total of $15,000 to high school seniors living in public
housing in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the fund came the day my mother was buried.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, people in neighborhoods like mine have needed
assistance paying for funerals or simply surviving after losing a
loved one. For as long as I could remember, members of the
close-knit community in our housing project had taken up a
collection when someone died, regardless of the survivors'
financial status.
</P>
<P>
   My mother's death did not impose any hardships on me or on my
sister, yet people still enclosed money in sympathy cards.
Residents of our building, No. 321, sent a group contribution of
$245; $460 came from colleagues at the New York City Board of
Education's Office of Facilities and Planning, where my mother held
a clerical job during the last years of her life.
</P>
<P>
   While writing thank-you notes, I imagined what Miss Dot must
have sacrificed to send us $5, and wondered what might be the most
meaningful thing to do with all the money _ almost $1,000 in bills
neatly folded into cards _ from all the Miss Dots my mother had
played bingo with or gossiped with on the bench in front of 321.
</P>
<P>
   My mother had not completed high school, but she had stressed
the importance of education. She could not help me do my homework,
but she always made sure I did it, and she proudly earned her
high-school equivalency diploma one year after I earned my
bachelor's from Vassar College. She was the best teacher I ever
had.
</P>
<P>
   Administering the Juanita James Memorial Scholarship Fund has
been a rewarding, sentimental, therapeutic and demanding second job
for which I had absolutely no training.
</P>
<P>
   THIS IS DEDICATED ...
</P>
<P>
   With $1,000 from the sympathy cards and my mother's $693 tax
refund, I opened an account in the commercial institution where I
did my personal banking. In no time, service charges began to
significantly decrease my sparse funds. Although I quickly
discovered savings banks where I would not have to pay monthly
fees, the scholarship fund would need far more than $1,693 before I
could even begin to think about seeking applicants. I didn't have a
clue about how to raise money, but I was motivated and determined.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the fall of 1986, I saw an advertisement for an
``oldies but goodies'' concert featuring the Chantels, the Penguins
and the Earls and had a brainstorm.
</P>
<P>
   I bought a discounted block of tickets at the group sales office
of the Westbury Music Fair. Using the mailing list from the
post-funeral thank-you cards, I stuffed about 300 envelopes with my
own fliers promoting the first Juanita James Memorial Scholarship
Fund benefit. I sold each ticket for $20 _ $4.50 above cost _ and
spent less than $200 on refreshments for a preconcert cocktail
party at my apartment.
</P>
<P>
   I wrapped all the unused gifts and other newish items that had
accumulated in my mother's apartment in colorful holiday paper for
a grab bag. She had so enjoyed saving things and reminiscing about
the people who had given them to her. We sang oldies _ ``In the
Still of the Night'' and ``This Is Dedicated to the One I Love'' _
and it was as if my mother had given us the gifts. I raised only
$500, but I got to spend time with my mother's friends.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, on my mother's 60th birthday, I tried it again.
This time I sold tickets for $35, $15 above cost, to a Johnny
Mathis concert. I raised only $265. But in between concerts, I
solicited funds through the mail.
</P>
<P>
   Since I worked full time as a math teacher at Roslyn High School
on Long Island and was studying for my doctorate in clinical
psychology at Hofstra University, also on Long Island, I could
spend only evenings and weekends doing the enormous clerical work
involved: sending out appeals, picking up mail from a post office
box, recording responses, making bank deposits, acknowledging
donations.
</P>
<P>
   But $5 here and there from my mother's buddies, $500 from people
who never knew my mother and numerous other acts of generosity
began to make the fund a reality.
</P>
<P>
   Enclosed with a $500 contribution was a note from one of my
Vassar classmates: ``Because of my own struggles with a teen-age
son who has everything but is rapidly throwing it all away, I feel
strongly the urge to help out a teen-ager somewhere who is willing
to work hard to make a better life for himself and his community.''
</P>
<P>
   Slowly I graduated from typewritten appeals to professional
color-coordinated brochures and envelopes. A Roslyn parent and
lawyer volunteered his help with the lengthy process of
incorporation so donations could be tax-deductible, and another
parent, an accountant, helped with filing regular reports with
federal and local tax agencies.
</P>
<P>
   A new friend, Jack Jordan, patiently and politely suggested that
I consider investing in mutual funds. I did some research, talked
with a consultant and invested, and the funds have flourished
beyond belief. (Today, we have $16,000.) I made another wise
decision: I married Jack.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   PRIDE IN THE PROJECTS
</P>
<P>
   With $4,228.29 in the bank in March 1989, I sent the first
letters recruiting applicants to every housing-project manager in
the Bronx and to Manhattan and Bronx high schools. There were 25 to
30 responses.
</P>
<P>
   Every year since then, the fund's board _ my sister, my husband,
a friend and myself _ has selected one student from a South Bronx
housing project to receive an award: $500 a year for at least four
years of college study. The amount may seem insignificant
considering college costs, but it has helped pay for travel
expenses, phone bills, books, clothing and even toothpaste.
</P>
<P>
   Selecting finalists among the strong candidates is always
difficult. I have often sat alone at my kitchen table, struggling
with up to 50 applications. From the initial group of applicants,
the board invites five to eight finalists to a group interview with
its members and former and present scholarship recipients, who also
use the time to lend advice about college and careers.
</P>
<P>
   We consider grades and class rank. (Any student taking
advanced-placement calculus has my vote automatically.) Applicants
must also write a one- to three-page essay addressing their
backgrounds, strengths and weaknesses, and how the money will help.
(One young woman who recycled a lovely essay on world peace was
flatly rejected.)
</P>
<P>
   But we look at what each person has to work with as well: A
20-year-old senior made the finals because of her determination to
graduate from high school. Unfortunately, she didn't show up for
the interview.
</P>
<P>
   If only the media were as focused on South Bronx scholars as on
South Bronx crime. Pessimists' despair would disappear if they
could visit our dynamic group interviews. Year after year, prompt,
well-groomed, articulate finalists discuss life in the projects,
peer pressure, role models and aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   Some of our scholars practically reared themselves. Some are
from families who receive public assistance; others have two
working parents. Some are the first in their families to complete
high school; others have siblings with college degrees. Juanita
James scholars do not fit any stereotype. Their one common
characteristic is residency in a housing project.
</P>
<P>
   Our first winner was Wilfredo Roman, a senior at A. Philip
Randolph High School in 1989. Wilfredo completed his bachelor's
degree in electrical engineering at the State University of New
York at Binghamton and then earned a graduate degree in physics
there. After teaching at Binghamton for several years, he came home
and got a job as an engineer with Computerized Elevator Control.
Wilfredo continues to be a volunteer and mentor for the fund.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Gimore, our 1992 recipient and a graduate of Alfred E.
Smith High School, said he couldn't believe it when he saw our
flier posted at his school. ``I had to look twice,'' he said. ``A
scholarship for people who live in the projects? That one is for
me!'' Frank went to the State University of New York at Purchase
until family problems interrupted his plans; eventually he returned
to school at Monroe College to study business.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, we selected Pamela Ware, the first recipient from our
own Melrose Projects. But Pamela did not go to college that year.
In fact, she did not receive her first $500 check until the spring
semester of 1998, when she finally responded to my continual
inquiries.
</P>
<P>
   ``After graduating from Kennedy High School in 1994, I intended
to attend Lincoln University,'' she wrote, ``but I was not
emotionally or financially prepared. I was forced to leave home and
secure my own housing in July 1996.''
</P>
<P>
   She finally enrolled at Hunter College for the spring and summer
semesters of 1997, earning a 4.0 and 3.5 average, respectively, but
she had to take time off when her mother died. ``These periods of
ups and downs have given me strength to know that I am capable of
achieving whatever goals I set for myself,'' she wrote. ``I am
destined to overcome all obstacles that come my way.''
</P>
<P>
   In the mentoring tradition of our scholarship fund, my sister
responded immediately when Pamela mentioned she needed a job. She
now works in the law firm where my sister is a legal secretary and
maintains a near-perfect average at Hunter.
</P>
<P>
   Kanika Brooks, the 1998 recipient, graduated from A. Philip
Randolph High School and enrolled in the engineering department of
Columbia University this fall. She grew up in the J.P. Mitchell
Housing Projects, though she spent most of her time at her
grandmother's apartment at the Melrose projects while her mother, a
single parent, worked a 12-hour day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although the road has been hard, support from my mother has
been the guiding light in my life,'' she wrote in her application.
``My mother never finished college, but she always struggled to
make sure that I received what I needed. She gave me
encouragement.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   REMEMBERING MY MOTHER
</P>
<P>
   ``Patty, get upstairs!'' That admonition from the 11th-floor
window of the Melrose Housing Projects was as familiar to the
community as the sound of church bells on Sunday morning. One would
have thought that my mother sat by the window all day, because she
always seemed to be there to see me doing something that she
prohibited. And just what were those delinquent acts?
</P>
<P>
   My sister and I were not allowed to swing Hula-Hoops around our
hips _ too suggestive. One afternoon, after checking that my mother
wasn't watching, I hurriedly borrowed a hoop and started swinging.
Within an instant we heard the familiar screaming.
</P>
<P>
   Barely 5 feet tall, my mother was a strong, intimidating and
demanding parent. She had to place her stamp of approval on all our
friends (no talking to anyone on her ``undesirable'' list), and she
had rigid geographical guidelines dictating where we could play
(within eyesight and earshot of her window). If I risked walking
around the corner with a friend, she was waiting at the window when
I returned. She actually persuaded me she would be able to look in
my eyes and tell if I had ``done anything with a boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years later, my high school friends still laugh about the
time we were coming home from a party and a boy on my mother's
``undesirable'' list happened to be simultaneously entering our
building.
</P>
<P>
   Helplessly, I shook my head. ``When I count to three, my
mother's going to scream,'' I sighed. And there she was, right on
cue.
</P>
<P>
   Her list was sometimes accurate (that boy died of drug abuse
before he reached 30) and sometimes unfair. (She banned a nice boy
simply because he had processed hair.)
</P>
<P>
   My mother was always the one we turned to, although my father,
who died in 1997, lived with us until I was 15. He was a police
lieutenant, and I considered myself fortunate to have a father who
had a good job and paid the bills. I have fond memories of going to
church by his side. But I hated seeing my mother unhappy on nights
he didn't come home, or when he came home drunk. I hated seeing her
verbally abused, and I'll never forget the times I saw her cry.
Alcoholism would eventually destroy his life.
</P>
<P>
   Juanita James strove desperately to keep us out of trouble, and
her efforts worked. She was just as strict and overprotective with
her baby-sitting charges, but she wove her maternal magic: It was
not unusual to hear children crying when their parents arrived to
take them home.
</P>
<P>
   As time passed, my relationship with my mother evolved into a
wonderful friendship. During my college years, she was still
weaving her maternal magic: It was not unusual to hear children
crying when their parents arrived to take them home.
</P>
<P>
   As time passed, our relationship evolved into a wonderful
friendship.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
