<HEADER>
A5448 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-PENN-STATION-REAL-     01-02 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PENN-STATION-REAL-750&AMP;ADD(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: CLEARING THE TRACKS FOR PENN STATION III 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVID W. DUNLAP   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After six years of pushing and pulling, negotiators
believe they have arrived at a workable division of the General
Post Office in Manhattan, allowing it to remain a hub of mail
service even as it is transformed into a new version of the lost
Pennsylvania Station.
</P>
<P>
   The Postal Service and Pennsylvania Station Redevelopment Corp.
are now talking about how to share the building rather than how to
partition it. The distinction is more than semantic.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of searching for a sharp line demarcating post office
from train station, the designers have found ways in which
passenger movement and mail handling can overlap in the massive
neo-Classical structure, known formally as the James A. Farley
Building.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've mixed and marbleized the cake,'' said Robert A. Peck,
the federal commissioner of public buildings, after a meeting Dec.
21 at which agreement was reached on the general layout of the
building.
</P>
<P>
   With the agreement in hand, the architects and engineers can now
begin a detailed redesign of the space within the 1.4
million-square-foot Farley Building. In broad outline, it will have
these features:
</P>
<P>
   The main entrances for Amtrak passengers will be on 31st and
33rd streets, between Eighth and Ninth Avenues. Driveways on both
streets will lead to a 300-foot ticketing hall _ as long as the
main waiting room of the original Pennsylvania Station.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers arriving on foot will be able to use entrances under
the niches on either side of the grand Eighth Avenue staircase. The
window-service postal lobby at the top of those stairs will remain.
(See you there April 15, 2003.)
</P>
<P>
   Passengers arriving on the Eighth Avenue subway will be able to
enter the Farley Building on an extension of the Long Island Rail
Road's West End Concourse. Those arriving on the Seventh Avenue
line would come through the existing Penn Station, which will
remain in use by New Jersey Transit and the LIRR.
</P>
<P>
   From the ticketing hall, passengers will proceed into a
160-by-205-foot atrium on the Eighth Avenue side of the building,
at the base of which will be a terraced series of three concourses
cascading down to the train platforms, some of which will be
visible through skylights. The platforms, which already extend
westward from the existing station, will be reached by stairway,
escalator or elevator.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll actually be able to see the trains as you're waiting,''
said David M. Childs of Skidmore, Owings &AMP; Merrill, part of the
team redesigning the space in the building.
</P>
<P>
   No one involved in the project presumes to say that this
concourse will make New Yorkers forget the glory of McKim, Mead &AMP;
White's original, which was torn down in the early 1960s. But they
are quick to note that it will share the quality of bringing
daylight and visibility down to track level.
</P>
<P>
   More than esthetics are served by this gesture. It will make it
easy for travelers _ particularly those arriving at the station for
the first time _ to orient themselves, unlike the current maze,
which is closer to a hamster run than a great train shed.
</P>
<P>
   Taking its cue from airports, Amtrak will build pre-boarding
lounges on the intermediate concourse level for intercity trains.
Commuters will use the lower concourse.
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania Station would also become an important destination
for air travelers early in the next century, on completion of rail
lines planned to link Newark International Airport to Amtrak and
New Jersey Transit trains and Kennedy International Airport to the
LIRR.
</P>
<P>
   Just how much the Farley Building project will cost has yet to
be determined, since the detailed design work is only now
beginning. Earlier estimates put the price tag at $315 million.
Officials hope to open the new station in December 2002.
</P>
<P>
   To accommodate the ticketing hall, the Postal Service will move
many of its truck docks into a new space below grade on the Ninth
Avenue end of the building, reached by ramps paralleling 31st and
33rd streets. To free up the interior courtyard for use as a
concourse, the Postal Service will move the letter-carrier sorting
stations into workrooms on the Ninth Avenue side.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's key is a phasing plan that will allow postal operations
to continue,'' said Rudy Umscheid, vice president of facilities at
the Postal Service. ``We don't want to compromise mail service
during construction. And we don't want to compromise the potential
for mail service in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Having said that, he added, ``Everyone wants this project to be
successful.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   For their part, state officials have temporarily set aside the
idea of building 200,000 square feet of retail space as part of the
station, which was proposed to help finance the project. ``The
short-term compromise will help us achieve a greater development in
the future,'' said Charles A. Gargano, chairman of the
redevelopment agency and its corporate parent, Empire State
Development Corp. Among other things, that compromise helped pave
the way for the Dec. 21 accord.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means we are definitely going to move forward,'' Gargano
said.
</P>
<P>
   Six years have already passed since a plan was first announced
to improve Amtrak's passenger areas by building a new concourse in
the General Post Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``It occurred to me that there was a monumental building that
kind of looked like a station right above the platforms,'' recalled
Fred Bartoli, the manager of high-speed rail and facility programs
in Amtrak's Metropolitan Division.
</P>
<P>
   What made the idea so appealing was that it offered a kind of
redemption for the demolition of the original station. ``You don't
get a second chance like this often,'' said Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan.
</P>
<P>
   Designed by McKim, Mead &AMP; White, the Farley Building opened in
1914 as a companion piece to the station. A Ninth Avenue annex was
added in 1935. Above a portico of tree-sized Corinthian columns is
inscribed the famous ``Neither snow nor rain'' motto. The Farley
Building was one of the earliest designated landmarks, protected by
a law that had been prompted in part by the demolition of the
station across the street.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, the inscription was a bit of a warning sign.
Postal officials are quite attached to the Farley Building; not
only because it has vast work floors and dozens of truck bays but
because it is a national cynosure, the grandest of the grand old
post offices. Some families have worked in the building for two or
three generations.
</P>
<P>
   Because it was moving some operations out of Farley to the
Morgan General Mail Facility annex at Ninth Avenue and 29th Street,
the Postal Service had subscribed nominally to the station
expansion plan from the outset. But the path from generalities to
specifics turned out to be tortuous.
</P>
<P>
   Postal officials were offended by what they regarded as cavalier
incursions into their space by people who had no idea how a post
office operated. And they resented implications that the General
Post Office was inefficient or unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably wasn't being utilized to its fullest efficiency,''
Umscheid said, ``but the fact is that there has been a growth in
mail volume and services over time.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, economic development officials and civic leaders were
growing impatient with what they saw as bureaucratic intransigence
impeding the conversion of an antiquated structure into an urban
dynamo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Postal Service bureaucrats go, well, they go postal when the
plan is mentioned,'' said a 1997 editorial in The Daily News, whose
offices are near the Farley Building.
</P>
<P>
   By late 1997, horns were locked. The Postal Service insisted it
could not give up more than one quarter of the Farley Building
(350,000 square feet) and the redevelopment agency insisted it
would need half.
</P>
<P>
   The Municipal Art Society went so far as to propose emptying
Farley of all postal operations except the service windows on
Eighth Avenue and turning it into a station, civic center, postal
museum and mall.
</P>
<P>
   The White House dispatched Peck, of the Federal Public Buildings
Service, to broker a compromise. ``Shuttle diplomacy wasn't
working,'' he said. ``It was more like long-range shelling.''
</P>
<P>
   In August, Pennsylvania Station Redevelopment Corp. designated
an architectural and engineering team headed by Skidmore, Owings &AMP;
Merrill and Parsons Brinckerhoff, with Castro-Blanco Piscioneri &AMP;
Associates, Hardy Holzman Pfeiffer Associates and Ove Arup &AMP;
Partners.
</P>
<P>
   A joint management committee was also formed that month,
bringing postal officials and state officials to the same table.
``There is a different tone now,'' Peck said. ``They're fully
committed.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides credit the architects with helping them find the
common ground necessary to apportion the building. ``S.O.M. has
been key in putting on their wisdom-of-Solomon hats,'' Umscheid
said.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Jordan Taylor, a partner in the Skidmore firm, likened
the process to solving a three-dimensional jigsaw puzzle, made
easier to solve because ``a lot of people in the post office rolled
up their sleeves and were ready to take a fresh look.''
</P>
<P>
   One big piece of the puzzle was the truck docks on the ground
floor, which an earlier redevelopment plan had proposed to
eliminate in favor of a pedestrian arcade. ``Without the docks, the
building has no functional value,'' said David Eales, the manager
of realty assets for the Postal Service.
</P>
<P>
   John D.T. Gerber, senior vice president of the redevelopment
corporation, said there was a ``great deal of competition'' for the
ground-floor space.
</P>
<P>
   The solution involves the construction of new loading docks
below grade, while keeping some supplemental docks on the ground
floor level for extra-long tractor-trailer trucks that could not
make a sharp turn on the ramps. Reducing the area of the
ground-floor docks will permit construction of a grand ticketing
hall.
</P>
<P>
   For the time being, at least, the Postal Service will not be
ceding more than 350,000 square feet, although it acknowledges that
it may be possible to move other operations out of the Farley
Building over time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our plans describe a project of independent utility that we
can begin very shortly,'' said Alexandros E. Washburn, president of
the redevelopment corporation. ``That doesn't preclude us from
weighing options for the eventual reuse of the entire Farley
Building.
</P>
<P>
   ``Postal operations seem to me more and more a form of
transportation,'' he said. ``And what we are basically trying to do
is improve transportation for New York City.''
</P>
<P>
   An advocacy group called the Committee for Better Transit fears
that the Farley concourses may create as many problems as they
solve. Among their concerns is that moving Amtrak across Eighth
Avenue will make it harder to reach from the Sixth and Seventh
avenue subways, leading in turn to more taxi and auto trips,
thereby worsening traffic and air pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak also has concerns about the mid-block ticketing hall.
``It has to look like a main entrance,'' Bartoli said. At the same
time, it cannot compete too strongly with the renowned Eighth
Avenue facade.
</P>
<P>
   The railroad expects some back-and-forth over the arrangement of
ticket counters and the location of stairways, elevators and
escalators. But it is generally satisfied with the plans drawn up
by the redevelopment corporation, Bartoli said.
</P>
<P>
   Walter R. Ernst, the general manager of Amtrak's Metropolitan
Division, recalled that the project could be traced to a need,
recognized a decade ago, for better access to the platforms below
and more waiting room in the station above. ``When the Farley
project is completed,'' he said, ``you'll have greatly improved
vertical circulation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody needs to deal with the problem of making Penn
Station better able to handle significant peaking levels of
passengers,'' Ernst said. Designed for a steady flow of intercity
trains through the day, the station was not equipped to handle
waves of commuter trains discharging or boarding more than 1,000
passengers at once.
</P>
<P>
   Other projects have been undertaken to improve conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The LIRR, which operates 542 of the 882 trains that run through
the station every weekday, completed a $190 million renovation in
1994. Designed by TAMS, it includes a new central corridor, a new
vaulted ceiling for the connecting corridor and more platform
access. A 90-foot-high entrance structure on 34th Street, by R.M.
Kliment &AMP; Frances Halsband Architects, restored some small sense of
the station as an important gateway. The LIRR also built the West
End Concourse to Tracks 13 through 21.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey Transit, which operates 219 trains daily, has begun a
$105 million waiting room and East End Concourse, to open in 2001.
A steel canopy over the concourse, leading to Tracks 1 through 12,
is meant to evoke somewhat the look of the old station. The
architects are Sverdrup &AMP; Parcel.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak, which operates 121 trains daily, has begun a $37.5
million renovation of the existing concourse, including three new
escalators and a waiting area for passengers boarding the
high-speed trains that are to begin running along the Northeast
Corridor later this year. The architects are Hellmuth, Obata &AMP;
Kassabaum.
</P>
<P>
   All but invisible to passengers is another critical improvement,
the $100 million upgrade to a switching and signaling system that
was essentially unchanged since the station opened in 1910.
</P>
<P>
   The work done by five control towers in Manhattan and Long
Island City, Queens, has been consolidated in a computerized
operating ``theater'' at the Claytor-Scannell Control Center at
Ninth Avenue and 31st Street, a joint venture between Amtrak and
the LIRR. It opened in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Dispatchers work at consoles in front of a 70-foot-long
illuminated board that shows the position of every train coming
into or out of Pennsylvania Station, from Morrisville, Pa., to New
Rochelle, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Impressive as this center is, it would not be enough in itself.
``Whatever is done to improve the signal system goes for nought,''
Ernst said, ``if you can't deliver people and get them off the
platforms quickly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
