u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDLIFE-CHOICE-$ADV03-     01-02 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDLIFE-CHOICE-$ADV03-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHOOSING A COLLEGE: WHICH WAY TO THE SALAD BAR? 
</HEADLINE>
  Linda Lee, an editor in the style department of The New York Times,
is writing a book on the choices facing high school seniors. 
 (For release on Sunday, Jan. 3.)  
(lb) 
 By LINDA LEE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When choosing a college, high school seniors and their parents
invariably say that cost and academics come first. Students also
want a school that is as far away from home as possible, or as
close as possible, and to go where siblings and friends have gone
before. But there are other, far subtler factors influencing a
student's choice.
</P>
<P>
   Mariah Balaban, 21, opted for Sarah Lawrence College because,
she said, she ``liked the way people dressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornelia Nicholson, a private counselor in Massachusetts who
helps students pick colleges, says she's heard it all. ``How about
two snowboarding requests in one week?'' she said. ``Another
student wants to go where he can windsurf!'' Call it the Club Ed
approach to choosing a school.
</P>
<P>
   In the competitive college climate, school officials know that,
all else being equal, a crispy cafeteria salad bar or an on-campus
McDonald's, a T-1 Internet hookup or a glossy health-club gym can
tip the scales in their favor. These are the goodies that influence
teen-agers nowadays during their campus visits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard admissions directors talk about managing the first
few hours a kid is on campus,'' said Patrick O'Brien, the president
of Making College Count, an advisory service in Green Bay, Wis. So
schools push their ``residential suites'' (preferable to
hotel-style dormitories) and the other essential accessories of a
good education, circa 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Here, according to admissions officials and college counselors,
is what sways students.
</P>
<P>
   A WARM AND COZY FEELING
</P>
<P>
   Choosing a college comes down to a feeling. ``Most college
freshmen are a little bit scared,'' O'Brien said. ``They'll do well
at a place where they feel comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Colleges know this and turn their brochures and videos into big,
ethnically diverse group hugs, often atop a grassy knoll.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien strongly recommends that students visit a campus to
check things out firsthand. ``If they visit, they are more likely
to go there, and more likely to stay,'' he said. ``They have a much
better sense of what the school is about.''
</P>
<P>
   BRIGHT KIDS, BIG CITY
</P>
<P>
   ``For so long, even a suburban school was thrown into the
category of being too close to a big city,'' said Nancy Monnich,
the director of admissions for Bryn Mawr College, near
Philadelphia. ``People would say, `What sane parent would send
their daughter to the evil city?' And now cities are so hot.''
</P>
<P>
   She placed Bryn Mawr firmly in the category of a city college.
``Not isolated like Sweet Briar,'' she said and laughed, perhaps in
sympathy. (Sweet Briar College is in rural Virginia.)
</P>
<P>
   According to Jennifer Ann Adams, a graduate student at
Pennsylvania State University who has done a study on campus
geography, more than half of all universities and colleges, both
two- and four-year, are now urban.
</P>
<P>
   Even if a college is not within shouting distance of a city, it
will stress its proximity to one. Admissions officers at their
respective schools promote the fact that Bard College, in rural
Annandale-on-Hudson, N.Y., is only two hours from New York City by
train; that Clark University, in industrial Worcester, Mass., is
less than an hour from Boston; that Princeton University, in its
tranquil New Jersey setting, is only an hour and 15 minutes from
New York.
</P>
<P>
   What draws students to urban campuses, according to Julia Eells,
the dean of admissions and college counseling at Miss Porter's
School, the private girls' school in Farmington, Conn., are
cultural events, internship opportunities and the fast pace of
urban life.
</P>
<P>
   For students who instead choose a more rural campus, ``there is
still the suitcase-college mentality,'' said Nancy King, the
president of the National Academic Advising Association, an
organization of 5,000 college advisers based in Manhattan, Kan.
``They are there during the week and off to a party school or home
on weekends.''
</P>
<P>
   A LITTLE DIVERSITY, PLEASE
</P>
<P>
   ``For my students, the diversity of the student body is probably
the biggest consideration, after academic reputation,'' said Ms.
Eells of Miss Porter's, where 11 percent of the students are from
other countries and 16 percent are minorities. ``My seniors are
surprised by the homogeneity they encounter on their college
visits, especially at the smaller, rural or suburban schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Students want schools that are sophisticated and open-minded.
Abraham Park, a 21-year-old senior at the State University of New
York at Albany, grew up in New York City. When he graduated from
Stuyvesant High School in Manhattan, the high school was 52 percent
Asian-American. Park chose SUNY-Albany because it was an urban
school far enough away from home (``Not that I don't love my
parents,'' he said) and sufficiently cosmopolitan. ``The student
body here is becoming more diverse every year,'' Park said. ``It's
not too homogenous. I've totally been happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Diversity, however, has different meanings to different people.
David Strauss, an executive at Art and Science, a marketing and
research group in Baltimore, points out that while students have
``bought what they've been told about the value of diversity,''
they sometimes have their own version of it.
</P>
<P>
   He recently asked 500 high school seniors, in a national survey,
how they would rank in importance various kinds of diversity on
campus. The highest rankings went to a wide range of courses,
social activities and housing possibilities. The kinds of diversity
most parents think of _ racial, regional, international, income
level and religious affiliation _ were less important.
</P>
<P>
   Yet these varying definitions found common ground. When asked
about roommates, the high school seniors said they were ready to
live with a roommate from overseas, or with one from a different
part of the country. They were also ready to live with a person who
had a different racial, income or religious background. ``The only
place where there is a problem,'' Strauss said, ``is with rooming
with someone with a different sexual preference.''
</P>
<P>
   LIVING LARGE
</P>
<P>
   The dorm situation can make or break a school on a candidate's
checklist.
</P>
<P>
   ``A long row of rooms with a telephone at the end of the hall,
the kind of dorm I had, aren't attractive anymore,'' Ms. Nicholson,
the college counselor, said. ``As colleges are constructing dorms,
they are well aware of the more comfortable circumstances kids have
grown up in. Now it's suites and common space. That old barracks
style is certainly on its way out.''
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to attract and retain freshmen (the most likely to
drop out of college) some schools have devised special-interest
floors for athletes, honor students, international students and
even students with similar hobbies. And Internet access from rooms,
for chatting with family and friends, is an essential.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   GLITZY GYMS
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a much more consumer-oriented generation of students
and parents,'' Ms. Nicholson said. ``They expect to see more
opulent campuses.'' That opulence extends to athletic facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Colleges with large endowments, for instance, have built sports
complexes that would rival Equinox fitness centers. The Rochester
Institute of Technology's Hale-Andrews Student Life Center, opened
in 1992, has weight-training rooms, three basketball courts,
racquetball courts and an indoor running track, as well as aerobic
dancing workshops with sign-language interpreters for the deaf.
</P>
<P>
   Students can assess various sports programs and facilities
through the Web site of the National Collegiate Athletic
Association (www.ncaa.org; click the icon for the choice of
sports).
</P>
<P>
   CAREER PLANNING
</P>
<P>
   Students always ask about job counseling.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the national data, the No. 1 reason students
are going to college is to get a better job,'' O'Brien of Making
College Count said. ``Obviously, adults and educators hope for
education, but they're thinking jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Some colleges have begun offering programs that place
undergraduates in short-term jobs before they graduate. Beyond
that, colleges are improving their career-planning centers to
attract students. Ms. King, the academic adviser, who is also an
executive in enrollment services at Kennesaw State University near
Atlanta, agreed that schools see more demand these days for helping
graduates obtain jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a consumer's market,'' she said. ``It's not enough to
just offer a degree program.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-02-99 1821EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
