<DOCNO> NYT19990102.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5454 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDLIFE-INTERVIEW-$ADV     01-02 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDLIFE-INTERVIEW-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENDPAPER: THE IMPORTANCE OF BEING BUSY
</HEADLINE>
  (For release on Sunday, Jan. 3.)  
(nk) 
 By JENNY LYN BADER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As with most elite schools, all Harvard applicants must submit
to an interview with a local alumnus, who describes Harvard to the
candidate and then the candidate to the admissions committee. The
chats take place in November and January. Jenny Lyn Bader, a
Harvard graduate whose ``Manhattan Casanova'' was featured in the
1998 National Playwrights Conference, has conducted such
interviews. They inspired this playlet.
</P>
<P>
   The Phone Call
</P>
<P>
   SCENE 1
</P>
<P>
   Interviewer: May I speak to Billy?
</P>
<P>
   Billy's mom: Sure, he's right here. May I ask who's calling?
</P>
<P>
   Interviewer: This is his Harvard interviewer.
</P>
<P>
   Billy's mom (hyperventilating): Billy!
</P>
<P>
   Interviewer: Billy, I'm calling to set up your Harvard
interview. Are you free tomorrow at 4?
</P>
<P>
   Billy: No problem. I've got nothing going on tomorrow. I like to
keep my afternoons pretty free. (Suddenly) Oops! Did you say
Harvard? I'm sometimes busy in the afternoons. Very busy.
</P>
<P>
   SCENE 2 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Interviewer: May I speak to Susan?
</P>
<P>
   Susan's assistant: I'm afraid not. May I take a message? I'm her
assistant. Actually, I'm her mother. But I feel like her assistant.
Susan won't be home till midnight. She has band practice, a track
meet and play rehearsal. She's directing a Lorca play in Spanish,
and did I mention she started a soup kitchen, where she tutors kids
from the projects with learning disabilities? Gee, looking in her
calendar, she has her piano students. She has Spinoza Club in the
morning. I'm sorry, it looks like she won't be home until
Wednesday. Can I take a message?
</P>
<P>
   Interviewer: I'm trying to set up her Harvard interview.
</P>
<P>
   Susan's assistant: Oh! I can page her if you like. I know she'd
love to go there.
</P>
<P>
   The Scores
</P>
<P>
   (The Harvard Club, later that week)
</P>
<P>
   SCENE 1 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Interviewer: What are your SAT's?
</P>
<P>
   Billy (musing): Gosh. What were they again? They were good.
Sorry, I usually try to remember things of moral or social
significance. SAT's aren't that important in the grand scheme of
life, are they?
</P>
<P>
   Interviewer: Well, no. But I need them for this form.
</P>
<P>
   Billy: But they've already been sent to the admissions office.
Why would you need them again?
</P>
<P>
   Interviewer: You're not going to believe this, Billy, but some
kids come in and lie about their scores, hoping we won't notice.
And some kids reel off all their scores from kindergarten onward,
which makes the interviewer worry about their mental state. And
some kids can't remember their scores, though I've never met one
before. It's actually refreshing!
</P>
<P>
   Billy: But it's not promising, is it?
</P>
<P>
   Interviewer: Well, sometimes the kids who forget are just flaky.
Or embarrassed their scores are low. But you seem to have forgotten
because you realize these scores are not among the really important
things in life. It's healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Billy: I guess. But it's the kids who remember their scores who
get in, right?
</P>
<P>
   Interviewer: Did I say that? I didn't say that.
</P>
<P>
   SCENE 2
</P>
<P>
   Interviewer: What are your SAT scores?
</P>
<P>
   Susan: 1570 the first time I took them; 1600 the second time.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewer: Why did you take them again?
</P>
<P>
   Susan: Um, I thought it would be fun?
</P>
<P>
   The Tough Questions
</P>
<P>
   SCENE 1
</P>
<P>
   Interviewer: What do you do after school, Billy? I'm always a
little startled to find a student at home when I call in the
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Billy: I see my friends. Hang out with my family. Go to the
movies. Read books.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewer: Are you directing a Lorca play in Spanish?
</P>
<P>
   Billy: No.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewer: What about Shakespeare?
</P>
<P>
   Billy: Did he direct a Lorca play in Spanish?
</P>
<P>
   Interviewer: No, but he didn't go to college. Have you founded
any nonprofit organizations or multinational corporations?
</P>
<P>
   Billy: Does it ask that on your form, too?
</P>
<P>
   Interviewer: Not really, but sometimes people forget to tell me
the most important things. How about titles? Do you have any
titles?
</P>
<P>
   Billy: Like Richard the Lionhearted?
</P>
<P>
   Interviewer: No, like editor in chief of the school newspaper.
Hmm, you said friends, movies, books, family. That sounds awfully
nice. Can you name them?
</P>
<P>
   Billy: Name what?
</P>
<P>
   Interviewer: Favorite books, movies, friends, family? I could
throw it in my report. ``Billy's favorite book is `Crime and
Punishment,' '' or ``Billy's favorite relative has changed his life
in profound ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy: If I had to pick a favorite relative, it would be my
Great-Uncle Alfred.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewer: Is he disabled in any way? You don't have any
community service, so I was thinking I could jazz up my report by
saying Billy frequently visits his ailing elderly favorite
relative, Great-Uncle Alfred, in a nursing hospice.
</P>
<P>
   Billy: Nah, Great-Uncle Alfred takes me race-car driving.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewer (brightening): Race-car driving? In the professional
athletic sense?
</P>
<P>
   Billy: No. For fun. There's no place for fun on that form, is
there?
</P>
<P>
   SCENE 2
</P>
<P>
   Interviewer: Are you really directing a Lorca play in Spanish?
</P>
<P>
   Susan (reciting a passage from ``Blood Wedding''):
</P>
<P>
   La luna deja un cuchillo
</P>
<P>
   abandonado en el aire,
</P>
<P>
   que siendo acecho de plomo
</P>
<P>
   quiere ser dolor de sangre.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewer: And you teach piano?
</P>
<P>
   Susan: Do you play? We could do a four-handed Tchaikovsky piece
I have with me.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewer: I'm a little out of practice. That piece looks
awfully difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Susan (puzzled): Didn't you go to Harvard?
</P>
<P>
   Interviewer: Yes, but things were different then. Do you ever
sleep?
</P>
<P>
   Susan: Why, does anyone sleep at college?
</P>
<P>
   Interviewer: Sure. Maybe you'll get some rest then. How's your
family life?
</P>
<P>
   Susan: I love my family! I see them on my vacations.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewer: Do you have any questions for me?
</P>
<P>
   Susan: Yeah. How's my mom? You spoke to her more recently than I
did.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewer: She seemed in good spirits.
</P>
<P>
   Susan: I'm glad. Send her my love.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
