<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5456 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELECTRONIC-TONGUE03-C     01-02 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELECTRONIC-TONGUE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What would you do with an electronic tongue?
 &HT;    By Dick Stanley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Some big companies want the technology to test
new food and drink products. The American military has something
more distasteful in mind: monitoring the disposal of chemical and
biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Competing with all of them to pick the first practical and
profitable use of an electronic tongue invented at the University
of Texas are four UT graduate business students who won't get their
master's degrees until May.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it really fits this community,'' said student Jason
Levin, director of business development for Vusion Inc., a new
Austin company.
</P>
<P>
   Levin, with classmates Richard Burgess, Kent Bradshaw and Paul
Kunko, created Vusion for a class competition, picked the UT
electronic tongue as its first product and won the contest. They're
now trying to raise the real capital they need to win a university
license to market the tongue to the pharmaceutical industry as a
control monitor for processing medicinal chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could give them instant feedback if there are problems with
quality,'' Levin said. ``We're not aware of any other technology in
the marketplace that can do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many consider the tongue's potential to be vast.
Invented by UT chemists and engineers to mimic the speed and
sophistication of human taste buds, the electronic tongue is
smaller than Lincoln on the head of a penny. It now consists of
hundreds of chemical microsensors on a silicon wafer, but future
tongues may be printed by the thousands on disposable plastic tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to license the technology to (Vusion) if possible,''
said Renee Mallett, assistant director of UT's Office of Technology
Licensing. ``But we can't give them special treatment because
they're students. They have to come up with the necessary
capital.''
</P>
<P>
   Mallett said at least 30 companies worldwide _ including some
big names in commerce _ have inquired about licensing the tongue.
He declined to say how much money the students need for a license.
</P>
<P>
   Levin said Vusion plans to raise $150,000 for company operations
through May, $2 million in June when it will hire a chief
executive, scientists and engineers, and $3 million in June 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Mallett said the tongue has so many potential uses that it
probably will be licensed to several companies, regardless of
whether Vusion wins a development license. The university and
inventors of the tongue would receive royalties from those
licenses.
</P>
<P>
   The tongue got its start in 1996 when co-inventors Dean Neikirk,
an electrical and computer engineer, and chemists John McDevitt,
Eric Anslyn and Jason Shear began kicking the idea around after
reading of efforts in Britain and Sweden to make biosensors to
mimic the sophistication of an animal's nose.
</P>
<P>
   Dogs, for example, have such an acute sense of smell that they
can sniff out particular molecules in vapor concentrations as low
as a few thousand parts per billion parts of air.
</P>
<P>
   The UT researchers built a test nose but decided what they
really wanted was to do something different, and a tongue fit the
bill. They made one by micromachining tiny inverted pyramids in a
silicon wafer to contain polymer microbeads, each one smaller than
the width of a hair and equipped with a sensor for a particular
class of chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   The sensors, which respond to chemicals by changing color, are
attached to a camera-on-a-chip to analyze color changes at 30
frames a second and report them to a computer.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, who would share in any royalties from the
invention, are now up to hundreds of bead sensors on a single
wafer, with the potential to rapidly analyze millions of chemical
combinations at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a variety of potential commercial uses, the
tongue is being considered as a tool for enhancing the speed and
accuracy of medical tests. The National Institutes of Health, for
instance, recently gave the UT researchers $600,000 to develop the
tongue to try to replace multiple, lengthy tests of blood and urine
with one rapid test.
</P>
<P>
   Levin said Vusion is considering a long-range effort to get the
tongue federally certified for medical uses, but they figure the
pharmaceutical industry is a safer bet for a quick return.
</P>
<P>
   The tongue's inventors agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a particularly clever utilization,'' McDevitt said,
``because new processing plants are constantly being developed to
commercialize new drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Neikirk added another reason why the inventors would like to see
the business students win a UT development license.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some big companies buy things and sit on them to avoid the
competition,'' Neikirk said. ``And, with these guys, we'd probably
have more input in seeing it come to fruition.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
