<HEADER>
A5457 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KATHLEENTURNER-MOVIES     01-02 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KATHLEENTURNER-MOVIES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kathleen Turner's movie memories
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kathleen Turner reminisces about some of her major movies:
</P>
<P>
   BODY HEAT, 1981's steamy film noir shot in Lake Worth, Fla., a
town she never really got to see: ``Well, you have to realize we
shot almost entirely at night. I remember vividly going home in the
vans at like 7 o'clock, 8 o'clock in the morning. I think we were
staying in Pompano. Basically, I never saw the town.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was the weather stifling, sticky hot, as required by the
script. ``We started shooting in December. It was damn cold. That
first scene on the beach, where I'm wearing the white dress and
they meet. The wind was so high and it was so cold, they drove the
trucks up on the beach and put plywood by the wheel bases to try
and block it, so we could actually get the shot.''
</P>
<P>
   But the characters needed to perspire. ``It was freezing and I
remember the make-up man kept coming up to me with his spray
bottle. And I looked at him and said, `Don't even think about it.
You want to live tomorrow?'''
</P>
<P>
   PRIZZI'S HONOR, as hit-woman Irene Walker (1985): ``That was
tough. John (Huston) said to me, `Everyone else is a member of this
club (the Mafia), and you're not.' And so you're the anchor, you're
the contrast to everyone else. Jack (Nicholson) was terrific.
Angelica (Huston) I didn't have any scenes with, but I used to go
and watch her work, because I think she was really doing some
on-the-edge stuff, which she was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always a student. There's nobody you can't learn from.''
</P>
<P>
   WHO FRAMED ROGER RABBIT, Unbilled as vamp Jessica Rabbit (1988)
_ ``The reason I didn't take credit for it was because of my
stature. They would have had to have given me equal billing with
Bob (Hoskins) and with Charlie (Fleischer), who did the voice of
Roger Rabbit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have anywhere near the amount of work or commitment
to the project that they did. I thought I was being graceful by not
taking credit,'' but it was perceived as an attention-getting
stunt. ``I suppose it's because people tend to look for the worst
interpretation they can, unfortunately.''
</P>
<P>
   SWITCHING CHANNELS, as cable news reporter Christy Colleran
(1988) _ ``The only film truly that I'm not proud of and that
wasn't my fault. I rehearsed that with Michael Caine and then they
threw in Burt Reynolds. Yuck!''
</P>
<P>
   THE ACCIDENTAL TOURIST, as estranged wife Sarah Leary (1988) _
``When Larry (Kasdan) sent me the script, he sort of said to me,
`Look at both women,' '' asking her to choose between Sarah and
dog-groomer/girlfriend Muriel Pritchett, the role that won Geena
Davis an Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got about halfway through and said, `Oh, I want the wife,'
because to me she was so interesting. She left him, she tried to
put together another life, she failed to do so, and then she came
back and then she had to accept the relationship on his terms.
Fascinating. I thought it was much more challenging, for me.''
</P>
<P>
   V.I. WARSHAWSKI, as the title detective (1991) _ ``That was a
big disappointment. This is where some of my ill feelings toward
Disney come from. They cut that film to shreds. They have a policy:
`Offend no one, upset no one.' And there was some hard-edged stuff,
they took it all out. They tried to make it a straight-line action
film or something. I was terribly sorry, but I can't do the
character again as long as she's under their control.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-02-99 1826EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990102.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5458 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDLIFE-ONLINE-$ADV03-     01-02 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDLIFE-ONLINE-$ADV03-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY: NOTES FROM CYBERCLASS
</HEADLINE>
   Bruce Weber is national cultural correspondent for The New York
Times. 
 (For release on Sunday, Jan. 3.)  
(dal) 
 By BRUCE WEBER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Adult education, the concept, has never much appealed to me.
Volunteer for more school? No thanks. I was quite pleased, more
than 20 years ago, when it was done with the first time. Every now
and then I still have that dream about being unprepared for a final
exam. (For some reason, the exam is always in French.) There's
something about entering a classroom that feels like a withdrawal
from the actual business of the world, participation in which I'd
earned by virtue of enduring two degrees' worth of pedagogy. I'm
not one of those people who get nostalgic about college: I like to
get paid for my work, not graded on it.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, augmenting one's education isn't anything you can
really be against, and I decided to go back to class, via the
Internet, spurred by an interest in exploring cyberspace and an
instinct that self-improvement wouldn't feel so burdensome if it
were a little more convenient.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, by many measures, going to school online is convenient.
You can go undressed. You can go in the middle of the night. You
can go in Kansas City. You can participate in discussions to
whatever extent you choose, sounding off overbearingly or keeping
smugly silent, without having to observe the ordinary etiquette of
classroom decorum. You can, in other words, construct your own
private experience.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, this ends up having its burdensome side. For
convenience, you pay with responsibility and accountability. Online
school is a venue for self-starters, which may be one reason that,
though 10 people enrolled in the class I took, only half were ever
heard from after the first few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The first problem any prospective student faces is simply
deciding what school to attend. The global reach of Internet
technology obviates geography and transportation as considerations
in making such a choice. From my home in Chicago I could get to
class at the University of California as easily as at the New
School for Social Research in New York, or to any of the hundreds
of places that now offer Internet classes. Any thorough perusal of
online catalogues is so time-consuming as to be daunting. I gave up
rather quickly, choosing the New School (www.dialnsa.edu) after
checking out only one or two others because it offered the class I
wanted _ a playwriting workshop _ and because it was familiar.
Until a year or so ago, I lived in New York, not far from the
campus. Call me homesick.
</P>
<P>
   Of the nine other people who enrolled in the same class, all but
one were New Yorkers. The exception was Angela Davis, a federal
prosecutor in Los Angeles. Ms. Davis, whose contributions to the
class documents were as voluminous and thorough as legal briefs,
told me that she chose the New School because she was impressed by
the resume of the instructor, Robert Montgomery (particularly that
he had attended Yale Drama School and had had a play of his own
produced at the Joseph Papp Public Theater), and because she wanted
a drama class taught in New York, which is, after all, the center
of drama. ``I was delighted that I had the opportunity to take this
`New York' class from my home in Los Angeles,'' she wrote to me in
an e-mail message.
</P>
<P>
   The second problem is one of access. In one way, real school is
a passive experience. You show up in class, the curriculum gets
flung at you and maybe, if you're not asleep, it sticks.
Cyberschool is a bit more active; you find your classroom and
negotiate around it. There's a facility to be learned _ the deft
burrowing of a computer mouse, not necessarily a natural thing for
a middle-aged man who is habitually behind the techno-curve. It
took me about an hour to get comfortable with the mechanics of
going to school. (OK, not as onerous as settling into a dorm room.)
</P>
<P>
   How it works at the New School is this: after online
registration _ and payment via credit card (the nine-week class
costs $450 for a non-credit student) _ I was sent a set of
passwords that granted me access to the online campus, which is
essentially a set of Web sites. A handful of them are accessible to
all students, no matter what classes they are taking. One is an
orientation site, where tips for efficient campus travel are
dispensed. One is a student lounge, where students can mingle,
posting messages either for general consumption or for individual
correspondents. (The tone of the conversation was distinctly eager
and friendly _ ``Hi everybody! This is my first online class and
I'm really psyched!'' _ much like what I remember freshman
orientation to have been so many eons ago. Some things transfer to
cyberlife undisturbed.) For some reason, there is also a room set
aside specifically to discuss movies.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is a separate site for each class for which a
student has registered, and inside that site is another set of
sites set up by the professor. In the playwriting class, Montgomery
had his own ``podium,'' as it were, from which he gave
``lectures,'' providing, about once a week, disquisitions on
elements of playwriting _ things like story, character, dialogue _
mostly tips for us students to keep in mind as we composed our own
scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Each of us had our own site as well, in which we were to post
our work for the consumption of our classmates and in which
Montgomery and our classmates could post commentary. Since we all
had access to all sites, we were able to keep tabs on our mutual
progress.
</P>
<P>
   Once I got the hang of it, I found it remarkably efficient and
ingenious. There were some obvious drawbacks. Any classroom
certainly is meant to take advantage of social intercourse and the
dynamic that develops when people are in actual contact with one
another. Online this is lost, by definition, but in a playwriting
seminar what is also lost is the opportunity for the writers to
hear their work read out loud, which it is, of course, meant to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``The presence thing, that's what's missing,'' Montgomery, who
also teaches playwriting in ``real space'' at the New School, told
me in a phone interview after the course was over, when I announced
my intention to write about the class. ``As a playwright you have
to know how to include it, the presence of an actor, in your
work.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
