<DOCNO> NYT19990102.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5459 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KATHLEENTURNER-COX     01-02 1522
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KATHLEENTURNER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Turner may have quirky taste, but she chooses roles carefully
 &HT;    (With KATHLEENTURNER-MOVIES.)
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORAL GABLES, Fla. _ Hollywood is a town that rarely knows what
to do with actresses over 40. Kathleen Turner is an outspoken,
44-year-old actress who rarely plays by Hollywood's rules. When
they collide, the smart money is on Turner.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I've decided is that I find most of the real studio
monolithic productions boring as hell,'' she says with her
trademark husky purr. ``As far as I'm concerned, they're all
men-with-guns. They could save a lot of money on promotion and
advertising if they just changed the numbers on the posters _ Men
With Guns 2, Men With Guns 3, Men With Guns September. They don't
need me for anything like that, frankly.''
</P>
<P>
   So as she has for the past 17 years, ever since she sauntered
and sweated on-screen, steaming up moviegoers' glasses in the South
Florida film noir ``Body Heat,'' Turner has hit the pause button on
her film career in favor of the theater.
</P>
<P>
   For every ``Romancing the Stone'' or ``Peggy Sue Got Married,''
she has gone off and done a ``Midsummer Night's Dream'' or a
``Camille'' in regional theater. After every ``Accidental Tourist''
or ``Serial Mom,'' Turner has turned down movie projects to star on
Broadway in a ``Cat on a Hot Tin Roof'' or an ``Indiscretions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to say no,'' she instructs. ``You're known as much
for what you won't do as for what you do. I truly believe that.''
</P>
<P>
   She has said a resounding ``yes'' to ``Tallulah,'' a one-woman
show about irascible, irreverent stage and screen star Tallulah
Bankhead, beginning previews Tuesday at the Coconut Grove
Playhouse, prior to its American premiere on Friday, Jan. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Although born in different halves of this century, Bankhead and
Turner are two theatrical souls connected by a common baritone.
``Yes, I'm often mistaken on the phone for a man,'' concedes
Turner. ``I always wonder whether or not to correct them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting across from her in the lobby of a waterfront condo near
Coconut Grove, it is impossible to make such an error. Her soft
blonde hair cascades around a flawless complexion. Dressed casually
but well, in a black pantsuit and turtleneck top, it is clear that
Turner has shed her early '90s, V.I. Warshawski heft. If she is no
longer ``Body Heat's'' Mattie Walker, she is at least her older
sister, and equally capable of driving men to do foolish things.
</P>
<P>
   Still, compared to Bankhead, Turner is Little Mary Sunshine.
Bankhead was a legendary partier, known for multi-day alcohol and
drug binges, for doffing her clothes in public and for taking on
uncountable lovers. Although wed to actor John Emery, marriage did
not agree with her and she divorced him four years later at the age
of 38. In contrast, Turner has been married for the past 14 years
to New York real estate developer Jay Weiss, with whom she has a
precocious 10-year-old daughter, Rachel Ann.
</P>
<P>
   `Great affinity'
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Turner knows a good role when she sees it. After
reading the script of Tallulah, which playwright Sandra Ryan
Heyward is said to have written with Turner in mind, she hit the
books.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did some research on Tallulah, read about five biographies
including her autobiography, which is flattering but not entirely
accurate,'' says Turner. ``And I was drawn all the more to her. We
are so totally different, and yet we are kindred spirits.'' When
the performance works, she adds, it is equal parts of Tallulah and
Kathleen. ``I don't think you can tell the difference,'' says
Turner. ``We seem to have a great affinity.''
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing the difference between a good role and a good play,
however, Turner took Tallulah to England's Chichester Festival to
test its stageworthiness. ``And the deal was that I would do
Somerset Maugham's ``Our Betters'' on the main stage if they would
let us do a workshop production of Tallulah on their smaller
stage,'' she says. ``We worked on the script there, adding things
in, taking things out, moving things around, shaping it, getting it
to the point where we were ready for the next step.''
</P>
<P>
   To make that quantum leap, Turner brought in director Michael
Lessac, who had directed her in the 1993 arty autism film, ``House
of Cards.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She is fearless,'' he says of Turner. ``I have never seen such
courage in an actress, taking on a challenge like a one-woman show
on Tallulah. I think you're going to see a more intimate Kathleen,
a more vulnerable Kathleen.''
</P>
<P>
   Not on her agenda
</P>
<P>
   Even before South Florida takes a look, though, Turner is
convinced the show is New York-bound. ``I think it belongs on
Broadway,'' she says, then wonders aloud, ``Does that sound
boastful?''
</P>
<P>
   Still, when asked if Tallulah aims to show Hollywood a different
side of her to gain better film roles, Turner wrinkles her nose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care, frankly. I mean, that's not the purpose,'' she
says. ``That isn't part of the agenda in my head.''
</P>
<P>
   True, the '90s have seen her trip in a succession of little-seen
films like ``Undercover Blues'' and ``Naked in New York,'' while
taking supporting roles in such non-studio films as ``Moonlight''
and ``Valentino,'' ``The Real Blonde'' and ``A Simple Wish.'' The
latter at least is a conscious choice, she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I've done really is let it be known that I'm very
interested in developing scripts and working with new directors,
young directors. But, there's a condition,'' Turner says
emphatically. ``They have to compress all of my character's work
together in the shortest period possible, three or four weeks being
optimum.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she can retreat to her Greenwich Village home and to her
family. ``So I'll work for a month, I'll go home for a month, work
a month, go home a month. It's wonderful. I have my life and I have
my work.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't feel sorry for Turner because she hasn't been starring in
major movies lately. ``I love it,'' she insists. ``I don't know
whether it's being 44 or whether it's just that I've done that,
I've been there. I don't have the same ambition. I don't want to
carry the entire film anymore. I don't want to stop my life for
five months while I do this monolithic production. I like having a
life apart from all that.''
</P>
<P>
   And don't feel sorry for Turner's agents and managers, or worry
that their children will starve while she feeds her artistic soul
doing Tallulah. After all, four of these small independent pictures
are poised for release in 1999, three with first-time directors.
</P>
<P>
   Among them is a dark comedy called ``The Virgin Suicides,''
directed by Sofia Coppola, the daughter of Turner's ``Peggy Sue Got
Married'' filmmaker, Francis Ford Coppola. ``I think it might be a
very moving piece,'' says Turner softly. ``Not easy, pretty tough
stuff. Five kids kill themselves, and I'm the mother.''
</P>
<P>
   In marked contrast is ``Baby Geniuses,'' in which she plays Dr.
Elena Kinder, a mad scientist who gathers a gaggle of pre-speech
infants, trying to crack the code of baby talk. ``I try and mold
their minds in order to take over the world,'' she laughs. ``It's
your basic take-over-the-world plot, OK?''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's ``a very sweet film,'' ``Prince of Central Park,''
where she is a demon cyclist who befriends a boy who has run away
from an abusive foster home and lives in Central Park. And most
recently, Turner completed a black comedy with Ed Asner, Jason
Alexander and Courtney Vance titled ``Love and Action'' in Chicago,
in which they work for a secret government unit known as the
Eliminator Corps. ``For example, when you have a diplomat who's
smuggling drugs and arms, but the government can't touch him, we
eliminate him.''
</P>
<P>
   No one can accuse Turner of not having quirky taste. As to these
films' fate at the box office, let's just say that ``Star Wars
Episode I: The Phantom Menace'' isn't worried. ``I don't think any
of them will be blockbusters,'' says Turner with a shrug. ``I liked
the scripts, liked the people, liked what they were trying to do.''
</P>
<P>
   If she had to adjust her salary downward to fit these
independent film budgets, she did so without qualms. ``We're doing
fine,'' she says. ``How much money does anybody need?''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it has been 10 years since Turner made the movie
exhibitors' list of top box office draws, but don't start feeling
sorry for her. She's doing exactly what she's always wanted to,
ever since her parents took her to the theater in London as a
child.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was way up on the third tier, and I leaned over and I
thought, `My god, people do this for a living,' '' she recalls with
another throaty laugh. ``It had just never occurred to me that I
could actually make my living acting out. Once I got that into my
head, that was it.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I have.''
</P>
<P>
   TALLULAH: Starring Kathleen Turner at the Coconut Grove
Playhouse, 3500 Main Highway, Miami, previewing from Tuesday1/5,
regular performances from Friday1/8 through Jan. 31. Tickets:
$35-$40. Call: (305) 442-4000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
