<HEADER>
A5461 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-SALES-TIPS-LADN     01-02 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-SALES-TIPS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROOMING TIPS CAN HELP PREPARE HOUSE FOR SELLING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The real estate market is hot in Southern
California's suburban San Fernando Valley, with both prices and
sales hitting their highest levels in years. So now might be the
time to wring a little equity out of your house.
</P>
<P>
   But it takes more work than calling up a broker, planting a
``For Sale'' sign in the front yard and waiting for prospective
buyers to call.
</P>
<P>
   You may have to invest some time and effort into your place to
turn it into someone else's dream home.
</P>
<P>
   In the language of the real estate game, give your house some
``curb appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are 10 tips on doing just that from the Southland Regional
Association of Realtors:
</P>
<P>
   1. Give the house a top to bottom cleaning. This signals to a
buyer that the home has been well cared for and is in generally
good shape. A dirty or messy house can highlight every flaw.
</P>
<P>
   2. Spread some paint around. Realtors say that nothing improves
the value of a home for a lower capital outlay than a fresh coat of
paint. And it is often easier to give a room a fresh coat of paint
than it is to scrub down the walls. Choose neutral colors, like
off-white. Hold those artistic vibes in check and avoid black,
violet and pink.
</P>
<P>
   3. Plan on sprucing up the grounds. Make sure the lawn and
shrubbery are neatly trimmed. Prune any trees whose branches are
touching the roof line, and make sure the clippings are either
bagged and placed in a trash can or stowed in an orderly fashion.
If you have a pool or spa, make sure the water is clean.
</P>
<P>
   4. Get rid of clutter and follow the general rule: Less is best.
Throw a garage sale, clear out closets and trash what you can't
sell. Less stuff in the house will make it look roomier.
</P>
<P>
   5. Let there be light. Pull back the drapes or open the shades.
Put brighter bulbs in the light fixtures, but don't go overboard
and blind prospective buyers with glare. Remember, dark rooms feel
gloomy. Bright, open rooms feel more inviting.
</P>
<P>
   6. Don't forget the Fido factor. If you have pets, send them
away for a while or take them away from the home when a prospective
buyer is coming by. Some people can be intimidated by pets or even
allergic to them.
</P>
<P>
   7. The same can be said for children. They can be noisy and
distract someone while they are looking at the home.
</P>
<P>
   8. Air it out. Try to get rid of odors that may be unfamiliar or
unpleasant such as tobacco, pets, cooking and old laundry. Put out
some fresh flowers or bowls of potpourri. You can also bake some
bread to give your house a homey fragrance.
</P>
<P>
   9. Fix what's broken, if possible. Include in this list
plumbing, electrical systems, switches, windows, TV antennas,
screens, doors and fences. If you can't fix it, get rid of it. A
window with no screen is better than a window with a ripped screen.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, buyers will make lower offers if the house is in
disrepair and still insist that everything be fixed before moving
in. This cuts down on the chance of buyers offering a lot less than
you are asking.
</P>
<P>
   10. Keep the noise down. Silence is as restful as it is golden.
Make sure the television is off; if you want some music, opt for
some soft instrumental numbers. If necessary, close windows to
block out street noise.
</P>
<P>
   You can also obtain a checklist of things to do from the
Realtors association by calling (818) 786-2110.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-02-99 1827EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990102.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5462 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDLIFE-ONLINE-$ADV03-     01-02 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDLIFE-ONLINE-$ADV03-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: your work.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the semblance of a writing seminar became quite
persuasive; the discourse involved healthy doses of both insightful
criticism and self-serving blather, just what aspiring writers
sound like when they gather in person. And because people are
forced to write out their reactions, the communication was
relatively lean. In writing, the speaking-to-hear-yourself-speak
impulse is curtailed. There's no blurting. People take care to say
what they mean, not just what has crossed their minds, so even when
someone had something silly to say, it was clearly expressed. (For
that alone, gratitude is in order.) Writing focuses thought; I've
rarely found that illustrated so acutely as I did during this
class.
</P>
<P>
   And, in a funny way, even without the familiar interaction in a
classroom, the human dynamic asserted itself. Personalities became
evident. People were supportive mostly, testy occasionally.
Alliances were formed. And a general allegiance to Montgomery was
forged, even though none of us ever laid eyes on him. (In four
years of teaching online, he told me over the phone, ``this is the
longest conversation with a student I've ever had.'')
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery, 52, who has taught playwriting for 20 years, is the
author of several produced plays, including ``Subject to Fits,'' a
musical takeoff on Dostoyevsky's ``Idiot,'' which featured Ben
Kingsley when it was produced in London in 1972. He proved to be a
careful, diligent reader and critic, offering firm but gently
worded suggestions that were both conceptual and quite specific
(for instance, line cuts and phrasing changes). I have a terrible
time beginning things, but something Montgomery wrote early on _
that each scene is like a play in microcosm, with the characters
wrestling with conflict and moving to resolve it _ helped me decide
that my play should start with the two main characters already
angry at each other. Otherwise, I'd have had them dithering around,
trying to make each other mad, but only frustrating the audience as
they frustrated themselves.
</P>
<P>
   My classmates _ a diverse bunch and distinctly adult, with
several, like me, in their 40s _ included an
actress-turned-hospital administrator, two massage therapists, a
nurse and an executive with a finance company. They were all, at
least the ones who stuck around, serious about writing for the
stage. I had wanted to take playwriting because it is a skill I
admire, and because I write about the theater as a journalist. It
couldn't hurt to get a little closer to my subject. But it was
daunting to hear about the projects the others were working on,
most of which were more ambitious than my own, an ostensible comedy
about two old friends in a battle over a cheap Manhattan apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Davis had already made considerable progress on a historical
drama set in 16th-century England. Another was adapting Dickens's
``Christmas Carol'' with gay characters in a contemporary Manhattan
setting. A third was writing about a man who, unhappy in love, was
getting nighttime visitations and advice from the ghosts of
historical figures like Lord Byron, who spoke to him in rhymed
couplets. The hospital administrator was working on a play about
Anna Mae Aquash, an American Indian activist whose 1976 murder in
South Dakota has never been solved.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, some of the writers were more polished than others,
but overall the reading was absorbing.
</P>
<P>
   That was a blessing, as there was a lot of it. Those taking the
course for credit were required to produce 15 finished pages, and
even with half the class falling by the wayside, several people
proved to be prolific revisers. (I'm a prolific procrastinator
myself, and by the end, I'd only offered an opening scene of four
pages. The verdict was that they were promising. Yeah, yeah.)
</P>
<P>
   But more than the actual scripts, what also had to be read was
the ongoing discussion, and herein lies the main difference between
real school and online school. The latter may be more user-friendly
than the former, but inattention costs more. Though there are no
occasions to show up for, that doesn't mean there are no classes;
rather, what it means is that the course is one continuous,
semesterlong session. In real school, if you cut a class, it is
gone, over, unreclaimable. Online, however, you never miss
anything. Whatever commentary is offered by the teacher or by
classmates is recorded, and whenever you sign on and check in, it
is all there, a linear record of what has gone on in your absence.
Which means that if you don't check in for a week, a week's worth
of discussion is there to be perused. Once, when I didn't sign on
for 10 days, there were nearly 200 entries waiting for me when I
returned, well over 100 pages of reading before I could begin
crafting any of my own responses to my classmates' work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interesting thing is that people think an online course is
going to be easier than a classroom course, but I've spent a lot
more time with this one than with the others I've taken at the New
School,'' said Joseph Carman, 42, one of the massage therapists,
who is finishing a degree at the New School, both online and in
class, that he left incomplete at Fordham University more than a
decade ago. ``It takes an awful lot of time, logging on, and then
deciding where to go first, and reading other people's work and
making a thoughtful response.''
</P>
<P>
   Carman, who said he signed into class about four times a week,
finished two long scenes during the semester and said he was going
to re-enroll so he could finish a draft of his play. His was the
one with the Byronic couplets. ``It would be interesting to get
everybody in a room without identifying ourselves,'' he said, ``to
see if we could pick out who's who.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm thinking about re-enrolling myself. I'd only managed to sign
on for class about once a week, and I'd only managed to produce
those four pages. My classmates reacted to me accordingly. In the
end, my Web site had less activity than any of the others. The
salient point, I realized, is that whatever I got out of the class,
I earned. Which may be the ultimate definition of adult education.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
