<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-PACKERS-FIX-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
49ERS VS. PACKERS CAPSULE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MITCHELL KRUGEL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
Green Bay (11-5) at San Francisco (12-4) 
Time: 3:15 p.m. today, KDFW/Channel 4 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Series record: Tied 25-25-1 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last meeting: Packers beat 49ers, 36-22, on Nov. 1 in Green Bay,
Wis. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Postseason records: Packers 22-9, 49ers 23-14 &QL; 
The story lines &QL; 
Packers are 5-0 in opening playoff games under coach Mike
Holmgren. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Packers quarterback Brett Favre has 4 TDs and 0 INTs in 3
playoff games vs. 49ers, and wide receiver Antonio Freeman has 11
catches for 300 yards and 3 TDs in past two games vs. 49ers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay has won the past five between these teams, including
three consecutive playoff victories. The most recent win came in
Week 9 of this season, a 36-22 victory at Lambeau Field. Can the
49ers finally get their revenge? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scouting Green Bay's offense: Now that primary offensive weapons
Freeman and Dorsey Levens are back in the lineup, quarterback Brett
Favre has less of the offensive burden on his shoulders. However,
he continues to throw interceptions, including two last week vs.
the Bears. In Week 9, interceptions almost cost the Packers a
relatively easy victory against the 49ers. With his team ahead
16-0, Favre had three passes picked off. Levens carried 17 times
for 52 yards last week against the Bears. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scouting San Francisco's defense: The defense is without
defensive tackle Bryant Young, out for the year with an injury.
They are so desperate for pass-rushing help that they signed former
All-Pro Charles Haley and plan to activate him for today's game.
The defensive backfield is weak, and without pressure from the
front seven, is vulnerable. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scouting San Francisco's offense: RB Garrison Hearst pulled his
hamstring vs. the Rams last week. If he isn't back to full
strength, San Francisco will have to rely on quarterback Steve
Young's ability to move the ball without a dependable running game.
The offensive line was surprisingly good early in the season, but
has gotten progressively worse in the past two months. Green Bay
sacked Young nine times in Week 9. Young, the most efficient passer
in NFL history, is a mind-boggling 0-8 in his career against the
Packers. Because he was under fire all day, Young threw for only
132 yards against the Packers in Week 9. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scouting Green Bay's defense: Is cornerback Craig Newsome
healthy? After suffering a serious knee injury late in the season,
he tried to stay in the lineup, but might as well have been wearing
a target. The secondary has been a problem for the Packers all
season, though, and Newsome's playoff experience could come in
handy. Vonnie Holliday is another player the Packers need healthy.
The rookie defensive end has been a force since training camp,
going hard after the quarterback and stopping the run effectively.
He's a star in the making. &QL; 
The bottom line &QL; 
The 49ers can't afford to get too far behind early. With the way
their defense is playing, they stand little chance of containing
Favre and mounting a big comeback. Green Bay, despite being on the
road, has had San Francisco's number in recent years and holds a
big psychological edge. San Francisco's best hope is a high-scoring
shootout. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Green Bay 28, San Francisco 24 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
