<HEADLINE>
LADY RAIDERS BEAT LADY BEARS AT BUZZER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Defending Big 12 women's basketball champion Texas
Tech yesterday did what many predict few teams will do this season
_ win at Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Keitha Dickerson swished a 17-foot jumper from out front
that she released just before the final buzzer to give the
eighth-ranked Lady Raiders a 51-49 victory over the Lady Bears
before a season-high Ferrell Center crowd of 4,192.
</P>
<P>
   ``If all Big 12 games are like this, I'll be in a cardiac unit
after the first half of the schedule,'' Tech coach Marsha Sharp
said. ``But Baylor played very well today. They're an awfully good
basketball team that is going to win a lot of games. We knew that
coming in here, and we're even more convinced of that now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Raiders (12-1) won their 11th consecutive game, on the
home floor of a team that along with ranked teams Tech, Kansas,
Iowa State and Nebraska expects to be among the league's best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you win on the road in the Big 12 it's going to be
significant,'' Sharp said. ``The champion isn't going to come out
undefeated or even with one or two losses. From that perspective,
\Rthe victory\S is huge for us.''
</P>
<P>
   consecutive game recovering from a cracked bone in her left
elbow. And Baylor's Lara Webb connected on only one of four 3-point
attempts. But] Lara Webb sank three free throws after being fouled
attempting a 3-pointer with 22.5 seconds left to tie the score at
49 in a game where the largest lead was six points.
</P>
<P>
   After Webb's free throws, Tech guard Melinda Schmucker brought
the ball downcourt and passed to Dickerson. She lofted a pass
inside to post Angie Braziel. But Webb flashed in on the baseline
and knocked the ball out of Braziel's hands.
</P>
<P>
   Braziel won a scramble for the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hesitant for a while,'' said Braziel, who scored a
game-high 17 points with 11 rebounds. `` I knew there wasn't much
time left. I was just looking for someone else to get off the
shot.''
</P>
<P>
   She found Dickerson alone out front.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just threw it up there and prayed it went in,'' said
Dickerson, who with 10 points and 11 rebounds recorded a fourth
double-double in five games.
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Bears (8-4) have little time to ponder the loss before
a game Tuesday night at preseason Big 12 favorite Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm upset about the loss,'' BU coach Sonja Hogg said. ``But I
know what we're capable of doing against good teams. The Lady Bears
have arrived and shall not go away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
