A5476 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBACOL03-COX     01-02 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBACOL03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NBA NOTES: Another basketball league? Forget it
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   While we're at the dawning of the new year, let's dispense with
one piece of foolishness, that being talk of a new professional
basketball league to rival the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   It won't happen.
</P>
<P>
   While union executive director Billy Hunter blusters about a new
home for his players, the facts say there simply is no meat for his
sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at it objectively, there's no question that our
players would suffer,'' Hunter said in a conference call last week.
``By the same token, I don't think that the NBA owners are prepared
to blow up something that they've spent 56 years building. Now,
they may, out of arrogance and power, thumb their nose at us and
cut off their heads to spite their face. But the reality is, the
downside is so great that I don't know if the NBA would ever
recover.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have 29 franchises that in the aggregate are worth
probably $5 billion to $6 billion, so are you going to jeopardize
your $6 billion investment? They may be independently wealthy and
may be able to survive it, but I don't think they'll be able to put
the league back together.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's to stop some other groups from stepping up (and
starting a new league)? I know the owners are aware there are other
people willing to replace them. They don't have a monopoly on
money.''
</P>
<P>
   So, it's apparently Hunter's view that there are wealthy men
across America who want to be insulted by Alonzo Mourning while
they pay him $15 million a year, that there is someone outside
Minnesota who wants to give Kevin Garnett $126 million.
</P>
<P>
   A new league cannot survive without television, and much of the
speculation from agents David Falk and Arn Tellem is that Rupert
Murdoch would like to bring his Fox network into play.
</P>
<P>
   Vince Wladika, senior vice president of media relations for Fox
Sports, points out that Fox carries games locally for 26 of the 29
NBA teams, with average contracts lasting seven years, and that
Murdoch also is a minority owner of the Knicks and thus in both
instances would be competing against himself by trying to form a
new league. For example, Fox Sports South carries 30 Hawks games
and 20 Hornets games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The agents are having a fun time trying to spread that around,
but we're not a company that has a tendency to devalue its
properties,'' Wladika told the New York Times. ``Those rumors are
being spread by people who don't know the reality.''
</P>
<P>
   A more realistic view comes from NBA commissioner David Stern,
who says his league ``will always be here. In the form that you see
it, the NBA will open next year. It may not have the same players
it does this year; it may not charge the same ticket prices, it may
not even have the expensive TV package, but it will be a league,
and it will survive for a long time, and it will re-grow and recoup
itself. It will have suffered tremendously, but it will be here to
live and entertain another day and ultimately thrive.''
</P>
<P>
   Heated
</P>
<P>
   If there is a season, Heat coach Pat Riley might have to do his
best job of coaching ever. First, if he re-signs defensive ace
Keith Askins, he will have to curb any problems with Alonzo
Mourning. Askins says the negotiating committee, with Mourning,
holds the masses hostage. And Tim Hardaway has taken some swipes at
Mourning for his comments regarding players' mismanagement of money
at the announcement for the Dec. 19 exhibition game in Atlantic
City, N.J. Hardaway ripped Mourning again after Mourning suggested
that part of the problem with negotiations might be related to
race.
</P>
<P>
   Lonesome
</P>
<P>
   Free agent Tom Gugliotta's talking like a homeless person.
``With the lockout, I've lost a lot of contact (with the Minnesota
team). I won't say there are hard feelings. I understand it's
business. But I feel like I'm out on my own. You can't use any of
the facilities. Like my teammate Sam Mitchell said, `My family has
been mad at me before. But they never locked me out of the
house.'''
</P>
<P>
   Omens
</P>
<P>
   A charity game planned for Durham, N.C., last week was canceled
because the gym was not reserved. Ron Mercer's planned public
practice at Brandeis U. was called off when no players showed, and
a Kansas City game was canceled because organizers said there was
not enough time to prepare. ``I definitely think (fans are) going
to get back at us,'' said the Lakers' Eddie Jones, who did play in
an exhibition game in Los Angeles. ``They're going to support a
charity event (maybe), but you're talking about an NBA game where
people are paying actual money that's going in someone's pocket. I
don't think they're going to support that at all.''
</P>
<P>
   They said it
</P>
<P>
   Gary Payton of the Sonics: ``The owners still have a billion
dollars in the bank. They are in their big houses, but they don't
have gold chains around their necks and Rolexes. They don't flaunt
it like we do.'' Gee, has Payton ever seen the Lakers' Jerry Buss?
</P>
<P>
   Bryant Stith of the Nuggets: ``I will go out and play if the NBA
calls us back to work now or in (1999-2000). Whatever the situation
is, I'm willing to accept and just move on. But I haven't put my
life on hold, just sitting by the phone and reading the paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Agent Dan Fegan: ``If I were the players, I wouldn't take the
deal on the table. I would pass on the season. The deal is
horrible. In my opinion, David Stern and the owners are greedy
pigs. They want to have their cake and eat it, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Free agent Brent Barry: ``We agreed during our (October) meeting
in Las Vegas that we wanted Billy and our committee to be the
megaphone for us. But at this point, maybe it is better if the
inmates run the asylum.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
