<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FSU defense knows ropes
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ On Sept. 14, Florida State went to practice with
a 1-1 record and a most uncertain future. The Seminoles had just
lost to N.C. State and wondered if their string of 11 consecutive
top-four finishes was in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   Mickey Andrews, Florida State's veteran defensive coordinator,
arrived at a team meeting holding a rope. The players in the room
rustled nervously.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're at the bottom of a mountain and you have to climb this
rope to the top,'' Andrews told his troops. ``Look around. Who in
this room do to you trust to hold the rope?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew exactly what he meant,'' said defensive tackle Corey
Simon. ``If we didn't trust every guy in the room to hold that
rope, none of us were going to get to the top of the mountain. If
we didn't believe in each other and take care of each other, we
were not going to reach our goals.''
</P>
<P>
   And the goal at Florida State, as always, is to play for the
national championship. That day the defense decided it could be
good enough to take the Seminoles there.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, No. 2 Florida State (11-1) will play No. 1
Tennessee in the Fiesta Bowl for the national title. And there is
no mystery why the Seminoles are here. Everyone, from head coach
Bobby Bowden to the water boy, knows that Florida State rode to the
national championship game on the backs of a defense that exceeded
everyone's expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers are impressive. Florida State leads the nation in
total defense, giving up only 241.8 yards per game. That's 42.9
yards better per game than No. 2 Ohio State. They are tops against
the pass, second against the run, and are giving up only 11.5
points per game.
</P>
<P>
   But the numbers tell only half the story, for there was no way
Florida State's defense could have been expected to enjoy this
lofty position.
</P>
<P>
   Andre Wadsworth. Greg Spires. Sam Cowart. Darryl Bush. Samari
Rolle.
</P>
<P>
   Losing any of those great players would be hard for a defense to
overcome. The Seminoles lost them all after the 1997 season. Even
their most diehard fan assumed there would be at least a slight
dropoff.
</P>
<P>
   Didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``People gave us no shot at being as good as we were a year ago,
but the truth is we're better,'' said Simon. ``We've proved it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seminoles gave up only 138 points this season, but again,
those numbers tell only part of the story. Of that total, Florida
State allowed only 45 points in the second half (3.75 avg.) of its
12 games. Six of its opponents (Texas A&AMP;M, Maryland, Clemson,
Georgia Tech, Virginia, Florida) were shut out in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have as many name players as we've had in the past,
but we've got a lot of kids who wanted to be something special,''
said Andrews, in his 15th season at Florida State. ``We set the bar
pretty high around here, and they were willing to work to go over
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrews works his defense as hard as anybody, but the fact is,
there was a lot of talent waiting in the wings. Senior Tony Bryant
and sophomore Roland Seymour stepped into the end spots vacated by
Wadsworth and Spires. Bryant was All-ACC second team and led the
team with seven sacks. Seymour (6-4), will some day be an All-ACC
player. Simon, Jerry Johnson and Larry Smith are all dominating
tackles (Smith will miss Monday's game with an injury). Mario
Edwards returned after a year's absence at cornerback and, as a
result, this secondary covers significantly better than the 1997
unit.
</P>
<P>
   And there is depth. Injuries have limited the playing time of
Smith, linebacker Lamont Green and a host of others, but every
time, somebody stepped in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Collectively, I thought we had more overall talent and depth
than we did a year ago,'' said Andrews. ``All they needed was some
experience, so this was a group that kind of grew up together.''
</P>
<P>
   If Florida State is going to beat Tennessee, the consensus is
that the Seminole defense will be the difference. FSU doesn't
figure to score a lot of points with sophomore Marcus Outzen at
quarterback, and with that defense, Bowden won't take a lot of
chances as long as he has the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, it changes the way you call a game,'' said Bowden. ``You
don't want to do something silly on offense when you've got that
kind of defense.''
</P>
<P>
   And the best is yet to come at Florida State. Seven of the
starting 11 and 15 of the top 22 on defense are scheduled to return
in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth, when we started the season I thought we
were a year away from being pretty good,'' said Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, wait until next year,'' said Simon. ``We'll be a lot
better.''
</P>
<P>
   That should make for a lot of sleepless nights throughout the
ACC.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
