<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5478 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-FULMER03-COX     01-02 1344
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FULMER03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hard-working Fulmer enjoys a breakthrough season
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ Given his surroundings, and given the fact that
Tennessee's Phillip Fulmer is about to coach the biggest game of
his life, he should be a bundle of nerves. That he is not is a
tribute to a man who, at 48, has finally found his comfort zone as
a coach, husband and father.
</P>
<P>
   Were this a year ago, Fulmer would not be smiling as he goes
through his daily media obligations prior to Monday night's Fiesta
Bowl, a game that will likely determine the national championship.
In Fulmer's mind, there would have been no room on the schedule for
grins.
</P>
<P>
   But this week in Tempe, Fulmer has surprised the masses with his
quick wit and his willingness to loosen up and have fun when the
stakes might suggest he behave otherwise. Bottom line, the old
Tennessee lineman is having a ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell you the truth, Coach has been pretty relaxed all year,''
said Tennessee quarterback Tee Martin. ``We didn't expect this trip
to be any different. We're just out here having fun and so is he.''
</P>
<P>
   So what has happened to Fulmer, the man who for seven seasons
drove himself to prove that he belonged at the top of his
profession? Several things.
</P>
<P>
   For one, with two straight SEC championships and Tennessee's
first 12-0 season in 1998, Fulmer has finally proven _ to himself
and others _ that he is a top-drawer coach. For the longest time,
Fulmer endured the rap of being a good recruiter who was destined
to come up short on game day.
</P>
<P>
   But this season, Fulmer did the best coaching job of his career,
beginning with his preparations last spring.
</P>
<P>
   After Tennessee's SEC's championship season of 1997, it seemed
inevitable that the Volunteers would take a step back this fall. In
addition to quarterback Peyton Manning, the Vols were losing other
NFL caliber players such as Terry Fair, Leonard Little, Jonathon
Brown and Marcus Nash.
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer was determined not to let that happen. In the spring, he
challenged his team and his coaches not to use those personnel
losses as an excuse for complacency.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind, there was no reason for this program to drop
back,'' said Fulmer. ``We had recruited well for several years and
had players who had been waiting their turn. I just believed that
if we were willing towork hard enough, it would not happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the loss of Manning and all those NFL draft choices
was liberating to Fulmer. With all those stars gone, he was free to
shape this team into his own image _ a blue-collar, lunch-pail
toting unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach ain't fancy and neither is this team,'' said senior
linebacker Al Wilson. ``This team is more like him than any I've
been on.''
</P>
<P>
   When Tennessee lost running back Jamal Lewis to an injury Oct.
3, Fulmer's doubters were convinced the Volunteers were done _ they
had a ready-made excuse. But it didn't happen because Fulmer
wouldn't let it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Jamal Lewis went down he never wavered, he never
complained. He just simply decided to move on,'' said John Ward,
Tennessee's longtime radio broadcaster. ``He doesn't make excuses
and doesn't want others to do so. I don't know a lot about
football, but that sounds like pretty good coaching to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee went undefeated and Fulmer won his first national
coach of the year honor from the Football Writers Association of
America. It was, said others, validation that had been long in
coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``It meant a lot,'' Fulmer said. ``You always appreciate it when
others recognize the kind of program that we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Secondly, one cannot measure the load lifted off Fulmer's
shoulders on Sept. 19 when Tennessee beat Florida 20-17 in overtime
after five straight losses to the Gators. Despite all his success,
Fulmer's critics said he could not match wits with the likes of
Florida coach Steve Spurrier and was therefore destined to play a
permanent second fiddle to Spurrier the SEC East.
</P>
<P>
   Not fair and not accurate, Fulmer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought it was fair to judge the quality of our
program based on just one game,'' Fulmer said. ``While it's true we
hadn't beaten Florida, a lot of people hadn't beaten Florida. But
that doesn't mean we were bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Fulmer got a reality check at home.
</P>
<P>
   Wife Vicky made him promise last summer to spend a little more
time at home with his three girls, Allison, 12, Brittany, 13, and
Courtney, 15. She felt adding a little more balance to his life
would make him a happier man and would probably make him a better
football coach. She was right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Phillip's happier because after seven years as a head
coach he's found the right formula to do his job,'' Vicky Fulmer
said. ``He knows how to delegate his work so that it all gets done
but it leaves some time for himself and his family. This is the
best year we've ever had, and it's not because we're undefeated.''
</P>
<P>
   Some things, however, have not changed about the new and
improved Phillip Fulmer:
</P>
<P>
   _ He remains incredibly competitive, no matter what he does.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do not want to play pickup basketball against him,''
defensive coordinator John Chavis said. ``Not unless you want to
get pushed around.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I play tennis with him and he can't stand to lose,'' Fulmer's
wife said. ``And if he can't beat you physically, he'll beat you
psychologically.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Guilty,'' Fulmer said. ``I don't like to lose in anything I
do. If I had stayed in law school instead of becoming a coach, I
wouldn't have been happy unless I was the best lawyer around.''
</P>
<P>
   _ In a profession filled with egos, Fulmer has managed to keep
his in check.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phillip knows it's not about him,'' said Anthony Edwards, a
former teammate of Fulmer's. ``It's about the kids and the
university of Tennessee. He's always known that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a lot of ego, but I do have a lot of pride,''
Fulmer said.
</P>
<P>
   _ His work ethic, particularly on the recruiting trail, remains
legendary.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will not outwork him,'' offensive coordinator Randy
Sanders said. ``And when you see the head coach putting in all
those hours, you don't mind doing it yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   _ With players, he has found the perfect combination of
friendship, discipline and tough love. And with that, he has
created a family atmosphere that has become one of the program's
selling points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach will joke around with us, but when he gives you that
look, you know it's all business,'' Wilson said. ``But at the end
of the day, we know he cares about us.''
</P>
<P>
   It would appear that Fulmer, having brought the Tennessee
program to the brink of the school's first national championship
since 1951, is in Knoxville for the long haul. He and his staff are
on the way to another nationally ranked recruiting class, led by
quarterback Chris Simms. Thirty-three of the top 44 players from
this team return next season, with a slew of good redshirt players
no one has even seen.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of what happens in Monday night's game, Fulmer will
go home a contented man, secure in this knowledge: This will be the
first time Tennessee has competed for a national championship under
his watch. But it probably won't be the last.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel good about where the program is and right now. We've
got the commitment to maintain it,'' Fulmer said. ``We're pretty
excited about the future.''
</P>
<P>
   THE PHILLIP FULMER FILE
</P>
<P>
   _ Born: Sept. 1, 1950, in Winchester, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   _ College career: Offensive lineman at the University of
Tennessee, 1968-71.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coaching career: Tennessee, 1972-73; Wichita State, 1974-78;
Vanderbilt, 1979; Tennessee, 1980-91; head coach since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   _ Personal: Wife _ Vicky; children _ Phillip Jr. (28), Courtney
(15), Brittany (13), Allison (12).
</P>
<P>
   _ Head-coaching record:
</P>
