<DOCNO> NYT19990102.0223 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5479 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-KEITHJACKSON03-CO     01-02 2271
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-KEITHJACKSON03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Last call of 'Whoa, Nellie' for old Georgia boy Keith Jackson
 &HT;    By Prentis Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When the final seconds tick off the clock Monday night
at the Fiesta Bowl, the aftermath of the game between Tennessee and
Florida State will be a familiar one: the unbridled joy of victory
in concert with the painful expression of defeat.
</P>
<P>
   The final scene in the ABC booth will be familiar, too. Bright
lights mounted on tall tripods will click off, and headsets will be
laid to rest on table tops in the press box. Except Monday night
will be no ordinary sign-off for ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Although the network will air another national championship game
in 2000, burly linemen will not be called ``big uglies'' and a
fluttering pass won't fall to the ground ``like a wounded goose.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite a 1998 season that has seen Keith Jackson perform as
passionately and colorfully as ever, the dean of ABC's announcers
has stayed the course to retirement. Monday's Fiesta Bowl will go
down as the final call in one of broadcasting's most storied
careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no pressure on me to leave, and nobody forced me
out,'' said Jackson, who did Saturday's Rose Bowl with partner Bob
Griese. ``(ABC Sports president) Steve Bornstein said I could stay
as long as I like. But I've had a good run, and it's time for the
next generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, 70, has regaled college football fans for 31 seasons on
ABC with a folksy, cornpone flair for description that has made him
a television icon. And when Jackson announced this year would be
his last ``Whoa, Nellie,'' fans at every stop on the farewell tour
have leaped at the chance to say thank you.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been modest about it, but when we traveled to college
towns this season, it was Keith everybody wanted to see,'' said Jay
Rothman, Jackson's game producer. ``It was like walking in with the
pope.''
</P>
<P>
   Even fans coming to big, sprawling towns like Atlanta for the
SEC championship nudged each other with elbows so they could turn
and shout their greetings to the man they recognized as the
national voice of college football.
</P>
<P>
   Although Jackson returned their star-struck attention with a
gracious wave of his hand as he weaved his way to the media
entrance of the Georgia Dome, he does not crave such limelight. In
fact, he's downright uncomfortable with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had my druthers, I think I'd have kept my mouth shut,''
said Jackson, who said he does not want any on-air celebrations of
his career when Monday's game is over.
</P>
<P>
   Such modesty about a lifetime of accomplishment comes easily
when it is grounded in a childhood that began on a dirt farm about
eight miles from Carrollton, Ga., and was spent traversing dusty
roads that led to such quaint towns as Tallapoosa, home of his
one-room schoolhouse; Tyus, site of his junior high; and Roopville,
where Jackson attended high school and played on a championship
basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   And when he wasn't traipsing to and from those tiny Georgia
towns, either on foot or horseback, Jackson was at the farm of his
grandparents, Jeff Robison and a family matriarch known
affectionately as ``Aunt Sug.'' Although in Jackson's recollection,
his grandfather ``Old Jeff'' had married the meanest woman he could
find.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Jackson's memory of his grandmother has been flavored by
``Aunt Sug'' telling the family about seeing young Keith in the
fields announcing his imaginary games to the milk cows.
</P>
<P>
   But it was also ``Aunt Sug'' who would spend many an evening
telling stories to young Keith, which, unbeknownst to her, was
laying the foundation for a sportscaster who would grow up to
become one of the best storytellers in the medium of television.
</P>
<P>
   As for ``Old Jeff,'' if people ever wondered why Jackson has
never been moved by the scores of awards and honors for
broadcasting excellence, perhaps it's because he never forgot what
his grandfather said after Jackson came home with a basketball
trophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Son, if you can't eat it, cash it, drink it or sleep with it,
don't worry about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Jackson has lived more than four-fifths of his life on
the West Coast and traveled to 31 countries in covering the wide
world of sports for ABC, he has remained unmistakably true to those
Georgia roots.
</P>
<P>
   However, except for a few distant relatives he brushes off as
``shirt-tail cousins,'' Jackson has only one real tie to his home
state, but it is a close and binding one.
</P>
<P>
   When Jackson's father divorced his mother, Polly, he also chose
inexplicably to sever any kind of a relationship with his son. But
Jackson was not destined to spend the majority of his childhood
without a father figure.
</P>
<P>
   While his mother was working at a Villa Rica hospital, she met a
man named R.C. Bragg toiling in a nearby construction camp. And by
the time Jackson was 9, Polly and R.C. were married.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember her telling me right off that she had a child. And
I said, `Good, now we don't have to worry about having any,''' said
Bragg, who to this day refers to Jackson as being ``home-raised,
hand-spanked and bread-fed.''
</P>
<P>
   In comfortable retirement at 86, Bragg still lives in Bremen,
about 55 miles west of Atlanta. Even when Jackson's mother died in
1989, no amount of urging from his stepson could get him to move
out of the plain, white one-story house near downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Bragg will visit his stepson in Sherman Oaks, Calif., on
occasion and has even been known to join Jackson and his family at
their getaway home in Garden Bay, British Columbia, a place where
many of the upcoming months will be spent now.
</P>
<P>
   But happiness for Bragg these days is to do a little bit of
fishing and a whole lot of lawn-mower repair, one of his favorite
hobbies. Bragg's face lights up when asked to talk about his
stepson, and he welcomes the opportunity to share those
well-preserved pictures of Jackson posing with his basketball
teammates and standing proudly in his cap and gown as a member of
Roopville High's class of '46.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keith used to listen to Red Barber, and he used to tell his
mother, `Someday I'll be as good as Red Barber,''' Bragg said,
while sitting in his yard on a bright, sunny day. ``When he
graduated from high school, he wanted to go to Georgia Tech. But he
couldn't get in Tech. It seemed like everybody was coming out of
the service at that time and was going to Tech. So my advice to him
was to go into the Marine Corps, and the military service would be
a way he could get in.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson took that advice, but never returned to Georgia to
enroll at Tech. Four years of military duty, most notably in China
as an aircraft mechanic, would lead to college at Washington State
in 1950. And while in Pullman, Jackson would come upon the most
important events in his life, both professionally and personally.
</P>
<P>
   The latter would come in the form of a tall, striking blonde of
Norwegian descent named Turi Ann, also a student at Washington
State.
</P>
<P>
   ``We met under a willow tree, and I was a goner,'' Jackson said,
breaking into the cherubic smile of a man who has been happily
married for 46 years.
</P>
<P>
   And on this particular assignment at the Georgia Dome, Turi Ann
has made the trip to Atlanta with him. She has accompanied her
husband on the road often through the years, and one needs to chat
with her for only a few moments to realize she has yet to meet a
stranger. Little wonder Jackson has only first thoughts about
spending more time with his wife and no second thoughts about
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   When Turi Ann comes to the stadium with her husband, Keith
becomes the second-most popular Jackson among his ABC colleagues.
She is especially happy this night because their youngest son,
Christopher, whom she lovingly calls their bonus baby because he
was born 10 years after his siblings Melanie and Lindsey, just
happened to be in town on business and was able to join his parents
for dinner and a ballgame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although Keith has traveled a lot, we've spent a lot of time
with each other, and he always found a lot of time for the kids,''
said Turi Ann, who is the best fisherman in the family, Keith and
Chris both acknowledge. ``But I'm really looking forward to having
him around all the time. The place we have up in Canada is
wonderful. We love it up there, and believe me when I tell you our
days will be filled.''
</P>
<P>
   When they became a couple in love at Washington State, the idea
of a fulfilling life weaved around the world of sports was not part
of the game plan. Jackson was in college to study criminology and
political science.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the only trouble was he kept listening to the games,''
Turi Ann said.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, Washington State was one of the first colleges to
operate its own radio station. Those fledgling broadcasts awakened
the Red Barber childhood dreams that had gone dormant during four
years in the Marines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember lying in the dormitory and thinking, `These guys
aren't all that good,''' Jackson said. ``So I decided to go for it.
A guy by the name of Burt Harrison was in charge. So I walked into
his office, introduced myself and told him, `I betcha I could do a
better job than the people you've got now.' He looked at me kinda
funny, and said, `All right, go record one, and we'll see.' So
that's what I did, and I never looked back.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson began calling football for Washington State in 1952, and
after graduating with honors in broadcasting in1954, he quickly
landed a job as a news anchor at the ABC television affiliate in
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson spent 10 years at KOMO, deftly mixing in play-by-play
work for the University of Washington and Seattle University
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a co-anchor with Herb Robinson, and we were the first
half-hour, two-man newscast,'' Jackson said. ``But we never saw
ourselves as being in show business. We saw ourselves as
journalists who were covering news and sports.''
</P>
<P>
   As time wore on and philosophies changed, Jackson grew
disenchanted with doing local news and took a job with the ABC
Radio Network in 1965, which included covering the NCAA basketball
championship between UCLA and Michigan. For four years, his work in
television was freelance. But all that changed in 1968 when ABC
Sports honcho Roone Arledge and his top producer, Chuck Howard,
needed someone in Seattle to call a parachute-jumping event for
``Wide World of Sports.''
</P>
<P>
   That someone would be Jackson, and ABC Sports would be the last
employer he'd ever have. Jackson will be linked indelibly to
college football, but hockey might be the only sport he never
called. The NBA, the first year of ``Monday Night Football'' in
1970, major-league baseball and the Olympics all are on the resume.
</P>
<P>
   Also on that resume, however, is the one incident that thrust
Jackson into a firestorm of criticism.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1978 Gator Bowl, a national television audience was
stunned when legendary Ohio State coach Woody Hayes punched Clemson
player Charlie Baumann after Baumann intercepted a pass to dash the
Buckeyes' last hope for victory.
</P>
<P>
   Even more shocking was the appearance that Jackson and partner
Ara Parseghian acted as if the punch didn't happen. Charges that he
was trying to cover up for Hayes were leveled at Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson never actually saw the punch from his vantage point
in the booth. And neither were he and Hayes bosom buddies,
especially after the week Hayes was a guest analyst with Jackson
and seemed more interested in plugging his book than commenting on
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``People fail to realize that I didn't get on well with Hayes,''
Jackson said. ``But the fact of the matter is I didn't see (the
punch). There were 143 people on the sideline, and if people go
back and listen, I said, `Let's look at the tape and see what
happened.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But we didn't see the tape because the network was
nickel-and-diming the operation at that time with a bunch of green
kids, and the tape was in New York, which did not feed to us in the
booth. I saw (the punch) for the first time at noon the next day on
NBC. But people took all the shots at me _ even though Ara didn't
see it, my spotter didn't see it, and the producer didn't say
anything about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The punch proved to be the undoing of Hayes' coaching career,
and a lesser talent than Jackson also might not have survived such
an oversight, because of the damage to his credibility.
</P>
<P>
   But survive Jackson did, to the point of being inducted into the
American Sportscaster Hall of Fame in 1994 and the National
Sportscasters &AMP; Sportswriters Association Hall of Fame in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Far more rewarding has been the response of fans and admirers
this year. He has received some token of appreciation at every
stop, from two rocking chairs presented by Penn State coach Joe
Paterno to a personally engraved cowbell from the faithful at
Mississippi State. And the ovation Jackson received from 110,000
fans at Michigan's stadium in Ann Arbor, including the presentation
of a Wolverine helmet by former coach Bo Schembechler, was among
the moments he said he'll never forget.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've kidded him unmercifully about this,'' said analyst Bob
Griese, Jackson's football partner for the last 12 years. ``He's
getting all this stuff, and I've had to tell him, 'What do I look
like, your valet?'
</P>
<P>
   ``All this attention has made him kind of uneasy. But we kept
telling him to enjoy it and have some fun with it. It's just people
wanting to show him how much they appreciate what he has done. He's
a legend, and I don't think there will ever be another one like
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
