<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AFC NOTES: Raven(s) maniacs
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The nucleus of solid young players like offensive tackle
Jonathan Ogden, wide receiver Jermaine Lewis, tailback Priest
Holmes, defensive end Michael McCrary, linebackers Peter Boulware
and Ray Lewis and corner Duane Starks could help Baltimore attract
a quality coaching prospect. But one still has to wonder how owner
Art Modell is running the franchise. Last Sunday night, the Ravens
contacted former San Francisco coach George Seifert about the
coaching job. Three weeks before that, vice president Ozzie Newsome
phoned Oregon coach Mike Bellotti. But on Monday, when they
announced the coaching change, Modell claimed that out of respect
for deposed Ted Marchibroda, the club had made no contacts. Like
everyone else, the Ravens have Mike Holmgren atop their wish list.
A more realistic working list now includes Vikes offensive
coordinator Brian Billick, Steelers defensive coordinator Jim
Haslett, former Eagles defensive chief Emmitt Thomas and Stanford
coach Tyrone Willingham. The team also has sought permission to
interview Jaguars defensive coordinator Dick Jauron. Seifert has
indicated to club officials that he's not interested.
</P>
<P>
   Kordell kaput?
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh management is disenchanted enough with quarterback
Kordell Stewart that the team already has discussed possible
veteran alternatives. Don't be surprised if the Steelers sign a
free agent like Rich Gannon and force Stewart to earn the starting
job. There's talk that, because of off-field problems and friction
with teammates, Stewart could find himself out altogether, just two
seasons after starting the AFC title game. Coach Bill Cowher, whose
ego approximates that of Stewart's, was calling many of the plays
and tutoring the quarterbacks the past few weeks. He could bring in
former San Diego coach Kevin Gilbride or promote tight ends coach
Mike Mularkey to replace Ray Sherman, who resigned Thursday as
coordinator. Cowher has also talked with Chicago quarterbacks coach
Matt Cavanaugh.
</P>
<P>
   Chargers chatter
</P>
<P>
   San Diego coordinator Joe Pascale did a masterful job in 1998,
turning a unit that has only two legitimate stars in linebacker
Junior Seau and strong safety Rodney Harrison, into the NFL's
top-ranked defense. But Pascale may have overplayed his hand last
Tuesday when interviewing with GM Bobby Beathard for the team's
head coach vacancy. Pascale told Beathard that if he wasn't head
coach, he wouldn't return in '99. Beathard wanted to keep the
defensive group of Pascale, line coach Wayne Nunnely, linebackers
coach Jim Vechiarella and secondary coach Rod Perry intact and was
taken aback by the news. He identified Washington coach Norv
Turner, who could bring along defensive boss Mike Nolan, as a
secret candidate. But with John Kent Cooke now likely to retain
ownership of the Redskins, Turner's job probably is safe.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   It probably won't be announced for another week or two, but
Jacksonville coach Tom Coughlin and owner Wayne Weaver finally have
reached a handshake deal on a contract extension. The deal,
expected to pay Coughlin about $2.5 million annually, was hammered
out between the two men after Weaver grew frustrated with agent
Robert Fraley. ... Indianapolis coach Jim Mora, who fired defensive
coordinator Rusty Tillman, probably will hire old friend Vic
Fangio, the former coordinator in Carolina, as his replacement. But
Mora and GM Bill Polian also will keep an eye on what transpires
with Dom Capers. ... Tito PaulSince his contract includes a
stipulation that he can't have a ``franchise'' designation, Oakland
will pay Jeff George
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-02-99 1908EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
