<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990102.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5481 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFCNOTES03-COX     01-02 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFCNOTES03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NFC NOTES: Seifert nearly set
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Assured they will not be considered by Green Bay coach Mike
Holmgren, the Carolina Panthers have settled on former 49ers coach
George Seifert to replace Dom Capers and an agreement could be
consummated by next week. Seifert interviewed Tuesday with owner
Jerry Richardson and, not surprisingly, was impressive. The
Panthers are so convinced of a deal with Seifert that they have
begun assembling a staff. The club retained offensive coordinator
Gill Haskell, tight ends coach Don Breaux and wideouts coach
Richard Williamson from Capers' staff. On Tuesday, Richardson will
interview highly regarded offensive line coach Tony Wise (Chicago)
and quarterbacks coach Bill Musgrave (Philadelphia). Richardson is
taking his cues from Dallas owner Jerry Jones, who played a major
role in assembling a staff for Chan Gailey.
</P>
<P>
   Skins game
</P>
<P>
   Washington president John Kent Cooke likely owes Richardson a
dinner. The Carolina owner played a key role in hooking up Cooke
with NationsBank chief executive Hugh McColl, and the marriage
resulted in a bid of $780 million for the team by the son of late
owner Jack Kent Cooke. The odds are now that Cooke purchases the
team from his father's estate and retains coach Norv Turner and
general manager Charley Casserly. Because the two have been sniping
at each other much of this season, the '99 campaign could be an
interesting one.
</P>
<P>
   Bad news Bears
</P>
<P>
   Chicago president Mike McCaskey ignored the wishes of his top
football men, director of operations Mark Hatley and pro personnel
director Rick Spielman, in dumping coach Dave Wannstedt on Monday.
Then on his way out the door to a ski vacation, McCaskey instructed
Hatley to begin interviewing potential replacements. The zaniness
is simply the latest manifestation of how McCaskey has undermined a
once-proud franchise. The rumors that the club could turn to Hall
of Fame linebacker Mike Singletary, who has no coaching experience,
weren't afforded much credence at first. But because McCaskey needs
to score a public-relations coup with his hire, in part to attract
public support for a new stadium, anything is possible.
</P>
<P>
   Passing the Bucs
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay quarterback Trent Dilfer will be back in '99, but look
for coach Tony Dungy and coordinator Mike Shula to bring in a
veteran to push him. The Bucs feel that part of the reason for
Dilfer's regression is that he didn't feel threatened by backups
Steve Walsh or Scott Milanovich. Also look for Dungy to be much
tougher on his team in training camp next year.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky getting picky
</P>
<P>
   Heisman winner Ricky Williams likely will be the second overall
choice in the '99 draft after Kentucky quarterback Tim Couch. But
the Texas tailback is hinting that he does not want to play for
Philadelphia, which owns the second pick. Williams knows of the
Eagles' poor facilities and owner Jeff Lurie's shallow pockets.
Operations director Tom Modrak may end up having to trade the
choice.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota offensive coordinator Brian Billick, the hottest
assistant in the NFL, likes the situation in Cleveland, where he
interviewed Monday, and is enticed by some of the young players in
Baltimore. But he really hopes to hear from Seattle owner Paul
Allen. Like many, Billick feels the Seahawks are a talented team
that underachieved in recent seasons. ... Former Atlanta personnel
director Ken Herock, of course, drafted tailback Jamal Anderson.
Notable is that Herock, while at Tampa Bay, also drafted James
Wilder, the man whose single-season carries record Anderson broke
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
