<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Where's Butler? A mystery for 49ers
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Lost in the speculation about where San
Francisco coach Steve Mariucci and Green Bay coach Mike Holmgren
might be headed after the season is a ``where'' question on the
game.
</P>
<P>
   It's the ``Where's Waldo?'' of football, with Packers strong
safety LeRoy Butler in the title role. Butler is a player the San
Francisco offensive line can't forget about if the team is to end
its five-game losing streak against the Packers.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the very first play, you have to locate Butler every
snap,'' 49ers quarterback Steve Young said. ``He's the key guy in
most of the creative stuff they do. He'll sneak up close to the
line to play the run. He'll blitz you from the inside or coming off
the edge. If you don't account for him in your (blocking) scheme,
he'll make the big play. You have to pay LeRoy lots of attention.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Packers' 36-22 victory over San Francisco on Nov. 1, the
49ers didn't pay enough attention, and Young paid the price.
</P>
<P>
   Butler sacked Young twice in that game, once on a delayed blitz
up the middle and the other from his slot-safety position. He made
six tackles and had a forced fumble, a pressure and one pass
defensed. More important, he set the tone for one of the worst
beatings _ and poorest performances _ of Young's professional
career.
</P>
<P>
   Young was sacked by Butler on the Niners' first snap of the
game. He was dumped by defensive end Reggie White on the third
play. On his sixth play, Young threw an interception.
</P>
<P>
   He was sacked nine times that day and, while White and fellow
end Vonnie Holliday combined for 5 1/2 of them, Butler was the key.
In the pass-rush game, he is the wild card for coordinator Fritz
Shurmur, who will position the strong safety in as many as six
different spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great run-stuff guy, but as far as pass protection,
it's hard to account for him,'' 49ers center Chris Dalman said.
``You can plan to block him in the running game, but if he's lined
up all over the place against the pass, it's tough. He's kind of
the `hot' guy. We gave up nine sacks that last time we played them,
and everyone said the line didn't block well. But watch film, and
you see they're rushing six people. We can't block two of them at a
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Butler, who has made a big play in each of Green Bay's five wins
over the 49ers since 1995, agrees with that assessment and revels
in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to play cat and mouse with them in terms of where I'll
be,'' he said. ``They have to find me before they can block me,
and, so far, they haven't done it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
