<SLUG> BC-HKN-GOALIES03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Search is on for Thrashers goalie
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Eighteen years ago, an obscure backup goaltender in
Los Angeles named Mario Lessard became the unforeseen centerpiece
on an unforeseen winning team.
</P>
<P>
   Lessard started 64 of 80 games for the second-place Kings, lost
only 18 and proceeded to _ oblivion. He lost the puck, he lost his
confidence, and three years later he was out of hockey.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Jim Carey made the all-rookie team with
Washington in 1995, was honored with the Vezina Trophy as the
league's top goaltender the following year and has de-evolved into
_ a member of the Providence Bruins of the AHL.
</P>
<P>
   More than any other position in hockey, goaltenders lives a
fragile existence. The dramatic decrease in scoring in recent years
actually has increased the pressure on goalies.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came into the league, we were allowed to let a soft one
in and get away with it,'' the recently retired Andy Moog said. ``I
don't know if you can do that now, because the games are so
low-scoring. We could make a mistake and grow up as player. But you
can't do that anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Moog has the job of determining which goalie is most likely
to withstand that pressure. If the goalie has a quick glove hand,
all the better.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Thrashers know that goaltending can make or break an
expansion team comprised of league obscurities next season, so they
hired the four-time All-Star, three-time Stanley Cup winner to
scout NHL backups who might be available in the expansion draft and
amateurs up for grabs in the entry draft.
</P>
<P>
   That Moog retired only six months ago after 18 seasons was key
to the Thrashers' interest in him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives us what I think is an inside person who really knows
a lot about these guys,'' Thrashers general manager Don Waddell
said. ``We need to know what these guys are like away from the ice,
whether they're high-character guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Work habits, the thinking goes, are a direct link to a
goaltender's longevity in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of reasons guys go on roller-coaster rides,''
Moog said. ``I wasn't mature enough to handle things in the NHL. I
got a taste of it when I was 20, but I didn't stick until I was 22.
I didn't realize what it took to stay there. Some guys don't take
the time to learn what it takes to be successful. They don't get
down and analyze their strengths and weaknesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Goaltenders ``don't lose skill overnight, but they lose
confidence,'' Waddell said. ``How is it that a goalie can get a
shutout one night? It's the pressure. A team loses 3-1, and all
people remember is the bad goal that got deflected in and they
blame the goalie. You hardly ever hear people say the forwards
didn't check at center ice.''
</P>
<P>
   Moog, who first was approached about the Thrashers job in
September by assistant general manager Les Jackson, will prepare
scouting reports on the top NHL backups who might be left
unprotected. Anticipating who might be available is difficult,
because some teams might opt to leave a high-salary starter
unprotected, believing that Atlanta would not want to pay his
salary.
</P>
<P>
   One possible example is Dallas, where starter Ed Belfour earns
$3.25 million and has one year left on his contract, while backup
Roman Turek (5-0-2 with a 1.94 goals-against average) is considered
the future of the franchise and makes only $725,000.
</P>
<P>
   Moog said his scouting reports won't be limited to game action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've told Don and Les that if I'm going to analyze someone
completely, I'll have to watch him in practice as well as games.''
</P>
<P>
   Does Moog think other teams will be so accommodating as to let
him watch practice?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' he said. ``I may have to sneak in.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
