</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLEAST03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NHL EAST NOTES: Habs and Hab-nots
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Although rumors throughout Canada have former New
Jersey coach Jacques Lemaire eventually taking over as coach or GM
of the floundering Montreal Canadiens, don't bank on it. Lemaire,
who had been doing some consulting work with the Devils this
season, primarily will assist in player evaluation in his new
position with the Canadiens. That is the job he enjoys most and is
what he did for Montreal before taking the coaching job in New
Jersey. Lemaire has said he has no desire to replace coach Alain
Vigneault. ``I don't want to coach. I don't want any part of
that.'' And neither does he especially relish the responsibilties
that go with being a general manager: making trades, negotiating
contracts, dealing with the media. It's also worth noting that
Lemaire and the Canadiens' maligned general manager, Rejean Houle,
are former teammates and close friends. ``Any decision will be
Rejean's and anything on the ice will be decided by Alain,'' said
Lemaire, who doesn't think that the Canadiens need an overhaul.
``My job is to tell them stuff that might help.'' That said, if
Lemaire contributes to Montreal's turnaround, he could have his
pick of jobs in the NHL. One postscript: Devils GM Lou Lamoriello
would not comment when asked if Montreal will compensate New Jersey
for letting Lemaire out of his contract.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a flyer
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia general manager Bob Clarke, whose future with the
team figures to be linked to this year's playoffs, did not make any
friends in the Flyers' locker room with this week's trade of
defenseman Petr Svoboda to Tampa Bay for defenseman Karl Dykhius.
The 6-foot-3 Dykhius, 26, is two inches taller and six years
younger than Svoboda. But Dykhius's minus-21 plus-minus rating also
ranks worst among NHL defenseman. Svoboda is a plus-five and
popular with his teammates. Eric Lindros waved off reporters when
asked about the deal and walked out of the locker room consoling
Svoboda, who said he was ``shocked.'' Clarke has made 10 roster
changes, nearly half the team, since the Flyers' playoff loss to
Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Your NHL bankruptcy update: Penguins co-owner Roger Marino said
part of the team is for sale and that Mario Lemieux might be a
buyer. Lemieux's interest is not surprising because partial
ownership is one way to lessen the $28 million in deferred salary
he is owed by the organization. Lemieux's stature also could aid
the Penguins' quest for a new arena. ... For a team losing several
million dollars in a half-empty arena, the Carolina Hurricanes took
a huge financial gamble in acquiring defenseman Paul Coffey from
Chicago this week. The 37-year-old, whose contract at $2 million
per year runs through next season, has missed 59 games with
injuries since 1996. Hurricanes general manager Jim Rutherford
needed a point man for his power play _ but Coffey won't help if
he's in the whirlpool. ... Washington was outscored 30-10 in the
first period of its first 31 games, but in Game 32 it took a 3-0
first-period lead against Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
