   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Jan. 2, 1999 -- EDLIFE-MOM, 1-2 -- At the
Melrose Housing Projects in the South Bronx, Patricia James Jordan,
left, talks with Letesha Reese, center, 1995's recipient of the
Juanita James scholarship, and Kanika Brooks, 1998's winner.
``Though she died more than 13 years ago, my mother is still having
an influence on the youth of the neighborhood through the
scholarship fund,'' says Ms. Jordan, who set up the college fund in
honor of her mother. (Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 2, 1999 -- IMPEACH-LOTT, 1-2 -- Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott, right, has consulted with many of his
colleagues, including Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., left, as the
Senate prepares to take up the articles of impeachment against
President Clinton. Conservative Republicans, of which he is one,
are pushing Lott to hold a full trial, with testimony from
witnesses, followed by a vote on the articles of impeachment. Many
of them disapprove of censuring Clinton. (Stephen Crowley/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Jan. 2, 1999 -- COLUMBIA-COUPLE-CANCER, 1-2
-- Mike Sardo, 27, who has a rare case of cancer in the spine, with
his fiancee, Kathleen Johnson, 27, at his parents home in Long
Island. Despite Sardo's illness, and constant work and distance
related conflicts, the Columbia University graduates and college
sports stars have always found laughter to be the main ingredient
in their life together. ``It's the way we get through the tough
days and nights,'' says Johnson. (Lois Raimondo/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Jan. 2, 1999 -- JOHNSON-DESCENDANT, 1-2 --
Thomas C. Colt III, 63, one of 10 living decendants of Andrew
Johnson, makes his living delivering pizza and selling hardware at
Sears. Colt has made a thorough study of his ancestor's
impeachment, and though he is a great-great-great grandson of a
president, even an impeached one, he does not blame his ancestor's
history for his own modest station. ``Don't do anything unless it's
worth doing, and by 'worth' I don't mean money,'' he says. (Mike
Peters/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NORTH ADAMS, Mass. -- Jan. 2, 1999 --
MASS-RURAL-INTERNET-2, 1-2 -- Brett McDowell, left, the new
Massachusetts Museum of Contemporary Art's director of information
and media technology, with Jeff Kleiser, president of
Kleiser-Walczak Construction, a film special-effects and animation
company. The cost of Internet connections concerns MASS MoCA, which
aims to be a ``creative campus'' with an emphasis on the
intersection of art and technology. (Keith Meyers/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NORTH ADAMS, Mass. -- Jan. 2, 1999 --
MASS-RURAL-INTERNET-1, 1-2 -- The cost of Internet connections
concerns the Massachusetts Museum of Contemporary Art, a mammoth
museum scheduled to open its first phase in May in North Adams. The
museum will offer performing arts as well as exhibitions, and aims
to be a ``creative campus'' with an emphasis on the intersection of
art and technology. (Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Jan. 2, 1999 -- NY-MARITIME-RELICS-3, 1-2 --
Peter Eagleton, 61, a retired ship broker, sketching the remains of
a diesel tug boat in New York Harbor. ``This harbor holds a whole
century of American maritime architecture and ship types. Once a
ship is finished, it's like a biography,'' says Eagleton. ``She's
been all over the world or the local harbor. To paint one is like
painting a story.'' (Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Jan. 2, 1999 -- NY-MARITIME-RELICS-2, 1-2 --
The timeworn pilothouses of a tugboat and a railroad barge are
among the wrecks at the Witte marine salvage yard off Staten
Island. Ships of every description lie in the yard, some rusted so
thoroughly that their iron decks are as thin and weak as old
cardboard. The boats contain no treasure, but to a small group of
maritime historians and archeologists, they represent a trove of
information about the days when New York was the biggest seaport in
the world. (Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Jan. 2, 1999 -- NY-MARITIME-RELICS-1, 1-2 --
A kayaker glides through the remenants of an old steam tugboat in
the Arthur Kill along Mariners Harbor, Staten Island. Hundreds of
similar relics, many of them deemed historically significant, dot
the New York Waterfront. The U.S. Army Corps of Engineers, which is
responsible for keeping channels clear, has drawn up a list of 75
historic vessels to be studied and salvaged before all the hulks
are cleared to prevent drifting timbers from threatening passing
ships. (Keith Meyers/New Yokr Times Photo)
</P>
