<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-IMPEACH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUESTIONS ON CLINTON TO TEST SENATORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Facing one of the most burdensome New Year's
resolutions in history, the Senate reconvenes this week with eight
new members, a new House of Representatives next door, and,
according to some, a renewed sense of worry over the upcoming trial
to decide whether President Clinton will be removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   It has been 15 days since the House impeached Clinton. In that
time, no one has suggested the same hard-driving impetus exists in
the Senate, where 67 votes would be necessary to convict, and where
a bipartisan compromise plan to speed up the trial process has been
under examination by Democratic and Republican leaders for the last
week.
</P>
<P>
   But neither has Clinton's fate been resolved. From the
logistical questions _ such as when the House will vote to fund the
managers who prosecute the trial _ to the broad questions of
whether the trial must be conducted in full, few in the Senate are
equipped with answers, or even solid predictions, about how the new
political season will unfold.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a tremendous number of unknowns,'' said Richard
Fenno, a political science professor at the University of
Rochester. ``Basically, you've got a lot of inexperience
confronting a very bizarre and unique situation. There are as many
computations and permutations as one could imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   With so many unknown factors, including what strategy the White
House will pursue, the only certainty is that a campaign of
lobbying and public opinion-swapping will unfold Sunday and in the
days to follow, congressional aides said.
</P>
<P>
   During the holidays, with senators relying on news reports and
scattered phone conversations to determine where others stand, no
one has truly been able to gauge the potential for compromise.
</P>
<P>
   According to two Democratic Senate aides, who declined to be
identified, both parties plan to meet behind closed doors in the
Capitol Wednesday morning to air their views on the bipartisan plan
for a speedy trial, which was co-designed by Democratic Senator
Joseph I. Lieberman of Connecticut and Republican Senator Slade
Gorton of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday, the Senate could be summoning Supreme Court Chief
Justice William H. Rehnquist to be sworn in to preside over the
proceedings. And by Jan. 11, some form of a trial could be ready to
begin.
</P>
<P>
   Hypothetical scenarios have been floated since the days before
Christmas, prompting varying responses on both sides, including
last-minute New Year's Eve objections and dozens of
senator-to-senator phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Lieberman-Gorton plan, which has been floated by
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi with the support
of Minority Leader Thomas A. Daschle of South Dakota, the whole
process could take less than two weeks. The Senate would hold what
amounts to a preliminary court hearing, listening to abbreviated
evidence, but no witness testimony, before voting on whether to
hold a trial at all.
</P>
<P>
   Under this proposal, a full-blown trial would proceed only if 67
senators voted for it. If there were not enough support, the trial
proceedings would stop, and the Senate would start considering
whether to censure Clinton instead.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, designed to placate members who see no point in
dragging out a trial in which conviction is out of the question,
has received unified support from Democratic senators, the two
aides said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   But it has come under attack from conservative senators, who
believe the Constitution mandates a full hearing of all the
evidence against the president.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Mike DeWine, a Republican from Ohio, objected to the
shortcut, warning that ``denied the closure of a trial . . .
censure would not end the civic ugliness in which we are currently
mired.'' Others, including New Hampshire Senator Robert C. Smith,
have also forsworn any form of censure, saying a trial is equipped
to determine guilt or innocence, not anything in between.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Clinton's tenure in office seemingly secured, the
fates of senators on both sides, particularly that of Lott, are
especially delicate as they begin to navigate the debate.
</P>
<P>
   Already, a House speaker and a speaker-designate have become
casualties of the congressional impeachment proceedings. According
to Fenno, whether Lott is in danger of following in the path of
Representatives Newt Gingrich and Robert Livingston will be
determined by his ability to ``work across the aisle, to do
something bipartisan.''
</P>
<P>
   And according to another Senate Democratic aide, Lott's
challenge, compromising with his conservative flank and the
Democrats, could threaten his own career.
</P>
<P>
   Although the number of senators publicly committed to raising
roadblocks is relatively small, there are ``people in both parties
who are not afraid to mix it up,'' the aide said, adding: ``And
Lott has seen what that's done to the House. I don't think he wants
that in the Senate, because he doesn't want to destroy himself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
