<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-COACHES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COACHES GET SIMILAR RESULTS WITH DIFFERENT STYLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
  TEMPE, Ariz. _ The coaches stepped up on temporary podiums set up
in Sun Devil Stadium at Fiesta Bowl media day last week.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Florida State's Bobby Bowden told stories. Lots of stories.
Funny stories. Old stories that had been recycled. New stories
tailored for the occasion. Football? Oh sure, that was part of it.
But it wasn't really necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee's Phil Fulmer talked about football. He talked about
defenses. He talked about special teams. Gradually the crowd of
reporters faded away, blitzed no doubt by the unrelenting package
of Xs and Os.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a question was asked about the difference between the
folksy Bowden and the no-nonsense Fulmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to get into a story-telling contest with
Bobby,'' said Fulmer with a smile. ``But that does not have
anything to do with the ballgame, does it?''
</P>
<P>
   No it doesn't. When the Fiesta Bowl finally is played Monday
night between No. 1 Tennessee and No. 2 Florida State, either
Bowden will walk away with his second national championship in six
seasons or Fulmer will trot away with his first.
</P>
<P>
   How they tell stories doesn't matter, but both have stories to
tell, stories that are about success, hard work, and overcoming
obstacles that would, and have, stopped other coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   He grew in Winchester, Tenn., watching football. Particularly
college football, and, of course, Tennessee football. ``Someday,''
Phil Fulmer told his mother, ``that will be me.''
</P>
<P>
   Nan Fulmer thought that was nice. Her son wanted to be a
football player. ``No,'' said Phil Fulmer, pointing to the sideline
and the coaches walking with headsets. ``That's what I'm going to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, Fulmer did the football thing for a while. He was a star in
high school and became a captain at Tennessee before moving on to
his boyhood ambition: coaching.
</P>
<P>
   At 48, he's near the top of his profession. Still, it seems,
until this season at least, he has done it in a vacuum. Even last
week he did his business with little fanfare. At media day, as
Tennessee began an hour-long interview session, a Fiesta Bowl
volunteer asked, ``Which one is Fulmer?''
</P>
<P>
   How is this possible? The man has been in the Top 10 the past
four seasons and has the best winning percentage among active
coaches in Division 1-A (.857).
</P>
<P>
   Not winning the SEC East was a problem. Not beating Florida was
another criticism that kept haunting him. This season, the
Volunteers took care of both.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Fulmer is Coach of the Year. He's smarter. Amazing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't worry about it,'' said Fulmer, when asked about the
perception of him. ``I don't read the papers. I don't listen to the
talk shows. I get around friends who I can tell to shut up if I
need to.''
</P>
<P>
   That does not lessen the intensity he feels. He's one of those
dawn-to-dawn coaches who spends more hours in his office during the
season than he does at home.
</P>
<P>
   But he also has a sense of family values. On Wednesdays and
Thursdays, he comes home in the early evening and spends time with
his wife, Vicky, and daughters Courtney, Brittany, and Allison.
``We do family things,'' he said. ``If my daughters have something
going on at school on those nights, I can see them. It's important.
Of course, after dinner, I might get on the phone and make some
recruiting calls.''
</P>
<P>
   All of it has helped in making Fulmer more than just someone who
took over for long-time Volunteers coach Johnny Majors in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's his own coach. Since taking over his alma mater, he's
won 66 of 77 games. He can go into any living room in the country
and talk about Tennessee football and people will listen. His
latest coup was getting a verbal commitment from blue chip
quarterback Chris Simms, the son of former Giants Pro Bowl QB Phil
Simms.
</P>
<P>
   There have been bumps along the road. Not being able to win the
SEC East because of the dominance of Florida under Steve Spurrier
had bothered him. And the rift with his one-time mentor Majors,
caused because Majors felt he was forced out of Tennessee before he
wanted (a situation in which he believed Fulmer may have been a bit
too opportunistic), cause him to tune out any questioner.
</P>
<P>
   But he also is getting some credit for what he is doing. Fulmer
says he has learned on the job. ``I hope I'm getting better at
seeing the big picture,'' he says. ``You learn a lot as you go
through this.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Bowden listened to the question with a grin and a nod of
the head, knowing it was coming. ``Bobby, you're 69. If you beat
Tennessee, will you think about retiring?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Never,'' he said. ``What would I do? Stay home and pull weeds.
As long as I've got my good health, I'll still coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden has been coaching in some capacity since he came out of
Samford University in 1953. He has seen fire and rain and times
when he couldn't find a friend.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he still loves it. Still likes the roar of the crowd, the
feeling he gets on game days. Sure, he's more of a CEO than a
hands-on coach these days, taking naps in the afternoons and
letting his coordinators put in game plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't mean he's not involved,'' said offensive
coordinator Mark Richt. ``He watches what we do. He goes around,
takes notes, and then at staff meetings he'll go over things he
sees that bother him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden even will call some plays, although Richt said he has
learned to distinguish between requests and suggestions. ``I say,
`Coach, are you suggesting we do this or are you saying that's what
you want?''' said Richt.
</P>
<P>
   Richt said most of the ``suggestions'' come when the Seminoles
are near the goal line. ``He likes to call touchdowns,'' said Richt
with laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden's success is unquestioned. He has 292 career victories,
12 consecutive years of 10-win seasons, of Top 5 finishes in the
polls.
</P>
<P>
   The success has set the bar of expectations high, with some
people grumbling that the Seminoles have won only one national
championship. ``A lot of people are thinking, `Golly, they have
been at least No. 4 in the nation the last 11 years and haven't won
but one national championship,''' said Bowden. ``That doesn't
bother me one bit. I can keep my job if I stay No. 4. I'm scared to
try No. 5.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden has changed with the times. When he first started he was
more general than grandfather, more inclined to get in people's
faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first year of coaching was back in '53,'' Bowden said.
``Back then you didn't explain. You said, `Go do it.' If a player
asked why, you said, `Get out of here.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you need to tell players why you are doing things and why
it will benefit them.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning the first national championship in 1993 released some of
the pressure that had been building. ``It was a feeling of relief
more than anything,'' Bowden said. ``It was, `Thank goodness. I
finally got that off my back.' Now they say, `How about No. 2?'''
</P>
<P>
   Football has been what Bobby Bowden does. Three of his four sons
have joined the profession. Tommy is the new coach at Clemson,
having taken Tulane to an unbeaten regular season before switching
to the Tigers. Terry coached at Auburn before resigning in the
middle of this season. Jeff is an assistant on Bobby's staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been our life,'' said Jeff Bowden, who also says Bobby
has softened over the years. ``When he first started, players would
fear him,'' he said. ``He has mellowed out. The kids have not seen
a side of him the way he was 30 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years ago, Bobby Bowden was one of those hot-shot young
coaches, looking around for a place to build a reputation. He began
building it at West Virginia, where he was 42-26, but they still
hung him in effigy. He came to Florida State in 1976 and began
building again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wherever I've coached, I've been an underdog,'' Bowden was
saying. ``At West Virginia I was always in the shadow of Penn State
and Pitt. At Florida State it was Florida, Alabama, and Auburn.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Bowden nor Phil Fulmer is in the shadows any longer, nor
is either an underdog.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, come Monday night, one of these two good ol' boys from
the South is fixing to become Top Dog.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-02-99 1948EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
