u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-JAGUARS-BOSELLI-B     01-02 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JAGUARS-BOSELLI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSELLI ALWAYS READY FOR HIS CLOSE-UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ Tony Boselli sits by his locker, willing
to take on all comers.
</P>
<P>
   The Jacksonville offensive tackle listens to all questions,
answers all questions, and usually in an insightful manner. Even
when a media member asks about the spotlight that is on him in all
games, a spotlight not often reserved for an offensive tackle.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much do you like it when they always have a camera
isolated on you,'' Boselli is asked, ``and they're looking to see
how you're doing against John Randle, Bruce Smith, Jason Taylor and
...''
</P>
<P>
   ``... and all those guys,'' Boselli replied with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   Right.
</P>
<P>
   All those guys.
</P>
<P>
   All those huge defensive linemen or linebackers, usually the
best defensive lineman, all intent on scorching past Boselli to
wreak havoc on the Jaguars' quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like it,'' Boselli says.
</P>
<P>
   And why not? Ever since Boselli devastated Buffalo's Bruce Smith
in Jacksonville's first-ever playoff game (a victory) two years
ago, and when he was first noticed by the football throngs beyond
the banks of the St. Johns River here, the spotlight has been on
him every game. The warfare between the offensive and defensive
lines in football always is mano-a-mano but this is so different;
this is television mano-a-mano and so the hype only grows and
grows.
</P>
<P>
   Not since John Hannah played for the Patriots has an offensive
lineman garnered so much TV time, but even that was in a more
subdued era. Now, TV is in excess mode, so it shows Tony Boselli
against The World.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like going against the best,'' Boselli says. All players do,
but Boselli truly believes it, and often proves it, as he will try
to do this afternoon when he goes against the Patriots and Willie
McGinest, his former teammate at Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is, I know Willie's moves from all the time we
practiced together in college,'' said Boselli. ``And I know Willie
is very good. I know that personally. But the other thing is I'm
not going to be going only against Willie all the time _ they move
him around _ and the other guys the Patriots have, Chris Slade and
(Ferric) Collons and all of them, they're very good, too.''
</P>
<P>
   But Boselli can be a gentleman football player, too, taking
pains to note that this Willie McGinest who will show up Sunday is
not the same Willie McGinest he played against last season or two
years ago in the AFC Championship game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Willie is a great pass rusher and a great defensive end when
he's 100 percent,'' said Boselli. ``I know he's nicked up now but I
also know him, that he'll turn it up and that he's the type of guy
who'll be huge in the playoffs. Willie's a guy you definitely have
to watch out for, to be aware of him at all times to make sure you
block him.''
</P>
<P>
   Boselli did not devastate McGinest in any of the three games
they have played against each other and, indeed, McGinest may have
gotten the better of Boselli in the AFC title game two seasons ago.
Only partisans of the Jaguars or Patriots would argue that either
was dominant; a standoff might be the best description. Of course,
when playing against Boselli, a standoff can be considered a
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Willie's pass rush is improved from college,'' said Boselli,
``in that he's able to do it a lot, but Willie has always been a
very athletic and physical player. He's a guy who likes to play
football and play hard.''
</P>
<P>
   As does Boselli.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monday Night Football'' fans can remember Boselli pointing at
Taylor, Miami's very quick defensive lineman, after Jacksonville
had made a big play, pointing at Taylor to get downfield and into
position so Boselli could get after him again. Boselli not only
taunted Taylor but embarrassed him on the field. Just as he had
done to the Chiefs' Derrick Thomas and many others.
</P>
<P>
   And Jaguar fans can recall how Boselli chased after Cincinnati's
Artrell Hawkins, who had recovered a fumble and was running toward
the goal line. But Boselli chased down Hawkins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen 330 pounds move that fast,'' said Jacksonville
quarterback Mark Brunell. ``What can I say? It saved a touchdown.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins, it must be noted, is a cornerback and, said Jaguars
coach Tom Coughlin, ``You're looking at a legitimate corner in the
league who had the opportunity to go all the way. Tony really
showed his athleticism and quickness and made the tackle.''
</P>
<P>
   So Boselli deserves the attention he receives, and his role will
be huge Sunday as he and his linemates may bear the burden of the
Jacksonville offense with Brunell less than 100 percent. The line
will have to open holes for running back Fred Taylor and, in
passing situations, keep McGinest and pals away from the
qurterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things get built up in the media,'' said Boselli, ``and
everyone wants to try their hand. If a guy beats me, hats off to
him. But if he beats me because I've done something mentally or
physically stupid, that's what bothers me.''
</P>
<P>
   So pay close attention to Boselli and McGinest Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Willie is a good, good defensive end,'' said Boselli, ``a guy
you have to block. You have to know where Willie is at all times
because he can cause problems.''
</P>
<P>
   And the very same words can be said of Tony Boselli.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
