<HEADLINE>
LEAFING THROUGH THE HISTORY BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the minds of Bruins fans, the closing of Maple Leaf Gardens
doesn't rank with the cathartic demise of the Montreal Forum (crank
to full volume here on the Hallelujah Chorus), but on Saturday
night, the Bruins will take their last skate in the historic
Toronto barn.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins and Leafs, two of the NHL's Original Six, will play
out their future matches in the Air Canada Centre, leaving in
darkness yet one more of the old, huggable, august buildings that
were once as much a part of the league's fabric as horsehair goalie
pads.
</P>
<P>
   Oh say, can I still hear the national anthem resonating, the
organ churning, in Chicago Stadium? Please, book me a seat on that
time machine and dial back the calendar, oh, I don't care, 10 years
will suffice. No hockey setting in the world could surpass the
stage that was the Stadium, especially the first five minutes of
play that dovetailed out of the emotional high of the anthem.
</P>
<P>
   Here in the '90s we've witnessed the closing of Boston Garden,
Chicago Stadium, the Forum and now the Gardens. True, the game
isn't about girders. But so much history surrendered so fast, so
many memories cashiered in the name of luxury suites and
mega-mess-ageboards, leaves a thumb print of abandonment and sad,
sad loss.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most vivid Bruins-Leafs memory for Boston fans is
the spring of '69 when Boston wiped out Toronto in a four-game
playoff bloodbath. The Bruins opened the series with their first
postseason victory in 10 years, a humiliating 10-0 pounding on
Causeway Street, followed the next night by a 7-0 hammering.
</P>
<P>
   Who could forget the pulverizing elbow Leafs defenseman Pat
Quinn KO'd Bobby Orr with in Game 1? Toronto's Forbes Kennedy, an
ex-Bruin tough guy, fought everything but the Zamboni, battling
first with Gerry Cheevers and eventually being beaten into
submission by Johnny McKenzie. Before he exited, the crazed Kennedy
even felled linesman George Ashley with a menacing left hand.
Imagine how that would play today in front of league disciplinarian
Colin ``Collar 'em'' Campbell. Fire up the electric chair. (It
turned out to be the 34-year-old Kennedy's last NHL game, anyway.)
</P>
<P>
   After a day off, the series moved to the Gardens, where the
Bruins delivered 4-3 and 3-2 knockout punches on successive nights.
It took 11 years, a few buckets of blood, and a trip to 60 Carlton
Street, but the Bruins made it to Round 2 of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins' most humiliating night in the Gardens came some
seven years later, Feb. 7, 1976, when Darryl Sittler torched them
for a record-setting 10 points (6 goals, 4 assists) in an
embarrassing 11-4 loss. Former University of Vermont netminder Dave
Reece suffered the beating between the pipes. Toronto lore has it
that Reece was being showcased for a potential trade that night.
There would be no trade. It was the last NHL game Reece would play.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Former Bruins coach  &UR; Brian Sutter  &LR; brings his Flames into town
Monday night. Calgary has struggled of late, mostly because of a
lengthy list of injuries to its goalies _  &UR; Ken Wregget  &LR; (back),
 &UR; Tyler Moss  &LR; (groin), and  &UR; Jean-Sebastien Giguere  &LR; (hamstring). The
Flames were forced to bring back  &UR; Andrei Trefilov  &LR; as a stopgap,
but it looks like lean times until Wregget gets back in shape. The
subplot still to be worked out: what to do with  &UR; Theo Fleury &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who
becomes a free agent July 1. Right now, he's due about $6 million a
year _ more than double his 1998-99 salary. Calgary is a small
market, much like Buffalo, and prudent economics would dictate a
deal that brings younger, cheaper talent. But even Buffalo forked
over the big money for one superstar,  &UR; Dominik Hasek &LR; , who will
collect a minimum of $23.5 million over three years, and if Fleury
is gone, the Saddledome could look like Greensboro West ... When
Sabres owner  &UR; John Rigas  &LR; popped Hasek and wife aboard a private
jet for a trip to the Mayo Clinic (Hasek's wife needed back
surgery), the 74-year-old cable-TV mogul jumped aboard for the
ride. Fully in the spirit of things, Rigas also underwent an
angioplasty while at the Minnesota hospital. Synergy, what every
club owner is looking for here at the dawn of the next millennium,
right? ... OK, I'm ready; when is  &UR; Dmitri Kvartalnov  &LR; coming back?
... First goal scored at Maple Leaf Gardens by a Montreal Canadien:
 &UR; Aurel Joliat &LR; , &UR;  &LR; Nov. 14, 1931. Last goal scored there by a member
of the Habs:  &UR; Stephane Quintal &LR; , &UR;  &LR; Dec. 26, 1998. Joliat made it to
the Hall of Fame. Quintal's enshrinement is, well, shall we say,
pending? ``But I'll always be a very good trivia answer,'' he said
... Edmonton's  &UR; Doug Weight &LR; , &UR;  &LR; when asked by Canadian television
what books he's read recently, said he prefers fiction, but never
seems able to get past the first seven chapters of whatever he's
reading. When the team flight ends, the book gets closed. ``I've
got some books I started eight years ago,'' said Weight. ``I can't
wait to see how they end when my career's over.'' ... The recent
hire of  &UR; Jacques Lemaire  &LR; in Montreal buys some time with the fans
for club president  &UR; Ron Corey  &LR; and GM  &UR; Rejean Houle &LR; , &UR;  &LR; but
ultimately Lemaire will replace Houle _ perhaps even before the end
of the season. Lemaire can tell talent, but at times underestimated
it during his days as Devils coach (witness the revived  &UR; Bobby
Holik  &LR; at Exit 16W). The single most important thing a front office
must be able to do is tell who can play and who can't (Wheat From
Chaff 101). Once the money men in Montreal figure that out, Lemaire
will get his chance to call all the shots ... Ex-Bruin  &UR; Andy Moog
 &LR; said in this space a few weeks back that he'd like to be a
goaltending consultant for an NHL club, just the job  &UR; Reggie
Lemelin  &LR; has with the Flyers. In case you missed it, Moog landed
the job with Atlanta last week, which means he will be front and
center at the Fleet June 25 when the Thrashers make their
selections in the expansion draft ... The Bruins ended 1998 with
four losses in five games, their only victory coming over the
Nashville Neophytes. Unless something happens to solidify a second
line _ i.e.  &UR; Joe Thornton  &LR; takes control, one of the Baby B's grows
up, or a trade is made _ you're going to see some more stretches of
.200 hockey. Until there's a real threat presented by a second
line, other teams' two or three best checkers most nights can
handle  &UR; Sergei Samsonov &LR; , &UR; Dmitri Khristich &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Jason Allison &LR; 
... Florida coach  &UR; Terry Murray  &LR; on defenseman  &UR; Ed Jovanovski &LR; :
``He's in his fourth year in the league now. Once you get in your
third year, you have to start getting better.'' And the point is,
Jova-novski leveled off early in his second year, which is why
you're going to hear his name in more trade rumors from now until
the March 23 deadline ... Ottawa GM  &UR; Rick Dudley  &LR; figures goal
scoring could be helped by increasing the net size by about 10
percent, from 24 to 26.388 square feet, adding 4 inches to the
width and 2 inches to the height. ``They've tried everything
else,'' said Dudley. A better idea: Leave the net alone but don't
allow penalized teams to clear the puck during man-short
situations, and have players serve the full two minutes of
penalties even if the other team scores ... In Pittsburgh, where
money is a problem these days, this greeting was on the Igloo
messageboard: ``Hope your holiday spending hasn't left you, shall
we say, bankrupt.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The cracked rib  &UR; Keith Tkachuk  &LR; suffered last week vs. Los
Angeles will keep him out at least three weeks. ``I was hit in the
exact same spot last year,'' said the Phoe-nix power forward. ``I
knew it right away.'' This time, Tkachuk wants to come back when
the crack is mended, which means he won't be pulling on one of
those flak jackets. Fellow Bostonian  &UR; Jeremy Roenick &LR; , &UR;  &LR; sidelined
by a concussion, should be out of the Phoenix lineup at least
through this week ...  &UR; Paul Kariya's  &LR; $8.5 million-a-year contract
in Anaheim is up at the end of the season. Where does that bidding
begin? The guess here: eight years, $100 million. And when that
deal's done, he'll be 32 years old, an unrestricted free agent
finally able to make real money ... The closest anyone has come to
Sittler's record since '76:  &UR; Tom Bladon  &LR; (Philadelphia),  &UR; Bryan
Trottier  &LR; (Islanders),  &UR; Peter Stastny  &LR; (Quebec),  &UR; Anton Stastny
 &LR; (Quebec),  &UR; Wayne Gretzky  &LR; (Edmonton),  &UR; Paul Coffey  &LR; (Edmonton),
 &UR; Mario Lemieux  &LR; (Pittsburgh), and  &UR; Bernie Nicholls  &LR; (Los Angeles)
all had 8-point games. Gretzky and Lemieux, in fact, twice tallied
8 points in a game. No one in NHL history has finished a game with
9 points ... Nice touch by Devils coach  &UR; Robbie Ftorek &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who makes
a point of personally handing the players their paychecks every two
weeks. Playing postman didn't do much for  &UR; Kevin Costner's  &LR; career,
but something's working for Ftorek, and maybe there is some
accountability built when the boss literally hands you the dough
... One theory around Pittsburgh has it that Lemieux will end up
owning part of the team, but not in a partnership with  &UR; Roger
Marino  &LR; (The two weren't exactly seen clinking champagne glasses
Thursday night). Interesting scenario, because Mario Magnifique
then would be the owner in charge of paying himself the millions he
is due in deferred money. Hey, if nothing else, maybe Fox can make
a 13-week sitcom out of it ...  &UR; Stephane Richer  &LR; says his
surgically repaired ankle is still hurting. Lightning doctors say
they can't figure it. It's reminiscent, says Lightning GM/coach
 &UR; Jacques Demers &LR; , &UR;  &LR; of injury episodes Richer lived through in
Montreal and New Jersey. Translation: a huge lack of trust between
the parties. Richer has some $5 million coming his way over the
next 2 1/2 years. The Bruins owe  &UR; Jim Carey  &LR; approximately another
$4 million through next season. Anyone else out there see some swap
possibilities? It appears the only value the Bruins see in Carey
right now is that he is a goalie they can expose in the expansion
draft, but no one wants to touch him at that price ... Two of the
reasons the Red Wings are faltering a bit:  &UR; Uwe Krupp's  &LR; bad back
and  &UR; Jamie Macoun's  &LR; rotator cuff injury. That's why the Winged
Wheels went out and picked up 33-year-old  &UR; Todd Gill  &LR; off waivers
from St. Louis ... Tampa Bay center  &UR; Chris Gratton  &LR; said he didn't
spit on referee  &UR; Paul Stewart &LR; , &UR;  &LR; but concedes maybe he ``sprayed''
him during an on-ice fracas. Sounds almost Clintonesque (well, it
depends what your definition of spit is). Collar-'em Campbell's
definition was a three-game suspension ... The Avalanche still
can't settle the nickels and dimes with holdout defenseman  &UR; Sandis
Ozolinsh &LR; . Until they do, the Colorado power play isn't going
anywhere, and their playoff hopes are headed in the same direction
... Look for the NHL not to have any of its clubs in the air Dec.
31, 1999, or the next day, because of the anticipated Year 2000
computer meltdown. The schedule-maker might slate games that night,
but only if destinations can be reached via ground transportation
... Phoenix defenseman  &UR; Oleg Tverdovsky  &LR; (once billed as the
Russian Bobby Orr) needled some of his teammates recently when they
griped about the lack of hot water in the club's hotel in Detroit.
The former Soviet Wing went without hot water for a whole year when
he played at the Sports Academy in Moscow. ``And it snowed in the
room and on the bed,'' said Tverdovsky. Must have been murder on
the Godiva chocolates the maid left every night.
</P>
