<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-JAGUARS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAME PLAN: A MATTER OF FOCUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ If there are as many mixed signals in
Sunday's game plan as there have been about Pete Carroll's future
with the Patriots, there might not be any future for the team this
season.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots coach and owner Robert Kraft had a long phone
conversation Friday in which they discussed the recent report that
Carroll had to win Sunday's wild-card game against the Jaguars to
retain his job.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Carroll nor the Krafts were happy to see stories of the
coach's possible ouster on the eve of their playoff opener, which
the Patriots go into without Drew Bledsoe and Terry Glenn on
offense and Ted Johnson and Todd Collins on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been very consistent in our comments throughout this
season,'' said Patriots vice president Jonathan Kraft, who denied
that Carroll's future will be decided by Sunday's outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've said that everyone gets evaluated at the end of the
season. How can you make an evaluation on anything before the
season is even over? Pete has done a lot of good things and he's
had to overcome a lot this year. I like Pete Carroll very much and
it bothers me that this is happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be Robert Kraft who makes the decisions on the team at
the end of the year and nobody else.''
</P>
<P>
   The Krafts' policy has been not to discuss Carroll's future.
Repeatedly, Robert Kraft has been asked by national and local
outlets whether Carroll would be his coach next season and each
time he has shied away from a direct answer.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Kraft said Saturday that the team's policy is not to
issue votes of confidence because if they did, then the public
would expect one every year. Red Sox CEO John Harrington began a
practice of issuing them to his managers over the years, but they
became a kiss of death as managers were fired.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Kraft also clarified reports that his father angrily
dashed into Carroll's office after the loss to the Jets a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robert just went in to shake his hand, wish him a Happy New
Year, and caught a plane back to Puerto Rico where we were
vacationing,'' said Jonathan.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll attempted to distance himself from the stories this past
week, but there's no doubt they have created tension. For the past
several weeks, Carroll had been discussing future personnel moves
and other team-related matters with Kraft, which is an indication
that he is staying around.
</P>
<P>
   But some comments by a few veteran players have been damaging to
the coach, and even if those players are in the minority, every bad
word has an effect.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Patriots head into Sunday's game with a sense of
bonding and purpose after the embarrassment of the 31-10 loss in
the regular-season finale. Veteran players have tried to rally the
troops toward a common goal. Two weeks ago, the Patriots responded
well after a horrible showing against the Rams _ a loss that seems
as responsible as last week's for Carroll's current predicament _
with a big win against the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   It is that rebound that gives Carroll and the team hope, for the
Jaguars are not the Jets (and they may not even be the 49ers). New
England is 3-0 all-time against the Jaguars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can beat Jacksonville,'' Bledsoe said this past week.
``There are matchups we can definitely exploit and that we have in
the past.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars have pretty much kept the same personnel over the
past couple of years, though rookie Fred Taylor has made all the
difference in the running game this season and taken considerable
pressure off quarterback Mark Brunell.
</P>
<P>
   There are two key names for the Patriots Sunday: Robert Edwards
and Willie McGinest.
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars' defense knows that if they shut down Edwards,
they've shut down the Patriots' offense for the day. And if
McGinest can't get after Brunell by fighting off tackle Tony
Boselli, then Brunell, though limited in mobility by a sore left
ankle, could pick apart the Patriots as a pocket passer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
