<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5502 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-CARROLL-     01-02 3076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-CARROLL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARROLL MUST TAKE CHARGE OR TAKE OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ I am conflicted this morning as the sun
rises over the sawgrass, for this is no place for a head coach to
expire.
</P>
<P>
   Not here, among the swamps and the mosquitos and the golf
courses. But, frankly, that is what Pete Carroll faces Sunday. If
his team plays as it did a week ago at the Meadowlands and loses
badly to the Jaguars, he loses more than a game. He loses the keys
to his Jaguar.
</P>
<P>
   If Pete's Patriots lie down, he is finished and deservedly so,
injuries or no injuries, because what happened last week against
the Jets cannot be tolerated. If it is repeated, no explanation
will be acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   If they do not lie down, however, Carroll will likely survive to
coach another day in New England unless being forced to move to
Hartford has taken away all sense of fairness from team owner Bob
Kraft.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll's track record _ two straight playoff appearances and a
19-13 won-lost mark _ cries out for another chance because of the
massive injuries his team has been forced to cope with the past two
years and because his mandate is to reach the playoffs and he has
fulfilled it. Yet doubts about his approach persist, fueled more by
his players' reaction to him than anything external.
</P>
<P>
   There is a growing sense of chaos in his locker room and on the
sideline, and not simply among a few isolated veterans as some
observers of the scene wanted you to believe this past week (was
rookie fullback Chris Floyd heard cursing out his coaches last
weekend on the sideline in New York, as someone whispered?).
</P>
<P>
   Doubt about Carroll is loose in his locker room, not just
lurking in the corners of a few players' minds. It is widespread
and growing, and it is in the minds of the Eagle Scouts as well as
those he perceives as malcontents, and he must find a way to stop
it. The only way is to accept what he seems to abhor. The only way
is to become his players' boss and not their favorite uncle.
</P>
<P>
   When Willie McGinest said last week that no one fears coming to
work after a loss, it was a far worse indictment of the Carroll
regime than Chris Slade's generalized talk of being ``outplayed,
outcoached, out-everythinged'' in New York. Yet it was Slade
Carroll chose to confront, not McGinest.
</P>
<P>
   If Carroll doesn't realize that McGinest's words were more
damning, he will never succeed as a head coach. If he does realize
it, then it is time for him to change his mode of operation, and
Kraft would be fair to demand as much.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean he has to turn into a tyrant. He doesn't need
to become a svelte version of Bill Parcells, because what works for
Parcells wouldn't work for most coaches, least of all Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll should forget about Parcells. He also should forget
about the 49ers' model he so often talks about because (A) he has
no exemplary superstar veterans like Jerry Rice and Steve Young in
his locker room to lead his young players where their coaches want
them to go and (B) he doesn't seem to understand that the backbone
of the 49er Way was not the light contact at practice. It was quite
the opposite of that and everyone who played there understood it.
</P>
<P>
   The backbone of the 49er Way, as former club president Carmen
Policy once described it to me, was, ``You win here or you die.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no tolerance for failure in San Francisco. No
tolerance for those who did not prepare to win.
</P>
<P>
   That's why even Charles Haley was eventually run out of there;
he became more trouble than he was worth even though he was still
one of the greatest pass rushers in the game, as he went on to
prove in Dallas. Compare that with Carroll's decision to start
Chris Canty at cornerback four days after Canty was busted while
asleep in a parking lot for having an open container of alcohol in
his car _ at 2:20 a.m., six hours before he was to have been at the
stadium for a special teams meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Did Carroll need to come out the next day and rant and rave
about Canty to the media? No. Did he need to belittle him, as
Parcells surely would have? Absolutely not. What he needed to do
was show Canty and everyone else on his team who controls access to
the field and how quickly it can be denied. He did not, and that
irked many of his players and worried others.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll didn't need to make Canty disappear. He did need to
discipline him by denying him what a player wants most _ a start.
When asked about this a week later, Carroll said, ``We've got
injuries everywhere. What am I supposed to do?''
</P>
<P>
   What you're supposed to do is run the place, and that means
making lonely decisions and unpopular ones. It demands that you
spend more time alone than with anyone else, particularly your
footsoldiers. They are not the coach's friends, as the Patriots
proved once again with the debacle in the Meadowlands. If you are
the leader, they are your enemy, whether they mean to be or not,
because few of them want to do what is required for victory. Few of
them want to sacrifice themselves.
</P>
<P>
   That is human nature, and the leader must understand that. Being
a leader demands that you play mind games with players, as Bill
Walsh did for so many seasons with one of the greatest quarterbacks
of all time, Joe Montana, and as Parcells does and Mike Shanahan
does and Mike Holmgren does and Jimmy Johnson does and all the best
of them do.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to do it the 49er Way, then do it the 49er Way. But
remember this. There was a lot more to the 49er Way than brie and
chablis. There was always, always, The Threat. The coaches felt it
from the owner and the players felt it from first Walsh and then
George Seifert.
</P>
<P>
   ``You win or you die.''
</P>
<P>
   They felt it the same way Parcells made the Giants and then the
Patriots and now the Jets feel it, although his outward method was
different. Nobody feels that way in Foxborough now.
</P>
<P>
   If Kraft has come to the opinion Carroll cannot or will not do
what he needs to do, then the owner has no choice but to act
because to delay only puts his team's future in further jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   But this cannot be a decision based on the humiliation Kraft and
his family felt a week ago at the Meadowlands when their Great
Satan, Parcells, destroyed their team again. It cannot be a
decision based on ``I thought we'd be better than this,'' because
the fact is without all of the injuries, they probably would be
better.
</P>
<P>
   A change should only be made if Kraft believes he is hiring
someone better than the coach he has. If he can hire Bill Belichick
away from the Jets, fine. That is addition by subtraction, because
Parcells has never done as well without Belichick on his staff as
he's done with him.
</P>
<P>
   If Kraft believes one of the hot young assistants like
Minnesota's Brian Billick or Pittsburgh's Jim Haslett, or fired
former Coaches of the Year Ray Rhodes or Dom Capers are better,
then he is justified in making a move.
</P>
<P>
   But if he believes Carroll can realize his deficiencies in
leadership before it's too late and change them, then Carroll
deserves another year because he is correct when he says over and
over, ``There's more than one way to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   There is more than one way to coach a team in the NFL. But there
is only one way to control a locker room, and that's for everyone
in it to understand who is in charge.
</P>
<P>
   If you are, don't change the schedule during the week after it's
been announced.
</P>
<P>
   If you are, don't show up late when you tell your players to be
on time.
</P>
<P>
   If you are, make your decisions quickly and then live with the
consequences, and that includes decisions made on the sideline,
because having too many men on the field (or too few) is the
coach's fault. That penalty is a galling insult to a coach and it
has happened far too many times during the Carroll regime to be an
accident.
</P>
<P>
   If you are in charge, don't listen to what your players say to
you, watch what they do for you.
</P>
<P>
   If you are in charge, be less understanding and more demanding.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, do not let them lie down on you Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Not if you want to be back Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Now that another regular season has come to an end, it's time to
pick an All-Pro team. Here is the way the ballot that came to this
address was filled out:
</P>
<P>
   QUARTERBACK:  &UR; Randall Cunningham &LR; , Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   If you deliver 34 touchdown passes, complete 60 percent of your
throws, lead the league in passing, come off the bench at age 35 to
lead your team to a 15-1 record and you aren't the best
quarterback, you need to try another line of work.
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING BACK:  &UR; Terrell Davis &LR; , Denver.
</P>
<P>
   It is always easy to simply pencil in  &UR; Barry Sanders's  &LR; name and
be done with it, but Davis became only the fourth guy in history to
rush for over 2,000 yards (2,008). Add to that 21 rushing
touchdowns (23 total) and a 5.1-yards-per-carry average that was
topped by nobody in the league, and the case for Davis is
overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   FULLBACK:  &UR; Sam Gash &LR; , Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   You ever see this guy block?
</P>
<P>
   TIGHT END:  &UR; Ben Coates &LR; , New England.
</P>
<P>
   This may seem like a hometown choice until you look at the
facts. He is the most marked man in the Patriots' receiving corps,
especially after Terry Glenn went down. Yet he led the team with 67
receptions and scored six times. Since he also blocks, that's more
than enough. And please don't bring up  &UR; Shannon Sharpe &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who is a
wide receiver in a tight end's body.
</P>
<P>
   WIDE RECEIVERS:  &UR; Antonio Freeman &LR; , Green Bay, &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Randy Moss &LR; ,
Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   It is tempting to write in  &UR; Jerry Rice  &LR; and whomever, but even
though Rice had 82 catches for 1,157 yards (14.1 yards a catch),
his numbers pale when compared with Moss's and Freeman's. Moss had
10 touchdown catches of 43 yards or longer, scored 17 touchdowns,
and averaged 19 yards per reception. Rookie or no rookie, he
destroyed the league. As for Freeman, he carried the Packers much
of the season, finishing with 14 touchdowns and a league-leading
1,424 yards. If you produce the most yards and more touchdowns than
all but one other receiver, you're one of the best. When you do it
in the mud and ice of Green Bay, you're one of the very best.
</P>
<P>
   TACKLES:  &UR; Tony Boselli &LR; , Jacksonville, &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Jonathan Ogden &LR; ,
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Boselli is simply the best young tackle in the game. He can run
block, pass block and trash talk. That about covers it. Ogden is
big, strong, mobile, and may be as good as Boselli, but it's tough
to notice that because his team stinks.
</P>
<P>
   GUARDS:  &UR; Kevin Donnalley &LR; , Miami, &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Will Shields &LR; , Kansas
City.
</P>
<P>
   Donnalley was imported to bring a running game to Miami. He
didn't quite pull that off, but only because the guys around him
can't block the way he can. People who get blocked by Shields say
he is still one of the best.
</P>
<P>
   CENTER:  &UR; Dermontti Dawson &LR; , Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Some will lobby for the Vikings'  &UR; Jeff Christy  &LR; or maybe the
Jets'  &UR; Kevin Mawae &LR; . Off one season, they may even deserve it. But
until someone proves otherwise to me, Dawson gets the meritorious
service award. Besides, he's still the best anyway.
</P>
<P>
   DEFENSIVE ENDS:  &UR; Reggie White &LR; , Green Bay, &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Michael
Sinclair &LR; , Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   White's 16 sacks may be as remarkable a feat as any produced
this season after the terrible back problems he faced a year ago.
White nearly retired; now people are begging him to stay, which is
the way to go out. Sinclair not only led the NFL with 16 1/2 sacks
but has 41 1/2 over the past three years, the most in the league.
What more does the Seahawks' designated quarterback killer have to
do?
</P>
<P>
   DEFENSIVE TACKLES:  &UR; Darrell Russell &LR; , Oakland, &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Bryant
Young &LR; , San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Russell has gone from rookie bust to sophomore bust-out. His 10
sacks made him a force and his overall play helped the Raider
defensive resurgence in a big way. If you don't think Young is
among the very best interior linemen, you haven't been watching the
49ers struggle without him. By the way, if you pencil in
Minnesota's  &UR; John Randle  &LR; over either of these guys, I can't really
argue with you.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE LINEBACKER:  &UR; Levon Kirkland &LR; , Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   He can still do more things better than anyone else playing the
position.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE LINEBACKER:  &UR; Ray Lewis &LR; , Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   When you keep leading the league in tackles playing the position
at which you're supposed to lead the league in tackles, doesn't
that end the debate?
</P>
<P>
   OUTSIDE LINEBACKERS:  &UR; Mo Lewis &LR; , NY Jets, &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Bill
Romanowski &LR; , Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis is the spiritual leader of the Jets' defense. He's also
their leading sack man and is second in tackles. Romanowski serves
many roles with the Broncos and is a marked man because so many
opponents hate his take-no-prisoners approach. Yet he covers
downfield, makes big plays, is tough against the run despite a lack
of size, and seems to be around the ball whenever there's a key
moment.
</P>
<P>
   CORNERBACKS:  &UR; Ty Law &LR; , New England, &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Shawn Springs &LR; ,
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Law has been asking for two years to cover the best receivers,
and now he's doing it. He led the league with nine interceptions
and that's a miracle since teams often had no interest in throwing
his way. When they did, he showed why it's a bad idea. Springs
barely noses out Miami's  &UR; Sam Madison &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who had one more
interception than Springs's seven. But Springs brought two back for
scores, which nearly offset the three he gave up.
</P>
<P>
   (By the way, when  &UR; Deion Sanders's  &LR; toe heals, he's back at the
head of this list.)
</P>
<P>
   STRONG SAFETY:  &UR; Rodney Harrison &LR; , San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   The Chargers had the league's best defense, and Harrison was all
over it. He led the team in tackles (which frankly isn't usually a
good sign, he being a safety), and had four sacks and three
interceptions. If there was anything else he could do for them,
they just should have just asked.
</P>
<P>
   FREE SAFETY:  &UR; Sammy Knight &LR; , New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   It's logical to pick Denver's  &UR; Steve Atwater &LR; , but Knight
intercepted six passes, recovered two fumbles, and also scored
twice. Free safeties are supposed to make plays. Tell me who made
more than he did this season.
</P>
<P>
   KICKER:  &UR; Gary Anderson &LR; , &UR;  &LR; Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   When you become the first kicker to go all season without a miss
and you set a record for kickers with 164 points, that just about
rules out anybody else, don't you think?
</P>
<P>
   PUNTER:  &UR; Craig Hentrich &LR; , &UR;  &LR; Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   The league's first million-dollar punter showed why he has
earned that distinction. He led the NFL in gross (47.2) and net
yards (39.2).
</P>
<P>
   KICK RETURNER:  &UR; Terry Fair &LR; , &UR;  &LR; Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   He had nearly 1,500 yards in returns, had the best average in
the league at 28 per return, and took two from coast to coast.
</P>
<P>
   PUNT RETURNER: Sanders, Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore's  &UR; Jermaine Lewis  &LR; is the consensus choice if you look
at all the All-Pro lists, but Sanders outdid him in every category.
Sanders's toe injury cut his season short, but he returned 24 punts
for a 15.6-yard average and two scores while Lewis didn't even lead
his conference, averaging 12.7 yards a return and scoring twice.
Sanders did more and did it more explosively, sore toe or not.
</P>
<P>
   There also are postseason honors to be voted on:
</P>
<P>
   COACH OF THE YEAR: Parcells, Jets.
</P>
<P>
   He took a team from 1-15 to 12-4 in two years. Shanahan deserves
a lot of credit for keeping the Broncos focused most of the season
coming off a Super Bowl victory, which may be one of the toughest
jobs in football. But nothing is tougher than winning in December
if you coach the Jets, and Parcells did it.
</P>
<P>
   ROOKIE OF THE YEAR:  &UR; Fred Taylor &LR; , Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   That is not a misprint. Sure, Moss scored 17 touchdowns, but so
did Taylor and he did it on a far weaker team. Taylor also rushed
for 1,223 yards and was fourth in the AFC in total yards from
scrimmage with 1,644. Moss had the benefit of playing on a team
with a multitude of weapons ( &UR; Cris Carter &LR; , &UR;  &LR; Cunningham,  &UR; Robert
Smith &LR; , &UR; Jake Reed &LR; ), so he was not the center of attention,
especially early in the season. Taylor was, especially once the
Jaguars were hit by injuries. Think what Taylor's numbers might
have been had he been starting all season.
</P>
<P>
   OFFENSIVE PLAYER OF THE YEAR: Davis.
</P>
<P>
   He carried the Broncos the way  &UR; John Elway  &LR; used to, even when
defenses were massed to stop him. It's difficult to ignore
Atlanta's  &UR; Jamal Anderson  &LR; because without his 1,846 yards and 14
rushing touchdowns  &UR; Dan Reeves  &LR; might have had chest pains a lot
sooner than he did in Atlanta. But who can deny that the Broncos
would be nowhere without Davis?
</P>
<P>
   DEFENSIVE PLAYER OF THE YEAR: White.
</P>
<P>
   The Minister of Defense had his best season since 1988 only
months after he said he was retired because his back had become too
painful to cope with. Once the season began, White was too much for
opponents to cope with.
</P>
<P>
   COMEBACK PLAYER OF THE YEAR:  &UR; Doug Flutie &LR; , Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham and  &UR; Vinny Testaverde  &LR; are strong candidates, but
they didn't have to come back through Customs. At 35, Flutie
silenced his critics with a remarkable season after taking over for
injured  &UR; Rob Johnson &LR; . The backup who wouldn't stay back finished
fifth in the NFL in passing, threw 20 TD passes, and completed 57.1
percent of his attempts while taking a team no one expected much
from into the playoffs after an 0-3 start. Think what he might do
if he just wasn't too small to play in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Got any arguments?
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Patriots defensive tackle  &UR; Henry Thomas  &LR; says he has no second
thoughts about leaving Minnesota even though the Vikings went 15-1
without him this year. Thomas played eight years in Minnesota, and
many of his former teammates are still there, and Thomas is happy
for them. ``All that stuff they're doing up there, I created,''
Thomas joked. ``I gotta get my credit somehow.'' The real credit
belongs to head coach  &UR; Dennis Green &LR; , &UR;  &LR; according to Thomas. ``He
consistently set the standards for what he wanted and it's paid
off,'' Thomas said. ``I see Dennis's mentality on the Vikings team.
I feel great excitement for all my friends I played with but I'm
not disappointed not to be there. I'm a Patriot now. I went in
another direction.'' ... Before Denver fans get too excited about
next weekend's home playoff game in Mile High Stadium, they should
consider this: The AFC's No. 1 seed hasn't won a playoff game the
last three years and hasn't reached the Super Bowl in four. The
Chiefs lost in 1995 and 1997 and the Broncos lost in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
