<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-HAMED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAMED STOPS FIGHT OVER CONTRACT DISPUTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first casualty on American soil has been sustained in the
battle for control of British-born World Boxing Organization
featherweight champion Prince Naseem Hamed: It is his planned March
6 return to a US boxing ring.
</P>
<P>
   Hamed will not fight as scheduled on HBO that night, and it
could be months before he reappears in the United States because in
the power struggle for control of his business future, it has not
yet been determined who will survive and who will perish from his
camp.
</P>
<P>
   That is what so often seems to happen when a young slugger
suddenly gains exposure to American fighting dollars _ 12 million
of them, to be exact. British promoter Frank Warren signed Hamed,
24, to a six-fight, $12 million dollar deal last year with HBO, one
that was preceded by a multimillion-dollar contract with SKY-TV,
the English equivalent of HBO, and therein began Hamed's problems.
</P>
<P>
   A spectacular American debut in Madison Square Garden a year ago
_ a knockout of former world champion Kevin Kelley _ was followed
this past Halloween by a miserable performance in Atlantic City in
his second HBO appearance, and things quickly fell apart around
Hamed, as they had been threatening to do for months.
</P>
<P>
   Hamed's eldest brother, Riath, took out a promoter's license,
and soon thereafter Warren was jettisoned. With him went trainer
Brendan Ingle, who had discovered Hamed at the age of 7 and
nurtured him. Hamed had been feuding with him ever since Ingle was
quoted in a book by a British journalist last year calling his
fighter a spoiled brat, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Ingle was beginning to feel himself being pushed to
the side by Hamed's growing celebrity and tightly knit family, and
he did not react well. When Hamed got into the ring in Atlantic
City on Oct. 31, it was painfully clear that he was not mentally
focused to fight or to listen to Ingle, steadfastly refusing to
look at him or acknowledge his advice between rounds.
</P>
<P>
   When the debacle was over, Hamed was ripped by the British media
for winning a lackluster, 12-round decision from Wayne McCullough,
and he returned fire. Soon Warren was out and Hamed's brother was
telling HBO the contract was invalid because it had been signed by
Warren, not the fighter.
</P>
<P>
   Hamed's problem is one that often crops up in boxing: He doesn't
like his end of the take now that he's a star, even though he knows
he wouldn't be in this position were it not for his connection with
HBO in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Before Hamed came to HBO, this Yemeni grocer's son had a bit of
a punch, bad pants, and seemed a bit of a buffoon with his absurd
entrances and weak list of opponents. HBO pumped $8 million into
promoting him, putting up huge billboards around New York and
showcasing him first at Madison Square Garden and then in Atlantic
City. By the time it was done, Hamed had become a cultural
phenomenon. He drew ratings as large as some of HBO's biggest draws
_ Oscar De La Hoya, Roy Jones, Lennox Lewis _ and wanted to be paid
like them even though his promoter had agreed to a long-term deal.
</P>
<P>
   So now Hamed's brother is quietly trying to renegotiate and HBO
is amenable in large part because Time-Warner Sports president Seth
Abraham has long espoused a philosophy that it is unwise to sign
fighters who don't want to fight for him.
</P>
<P>
   Since it seems clear to both sides that Hamed probably didn't
know the terms of the deal Warren signed, it's likely that a
shorter deal will be worked out. But there are other problems that
may be more knotty.
</P>
<P>
   First, SKY-TV wants Hamed on prime time in England when he
fights, and it signed him first. HBO wants him on prime time in the
US, and it signed him for more money. There is five hours
difference between prime time in the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   HBO ultimately may agree to a short-term deal and then see where
things go, knowing that Hamed has caught the interest of sheiks
with deep pockets, because of his Arab background, and renegades
within the boxing business who would love to cherry-pick him off
the vine.
</P>
<P>
   Even if HBO and Hamed can iron out their dispute this month, he
has no trainer at the moment, because Ingle sided with Warren, and
no experienced promoter. Considering that Riath is a former
community liaison officer in Sheffield and his other brother was
working as an auto mechanic when the Prince's career began, they
are incapable of filling the trainer's role and are novices in the
promotional one.
</P>
<P>
   The result is that Hamed's career has ground to a temporary halt
just as it began to take off. The British media is sick of him, and
he has disappeared in the US.
</P>
<P>
   What Hamed's family is trying to do is noble enough in that they
want to protect him from the sharks who fill boxing's seas, and
they understand that remaining a promotional free agent is the best
way to do so. But to argue that they don't have a valid contract
with the cable network that did the most to turn Hamed from a local
hero into a multimillionaire seems an unwise business practice.
</P>
<P>
   HBO believes it can work out a new deal that will be amenable to
Hamed and still protect the rights it received when it started
paying him $2 million a fight. Hamed's brother reportedly has been
a reasonable negotiator, carefully avoiding public condemnation of
HBO.
</P>
<P>
   The Prince should pray that this works out, because if it
doesn't, he may enter the ring for his next fight in America with
Janis Joplin singing, ``Freedom's just another word for nothing
left to lose,'' in the background.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   HBO is hoping to replace Hamed's appearance with a world title
fight for Olympic gold medalist  &UR; David Reid  &LR; (11-0) against World
Boxing Association junior mid-dleweight champion  &UR; Laurent Boudouani
 &LR; (38-2-1) on a card that would also include a rematch between
 &UR; Miguel Angel Gonzalez  &LR; and  &UR; Kosta Tszyu &LR;  ... As expected, Dec. 23
came and went and  &UR; George Foreman  &LR; and  &UR; Larry Holmes  &LR; did not
receive the letters of credit they were due to insure their Jan. 23
fight in Houston's Astrodome. Thus the Battle of the Aged died last
week not with a bang but a whimper, and boxing is the better for
it. The fight's scrambling promoter,  &UR; Roger Levitt &LR; , &UR;  &LR; continued to
the end to insist the bout would come off. ``All the financial
arrangements that need to be put in place will be done so,'' he
insisted early in the week. Foreman and Holmes extended by a week
their deadline for receiving letters of credit of $9 million and
$3.6 million, respectively, but it didn't help Levitt, whose major
backer pulled out two weeks ago. So the two fighters collected
advances of $1 million and $400,000, respectively, without getting
hit. Once  &UR; Mike Tyson  &LR; decided to resume his career the weekend
before Foreman-Holmes, the bout was in big trouble. Instead of
being the off-week entertainment between the NFL's conference
championship games and the Super Bowl, Foreman-Holmes found itself
sandwiched between two mega-events, Tyson's return and the Super
Bowl, and that was a pending pay-per-view disaster that had to be
avoided ... Anybody notice that highly rated but lightly skilled
 &UR; Jade Scott  &LR; lost to journeyman  &UR; Melvin Foster  &LR; a week ago? As one
boxing insider said, ``That tells you all you need to know about
the ratings.'' In other words, they mean nothing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
