<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5505 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-JACKSONVILLE-THOM     01-02 1354
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JACKSONVILLE-THOMAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOMAS NOT ON HIS LAST LEGS LEFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ For nearly two months now, Henry Thomas has
defied one of the most basic axioms. Each Sunday the 33-year-old
former All-Pro defensive tackle has run before he could walk.
</P>
<P>
   Mothers have warned their children against this. Fathers have
counseled their rash sons against it while using the phrase in
different contexts. Obviously, none of them ever met Henry Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Thomas smashed up his ankle on Nov. 1 against the
Indianapolis Colts, he has spent six days a week barely able to
walk across the locker room and the seventh running around like a
wild man while 300-pound enemies try to knock him off his feet.
More than half that time, he was running when he literally couldn't
walk.
</P>
<P>
   It is not an easy thing to do; even Thomas understands that. The
former LSU communications major knows his ankle was not meant to do
what he has been asking of it. It was not meant to support his
277-pound body and propel it around a football field while others
roll on top of it. Not when it is swollen to the size of a
grapefruit, badly discolored, and thoroughly reluctant to even let
him shuffle along on weekdays.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas knows this, but he also knows no one wants to hear it.
Not from a pro football player. No one cares how you feel; it's all
about how you play. And, in some cases, if you play.
</P>
<P>
   On Sundays, Thomas believes, you play unless doctors are
standing between you and the field. If he didn't think that way, he
would have been on disability leave a long time ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a warrior,'' said Patriots linebacker Chris Slade, who
likewise played much of the season with a severe ankle sprain.
``He's the true definition of a football player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Henry can barely walk, but guys still can't block him when
he's on one leg. He's tough as nails. Any player, at any age, can
learn from him. He's well established in this league. He's been
here 12 years. But he's out there every day fighting for his job.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll be out there this afternoon, fighting the Jacksonville
Jaguars for the chance to beat up his ankle for at least another
weekend in the playoffs because that is how he has approached his
job since he arrived in the NFL in 1987 and became an immediate
sensation. Success has changed nothing for Henry Thomas but his
bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Early glory
</P>
<P>
   In his early days, Thomas combined with Keith Millard to form a
combination that terrorized quarterbacks from the inside rush
position in Minnesota. When Millard's body began to give out from
doing the kind of things Thomas is doing today, Thomas joined young
John Randle and continued to do the same things, just with a louder
partner.
</P>
<P>
   Twice Thomas went to the Pro Bowl and several more times he
should have. In 1994, for example, he and Randle combined for 20
1/2 sacks, the highest total in the league for a tackle tandem.
Thomas had 8 1/2 of them but Randle had a few more sacks and a lot
more loud conversations with anyone who would listen, so he went to
Hawaii while Thomas went home.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings were so enthralled with Thomas, however, that they
made him _ a defensive tackle, remember _ their transition player
one season and their franchise player the next. Then they did what
a lot of teams have done with guys like Thomas. They made a
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring of 1995, the Vikings took the franchise
designation off him and let him enter free agency. A few months
later, he was the Detroit Lions' defensive MVP after registering
the most sacks of his career, 10 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   That was the most by a Lion since Mike Cofer had a dozen in
1988, and they were instrumental in propelling Detroit into the
playoffs. But then injuries began to hit Thomas, and the Lions
began to worry about him.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas suffered through most of 1996 with a nagging groin pull
and was not the same player he had been, especially in the second
half of the season as his injury worsened. The Lions decided that
his slump to only two sacks in the final eight games of the season
(after registering four in the first six before his injury) was a
sign that Thomas was finished, and they let him go.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas was damaged goods, they said, past his prime at 31.
Perhaps that was true when compared with the guy who terrorized
teams in his early years with the Vikings, but as he has shown for
two seasons in New England, that didn't mean he couldn't still rush
past an offensive lineman and make plays.
</P>
<P>
   The plays have been different from the ones he once was noted
for, even though he has 13 1/2 sacks in his two seasons here. That
is just about on pace with his career average of 7, but Thomas has
made his presence felt most on the goal line and in short-yardage
situations, those moments when everyone is digging in and a bad
ankle isn't as much of a traitor to you as it is when you try to
rush the quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   He has made no concessions to his balky ankle, but a veteran
makes adjustments to the vagaries of his game, and so Thomas does
what he can when the quarterback is in retreat and the rest of the
time he does the grunt work that has made him the team's leading
tackler among defensive linemen despite having to do it with a
limp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I can still do those things I did before, but I've
been nursing this nagging ankle for eight weeks,'' Thomas conceded.
``It's not that I'm not trying to do the things I did in Minnesota.
I'm trying to make those things happen, but I know my role in this
defense and it's a little different.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that I'm not trying to get to the quarterback. It
just looks like I'm not. Trust me. I'm trying. But the way things
have turned out, a lot of my plays have come on goal-line and
short-yardage. It's disappointing to finish with only 6 1/2 sacks,
but I still think I'm a pretty good nose tackle.''
</P>
<P>
   A different feeling
</P>
<P>
   When Thomas dives low and then rises up and drives a guard or
center backward or slashes between two men trying to knock him
backward and upends a running back silly enough to think he is
going to get a first down through the heart of New England's
defense, he makes that point. Henry Thomas is indeed still a pretty
good nose tackle.
</P>
<P>
   But just as important _ as he'll show again Sunday when he
throws away his crutches, takes his ``treatment'' in the form of a
needle or two of pain killers, and goes out to play _ he is still a
football player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do this because I love to play football,'' Thomas said.
``When I first came into the league I played with Doug Martin and
he showed me the ropes. His last season, he played with a really
bad shoulder. It bothered him all week but not in the games. I just
thought that's how everybody did it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess that attitude all comes from my father. He owned a
restaurant for 17 years. He was there every day at 5 a.m. and
didn't come home until 8 p.m. I never remember him being sick.''
</P>
<P>
   No one playing with Thomas will be able to say anything
different about him. Yet he knows the difference in him these past
eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   He knows he hasn't been playing his game his way. Knowing that
is harder to swallow than knowing about the pain that awaits him
every Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the field, I don't notice it, but when I'm watching myself
on film and I see a move I couldn't make that I would have used
before to get free, it's heart-wrenching,'' Thomas said. ``In this
situation I'm in, you have to rely on your teammates to protect you
when you can't change direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a quick guy. That's my game. Sometimes I'll be watching
film and see me make a great move and then see that I couldn't
counter the lineman's response with another one and it gets
depressing. When it does, I put a little more ice on my ankle. But,
no, I never doubted I'd be there every week.''
</P>
<P>
   And so he has been. And so he will be Sunday. And if things go
well and the Patriots surprise Jacksonville, he will be there next
week. In Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Running, whether he can walk or not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
