</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT WILD ABOUT THEIR PROSPECTS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ Bob Kraft will show up looking as though he
just beat George Hamilton in the International Tanning Festival in
Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Bledsoe will stand on the sideline, holding a clipboard,
wearing a headset and a beard.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Carroll _ who appears to be little more than a smarter,
drug-free Butch Hobson _ will perform his ``Boola Boola'' routine,
looking over his shoulder for smoke signals from Kraft's luxury
box.
</P>
<P>
   And after a tumultuous week that was downright Red Soxian, the
Patriots Sunday will play a wild-card game against the Jacksonville
Jaguars in Alltel Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Yeesh. Jacksonville. This place makes Hartford look like Rio de
Janeiro.
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville. Is this where it ends? Or do we make that trek to
Denver and watch the Patriots get routed again by the Broncos next
Saturday?
</P>
<P>
   In the greatest movie of all time, ``Butch Cassidy and the
Sundance Kid,'' it was sheriff Ray Bledsoe (honest) who told Butch
and the Kid, ``You're gonna die bloody and all you can do is choose
where.''
</P>
<P>
   So where will it be, fellas? Here or Denver? And what happens to
Carroll when the Patriots finally end this season of the witch?
</P>
<P>
   Carroll's employment status has become the trendy story line of
Wild Card Week, which says something about him and something about
the town in which he works.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the state of the media situation,'' he said calmly last
week. ``It's ongoing about people's jobs. It's difficult to deal
with it, but you have to understand the nature of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Foxborough was not a laugh riot in the week after the Jets loss.
Unless you cite any Red Sox postseason of the last decade, it would
be difficult to find another playoff team in deeper turmoil than
Sunday's Patriots. In the wake of the New York mugging, the
playoff-bound Patriots were asked about dissension, injuries,
quitting, and firings.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll was decent about everything. When he was asked about his
job security after Bloody Monday (when five NFL head coaches got
the ax), he turned the question back to the media and asked how we
would feel if five of our brethren lost their jobs. When the
assembled reporters expressed no sympathy, Carroll laughed. By the
end of the week, there was no laughter. A proverbial ``inside
source'' (is that you, Jonathan?) was leaking Carroll rumors to
gossip columnists and the coach said he would entertain no more
questions on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   He may be gone. And it may be unfair. But can people stop
bragging about Pete because he got this team into the playoffs two
years in a row? It's like the Washington Post celebrating being
named one of America's top 10 newspapers. It's insulting. Carroll
inherited a young Super Bowl team. Making the playoffs was supposed
to be a given. He was hired to take the Patriots deep into the
postseason. Nothing less.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, this playoff ride lacks all the good feeling usually
associated with postseason ball. It feels a little like 1990 when
the Red Sox won the American League East but we all knew they stood
no chance against the mighty Oakland A's in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   This time, it's not the opponent that makes us feel hopeless.
It's the Patriots themselves. The embarrassment against the Jets,
the injuries, the planned flight to Hartford, and the uncertainty
about Carroll make this a Wild Card Weekend without much hope.
</P>
<P>
   Remember four years ago when the young and hungry Patriots had a
playoff game in Cleveland on New Year's Day? It was their first
postseason appearance in eight years and they went in with a
seven-game winning streak. There was a buoyancy about the team that
reappeared two years later when they made it all the way to the
Super Bowl. In those days, the Patriots went into the playoffs as
the hot team, the team nobody wanted to play.
</P>
<P>
   Now they are the team everybody wants. But it is their good
fortune to be playing the other team everybody wants. Truly. Take a
look at the dozen NFL playoff entries and it's clear that the two
teams waiting to be beaten are playing one another this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   We tried all week to get the Patriots to say something
meaningful about this game, but the answers were flat and
predictable. The Patriots are wounded and playing without Bledsoe,
their leader. Some want out. Others want a new coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got our ass whipped last week, and (Scott) Zolak's the
starter this week,'' said safety Willie Clay. ``That's all there is
to say.''
</P>
<P>
   That's about all there is to say. Meanwhile, the ghost of the
Great White Tuna is not going away. The Patriots were a 5-2 team
when Parcells first beat them last year. They proceeded to lose
three of their next four. They were a muscle-flexing 4-1 when the
Tuna came to town this past October. That defeat sent them reeling
to four losses in five games.
</P>
<P>
   Now they have a playoff game one week after being humiliated by
Parcells. Kraft hasn't commented, but he no doubt was mortified and
stupefied by what he saw in New York. And one of his people is
planting rumors about hiring Parcells's assistant, Bill Belichick.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries aside, the Jet debacle followed by a one-and-out
playoff experience could be enough to get this coach fired. But
right now there's a wild-card game to be played.
</P>
<P>
   Whoop-de-do.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
