</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-ANDRADE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANDRADE MAKES THE TURN ON UPSWING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He is in a tropical paradise, a far cry from the golfing hell he
had been in just four months ago. Billy Andrade made the trip to
Maui from his home in Atlanta the other day, but, in truth, it was
a journey that began on a Friday in early September in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Golf was beating up Andrade, which would be no big deal if not
for the fact that in his line of work, bad play means no pay. The
pride of Bristol, R.I., was in a horrendous stretch when he opened
with a 74 at the Greater Milwaukee Open. ``I was almost in last on
not a really, really hard course,'' said Andrade. A week earlier,
he had missed the cut at the Greater Vancouver Open. Before that,
he had missed the cut at the Sprint International. Before that, he
had missed the cut 10 times in 21 starts.
</P>
<P>
   The checks, when they did come, were small. The frustration was
large.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was either go home and a take a while off or figure
something out,'' he said. ``I don't know if I've gone that long
with playing that bad ever before.''
</P>
<P>
   There were mechanical problems, said Andrade, but mostly he was
never giving himself a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was constantly 3 over after seven holes, constantly shooting
myself out of it,'' he said. ``But I knew (in Milwaukee) that I had
to get myself up the next day and play out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Golf can be a cold-hearted game that penalizes those who make
even the slightest mistake, but on the other hand, it is
marvelously rewarding to those who persevere. So it was that on
that Friday in Milwaukee the sport extended a gentle embrace and
Andrade turned his season around. The swings were true. Putts
dropped. The trademark smile returned. He shot 64. When he followed
that with rounds of 65 and 68, Andrade finished tied for ninth, his
first Top 10 since the opening event of the season, and he had shot
three consecutive sub-70 rounds for just the second time in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   He rode that momentum to an emotional win at the Canadian Open
the next week, his first on Tour since back-to-back triumphs in
1991. Just two shots out of the lead through 54 holes, Andrade was
wakened by a phone call that Sunday morning. Bobby Orr, a partner
in Woolf Associates, which handles Andrade's affairs, wanted to
know if the golfer was ready. ``Bobby,'' said Andrade to the NHL
Hall of Famer, ``I better be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrade prevailed in a playoff over Bob Friend, dispelling any
lingering doubts that he would win again. Gone, too, were those
haunting thoughts at the back of his mind of not making the Top 125
in money and possibly losing exempt status. Instead, Andrade earned
a $396,000 check, two years exempt status, not to mention a pair of
priceless passes to Augusta National and Carnoustie for this year's
Masters and British Open. (He still has to earn his way into the US
Open, though that is a matter for another day.)
</P>
<P>
   There were two more Top 20 finishes following the Canadian Open,
and in his final 29 rounds of 1998, Andrade broke 70 14 times. He
finished 41st in money ($705,434), rather remarkable considering
that he had earned just $189,380 through the first eight months,
and he hopes to ride that strong finish into the new season.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, 1999 is a perfect time to kick into high gear if
you're a player of Andrade's stature.
</P>
<P>
   There is the introduction of the World Golf Championships,
select-field events that will offer $5 million purses, not to
mention the looming Ryder Cup matches at The Country Club in
Brookline.
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' said Andrade, ``is the ultimate goal. It would mean so
much to me and Brad Faxon and Brett Quigley, guys from New England,
to play what would amount to a home game. I've played (The Country
Club) a lot and nothing would be better than to represent your
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrade, like many of his colleagues, will start paying
attention to his world ranking, for that is how the fields will be
drawn for the WGC events, a group effort of the pro golf tours in
the US, Europe, Australia, Japan, and South Africa. The top 64 will
qualify for the first event, the Feb. 24-28 match play competition
at La Costa, and Andrade is on the outside looking in, ranked 78th.
</P>
<P>
   Andrade was back in Rhode Island for Christmas, but thanks to
his Canadian Open victory he is in the field for this week's
kickoff to the 1999 PGA Tour season, the Mercedes Championship (for
1998 event winners only) at Kapalua's Plantation Course on Maui. He
is about to commence his 12th year on the PGA Tour, an
accomplishment of which he should be proud, and just a few weeks
shy of his 35th birthday he remains one of the friendliest
personalities in a line of work that desperately needs more of
them.
</P>
<P>
   The trip to Hawaii is a two-week affair (Andrade will also play
in next week's Sony Hawaiian Open), and he was able to travel with
his wife and two children, combining work with pleasure. Daughter
Lelia, at just 20 months, said Andrade, would make for an
interesting traveler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good luck to the passengers,'' he said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The Royal and Ancient announced that the Open Championship will
be staged at Royal Lytham &AMP; St. Annes in 2001 and at Muirfield the
following year. It stops at Carnoustie this summer and at St.
Andrews in 2000 ... Andrade isn't the only notable player looking
to work his way into the WGC Match Play bonanza in February.  &UR; Scott
McCarron  &LR; (75th),  &UR; Steve Pate  &LR; (76),  &UR; Robert Allenby  &LR; (85),  &UR; Tom
Kite  &LR; (87),  &UR; Costantino Rocca  &LR; (91),  &UR; David Frost  &LR; (94), and  &UR; John
Daly  &LR; (121) are all on the wrong side of the number. Rocca and
Frost have plummeted, having been 52d and 51st, respectively, at
the end of 1997 ... Dates are being finalized by the Women's Golf
Association of Massachusetts, which has secured some outstanding
sites for its premier 1999 events: Sankaty Head on Nantucket for
the Baker Trophy, Eastward Ho! in Chatham for the Stone Cup, and
Oak Hill in Fitchburg for its Association Championships.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
