<HEADER>
A5512 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-FUTURE-     01-02 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-FUTURE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS A&AMP;M SETTING SIGHTS ON NATIONAL TITLE IN '99
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Texas A&AMP;M began and ended its 1998 season with
narrow losses to teams that remain in the mix for college
football's national championship.
</P>
<P>
   In between, the Aggies ruined the title aspirations of opponents
ranked No. 1 and No. 2 in the respective polls with two stunning
upsets as double-digit underdogs.
</P>
<P>
   The encouraging returns from such extended exposure to members
of college football's upper crust boosted the Aggies' confidence to
a level unprecedented in 10 seasons under coach R.C. Slocum.
Instead of hanging their heads after a 24-14 loss Friday to No. 3
Ohio State in the Sugar Bowl, A&AMP;M players talked yesterday about
using the experience as a steppingstone to a run at the 1999
national championship.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M (11-3), ranked No. 8 in The Associated Press poll, returns
16 starters next season, including its leading passer, rusher and
receiver. All will return with an ingredient that had been missing
in the Slocum era: the self-assurance gained from victories against
top-five opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll come back next year gunning for that national
championship,'' said tailback Dante Hall, who rushed for a
team-high 1,024 yards and eight touchdowns. ``We should be right
there in the mix, I think. This season showed us that hard work and
great togetherness can go a long way. Even ending with a loss, we
can take the Ohio State game and build on it as something to push
us in the off-season.''
</P>
<P>
   After the 1997 season, A&AMP;M players admitted to self-doubts about
their place in college football's pecking order. That no longer is
the case, thanks to upsets of then-No. 1 Kansas State (36-33) and
then-No. 2 Nebraska (28-21), as well as respectable showings
against Ohio State in the Sugar Bowl and No. 2 Florida State in the
Kickoff Classic (a 23-14 loss).
</P>
<P>
   ``We're over that hump. We've beat the good teams,'' said
fullback Ja'Mar Toombs. ``We know what it takes to contend with the
best. We're building a team that can be a powerhouse. When people
look at us now, they are going to have to say, `A&AMP;M is a really
good football team' instead of, `A&AMP;M ... they're OK.'''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest evidence of the change, tight end Dan Campbell said,
is in the way players respond in preparation for meetings with
top-10 opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't stress anyone, regardless of who we play. And that
hasn't always been the case,'' said Campbell, a senior. ``That's
what we accomplished this year that we'll pass along to the younger
guys. These guys know they have a chance to win every game. We're
on Florida State's level and Ohio State's level.''
</P>
<P>
   Those two teams join top-ranked Tennessee (12-0) as the only
remaining pieces in the puzzle for the 1998 national championship.
At A&AMP;M, the focus already has shifted to 1999. The Aggies consider
themselves a huge piece in that puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this team will do what it takes this summer and a couple of
guys step up, I see no reason why it can't contend for the national
title next year and beat everyone on the schedule,'' strong safety
Rich Coady said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, I think we set our goals too low,'' Hall said. ``We
wanted to win the Big 12 South, and then the Big 12. That's all we
talked about. If we come back with a higher goal in mind, we'll
probably be able to accomplish that.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, the Aggies are talking of pursuing the ultimate goal in
1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
