<HEADER>
A5514 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-H     01-02 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRAN BLINEBURY  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
SAN FRANCISCO _ Here's all you need to know about this wild-card
battle of titans: Charles Haley just might suit up and play for the
49ers.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Presumably, that means that means Dick Butkus wasn't available.
Or Tommy Nobis or Chuck Bednarik.
</P>
<P>
   Possibly, it means that Bart Starr will pull on the helmet again
for the Packers. Or even Max McGee or Paul Hornung.
</P>
<P>
   If you were promoting this as a heavyweight fight, it would
likely be the NFL equivalent of George Foreman vs. Larry Holmes. A
pair of doddering ex-champions trying to pass themselves off as
real contenders.
</P>
<P>
   It certainly won't be just another playoff game when San
Francisco hosts Green Bay at 3Com Park. It will definitely be the
end of an era. It could be the end of several eras.
</P>
<P>
   Just say that there are so many comings and goings on both
sidelines that the respective franchises might be best served
installing revolving doors in their training facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, it was less than a year ago, heading into the Super
Bowl against Denver, that the word dynasty was being used to
describe this new version of the Packers.
</P>
<P>
   So they promptly were dethroned by John Elway and the Broncos
and spent all of this season looking up at Randall Cunningham,
Randy Moss and the Vikings. Now, the most popular activity in
Cheeseland is betting on who catches the first plane out of town _
defensive end Reggie White or head coach Mike Holmgren.
</P>
<P>
   White, of course, retired after last season, then changed his
mind and came back and now swears that this is his farewell tour.
After Holmgren led his team to the Super Bowl title in 1997, he was
honored by having a street named after him in Green Bay. But that
honor is diminished when you consider that Holmgren Way is usually
covered by six inches of ice, and it seems that things have gotten
too cold for the coach.
</P>
<P>
   Some contend Holmgren wants to go someplace where he can run his
own show, holding the titles of both coach and general manager.
There is also the speculation that he is holding out for an
opportunity to come right back here to the Bay Area, where he used
to be the offensive coordinator, and take over the reins if Niners
boss Steve Mariucci should decide to follow Carmen Policy and
Dwight Clark to the expansion world of Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren's response to rumors about a return to the Bay Area was
to say very little, which only served to fuel the feeding frenzy
even more. Not that a little more blood in the water would even be
noticed by Niners fans.
</P>
<P>
   The chardonnay-sipping faithful are frothing over the fact the
Niners have lost their last five meetings with the Packers,
including three in a row in the playoffs. And don't think for a
minute that quarterback Steve Young isn't being saddled with much
of the blame.
</P>
<P>
   In his eight years as the Niners' starting quarterback, Young
has developed into the NFL's most accurate and highest-rated
passer. But he has not been able to clear the hurdle of the
Packers. In his last three full games against Green Bay, Young has
thrown just one touchdown pass against four interceptions and been
sacked 16 times.
</P>
<P>
   For all of the wins and all of the big numbers, the critics are
again coming out of the woodwork to tell Young what he already
knows: He's not Joe Montana. There is a school of thought that says
for all of his accomplishments, including winning a Super Bowl
title, the only really big game Young has ever won was the 1994 NFC
title game against the Dallas Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   All of this has led to speculation that Young, banged up and
with a history of concussions, might walk off into retirement if
the Niners lose this game, paving the way for a complete rebuilding
of the team once Ed DeBartolo Jr. regains control of his franchise,
which seems only a matter of time.
</P>
<P>
   When DeBartolo finally clears his legal problems and is given
the OK by the NFL to move back into his office, he will definitely
bring back former coach and guru Bill Walsh, maybe as GM, maybe as
general overseer. There was even one rumor that Walsh was going to
start working again the week leading up to this game.
</P>
<P>
   Now, wouldn't that be ridiculous, bringing back an old name from
the past as a display of panic?
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to Haley, who spent six years with San
Francisco, was traded to Dallas in 1992 and retired from the
Cowboys with a bad back following the 1996 season. Haley was in
town for a physical and could be in uniform today because the
Niners have been devastated with injuries on the defensive line to
Chris Doleman, Roy Barker and Bryant Young.
</P>
<P>
   Two years on the shelf and now likely straight into the
playoffs. That says it all about Packers vs. Niners '98. How the
mighty have fallen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
