<HEADER>
A5515 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-FIESTA-PRICE-HNS &LR;      01-02 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-PRICE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL SULLIVAN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
TEMPE, Ariz. _ He heard the roar go up immediately, but he figured
it was more for the result than for any style points that might
have been involved.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Big play. Big moment.
</P>
<P>
   Timely, too, of course, but what else was new?
</P>
<P>
   Then the man of the moment sneaked a glance at the Georgia Dome
replay board, and even a fellow with a name like Peerless was
impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize how tough a catch it was until I saw the
replay,'' Peerless Price said here the other day. ``It was real
close.''
</P>
<P>
   Often as not, it is. When Tennessee gets around to calling on
its big-play receiver, the Volunteers are in a bind, in need of
something special, a role Price has been happy and able to fill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I have to make a big play in every ballgame I
play,'' he said matter-of-factly. ``There's going to be a play to
be made in the passing game by me, and hopefully I'm going to come
down with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Breaking in a new quarterback, Tee Martin, Tennessee opened this
remarkable season with a clear preference to run first, second and
maybe even third, throwing only often enough to remind opponents it
wasn't out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Price made the most of his opportunities, catching 61
passes for 920 yards and 10 touchdowns in helping the Vols to a
12-0 season and a spot in Monday night's Fiesta Bowl against
Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those plays were big, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Others were merely huge.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for instance, the two touchdown catches in the
season-opening nail-biter at Syracuse, and a big touchdown
reception in the home win over Florida. Or the 10 catches for 165
yards and a pair of scores against South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   There was more, too. A 36-yard touchdown reception started
Tennessee on its way back from an 18-point deficit against
Arkansas. Finally, Price wrapped up the regular season with seven
receptions for 181 yards and a touchdown at Vanderbilt.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was the catch-and-run act the extent of his contribution.
When Alabama limited him to one reception for nine yards, Price
made his presence felt with a 100-yard kickoff return for a score.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the best we've had here, no question about it,''
Vols coach Phillip Fulmer said. ``He's made a lot of big plays for
us this season when we really needed them.''
</P>
<P>
   None, though, was bigger than the one Price made midway through
the fourth quarter of the Southeastern Conference championship game
against Mississippi State in Atlanta. With his team trailing 14-10,
he pulled down a 41-yard throw from Martin despite tight coverage
to put Tennessee ahead for good, earning game Most Valuable Player
honors with his six catches for 97 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peerless is a guy who's going to make plays,'' Martin said.
``You know if you give him a shot, he's going to get in there and
get it for you.''
</P>
<P>
   The raw numbers might not look sensational compared to the
recent 1,000-yard seasons of former teammates Joey Kent and Marcus
Nash, but Price's accomplishments might be more remarkable. Those
others, after all, had the advantage of working with Peyton Manning
in a more pass-oriented offense; Price was left to help ease the
transition to the inexperienced Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Price finishes third on the all-time Tennessee
receiving list in catches (147) and yards (2,298), trailing only
Kent and Nash in each category. In the course of things, he passed
the likes of Alvin Harper, Carl Pickens and Tim McGee in the
Tennessee record book, despite being slowed his junior year by a
hurried recovery from a broken fibula and torn ankle ligaments
suffered in the 1997 spring game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I can't say I fit in, because those guys went on to
have great professional careers,'' he said. ``But I know I broke a
lot of their records. I'm in the top two or three in most
categories.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Price hopes to be Peerless in a different way, helping
Tennessee to its first national championship in 47 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we've been talking about all season,'' he said.
``This is where we all wanted to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the Vols are just a big play or two from the title. If
the opportunity arises, Peerless Price would like nothing better
than to provide it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
