<HEADER>
A5517 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-FIESTA-WARRICK-HN     01-02 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-WARRICK-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL SULLIVAN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
TEMPE, Ariz. _ All things considered, Mario Edwards gladly will let
someone else take a crack at the job.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dealing with Tennessee's Peerless Price will be enough of a
challenge in Monday night's Fiesta Bowl, the Florida State
cornerback says. But what about trying to defend against a fellow
he sees in practice every day?
</P>
<P>
   Good luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``A one-on-one matchup? No,'' Edwards said. ``On this level, I
don't think anybody can stop Peter Warrick.''
</P>
<P>
   The Volunteers will have to try, of course. Sometimes, that will
leave corners Steve Johnson and Dwayne Goodrich with the unenviable
task of keeping the 6-foot, 190-pound Warrick in check without
help.
</P>
<P>
   This is not something Edwards _ a fellow hardly lacking in
confidence _ would care to attempt on a regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very rare that you see a guy with that kind of mobility,
who can stop on a dime and then accelerate like he can,'' he said.
``He's just a special guy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vols, of course, aren't the only ones who have noticed. In
FSU's 11-1 season, Warrick averaged 20.2 yards on his 61 catches,
scoring 12 touchdowns. Against Florida, he turned a deflected pass
into a scoring catch-and-run, then broke open the game with a
46-yard touchdown pass off an end around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I get the ball, I feel I have to do something with
it,'' the former high school quarterback said.
</P>
<P>
   Should Tennessee stick with its standard defense, heavy on
man-to-man coverage, Warrick might have some chances to do
something special Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like it when they come up and press me,'' he said. ``If they
miss the jam, it's all over.''
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers defensive coordinator John Chavis concedes the risk.
At the same time, Chavis says it is too late to revamp a successful
scheme to accommodate one player _ as special as that player might
be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, I think he may be the very best receiver in college
football,'' Chavis said. ``But we've played against good receivers
all year.''
</P>
<P>
   With redshirt sophomore Marcus Outzen making only his third
career start at quarterback, that strategy might play into FSU's
hands. As the Seminoles ask a passer with little experience to lead
them, a big-time receiver could enjoy an even bigger role.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Outzen has considered the possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peter Warrick is one of a kind,'' he said. ``You think you
have him covered, but it's impossible to be as quick as he is, so
he gets open.''
</P>
<P>
   Seminoles fans might witness that for the last time Monday
night. Warrick, a junior, has been coy about his plans for next
season, but most FSU insiders expect him to wear an NFL jersey come
summer.
</P>
<P>
   For now, there remains a bit of unfinished business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot about this national championship,'' Warrick
said. ``We made it here, and we need to make the best of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we can go out there and dominate.''
</P>
<P>
   If form holds, Warrick will keep up his end of the bargain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
