<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5519 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHLWEST03-COX     01-02 0421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLWEST03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NHL WEST NOTES: Motown, Woe-town
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Many people think Detroit has too much talent for this
season-long funk to continue, but there are indications general
manager Ken Holland is ready to make a move. The Red Wings allowed
26 goals during a six-game winless streak, including a loss to
Nashville, and the team's goals-against average of 2.79 ranked only
19th in the league. The team even put in a waiver claim on St.
Louis defenseman Todd Gill. Holland expected motivation problems in
the first 20 games this season, but the Wings are nearing the
midway point of the season. As to conversations with other teams,
Holland said, ``You go through some spans of time when you're not
really talking. Now, I'm trying to touch base with as many people
in the league as I can. I want to make sure I know what's going on
and get a feel for how teams are thinking. I want to make sure we
don't get caught by surprise and miss a chance to get one of the
guys we have interest in. If one of those guys is being moved, we
want to be on top of it.'' The Wings remain in first place in the
Central, and Holland is far from panicking, but he said, ``It's
still the regular season, but you can't just all of a sudden turn
it on come April 1 and find your 'A' game. You need to get it going
at some point in the regular season and play your 'A' game.''
</P>
<P>
   Dollars and sense
</P>
<P>
   Colorado goalie Patrick Roy, potentially only six months away
from unrestricted free agency, has not signed a new deal with the
Avalanche. A number of teams, including the Thrashers, are keeping
an eye on developments, but Dallas forward Mike Keane said he
thinks the Avalanche would be crazy not to re-sign Roy. ``They're
moving into a new building, and you'd think they'd want a strong
team to build around,'' said Keane, a former teammate of Roy in
Montreal and Colorado. ``That means not getting rid of Patrick Roy.
You can see how much a great goaltender means. ... I know Patty
wants to play in Denver the rest of his career. He has roots here.
He really wants to stay.'' The Avalanche, meanwhile, has rebounded
nicely from a 1-5-1 start this season, despite a string of injuries
that has sidelined six regulars, including Roy. A 4-2 win in
Vancouver earlier this week left Colorado in undisputed first place
in the Northwest Division for the first time this season.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Doug GilmourFrom St. Louis forward Kelly ChaseKeith
TkachukJeremy RoenickDallas Drake
</P>
</TEXT>
