<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5520 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-49ERS-FUTURE-COX     01-02 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-FUTURE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    San Francisco soap opera
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A once and perhaps future king in this city,
Green Bay Packers coach Mike Holmgren landed here Saturday evening.
By the time his team departs tonight, conventional wisdom is that
he and his wife, Kathy, could be dusting off the furniture at the
home they never sold in nearby Santa Cruz.
</P>
<P>
   Preposterous as it once seemed, it could happen.
</P>
<P>
   The various job-related permutations involving Holmgren and
incumbent San Francisco coach Steve Mariucci include more twists
than Lombard Street, the famous and narrow 45-degree slope here
that could double as a grand prix course. How the fates of these
two men came to be so intertwined is a tale replete with the
hackneyed elements more typical of a cheap paperback mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Pride, avarice, ego, ambition. They all play a role in a
real-life drama that has placed enormous pressure on Mariucci. A
likable and gregarious coach who has won 26 of 34 games in two
years, Mariucci's only shortcoming is that he has failed to augment
the franchise's collection of Super Bowl hardware.
</P>
<P>
   That egregious oversight, along with the pending return of
exiled owner Ed DeBartolo, could be enough to earn Mariucci a pink
slip and send him packing to Cleveland to fill the coaching vacancy
there.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly three months ago, the Niners presented Mariucci with a
proposal for a contract extension through the 2005 season. Because
of the uncertainty surrounding the return of DeBartolo, the coach
tossed the contract in his car trunk and sought clarification on
what his expanded role might be in an organization that will be
reshaped following the departures of team president Carmen Policy
and vice president Dwight Clark.
</P>
<P>
   When he couldn't get a straight answer, Mariucci decided three
weeks ago to sign the contract and take his chances. The only
catch: The 49ers suddenly weren't so eager to have his autograph on
the new deal.
</P>
<P>
   And so the young coach privately steams and figures to spend
much of today glancing over his shoulder at the specter of
Holmgren. Indeed, objects in Mariucci's rear-view coaching mirror
are closer than they appear.
</P>
<P>
   Agent Don Yee, who represents Mariucci, acknowledged last week
that ``any one of three things'' could happen after today. Asked if
those three options were consummating the extension, dismissal or
resignation, Yee allowed: ``You're three-for-three, I'd say.''
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci, after all, was hired by Policy, suddenly persona non
grata with the Niners. In the current atmosphere, in which
DeBartolo is attempting to expunge anything that has Policy's
fingerprints on it, all things are possible. George Seifert, after
all, exited the 49ers in 1996 after posting a .755 career winning
percentage and claiming two Super Bowl titles.
</P>
<P>
   Only this much seems certain: DeBartolo, in exile while he
battled federal racketeering charges in Louisiana, desperately
wants to return with a splash.
</P>
<P>
   Bringing back former coach Bill Walsh in some management role _
and as the tangible reminder of this franchise's halcyon days _
figures to be the first step. The return of Holmgren, who served as
offensive coordinator here and is like a son to Walsh, could be the
second half of the daily double.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren has a terminal case of the seven-year itch. He longs to
run his own show and has a stipulation in his contract that allows
him to leave for a combination job that includes the coach and
general manager titles. His brilliant record aside, the options are
dwindling for Holmgren.
</P>
<P>
   It appears Carolina has settled on Seifert as its next coach.
Holmgren confided last week that he likes the potential in
Washington, but the likelihood that John Kent Cooke will retain
ownership of the franchise probably means Norv Turner will survive.
The Seattle job he explored a year ago isn't as attractive now to
Holmgren.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Packers general manager Ron Wolf suggested to
Holmgren that he sign the lucrative extension Green Bay has offered
and stay put. That option doesn't look as bad to Holmgren now. Even
in the league's most remote outpost, after all, $3 million a year
can buy a lot of happiness.
</P>
<P>
   But there is DeBartolo, said to be in the throes of emotional
mood swings over what to do about his coach. And there is Mariucci,
twisting in the wind. And there is the house in Santa Cruz and the
several business interests Holmgren maintains in the Bay area.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how the drama would play out, 49ers quarterback Steve
Young offered the kind of answer inherent to such soap operas.
``Stay tuned,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
