<HEADER>
A5527 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-02 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
TEMPE, Ariz. _ It took more than four months of pleading, griping,
inputting, ciphering and sorting.
</P>
<P>
   Geeks told us about victory-margin formulas and schedule
calculations. Coaches made impassioned testimonials for their
teams. Fans demanded a playoff resolution on the field. Teams tried
to run the score up, hoping to climb a little higher in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   And through it all, the Bowl Championship Series leaders told us
it all would work out in the end.
</P>
<P>
   For Florida State and Tennessee, it did.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 college football season will end Monday night with one
game, one champion. It will be Tennessee-Florida State in the
Fiesta Bowl for the whole enchilada, not to mention all the
Tostitos.
</P>
<P>
   There will be no reason for any other contender to argue. There
will be no way any other team could cast doubt on No. 1, even if
Ohio State's John Cooper prays over his black-eyed peas that FSU
wins a ``sloppy'' game.
</P>
<P>
   It might not have been a perfect ride to a single championship
showdown, but it worked. It is the contention here that anything
short of a playoff still shortchanges players, fans and coaches.
</P>
<P>
   But in this system, in these times, while we still might not
know which team will win college football's national championship,
we do finally know which teams will not win it.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State? No second half, no Sugar Bowl rout, no cigar. Kansas
State? No focus, no case for the ring. UCLA? No defense, no chance.
</P>
<P>
   Any of those teams might still believe it could defeat both the
Seminoles and the Vols. Any of them, except for UCLA, might in fact
be good enough to do such a thing if there were a playoff. And
other teams, namely Arizona and Wisconsin, could legitimately talk
about being the best in the land.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the Seminoles and Vols smiling as they walked off the
practice fields Saturday, finally knowing that theirs will be the
once-and-for-everything Game of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   And they should have been smiling. They are the teams that
should play for the ring, because while everyone else was griping
and pleading for a way to get it done under the BCS system, the
'Noles and Vols showed us how it is supposed to be done.
</P>
<P>
   Rule No. 1: Beat everybody. If the program and conference are
strong enough, it will work out no matter if there is a cheap
fumble recovery against Arkansas in the final minutes, a close win
at Syracuse to begin the year and doubt cast from skeptics
coast-to-coast.
</P>
<P>
   Tulane, a usually feeble program from an upstart conference,
also went undefeated this season. But the Green Wave didn't have
the tradition and monster conference affiliation that the Vols
have. Too bad.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the right way to decide champions. In a playoff, the
Green Wave might keep winning and might even knock off a Tennessee
or Florida State. But that's how it is.
</P>
<P>
   That's how the Vols earned this shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a kind of magical year for us, yeah,'' Vols
quarterback Tee Martin said. ``But sometimes, you work for that
magic. Look at what's happened. Look at the Arkansas game. If our
defensive lineman doesn't bust his tail if he thinks the game is
over, then maybe he wouldn't have gotten to that ball. You can
always be fortunate, but you have to do the job even when you're
fortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   Rule No. 2: If you don't win them all, then win the ones that
count. The ones late in the year. The ones against the rivals. The
conference-championship games.
</P>
<P>
   The Buckeyes couldn't beat Michigan State late in the year. The
K-State Wildcats couldn't hold off Texas A&AMP;M in the Big 12 title
game. The Bruins couldn't stop Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Seminoles came back from an inexplicable
early-season loss to North Carolina State and showed how title
contenders get on a roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``We showed how you rebound from adversity and put together a
great season,'' FSU safety Dexter Jackson said. ``If Ohio State
thinks it should be here, it should have beaten Michigan State.
That's just how it works.''
</P>
<P>
   That's just what the 'Noles know from experience, having won the
1993 national title with a loss.
</P>
<P>
   And after watching all the bowls thus far, the Seminoles also
now know that no team could legitimately cast doubt on their
championship if they can defeat Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It worked out about as good as it could have,'' FSU coach
Bobby Bowden said.
</P>
<P>
   The Buckeyes didn't get the romp over the Aggies they so
desperately craved. The Wildcats and Bruins didn't even get a bowl
win.
</P>
<P>
   Geeks can power down their computers. Coaches and fans can quit
their moaning and lobbying. This might not be the best way to
determine a champion, but it's the way it's done now, and this time
it worked.
</P>
<P>
   One game. One champion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
