<SLUG> BC-FBN-HALEY-49ERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER COWBOY HALEY RETURNS TO 49ERS TO ``GO GET BRETT FAVRE''
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE FISHER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. _ For three years, the Cowboys have been
trying to sign ``the next Charles Haley.''
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, the San Francisco 49ers signed the original, just in
time for today's first-round playoff game vs. Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming back to the 49ers feels like old times,'' Haley said
yesterday. ``My job is simple and plain: Put my hand down and go
get Brett Favre. That's what I'm here to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The unusual signing is another odd twist to a
glorious-but-bizarre career for Haley, a former NFL defensive
player of the year and a five-time Super Bowl winner who was run
out of San Francisco and acquired by Dallas in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Haley, 34, hasn't played football in two years. He retired from
the Cowboys after being limited to playing five games in 1996
because of chronic back problems. He participated on two Super Bowl
champions with San Francisco in the first six years of his career.
He was on three Super Bowl champions with Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't spell `Super Bowl' without Charles Haley,''
Cowboys owner Jerry Jones once said, explaining how Haley's
presence made him such an important puzzle piece.
</P>
<P>
   After using a trio of premier picks in the past three years
seeking Haley-like defensive ends, the Cowboys earlier this season
contemplated re-signing Haley. But the Cowboys passed, as did San
Francisco, which worked him out on Sept. 1 but bowed to concerns
about his back and his possibly negative locker-room effect.
</P>
<P>
   Friends say Haley has mellowed since his retirement, a change
perhaps motivated by the illness of his daughter, who has leukemia.
Still, Haley said his volatile reputation might be a factor in the
way he's perceived.
</P>
<P>
   But, Haley said yesterday, ``I'm not one to put a lot of weight
into whether someone cares whether I'm here or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Haley probably won't be a locker-room favorite with the 49ers,
though coach Steve Mariucci said yesterday that the acquisition was
approved by his ``Dirty Dozen,'' a group of 49ers veteran team
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco has needs. Defensive ends Roy Barker and Chris
Doleman are limited by injuries, and tackle Bryant Young is out
with a broken leg. San Francisco had 46 sacks in its first 12
games, but has five sacks in the four games since Young was hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charles Haley is coming to do a job,'' Doleman said. ``We're
on the eve of creating history. We have to put personal feelings
and a lot of stuff aside.''
</P>
<P>
   Haley underplayed concerns about his back, though he has had
three recent surgeries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'll be OK,'' Haley said. ``We'll see on Sunday. We'll
see on Sunday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
