u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-UCONN-WVA-BOS &LR;      01-02 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-UCONN-WVA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUSKIES SPREAD THE WEALTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD _ Before Saturday, the University of Connecticut and
West Virginia women's basketball teams had played seven times
dating back to 1982, with the Mountaineers winning just once.
Saturday was not the time to try and reverse that trend.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies left no question as to why they are ranked No. 1 in
the country and have a perfect record after 11 games. Seven players
scored in double figures as they soundly defeated West Virginia,
116-71, before a sold-out crowd of 16,294 at the Civic Center. It
was the eighth time this season the Huskies scored more than 100
points, breaking their team record.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Geno Auriemma passed the minutes around and used 13
players. They shot 65 percent from the floor, compared to 34
percent by West Virginia. It didn't seem to matter that the Huskies
were missing starting point guard Sue Bird, who's out for the
season with an ACL injury, or forward Swin Cash, who is out with a
stress fracture.
</P>
<P>
   ``When somebody's missing, they all try a little harder,''
Auriemma said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed they did. Despite the disappointing first-half play by
Svetlana Abrosimova, who was 0 for 2 from the floor and made only
one free throw, she came back in the second half to hit 9 for 10,
ending up as high scorer with 23 points. Adding to the Huskies'
totals were Shea Ralph (20), Tamika Williams (14), Asjha Jones
(12), Amy Duran and Kelly Schumacher (11 each), and Stacy Hansmeyer
(10).
</P>
<P>
   High scorers for West Virginia were Maria Tchobanova and Rebecca
Burbridge, with 15 each, followed by Val Zona with 11.
</P>
<P>
   With seven minutes to go in the first half, after West Virginia
had tossed in its third 3-point basket in four minutes, Auriemma
took off his blue jacket and stood up to bark at his players,
fearing they would let their 12-point lead slip away. But it's
doubtful he was really worried. The Mountaineers, who had not had
the lead since the score was 4-2 in the opening two minutes, could
not contest for the Huskies' hot-shooting, fast-breaking play and
never got closer than 6 points.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Huskies' surges that seemed to frustrate the
Mountaineers. UConn took off with a 20-7 run in the first half, but
was slowed when West Virginia narrowed the gap with two layups and
two free throws. Not to worry (despite their coach's yelling), the
Huskies seemed to say. They came back with two rebounds by freshman
forward Williams, followed by two layups, and after a run of their
own, took a 54-28 lead into the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``They play in spurts, and any time you drop your head, they're
going to take advantage of that,'' said West Virginia coach Alexis
Basil. ``And they have a lot of depth, they can match up with
anybody in the country. And the intensity that the young players
have coming off the bench is incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   As for her cold first half, Abrosimova said she didn't look at a
stat sheet at halftime, ``but I felt I played horrible.'' The
coach, she acknowleged, told her to get going.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, during the game he was screaming at me,'' she said. ``I
made some bad decisions. I bave no idea why, the coach says it's
all in your mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Auriemma didn't deny that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if Svet's mad at me, you've got to be mad at
somebody to play this game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Abrosimova's second-half heroics, the crowd
erupted when, with 9 seconds to go, rarely-used guard Courtney
Gaine took a back-pass steal by Hansmeyer and went in for a layup.
No wonder that Gaine watched the basket go in, and exulted; those
were her first 2 points of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The next test for UConn is the game against No. 2 Tennessee next
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph, who was 8 for 8 from the field, said she's ready, and
admitted that maybe the Lady Vols are looking over their shoulders
at the undefeated Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I don't know what they're thinking, but I'd be a little
concerned,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After seeing Saturday's score, they probably are.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
