<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5534 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STORM-MAIN-COX     01-02 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STORM-MAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WEATHER: Train echo system drops 31 inches of rain in 9 hours in
Palm Beach County, Fla.
 &HT;    From staff reports
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A violent storm named for a locomotive
steamed through northern Palm Beach County without warning early
Saturday, fueling a tornado and dropping 31 inches of rain in nine
hours that flooded hundreds of homes and streets.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service, which had predicted only a 20
percent chance of rain before the storm, said the county was hit by
a ``train echo'' system that is extremely rare.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach Gardens suffered the worst. Water creeped into more
than 100 homes scattered throughout the city, police said, from the
older neighborhoods east of I-95 to the higher-priced homes in the
PGA National community. And that's conservative, said fire shift
commander Evan Bestland.
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere cars were stranded and streets were impassable by
midday. The parking lot of Gardens Park Plaza on the southwest
corner of Military Trail and PGA Boulevard turned into a lake.
Winn-Dixie Market Place, Eckerd Drugs and a dozen small business
had up to five inches of water running through their aisles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a disaster to us,'' said Value Card and Gifts owner
Suzanne Slate, who estimates between $20,000 and $30,000 in damage,
plus whatever business is lost. ``We lost everything we made for
Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida Highway Patrol officials closed all northbound lanes on
Interstate 95 from 45th Street to Blue Heron Boulevard Saturday at
about 12:30 p.m. after Riviera Beach firefighters reported watching
a concrete construction extension start to crumble, making a half
circle about 40 feet deep. A portion of the sand foundation
supporting the extension had been washed away during the early
morning storm.
</P>
<P>
   At a makeshift command center on Old Dixie Road and 10th Street
in Riviera Beach, Palm Beach County Sheriff's deputies said about
eight units assisted Riviera Beach police with road closings.
</P>
<P>
   The heaviest-hit area was at Old Dixie and 10th Street, where
all that was left of one traffic light was the top third. The
yellow and green portion was found nearly two blocks away in a
restaurant parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   At Mom &AMP; Dad's Restaurant and Take Out, manager Lonnie Lovett
said his sign was found about three blocks away. Inside, the
employee time clock stopped at 5:39 and an employee who was inside
when the twister hit lamented his car's broken windows.
</P>
<P>
   The series of storms called a train echo began pounding the
northern part of the county just after 2:30 a.m. Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters at the National Weather Service in Miami say they
could not have predicted the pummeling storm, but its special
characteristics were clearly recognizable on radar screens once it
started.
</P>
<P>
   In a train echo, heavy showers line up in an area like ``like
boxcars on a train,'' said meteorologist Scott Carroll of the
National Weather Service. ``Echo'' is a radar term for a repetitive
weather pattern.
</P>
<P>
   Early Saturday morning, showers that carried north past the
Florida Straits, and then up through Miami-Dade and Broward
counties eventually collided with moisture and air moving west
across the Atlantic Ocean from the Bahamas and into Palm Beach
County, said meteorologist Wayne Colin of the National Weather
Service.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting of those two weather systems spawned a diagonal line
of thunderstorms and rain showers stretching southeast of West Palm
Beach northwest to the Martin-Palm Beach County line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole area blew up,'' Colin said.
</P>
<P>
   The most intense of the showers hit Riviera Beach, where a small
tornado hit a four-block area, and 31 inches of rain was recorded
by a gauge in the C-17 canal in North Palm Beach that is controlled
by the South Florida Water Management District.
</P>
<P>
   The storm was not related to other weather systems or fronts
moving in and out of Florida, forecasters said. Unlike typical
thunderstorms that flare up and move by rapidly, train echo rains
grind away along a single track without let up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It keeps raining over the same area time after time after
time,'' Colin said. ``There's almost no way to forecast if it's
going to happen and where it's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Other areas of the county had heavy rain _ 3.75 inches was
recorded at Palm Beach International Airport _ but were spared of
floods because the locomotive-like rain confined itself to one
track.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those freakish weather things that happen,'' said
district spokesman John Neuharth. ``It caught everybody by
surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
