<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIESTA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIESTA PARADE CROWD CHEERS GLENN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD RUELAS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bands and floats got the expected cheers from the crowd
watching the 28th Annual MicroAge Fiesta Bowl parade Saturday. But
the crowd of 400,000 saved their biggest applause for John Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn and his fellow crew members from the space shuttle
Discovery, riding in a convertible stretch limousine, were welcomed
with a standing ovation along the four-mile parade route.
</P>
<P>
   Paradegoers rushed up to Glenn for a photograph, some thrusting
their kids into his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got him. Our kids are part of history,'' said Gina Riordan,
28, from Rockville Center, N.Y., after getting a picture of Glenn
and her 3-year-old daughter, Maggie.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave a thumbs-up and the kids saluted him and everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Those seated just north of Indian School Road were lucky enough
to get five whole minutes of the oldest astronaut. The parade came
to a standstill because the float in front of Glenn caught fire.
</P>
<P>
   Oil leaked from the engine powering the ``Undersea Adventure''
float, causing lots of smoke and a few flames.
</P>
<P>
   Neptune, we have a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in the capsule-like driver's seat, Bob Towne, 51, of
Mesa, said flames shot to his neck before he doused them.
</P>
<P>
   The mermaid riding atop the float had no idea it was aflame
until the crowd told her in jeers.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was saying, `Can you swim?' and I said, `Can you say
fire?' '' said Vanice French, 50, of Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Children riding in the submarine dashed off without injury. The
mermaid, who can't walk on dry land because of her fin, was carried
to safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have this problem under the sea,'' said the ocean
nymph, who preferred to stay anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   It was the only glitch among the 83 entries.
</P>
<P>
   The grand-prize float featured Peter Pan on a flight to
Neverneverland. It was one of the few flights not delayed by the
snowstorm in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   The second-prize float, sponsored by a cell-phone company, had
Little Red Riding Hood going wireless to alert the woodsman that
she was being chased by a big, bad wolf.
</P>
<P>
   The marching bands that received the most applause were from the
University of Tennessee and Florida State, the universities who
square off for Monday's Fiesta Bowl championship game.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State fans gave out spirited Seminoles chops and
Tennessee band members were greeted with shouts of ``Go Vols.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., and his wife walked the route,
alongside the convertible carrying their children. He waved and
smiled like a guy running for president.
</P>
<P>
   Although most watchers sat in the traditional lawn chairs and on
blankets curbside, some found creative perches from which to view
the parade.
</P>
<P>
   People used stepladders, climbed billboards, stood atop RVs and
climbed into paloverde trees. Several sat on rooftops of downtown
building or peered from their apartment balconies.
</P>
<P>
   Some assured themselves a good spot by buying bleacher seats in
advance.
</P>
<P>
   Sterline Seaboch, 45, of Phoenix, was one of them. But he didn't
want to be.
</P>
<P>
   `It's almost un-American,'' said Seaboch, who said he was in the
bleachers only because he got them from a Fiesta Bowl connection.
``See that guy back there with the kid on his shoulders? That's how
you watch a parade.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Bartley was a guy who had a kid on his shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in good shape for it after the block party,'' said
Bartley, 41, of Chandler, hoisting 5-year-old Kaleb on his
shoulders. Bartley said his son was on the same perch during the
New Year's Eve countdown on Mill Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   People lined three to four rows deep along the parade in most
spots.
</P>
<P>
   Some showed up early.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Jardine, 40, of Phoenix, was up out at 5:30 a.m. setting up
22 seats right across from the television cameras set up for a
live, local broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the only certain place where the bands play,'' he
said, explaining his choice of spot.
</P>
<P>
   Jardine has dragged his reluctant family to the parade every
year for about 15 years, he said. He would never settle for
watching it on TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the difference between reading about life and living
life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Alice, didn't agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be very happy watching it on TV,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some showed up late.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really lucked out,'' said Steve Frisch, 46, who showed up
with his wife, Nan, 47, and their 7-year-old daughter, Sienna, just
20 minutes before the parade.
</P>
<P>
   They ended up with a prime, uncrowded spot and a parking space
just a few yards from Central Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is great,'' Frisch said. ``I've lived here all my life
and this is my first Fiesta Bowl parade.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife wanted to keep their spot a secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell them it's private,'' she said, ``or we'll never get it
next year.''
</P>
<P>
   The secret spot is on Central and Orange Drive. Don't tell
anybody. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Republic writer Chris Fiscus contributed to this article. &QL; 
Richard Ruelas can be reached at 444-8473 or at
richard.ruelas(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
