<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA PONDERS OFFSEASON QUESTIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The season ends and the questions begin. Among
those UCLA must answer in the coming weeks:
</P>
<P>
   Will Kris Farris bolt for the NFL? Farris, a junior offensive
tackle and the Outland Trophy winner, is expected to announce his
decision early this week. (The deadline for underclassmen to
declare is Friday.)
</P>
<P>
   A source close to Farris said there's a 90 percent chance he'll
leave school. After the Rose Bowl, Farris certainly sounded like he
had played his last game.
</P>
<P>
   He downplayed two holding penalties: ``They could call holding
on every play.''
</P>
<P>
   He was quick to note the final sack of Cade McNown ``came from
the right side.'' (Farris plays left tackle.)
</P>
<P>
   He implied he has maxed out collegiately: ``I played the game of
my life, but I'm just a lowly lineman. I could play great, and we
could still lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Will strength coach Kevin Yoxall depart? Yoxall is mulling an
offer from Auburn and said he'll decide this week. He worked with
several Auburn assistants at Texas Christian in the early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't looking to leave, but (Auburn) came to me,'' said
Yoxall, who was one of coach Bob Toledo's first hires in Feb. '96.
``UCLA has done a great job in putting things together to try to
get me to stay. They've given me a lot to think about.''
</P>
<P>
   How important is Yoxall? Ask Toledo to account for UCLA's recent
rise to prominence, and the first thing he mentions is Yoxall's
impact.
</P>
<P>
   What of the defensive staff? Toledo will meet with his
assistants Monday to review performance and plot strategy for '99.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo declined to discuss potential changes until he meets with
the staff, but defense is obviously his priority.
</P>
<P>
   Among the possible changes:
</P>
<P>
   Switching to a 4-3 alignment from the 3-4 set used this season.
The Bruins will have a slew of big, experienced linemen next
season, and a 4-3 would best suit the talent.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a 4-3 would place freshman Robert Thomas, perhaps
UCLA's most gifted player, in his natural position: middle
linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   Reshuffling the defensive staff. Nick Aliotti will be retained
as defensive coordinator if he agrees to play a 4-3 and use more
zone coverage.
</P>
<P>
   But don't be surprised if Toledo rearranges assignments: either
Marc Dove (inside linebackers) or Bob Field (outside linebackers)
could replace Aliotti as the secondary coach. That would give
Aliotti more time for tactics and teaching his complicated system.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility is assigning two coaches to the line: one
for tackles, one for ends.
</P>
<P>
   Will Borges bolt? Offensive coordinator Al Borges reportedly is
a secondary candidate to fill the vacancy at the University of
Washington, but he lacks two critical ingredients: no Washington
ties and no head coaching experience.
</P>
<P>
   However, Borges may be a prime candidate for a coordinator post
in the NFL. Those offers probably would come after six teams (San
Diego, Philadelphia, Carolina, Baltimore, Chicago and Seattle) hire
head coaches.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
