r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCAIN-AZR &LR;      01-02 1463
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN'S CAMPAIGN REFORM ROLE MAY HURT FUNDRAISING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAT FLANNERY  
 and MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Sen. John McCain led the politically unpopular charge for
campaign finance reform, a Republican colleague, Fred Thompson of
Tennessee, offered a humorous perspective on their travails.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd follow McCain over a cliff,'' said Thompson, a co-sponsor
of the legislation. ``In fact, I've already done it.''
</P>
<P>
   A backlash against the legislation could eventually cost McCain
critical support from certain conservative constituencies, among
them big business.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain, like Thompson, revels in the role of political
maverick, a Republican risk-taker willing to venture into new,
potentially dangerous territory even if it isn't on the GOP's
strategic map.
</P>
<P>
   Now that he has officially set his sights on the Republican
presidential nomination, McCain faces the most crucial test of his
political career. Can a stubborn nonconformist who delights in
bucking trends win enough support to lead the right-leaning
Republican Party closer to the center?
</P>
<P>
   By nearly all accounts, it's a long shot.
</P>
<P>
   Though McCain is no stranger to the national stage, it is his
first national campaign. Forging a solid national base and raising
the requisite $20 million to finance a competitive race could be
daunting, particularly in what is expected to be a crowded field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are there enough McCain types out there to raise that kind of
money? I'm not sure,'' said Ladonna Y. Lee, partner the Eddie Mahe
Co., a Republican consulting firm in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's potential GOP rivals include Thompson, Texas Gov.
George W. Bush, wealthy publisher Steve Forbes, former Vice
President Dan Quayle, former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander,
conservative Family Research Council President Gary Bauer, Missouri
Sen. John Ashcroft, Sen. Bob Smith and conservative radio talk-show
host Alan Keyes.
</P>
<P>
   Also mentioned in some circles are Elizabeth Dole, Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi, Vermont Sen. Bob Smith,
former House speaker Newt Gingrich, former New York Congressman
Jack Kemp, and Colin Powell, former head of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff.
</P>
<P>
   Republican National Committee Chairman Jim Nicholson said
McCain's occasionally unpopular stands on issues like campaign
finance or a national tobacco tax aren't enough to scuttle his
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``In spite of the fact that I have very serious differences with
him about his approaches to reforming campaign financing, I admire
John,'' Nicholson said. ``He is fully capable of being president of
the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain enters the race with several important positives: a
reputation for speaking his mind, an ability to transcend partisan
concerns and, importantly, a proud Navy career that included 5{
years in a Vietnamese prison camp.
</P>
<P>
   The enduring image of McCain's war years is that of a skinny,
silver-haired young man on crutches stepping off a plane after
years of torture and humiliation as a POW. It could help him carve
out a niche among the legions vying for the GOP nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a hero to many people,'' said Greg Stevens, McCain's
media consultant. ``For people who raise money in politics, that
turns them on. It brings them in.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona GOP National Committeewoman Lori Marsh says McCain's
powerful personal history makes him a speaker in demand on the
eastern Republican chicken-dinner circuit.
</P>
<P>
   On the negative side, McCain must cope in the coming months with
the resurrection of less flattering chapters in his personal
history, notably his membership among the infamous ``Keating
Five,'' his wife Cindy's battle with addiction to prescription
drugs, and his legendary temper tantrums.
</P>
<P>
   Given those variables and the number of potential candidates
involved, national political observer Larry Sabato said ``it's
literally impossible to know'' how McCain's political fortune will
play out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can change overnight,'' said Sabato, a political science
professor at the University of Virginia. ``If you're going to run,
you have to do what McCain did _ throw caution to the wind, dare
and jump in.''
</P>
<P>
   If Bush joins the race, the field would probably shrink
dramatically. Thanks to his father's presidency, Bush brings with
him instant name recognition, a national base of support to build
on and reams of recent favorable national publicity.
</P>
<P>
   With most of the other likely GOP candidates falling to the
right of Bush, McCain could find himself competing with Bush for
the same ideological ground. But Bill McInturff, a GOP pollster
advising McCain, said surveys showing Bush as the front-runner
don't mean much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Front-runners stumble,'' McInturff said. ``I did (Bob) Dole in
the last primary and he started at 51 percent in New Hampshire and
ended up at 28. Once you get into a real campaign, high numbers now
start shifting radically.''
</P>
<P>
   Polls suggest there is plenty of room for McCain, whose name
identification nationally is not as high as candidates like Forbes
or Alexander, who have built a national following.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than Bush, all those people are in mid-single digits,''
McInturff said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet McCain barely registered a blip in Iowa and New Hampshire
polls last year. A mid-year straw vote in South Carolina, which
holds the south's first primary, showed Ashcroft, Bush and Keyes as
the top vote-getters.
</P>
<P>
   Though these are inauspicious signs for a dark horse candidate
in a party that traditionally ignores dark horses, the time was
never better for a political outsider to ride to victory.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts across the board say deep public discontent
over the Clinton presidency and recent events on Capitol Hill have
given a leg up to candidates who are outside the political
establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, a Westerner and Beltway outsider, is certain to capitalize
on those credentials if he runs. So will McCain, Forbes, even
Quayle, who moved to Arizona in part to distance himself from his
Beltway past.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Stevens, McCain's media consultant, predicted McCain will
wage ``a different campaign that cuts across conventional wisdom.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's different than a lot of the people that voters see coming
at them, particularly from Washington,'' Stevens said. ``People are
looking for something different. They're looking for people that
are honest. They're looking for people that speak their mind.
They're looking for people that take on special interests. That's a
powerful message.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is still the matter of filling campaign coffers and
finding enough support to make it past the first few primaries.
That means building momentum in the early going.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has his work cut out for him. Key McCain aides like chief
of staff Mark Salter and administrative assistant Deb Gullett are
from Iowa and know the political landscape there well. Former New
Hampshire Sen. Warren Rudman is co-chair of McCain's exploratory
committee.
</P>
<P>
   But Iowa GOP Chairman Steve Grubbs noted that McCain is
nonetheless starting late, compared with competitors who spent
years cultivating support. And if many Iowa Republicans know
McCain's name, ``most would probably say they don't know enough
about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, by comparison, is also starting late but ``he has been on
the front of every national magazine for the last two months,''
Grubbs said. Grubbs has already offered to go to work for Bush if
he runs.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, McCain ``fits quite nicely into the ideological
mold of Iowa voters,'' Grubbs said. He estimated about one-third of
the GOP caucus voters are sympathetic to the Christian right. The
rest are ``establishment voters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``John McCain seems to move pretty well among all of those
groups,'' Grubbs said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain earns good marks from the Christian Coalition and other
religious groups for his socially conservative positions on
abortion, gay rights, welfare reform and pornography.
</P>
<P>
   Yet moderates have been impressed by a range of actions: his
efforts to rein in campaign spending, to impose a tobacco tax and
his support for renewed diplomatic relations with Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's willingness to break with the party line also endears
him to the powerful Washington press corps, which has showered him
with favorable coverage. Sabato thinks the mutual admiration could
hurt McCain with party conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their endorsement is usually the kiss of death,'' Sabato said.
</P>
<P>
   On the flip side, it could benefit McCain if the primary field
remains crowded. In that case, the powerful national press will
winnow the field by limiting coverage to those it considers key
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain will be in the top tier,'' Sabato predicted. ``They
would never leave their boy out.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-02-99 2229EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990102.0269 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5777 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-BICKLEY-AZR     01-02 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE, EMOTION LIFT CARDINALS TO VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ It didn't come in drops, it came in waves. A river of
respect that crashed through the dam, washing over them, cleansing
them of their past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone got dominated today,'' Andre Wadsworth chirped in the
locker room. ``Someone got dominated today.''
</P>
<P>
   It happened in Dallas, where they've learned to snicker about
the Cardinals, a team that was once a nice piece of chew. Soft,
tender and easy to spit out. Just don't get any on your boots.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team had been kicking us around for a long time,'' Lomas
Brown said. ``I mean, it was time. Time for a change.''
</P>
<P>
   And it happened on national television, a game that validated
all the close victories and the last-place schedule. A game when
the country not only accepted the Cardinals, but in all
probability, adopted the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got our minds right,'' Simeon Rice said. ``We came in today
and said, `We just got to have it. We just got to have it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   So the reward is a trip to Minnesota, a chance to compete with
the best team in the NFL. The reward is 10 victories, one of Jake
Plummer's preseason guarantees. The reward is a struggle that would
end in the sweetest possible way:
</P>
<P>
   Sucking the life out of the Cowboys. Making them quit. Forcing
the most lovesick fans in the world turn on their beloved heroes.
</P>
<P>
   Too often, you've heard them cheer the Cowboys at Sun Devil
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the Cardinals made them boo the Cowboys in their
own back yard.
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't get any better than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excuse me! Excuse me! Excuse me!'' Eric Swann shouted, working
his way past a crowd and into the locker room. Once inside, he
hugged everyone he could find. Players sought him out, wishing him
well. And this giant of a man, this man you want to say doesn't
care, the man who took so much ridiculous grief . . . this man
started to cry.
</P>
<P>
   After wiping away the tears, this space became his:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm real proud. Real, real proud. Seeing the guys step up,
Corey Chavous making huge plays, Aeneas Williams just shutting down
Michael Irvin, Jamir Miller piercing through the line, Andre
Wadsworth coming back to where he played his first game and getting
a sack, seeing the destroyer defense being played, a relentless
effort that just took everything away . . . I've just never seen
the defense play like this. I was standing on the field and it was
like I was dreaming. Simply amazing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things didn't work out for me, but you have to look at the big
picture. All the skepticism, all the critics, all the hopes, all
the dreams, all the expectations . . . they are there.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've made it. And you know what? I'm feeling what they're
feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Right then, as Swann started to smile, Rice peeked his head
around the corner. They shook hands, locking the grip and holding
it, these two men who supposedly can't get along. And if you
could've only seen the warmth in their eyes as they gazed at one
another, warrior to warrior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next year,'' Swann said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, man. That's going to be ugly,'' Rice responded.
</P>
<P>
   For everyone but Swann, there is still some of this year left.
Brown, ever an optimist, openly talks about reaching the Super Bowl
this year, but it's all gravy now. They've broken through the glass
ceiling, and now they're flying.
</P>
<P>
   It was an afternoon when Dave McGinnis, the defensive
coordinator, may have locked up the big chair in another city. An
afternoon when the defense found the way to Troy Aikman, picking
the right seams to deliver an assortment of blitzes. A day when the
Cardinals showed them look after look _ four different schemes on
the first series alone _ until the Cowboys didn't know what to
expect.
</P>
<P>
   A day when they gathered at a bar in Scottsdale to watch the
Cardinals. And in the fourth quarter, when it was long past over,
when the owner was shown standing on the sidelines, Bill Bidwill
received a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the past has buckled under to the present. The bus is
rolling. And you'd be a fool not to believe. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 444-8253 or at dan.bickley(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
