<HEADLINE>
IS COLLEGE FOOTBALL TOO COMMERCIAL? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER CORBETT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nike-clad Florida State, coached by Burger King Whopper hawker
Bobby Bowden, will tee it up against Adidas-sponsored Tennessee in
the Tostitos Fiesta Bowl, brought to you by ABC-TV, for the
ultimate college football prize _ the Sears National Championship
Trophy.
</P>
<P>
   And now we pause for a commercial message.
</P>
<P>
   When the Seminoles battle the Volunteers on Monday night in
Tempe, that may not be much of an exaggeration of how ABC's Keith
Jackson kicks off the broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   College football and its realigned major bowls are rolling in
corporate sponsorships.
</P>
<P>
   Bowls and ABC line up the corporate sponsors for the Bowl
Championship Series and first unified title game to help finance
the staggering pot of $13 million per team.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers say fans don't mind the commercialization of college
football. But some football diehards, like John MacDonald of Tempe,
wonder if it's worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult for me to sit through a college football
game, as much I love them,'' said MacDonald, an Arizona Supreme
Court communications officer who grew up on Frank Kush-era Sun
Devil football and a fledgling Fiesta Bowl. ``Big-time college
athletics and commercialization have become forever entangled, and
it makes me wonder if the big time is worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Corporate sponsor dollars funneled towards sporting events,
including college athletics, are expected to surge to $5.1 billion
next year, more than double its 1993 level, said Lance Helgeson,
managing editor of the ``IEG Sponsorship'' ``Report,'' a newsletter
that tracks sponsorships.
</P>
<P>
   Herman Frazier, Fiesta Bowl president, said the Fiesta Bowl has
been forced to boost corporate involvement to stay competitive with
the other top bowls and remain in the championship game rotation.
``The Arizona Republic'' is among dozens of Fiesta Bowl sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of fans that would like for it to remain pure,''
he said. But he said the sponsors help keep ticket prices down and
they have gilded the payoff to the colleges.
</P>
<P>
   Each of eight BCS teams will receive about $13 million, which
they will share with their respective conferences. That helps
support other college sports and student athletes, said Frazier,
senior associate athletic director at Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   But the blitz of advertising drowns out the cheerleaders, bands
and referees' whistles, and hurts the college game experience,
MacDonald said.
</P>
<P>
   For him, the second half of the ASU-Notre Dame game was the most
enjoyable game in a long time because a stadium power failure
pulled the plug on the advertising.
</P>
<P>
   MacDonald, an ASU basketball team manager from 1980-84, takes
his kids to high school games to get a pure football experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still go to ASU games and I still enjoy the Fiesta Bowl, but
it's different. It's the difference between the county fair and
Disneyland. Is one more enjoyable than another? Is one better
because it's bigger and brighter and louder? I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Tostitos and ABC officials say they think most fans understand
the commercial marriage of the sponsors, networks and bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Tostitos spokeswoman Lynn Markley said the company has taken the
sponsorship ``to the next level, but we do it tastefully.''
</P>
<P>
   Sun Devil Stadium undergoes a transformation for the Fiesta
Bowl, with hundreds of yards of bunting resembling the design on
Tostitos bags. The field and the players' uniforms also are adorned
with a logo in which the Tostitos name is the dominant image, about
three times larger than Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Tostitos says the sponsorship has helped the company create more
consumer awareness of its products.
</P>
<P>
   The Fiesta Bowl is a huge national platform, Markley said, and
``it was something we could own, whereas a lot of events are
sponsorship cluttered.''
</P>
<P>
   Teri Wagner, ABC marketing director, said the BCS sponsors _
Tostitos Fiesta, Nokia Sugar Bowl, FedEx Orange Bowl and Rose Bowl
presented by AT&AMP;T _ use restraint in their advertising to avoid any
fan backlash.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsors are interested in the rub-off effect of being linked
with the passion of college football and its wholesomeness, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds corny, but I really believe that,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   It's no surprise that college football games are huge commercial
ventures. The ``granddaddy of them all,'' the Rose Bowl, has its
roots in the first Tournament of Roses, staged in 1890 to promote
California's warm climate. Football became a permanent part of the
Pasadena festivities in 1916.
</P>
<P>
   All the bowl games that have followed, including the 28-year-old
Fiesta Bowl, were launched by civic leaders to attract visitors and
show off their communities, said Mark Eschenfelder, an assistant
economics professor at Robert Morris College in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a logical way of promoting your community, and the bowls
have gotten a lot better at it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the Fiesta Bowl arguably has done the best job
of elevating fan and corporate interest, said David Carter, a
sports management professor at the University of Southern
California.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fiesta Bowl has pulled off that last chip, so to speak, to
be one of the premier bowls,'' said Carter, author of ``Keeping
Score:'' ``An Inside Look At Sports Marketing''.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Tostitos is really the poster child for what's right with
corporate sponsorship,'' and fans have come to accept sponsors, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In a Roper Organization survey reported in his book and the
``IEG Sponsorship'' ``Report,'' 76 percent of the public and 80
percent of sports enthusiasts agreed that ``corporate sponsorship
is a fair price to pay to keep sports on free TV and hold down
ticket prices.''
</P>
<P>
   In terms of what corporations get for supporting bowls, Carter
cites the experience of John Hancock Financial Services, which
sponsored the Sun Bowl in El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Hancock spent $1.6 million sponsoring the bowl and
received the equivalent of $4.86 million in advertising value,
Carter writes in ``Keeping'' ``Score.'' That included ``1.2 billion
impressions _ the number of times the consumer is exposed to the
company name or logo, such as on billboards, TV, or print media.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fiesta Bowl pioneered title sponsorships in 1985 when
Sunkist Growers signed a five-year deal to underwrite the game and
parade.
</P>
<P>
   Other bowls followed suit, except for the Rose, which resisted
sponsorship. For 1999, AT&AMP;T became the ``presenting sponsor.'' It's
the ``Rose Bowl presented by AT&AMP;T,'' rather than the ``AT&AMP;T Rose
Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When that was announced, people said that was the final piece
and the world's coming to an end,'' said Mark Mandell, ABC director
of media relations. ``But the Rose Bowl is still going to keep its
tradition _ dignified and classy _ without logos plastered end to
end.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter said he wonders whether the presenting sponsorship is an
interim step and that there will be some ``mission creep,'' in
military terminology, so that eventually the Rose Bowl adds a title
sponsor and becomes commercial.
</P>
<P>
   MacDonald said he would hate to see that. The absence of
commercial signs in the Rose Bowl and other stadiums like Notre
Dame's is something that stood out when he went to South Bend,
Ind., and to Pasadena for the 1997 Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   He said one of his fondest memories of college football occurred
near the end of that Rose Bowl game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was around dusk, drizzling rain and it was cold. It was a
great game. ASU was behind at the time and things were looking
bleak,'' MacDonald said.
</P>
<P>
   In the mist, steam was rising off the Sun Devil players and you
could see their breath. There were a lot of fans in maroon and
gold, and scarlet and gray in the stadium but not one advertising
sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my wife to look around for a minute. This is what
college football is all about,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ASU's Jake Plummer scored a go-ahead touchdown, but it ended
badly when Ohio State answered. Still, MacDonald said that moment
is frozen in his mind.
</P>
<P>
   For fans like him, the bloom would be off the Rose if it got on
the corporate bandwagon with the Fiesta and the other bowls. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Peter Corbett can be reached at 444-4815 or at
peter.corbett(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
