<SLUG> BC-FLOODS-C0X </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WEATHER: A flooded New Year in South Florida
 &HT;    With STORMS-MAIN, TORNADO.
 &HT;    By Scott McCabe
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Highland Pines woke up Saturday to find
their neighborhood engulfed in a 3-foot-deep lake _ full of raw
sewage.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look out the window and see a geyser of water pouring
with brown things floating...We're catching hell back here,'' said
Vern Wiggins, who was able to move his car to dry land at the
neighborhood entrance at PGA Boulevard, just west of Military.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Anderson wasn't so fortunate. His Ford Taurus was half
underwater, and 6 inches of water flowed through his kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   The china cabinet was ruined. The new dining table, still
unassembled, was lost. So were his children's toys, shoes and
clothes. Still, he kept his spirits up. It was, he said, all he
could do.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least we don't have to water the Christmas tree,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Tillman, whose house was the last to escape the water,
ferried neighbors in his canoe and warned the children about
playing in the lake.
</P>
<P>
   This flood wasn't bad as the one in 1996, residents say. But
they fear that with all the development, things will only get
worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never had any problems until they built Ballens Isle,''
said Donna Morris, a 10-year resident.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is that Highland Pines is in the county
(Palm Beach County) but surrounded by cities that approve all the
development. Compounding matters, a dam at the intersection of
Canal C-17 and Military Trail blocks the natural flow of water.
</P>
<P>
   Wiggins has been waiting for a new storm drainage for three
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``But nobody wants to take responsiblity,'' Wiggins said. ``Each
government just points at the other. It's a comedy of errors. But
when you got people with 6 inches of water in their house,
somebody's got to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
