<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-OF-2000-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAR FANS GET GLIMPSE OF FUTURE IN LOS ANGELES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY PETER HARTLAUB  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- If there's one thing to be learned at the Greater
Los Angeles Auto Show this week, it's that the year 2000 will
deliver a lot more than a computer virus.
</P>
<P>
   How about a sporty new Chrysler Chronos instead?
</P>
<P>
   Forget about the fact that we're only a few days into 1999:
Every major auto maker in the world is participating in the
exhibition at the Los Angeles Convention Center, which started
Saturday and runs through Jan. 10, and most are already trying to
put Y2K in a positive light.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's typical for auto shows -- especially at the major shows
-- to give people an early look at next year's car,'' said Danny
Jacobs, who was displaying the not-yet-for-sale Honda S2000
roadster. ``It just happens next year is the turn of the century.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs is a ``product specialist'' for Honda. In layman's terms,
he's the well-dressed guy who stands on the giant turntable with a
microphone pointing at the car.
</P>
<P>
   By early Saturday afternoon, Jacobs had the type of swooning
crowd associated with Tony Bennett -- with consumers packed five
deep around his rotating stage, hanging on his every word as he
described the cherry red coupe.
</P>
<P>
   Art Gomez was mesmerized, even though he came for a $20,000
Dodge Intrepid. The projected $30,000 sticker price on the Honda
was way out of his price range.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you never know when you're going to hit it big and be able
to buy a toy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The show features more than a dozen prototypes for the year
2000, even though most will not enter showroom floors until the
fall. Dealers are clearly trying to convey that there will be a car
for everyone in the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   For those who find the 2000 Lincoln LS too domestic, there's the
2000 Jaguar S-type luxury sedan. For those who find the 2000 BMW M5
too regal, there's the Nissan 2000 Frontier four-door.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, customers this week will have to take a
look-but-don't-touch approach to the 2000 cars and settle for a
chance to slide into the already-ancient 1999 models.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had one gentleman tell me that we were treating him like a
horse, dangling a carrot in front of him,'' Jacobs said.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 1,000 carrots dangling in front of consumers
on more than 760,000 square feet of convention floor, including
cars, trucks, minivans, sport-utility and alternative-fuel
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   More than one product specialist said the Los Angeles show is
one of the biggest in the country, along with Detroit, New York,
Chicago and Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Hours are 10 a.m. to 8 p.m. today and 11 a.m. to 10:30 p.m. on
weekdays. Admission is $7, and children 12 and under are free when
accompanied by an adult.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett and Brenda Gross of suburban Sherman Oaks hadn't been to
an auto show in 15 years, and they were marveling at both the
technological and social advancements.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't as many girls in swimsuits and evening wear
pointing at things,'' Brenda Gross said.
</P>
<P>
   David Valla wore a conservative, double-breasted suit as he
pointed at the new Rolls-Royces and Bentleys in one of the pricier
displays.
</P>
<P>
   While the pristine autos were kept behind a short Plexiglas
barrier like the chimpanzees at the Los Angeles Zoo, Valla quietly
admitted that anyone in the three-deep crowd could cross over at
any time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need that little barrier,'' he said. ``It has to seem more
unattainable than it really is.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
