<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLES-SHARKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARKS BEAT SLANDERS, 4-3  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ After Saturday's 4-3 overtime loss to the San
Jose Sharks, the Islanders' fourth straight defeat, a disgusted
Mike Milbury considered shaking up the team before the next game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's certainly something we'll have to think about the next
48 hours as we get ready for Chicago,'' Milbury, the Islanders'
coach and general manager, said when he was asked what was next for
his team. ``But this is not acceptable, from a coaching standpoint,
from a managing standpoint, from a player's standpoint.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what we'll do,'' added the coach, who seemed more
upset with this loss than any of the recent losses at Florida,
Tampa Bay and Chicago. ``But we'll have to do something to get it
going in the right direction. It doesn't get any worse.''
</P>
<P>
   As the playoffs slid further from the Islanders' reach Saturday,
Milbury was left with these questions to study: Make a trade?
Promote a few farmhands? Bench some veterans?
</P>
<P>
   Something has to be done.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the mid-December signing of Zigmund Palffy, who scored
twice Saturday, the team needs another playmaking forward. There
are a few players in the minors _ wing Warren Luhning tops that
list _ who deserve a shot. There are several veterans _ including
Bryan Smolinski and Robert Reichel _ who merit a seat in the press
box, and Milbury will not hesitate to do that. Ask defenseman Scott
Lachance, who sat out this past week.
</P>
<P>
   Milbury made his comments after the Islanders had lost to
another struggling team, dropping their record to 13-22-2, last in
the Atlantic Conference and 9 points out of the last playoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders fell behind by 2-0 in the first period against the
Sharks (11-16-8), came back in the second period and went down by
3-2 in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Once more, the Islanders came back to send the game into
overtime. It seemed to be anybody's game, but less than two minutes
into the extra session, a blown coverage led to Marco Sturm's
one-timer, which beat Islanders goaltender Marcel Cousineau (25
saves). The Sharks' Steve Shields made 18 saves.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders performed miserably in the first period and were
fortunate to trail by only two goals. The Sharks' first goal was
scored shorthanded, the other came on a blunder by the Islanders'
goaltender.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Ricci, who scored twice, banged in a cross-ice pass from
Stephane Matteau at 11 minutes 4 seconds. Owen Nolan, the Sharks'
captain, scored San Jose's second goal on a dump-in. He flipped the
puck on the Islanders' net from inside the blue line, and it got
behind Cousineau, who appeared to have been off guard. Nolan's
goal, at 13:43, was just his fourth of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders were as inspired as they have been at the start of
the second period, scoring two early power-play goals to tie the
score. Kenny Jonsson tallied the first. The other came from Palffy,
who has 5 points in six games since ending his holdout.
</P>
<P>
   Jonsson's power-play goal at 5:11 of the second period ended the
Islanders' scoreless streak at 178 minutes 55 seconds, a team
record. The old record, set in 1973, was 176:11.
</P>
<P>
   In the third period, Ricci gave the Sharks a late 3-2 lead with
a power-play goal at 16:34. Palffy tied the score 17 seconds later
by one-timing a pass from Reichel past Shields.
</P>
</TEXT>
