</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-CARDINALS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINALS CRUSH COWBOYS' PLAYOFF DREAMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The 1998 Cowboys will be known as the first team
to win every regular-season game in the NFC East. But they couldn't
win the game that counted most.
</P>
<P>
   An offense of superstars reverted to its woeful ways of last
month, and a defense with Deion Sanders was not enough to stop the
underdog Arizona Cardinals, who pulled off a 20-7 upset in a
wild-card playoff game yesterday at Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   And so after a promising 8-3 start, the Cowboys' season is over.
It might not be down to the rock-bottom depths of 1989, but the
Cowboys franchise was sent spiraling downward. Besides anger,
despair and shock, the feeling among players in the losing locker
room is that team owner Jerry Jones needs to make changes to a club
that dropped four of its past six games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nucleus of the team is not getting any younger, and it's
time to step up or step out,'' said Sanders, who played for the
first time since Nov. 22. ``I couldn't put up with it if I was Mr.
Jones. If this was my money, it's got to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Said quarterback Troy Aikman: ``Sometimes there is a tendency to
look at some of the guys that have been here through the better
years and then everyone wants to think that this is the same
Cowboys team. We're not the same team. We're relying on a lot of
different people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is the window closing?'' he asked rhetorically. ``For a lot of
people, that window was shut a long time ago. We don't have a lot
of the players we had when we had that success. We're looking
through a different window right now.''
</P>
<P>
   History was on the Cowboys' side yesterday. They had not lost to
the Cardinals in Dallas since 1989. The Cowboys had defeated the
Cardinals 16 of the past 17 times. They had not lost a home playoff
game since 1983. The Cardinals had not won a playoff game anywhere
since 1947.
</P>
<P>
   But history couldn't help the Cowboys' offense.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys had averaged 36.5 points in the two regular-season
games with the Cardinals. But they needed a 6-yard Aikman-to-Billy
Davis pass with 3:33 remaining to avoid being shut out by the
21st-ranked defense in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman, who entered the game with the second-highest postseason
passer rating, had a miserable afternoon. He completed 22 of 49
passes (44 percent) for 191 yards. He was sacked four times and
threw three interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not show up to play today,'' Aikman said.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman was not alone in his offensive misery. His receivers
dropped five passes. Michael Irvin, shut out the last time the
Cowboys played Arizona, did a little better with four receptions.
But he was not a factor against Pro Bowl Cardinals cornerback
Aeneas Williams, who had two interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They pressured us,'' wide receiver Patrick Jeffers said, who
had a game-high seven receptions for 92 yards. ``Sometimes, we'd be
open but we didn't protect long enough to let Troy get us the ball.
And other times, he had time to throw and we couldn't get open.
They were not playing a lot of bump and run. They were just sitting
on some things where it was hard to run our routes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
