   2. THE CENTURY, by Peter Jennings and Todd Brewster.
</P>
<P>
   (Doubleday, $60.) An account of the 20th century,
</P>
<P>
   complete with photographs and first-person narratives.
</P>
<P>
   3. TUESDAYS WITH MORRIE, by Mitch Albom.
</P>
<P>
   (Doubleday, $19.95.) A sportswriter tells of
</P>
<P>
   his weekly visits to his old college mentor,
</P>
<P>
   who was near death's door.
</P>
<P>
   4. BLIND MAN'S BLUFF, by Sherry Sontag and Christopher
</P>
<P>
   Drew with Annette Lawrence Drew. (Public Affairs, $25.)
</P>
<P>
   American submarine espionage from the early Cold War
</P>
<P>
   years to the present.
</P>
<P>
   5. THE PROFESSOR AND THE MADMAN, by Simon Winchester.
</P>
<P>
   (HarperCollins, $22.) How a murderer helped compile the
</P>
<P>
   Oxford English Dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   6. WE INTERRUPT THIS BROADCAST, by Joe Garner. (Sourcebooks,
</P>
<P>
   $45.) How radio and television reported historic events
</P>
<P>
   over the past 60 years.
</P>
<P>
   7. THE DEATH OF OUTRAGE, by William J. Bennet. (Free Press,
</P>
<P>
   $20.) The former secretary of education takes a critical
</P>
<P>
   view of the Clinton presidency. (b)
</P>
<P>
   8(x). FOR THE LOVE OF THE GAME, by Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Edited by Mark Vancil. (Crown, $50.) The NBA superstar's
</P>
<P>
   profusely illustrated memoir.
</P>
<P>
   9. A WALK IN THE WOODS, by Bill Bryson. (Broadway,
</P>
<P>
   $25.) A journalist finds beauty and humor while hiking
</P>
<P>
   the Appalachian Trail.
</P>
<P>
   10. LINDBERGH, by A. Scott Berg. (Putnam, $30.) The
</P>
<P>
   checkered life of Charles A. Lindbergh.
</P>
<P>
   11. THE ENDURANCE, by Caroline Alexander. (Knopf, $29.95.)
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Shackleton's 1914 Antarctic expedition.
</P>
<P>
   12. THE AMERICAN CENTURY, by Harold Evans with Gail
</P>
<P>
   Buckland and Kevin Baker. (Knopf, $50.) A copiously
</P>
<P>
   illustrated political history of the 20th century that
</P>
<P>
   emphasizes America's role.
</P>
<P>
   13. A PIRATE LOOKS AT FIFTY, by Jimmy Buffett. (Random
</P>
<P>
   House, $24.95.) Traveling from Florida to the Amazon,
</P>
<P>
   the singer-songwriter reflects on his life.
</P>
<P>
   14. THE TEN COMMANDMENTS, by Laura Schlessinger and Stewart
</P>
<P>
   Vogel. (Cliff Street/HarperCollins, $24.) The significance
</P>
<P>
   of the Ten Commandments today.
</P>
<P>
   15. CONVERSATIONS WITH GOD: Book 3, by Neale Donald
</P>
<P>
   Walsch. (Hampton Roads, $22.95.) More discussions of
</P>
<P>
   moral questions.
</P>
<P>
   16. VALUES OF THE GAME, by Bill Bradley. (Artisan, $30.)
</P>
<P>
   A lavishly illustrated collection of essays about basketball
</P>
<P>
   by the former player and Senator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ADVICE, HOW-TO, AND MISCELLANEOUS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. THE GUINNESS BOOK OF RECORDS 1999. (Guinness,
</P>
<P>
   $24.95.) An updated, profusely illustrated collection
</P>
<P>
   of records about subjects like sports and business.
</P>
<P>
   2. THE 9 STEPS TO FINANCIAL FREEDOM, by Suze Orman.
</P>
<P>
   (Crown, $23.) Practical and spiritual steps for
</P>
<P>
   managing your money. (b)
</P>
<P>
   3. ONE DAY MY SOUL JUST OPENED UP, by Iyanla Vanzant.
</P>
<P>
   (Fireside/S&AMP;S, $13.) How to raise one's morale and
</P>
<P>
   realize one's ambitions. (b)
</P>
<P>
   4. EMERIL'S TV DINNERS, by Emeril Lagasse with
</P>
<P>
   Marcelle Bienvenu and Felicia Willett. (Morrow, $25.)
</P>
<P>
   Recipes televised by the New Orleans chef. (b)
</P>
