</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING OLD GLORY DAYS WON'T BE AN EASY TASK FOR COWBOYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Dallas dynasty died two seasons ago, but
torture for the Cowboys has only just begun. The past haunts them.
The future ignores them.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, however, was all about the present. And while brutal
reality was on display at Texas Stadium, it was actually only a
continuation of the decay that began in '96.
</P>
<P>
   What the Cowboys were, they will never be again. But what they
became yesterday was a toothless old relic, moving at 45 RPM,
unable to dodge a knockout punch, unable to avoid the humiliation
of being dominated at home by the...
</P>
<P>
   Say it ain't so.
</P>
<P>
   Not the Arizona Cardinals. Not in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Chan Gailey arrived this season, and was asked to dig up the
dead, revive the Cowboys' playoff history, and return some life to
both the offense and January.
</P>
<P>
   As of yesterday, Gailey officially failed. There is no question
Gailey restored a football mentality to Valley Ranch this season,
but the bottom line is about January, and there is no exception or
excuse for losing, 20-7, to the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Easy answer for 1999:
</P>
<P>
   Blow up the team, and start all over again. Let a total
rebuilding begin, and that rebuilding doesn't necessarily have to
include any of the Triplets, meaning Emmitt-Aikman-Irvin, or Deion,
either.
</P>
<P>
   Easy answer for the blow-up-the-team theory:
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't work that way in the NFL, not with the salary cap
money meshed into the fiber of big cash contracts. And with the
Cowboys, it's particularly impossible. Jerry Jones has repeatedly
traded up-front money and extended years on contracts for the right
to create extra salary cap space.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't even consider it anyway,'' said Jones, who was
among the multitude suffering from postgame shock in the Dallas
locker room. ``You don't blow it up when you've got a Troy Aikman
and a Deion Sanders. Why start all over when, in general, you can
figure them for four or five more good years?''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman's performance yesterday didn't suggest four or five good
games left, much less seasons. The only consolation for what had to
be Aikman's most frustrating postseason moment was the disgusting
lack of help provided by receivers, who either couldn't work open
or dropped passes when they did.
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of Deion, since Jones brought up the name.
Nine-Toed was back on the field yesterday. Played the whole game.
All it proved was the obvious _ the Cowboys' late crumble that
began in December had little if anything to do with Sanders'
absence. And his return provided no ``spark.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tough time for me to try and give snap answers to
what needs to be done for next season,'' said Jones. ``But I will
say we won't blow things up. What we have in mind is being more
imaginative under the cap and making good personnel moves, both in
free agency and the draft.''
</P>
<P>
   One word of caution, however. Jerry had the same roster plan at
the end of last season. But to his credit, and Gailey's, that plan
appeared to be working. Ernie Mills was a newcomer who was by far
the most consistent receiver until a season-ending injury in
November. Running back Chris Warren also arrived to play a key
role, until injuries took him down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want it understood,'' added Jones, ``that the season overall
was not a disappointment for me. Not at all. The disappointment
came today, and losing the opportunity to go to Atlanta next week.
I didn't see that happening to this team. I thought we'd move the
ball and score on Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   Except the Gailey offense that lost its pop in December
continued popless yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing about today that I view as a negative on
Chan,'' said Jones. ``I was and am totally sold on him. This loss
won't change that. His fundemental approach to offensive football,
and to the football team, is really solid.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the most important portion of the NFL season _ the only
segment of the season that really counts, the Cowboys failed
miserably. And they were also undressed by a divisional neighbor in
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   While there won't be a rush to judgment _ not here anyway _ to
anoint Arizona as the NFC East's new bully, the comparisons don't
look good for the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Jake Plummer is the first divisional quarterback of the '90s who
over the long haul can prove to be Aikman's equal, or, as of
yesterday, superior to Aikman.
</P>
<P>
   And with young talent like Plummer now starting to jell, the
Cardinals will also have the eighth pick in the first round of
April's draft, plus another pick in the low 20s of the first round.
</P>
<P>
   More than all that, however, the Cowboys simply looked old and
tired yesterday. Worst yet, they are old and tired, and that won't
change anytime soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
