<SLUG> BC-BURNED-BOYS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA TEEN DIES FROM BURN INJURIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY SHERRY JOE CROSBY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- One of two brothers critically burned in a Val
Verde, Calif., Christmas tree fire died Saturday following surgery
at the Grossman Burn Center at Sherman Oaks Hospital, approximately
15 miles northwest of downtown Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital spokesman Larry Weinberg said that Shawn Williams died
at 2:24 p.m. of respiratory failure that brought on cardiac arrest.
</P>
<P>
   The youth stopped breathing at 1:34 p.m. and doctors worked on
him for 50 minutes before pronouncing him dead, Weinberg said.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's mother, Lisa Reese, was joined Saturday by her pastor,
friends and family at the hospital, Weinberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The loss of a child is devastating,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn, 17, suffered second- and third-degree burns over 43
percent of his body in the fire, which arson detectives continued
Saturday to investigate as having suspicious origins. Shawn
underwent surgery earlier Saturday to remove dead tissue and cover
burn areas with cadaver skin to ward off infection.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn's half-brother, Patrick Crawford, 7, who suffered
third-degree burns over 65 percent of his body, underwent his first
surgery Saturday and was in extremely critical condition, Weinberg
said.
</P>
<P>
   The surgery was to relieve swelling that was threatening blood
flow in Patrick's hand, forearms and left upper arm.
</P>
<P>
   He is scheduled to undergo a second surgery similar to Shawn's
on Monday, Weinberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to use a variety of different methods to remove
the dead, nonviable skin that covers 65 percent of his body,''
Weinberg said. ``Ultimately, they need to find viable tissue to
serve as a platform for skin grafts.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrick was so badly burned that doctors were unable to use the
boy's own tissue for skin grafts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's burned in all the places where they take skin to use as
skin grafts,'' Weinberg said. ``Ultimately he'll be covered with
some cadaver skin and some donor skin.''
</P>
<P>
   The greatest challenge facing Patrick is organ failure, Weinberg
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have great concern that he may suffer major system
failure as Shawn did,'' Weinberg said. ``That's been our concern
since he arrived here, and that remains our concern today.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors also worried about the risk of infection -- a danger
because bacteria from the dead tissue could enter the boy's
bloodstream.
</P>
<P>
   ``The longer they wait before removing the dead tissue the
greater the chances of infection,'' Weinberg said, ``but they have
to balance that concern with whether he is ready to endure the
rigors of surgery.''
</P>
<P>
   The brothers and two other people were injured in the fire that
broke out shortly after 8 a.m. Dec. 30 in the Santa Clarita Valley
northwest of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn's friend Patricia Lynn Martin, 20, was injured along with
the boys' aunt Dawn Carter, 45.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who suffered second- and third-degree burns over 18
percent of her body, remained in critical condition in the burn
intensive care unit at Los Angeles County/USC Medical Center,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, who fractured her ankle after jumping from an upstairs
window, left the facility early Saturday afternoon, said Sgt.
George Ducoulombier of the Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arson investigators went to talk to Dawn Carter, but she left
the hospital against medical advice,'' Ducoulombier said. ``They're
looking to talk to her'' about the origins of the fire.
</P>
<P>
   A hospital nurse said Carter's sister took the injured woman to
a Veterans Administration hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Ducoulombier said arson explosives detectives continued to
search the charred house for clues to the fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an ongoing investigation, and the fire still is
suspicious in nature,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
