<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-DEFENSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINALS' DEFENSE LEAVES COWBOYS FRUSTRATED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDY FRIEDLANDER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Cowboys' season didn't die of snakebite. It
was a casualty of war.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona quarterback Jake ``The Snake'' Plummer was impressive in
yesterday's 20-7 playoff upset of the Cowboys at Texas Stadium,
throwing for 213 yards and two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   But Plummer is not the reason the Cardinals will face Minnesota
in the NFC divisional playoffs while the Cowboys watch from home.
The Cardinals didn't need their young star's patented last-second
theatrics thanks to a defense that, according to cornerback Aeneas
Williams, ``declared war on the state of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody on our team believed we were at war,'' Williams
said. ``We were trying to take enemy territory. We had to take that
attitude. Obviously, it's not as serious as Desert Storm or Desert
Fox, but we wanted a sense of urgency on this team. We wanted them
to know we were serious.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys found that out quickly, especially quarterback Troy
Aikman, who was battered mercilessly.
</P>
<P>
   With the Cowboys behind all day, Aikman wound up throwing 49
passes but completed only 22 for 191 yards and was intercepted
three times. More important, he was sacked four times and hit time
after time by the Cardinals' pass rush.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what it takes to win,'' said linebacker Jamir Miller,
who finished with 12 tackles and two sacks. ``You have to rattle
the quarterback. And we got to Troy. I think he got a little dinged
and started throwing the ball up for grabs. Maybe he was frustrated
or maybe he was dinged, but that pressure made a difference. He was
thinking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The pressure came in part from a few surprises put into the
Cardinals' game plan this week by defensive coordinator Dave
McGinnis. After watching film of Arizona's two regular-season
losses to the Cowboys, McGinnis decided he needed to stop Dallas'
inside running game and installed a five-man front, replacing
linebacker Patrick Sapp with defensive tackle Carl Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   Then he added even more pressure by blitzing Miller often,
leaving cornerbacks Williams and rookie Corey Chavous in single
coverage on Dallas' receivers. Williams shut down Michael Irvin for
the second consecutive game, holding him to 32 yards on four
catches and intercepting two passes. Chavous prevented big plays on
the other side.
</P>
<P>
   ``We challenged our corners and they accepted,'' McGinnis said.
``But that's what we expect of them. We used our ability to be
flexible and move people around, and overall, it was pretty
decent.''
</P>
<P>
   And then some. The Cowboys managed just 260 yards _ an average
of 3.6 yards per play _ and one meaningless touchdown with 3:33
left.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very disappointed they got one in the end zone, I'll
tell you that,'' McGinnis said. ``The guys were extremely upset
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cards' biggest defensive play, the one that turned the game,
came in thw second quarter. And it was head coach Vince Tobin who
gets credit for the idea. McGinnis said Tobin added a couple of
late adjustments to the game plan, including a short-yardage
scheme, adding an extra linebacker, Mark Maddox, in place of a
defensive back.
</P>
<P>
   The Cards, leading 7-0, used the formation on fourth-and-one
from the Arizona 7, with the Cowboys on the verge of tying the game
and grabbing the momentum. Maddox got inside and dropped Emmitt
Smith for a 1-yard loss, ending the threat and visibly deflating
the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is to make the calls,'' McGinnis said. ``The players'
job is to make the calls work. Today, we both did our jobs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
