<SLUG> BC-STRANDED-FANS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WISCONSIN FANS IN NO HURRY TO LEAVE LOS ANGELES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY SHARLINE CHIANG, DAVID ZAHNISER AND ANDREW FAUGHT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif.  &UR; -- &LR;  The Midwest blizzard shut down airports in
Chicago, Detroit and St. Louis on Saturday, stranding throngs of
University of Wisconsin fans who came out for the Rose Bowl for a
few more days.
</P>
<P>
   Not that they were complaining.
</P>
<P>
   Still savoring the Badgers' 38-31 win over UCLA, Dennis
Tauscher, 45, of Marshfield, Wis., said he welcomes the extra time
in sunny Southern California. When he left Wisconsin last week it
was 18 degrees  &UR; -- &LR;  or 40 below zero with the wind-chill factor.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Pasadena reached a balmy 77, missing its record
high, set on the same day in 1994, by 1 degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here it's almost like we're in heaven,'' said Tauscher, a
sportswriter who planned to fly out this morning. So far, he and
his family have visited Universal Studios Hollywood, Disneyland and
Venice Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're delayed, we will just sightsee and tour again,'' he
added. ``We really haven't seen a lot of Hollywood.''
</P>
<P>
   Though several charter planes made it out of Southern California
early in the day, several more faced more questionable chances of
getting in the air by afternoon, said hotel operators and tour
organizers.
</P>
<P>
   Major airlines canceled hundreds of flights as blizzard
conditions forced the closure of Midwestern airports. Snow blew in
drifts that reached 8 feet in some areas of northern Illinois, not
far from the Wisconsin border.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Greater Los Angeles, temperatures soared about 10
degrees above normal and are expected to stay there through
midweek, according to the National Weather Service. The weather
today and Monday in suburban Woodland Hills in Los Angeles' San
Fernando Valley should be sunny and breezy, with highs of 80 today
and 81 on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not too upset about it, let me say that,'' said Jeff
Jankiewicz, 46, of Milwaukee as he planned an unexpected trip to
the beach. ``Most Badger fans are pretty happy right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as he continued to hold the phone for United Airlines,
Douglas Alexander of Madison, Wis., thought he might spend today at
the Huntington Library, Art Collections and Botanical Gardens  &UR; -- &LR; 
and watch the Green Bay Packers' NFL playoff game on television.
</P>
<P>
   As he stood at a row of pay phones at the Pasadena Hilton,
Alexander, 41, was only slightly worried about missing his first
day at his new job Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They, of course, will understand, because going to the Badger
Rose Bowl is the ultimate excuse,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Quality Inn in Pasadena, some 30 families of Badgers fans
booked longer stays, hotel managers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're staying two more days because of the stormy weather,
but they're happy here because they won the game,'' said hotel
manager's assistant Lily Yu. She noticed many fans headed to San
Francisco to watch the 49ers battle the Packers.
</P>
<P>
   Others ``have been going to Universal tours, or to the bar,'' Yu
said. ``They're really nice people. We don't want them to leave.
They're beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Since airline phone lines were jammed Saturday, many fans still
didn't know what the reports of bad weather meant for today's
flights. Several said they planned to spend the day camping out at
Los Angeles International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm planning to do? I'm not sure,'' said waitress Sandy
Sternitsky, 28, also of Marshfield, Wis. ``I've never been in this
position before, ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called home and they're basically snowbound. They said, Stay
where it's warm.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
